She is furious he dishonors her, but he fell in love with the ferocity in her eyes, he explains to her. She can not stand the sight of him and says "I gave you that look in battle only because no one is supposed to live afterwords." 
Whatever battle charm she used left the fool Reubin still in love with her, even after the battle ended. Maybe a bit of Sylvius / Phoebe?








































                IV.2 Leaving the Roost


ADRIFT IN A CLOUD spun of wayward dreamstuff, Diame felt the free floating weightlessness of an ocean around her. Mirages in her slumber tried to take shape within what looked like a dense fog unlit by the sun, and whatever oddities she could see in the murk she already unquestioned as reality. The sound of clopping horse hooves slowly turned her attentions, and a shape of a large animal finished galloping into a cloud, the stir of the fog and fluff around the area was all that remained. At the sight of nothing out of the ordinary, Diame rolled over in a suspended spin, rolling in her lengths of red hair and floating folds of her shift drifted in suspense through the sea of dense fog.
A sharp harking called Diame's attentions and the dreaming priestess gazed upwards in a loll, and witnessed a bird made of mist dive down from a bright white sky and disappear into the dark plumage of clouds, its cry lasting as an echo into the foggy void. Such a sight she, too, regarded it as any other thing in her dream, and it passed her throughts just the same. She muttered something about time and yawned.
The fog thickened and a sudden oncoming darkness cast over the sea of clouds. Diame thought it must have blocked out the sun, but she did not recall seeing in the first place, so did not question the change of scenery as she couldn't quite remember where she was either way. Back into her half awake state she returned.
A pitch blackness took away the vision of the clouds, and what little light there was faintly illuminated an arms reach around Diame's weightless body. She felt somewhat thankful that when wherever she was became darker it allowed one to better sleep, but didn't know why she was glowing so bothersomely. As she shrugged that off as well in her thoughts, she tried to resume resting, only to stirr once more, vexed at the sound of a distant hissing noise. 
Searching for the source of the sound in the unseeable darkness, there seemed to be two points somehow darker than all the rest, slanking side to side. Diame could feel some sort of chill, as if it were a creature gazing up on her, but she could not see what would have eyes blacker than black, growing larger with each movement. 
Something about Diame's dream disturbed her, and she tried to give thought to what it possibly could have been. Puzzled, she stared silently at the thing approaching her, slowing coming to the conclusion that wherever she was floating, it may not be as safe as she once thought. Shuddering again from a chill, she knew she felt the presence of some sort of creature, even though she could not see what the darker than dark thing was, approaching her from the sea of thick mist.
Diame thoughts spun to try to give reason to what was happening around her, but her mind felt slow and sluggish, as if she were in a daze she couldn't awaken from.
Flashes of lightning fulminated from the two points of darkness, crackles of blue light lit up the sea of mist around her and beyond. Whatever the two points of darkness were, they stayed as dull shadows wrapped in the thick clouds lit by lightning flashes, and Diame chilled when the storm headed towards her.
 The priestess determined she was faced with some sort of fearful vision and she tried to call out to God for protection, but her fear turned to terror when she could not inhale to shout out. She willed her voice and to her horror, not a sound escaped her, she twisted as she floated mid air in the mist. The roar of thunder tore all around her, and she was engulfed in flashes of searing hot blue light.


"Evaz'sa watch over me!" Diame shouted as she sprang upright, widened blue eyes staring up through the bed canopy at the mural of God in the sky painted on the ceiling. Her panting breaths calmed as she gazed up to the image of the Goddess of the Sun, wings spread in golden sunlight surrounded by Angels. She gulped at air, "A dream..." she exhaled breathlessly. "'Twas only a dream." She assured herself as much that it wasn't reality, and in the haste of her waking moments, the High Priestess of Water set aside the thought that it could be yet another vision foreboding of something ill to come. 
Remembering where she was, she took in the room of the inn she was staying at, dimly lit by several candles. Most of the wicks on the chandeleir up above were shortened and still lit, as were the candles on the nightstands beside her. The large wax candle of the woman holding the urn had burnt down such that the flame was where the head would be, and the hands had melted off into two held up stumps for arms. 
"Oh, I suppose I am awake enough." Diame judged as much even with how groggy she felt, but nonetheless she was refreshed. "I need to be back on the road, I-" She pulled the covers off her and realized her hands trembled, and clasped them together. She felt alert but as by something startling her out of her sleep, though she could not recall what, which disturbed her. I must make haste, that is all I can do. There certainly isn't any going back. 
The priestess put her bare feet out into the cool air on to a soft carpet, and saw the sky still dark outside the large windows. Perhaps to anyone else they would not notice the sun was about to rise, the pitch black sky could have easily been mistaken for the deepest part of the night. However, years of waking up before dawn had trained her senses to the subtle rises of moisture in the air, the crisp way plants smell in the coldest part of the predawn, the chattering of early birds. She also knew her senses were experiencing strange sensations, delving deeper than any normal person could. She felt as though she were outside in the deep forest, breathing in cool air from an enormous fog bank, rolled down from the surrounding mountains in the night. She tried to stop herself from thinking anymore of it when she realized she somehow knew the way the cloud had traveled, as if she had the memory of seeing it herself.
Becoming aware she could uncontrollably sense all the water in the air, she began a mantra. "I am complete control of my magicks..." Diame prayed quietly to herself, aware she still had not performed any of her cloister rituals, not releasing any of the water aether she carried with her. I have come thus far on what I had set out to do. If I can not show I am capable of handling these powers, how can I prove any of what I have seen has merit to Bishop Malbourne? But he has to believe me, must he not?! A pang of worry struck over her, and she shook it off and repeated, "I am in complete control of my," 
A knock at the door followed by a concerned whisper interrupted her, "Did you summons, mi'lady? May I enter?" The door cracked and the young serving girl in plain livery and dark hair pulled back into a braid stood into the candle light.
Straightening her shift as she sat upright in bed, Diame cleared her throat, nearly forgetting the inn's staff was waiting on her. "Aye, come in, please." She spoke, trying to sound pleasant as she calmed her nerves, still shaken from the wakening jolt of her nightmare.
The maid entered carrying a ceramic pitcher of washwater and in one arm and bowl in another with a cloth draped over her arm, "Good morrow, mi'lady." She said as cheerful as she could be, probably having worked through the night. "Did you rest well?" she said as she placed the washstuff and pitcher of steaming water on the table next to the wax candle of the melting woman and turned round to meet her.
        Diame met her with a tired nod, "Aye, thank you." She said, nearly stifling a yawn.
        "Well, mi'lady, you said you would be up early to resume your travels, so I brought fresh washstuff and I shall return with a hot breakfast the Roost has prepared for you. If that will be all, so please you?" She curtsied before her and seemed to await Diame's assent to leave.
Alright, I haven't the time to waste. I shall prepare quickly and then I must make haste. "Aye, thank you." 
The moment it was said, the maid deepened her courtsy and then turned round, briskly leaving out the door she came in from. 
Diame gave pause, knowing that being brought here to this sort of service was not just good fortune on the road. Such safety and luxuries were arranged under God's watchful eyes, and whatever dreadful dream I had awoke me to ensure I get to where I need to be swiftly. She nodded, reminded of her resolve. "I have already traveled much farther than I would have thus far, I can arrive in Ijia on my own by the end of the day, I think." She assured herself as she stepped out of bed to the washstuff and sat on a cushioned chair by the table side.
She gave her face a wash with the cloth and hot water, and felt revived out of drowsiness, and remarked on how she never had enjoyed such things prepared for her. No sooner than when she finished drying herself did the maid enter once more with a covered silver plate. She revealed a plate of two overturned eggs, a thick slab of cured bacon, a buttered roll of freshly baked home bread, and a bowl of apples and pears cut into bite sized pieces topped with sweet cinnamon.
Diame had not eaten a breakfast so hearty in a long while, used to eating only produce harvested from Teva's farms, but she did not complain as she savored what she could as she ate in a hurry. The maid brushed off what dirt had collected on Diame's blue robes, and helped her get dressed in them as fastly as possible while telling her of the best routes through the forest to Ijia. She then aided the High Priestess shoulder her satchel and even handed her her driftwood walking staff, never taking her for anything else than a traveling noblewoman.
 Diame thanked the maid profusely for all her attentive services, even whilst she made her way swiftly down the inn's hallway and descended the stairs to the small lobby, the maid was at her heels, asking over and over if there was anything else that she needed.
Once again, Diame kindly assured the maid that she had everything she needed to get to Ijia, and before she could thank her again, she noticed the middle aged lady in the green dress looking up at her from behind the desk counter. Weariness showed through the smile she wore as she held a pen to one of many scattered recipts and ledgers about her, yet she gave a gracious nod to the traveler who paid to stay in the nicest room, and Diame returned it. 
The maid went to open up a large oaken door that lead out to the forest, it seemed to be the main entrance to the Inn's lobby. No sooner than when the big door opened did plumes of cold mist spill onto the lobby floor and dissipated. Diame pushed the volumes of red curls behind her circlet and tucked her hair in the back of her blue robes, then donned her hood to stay warm, even though the cold couldn't bother her. She gave the young girl another nod for her services, and stepped out the inn's door out into the brisk forest air, faintly lit blue by approaching dawn.


Diame descended down a step onto a covered porch area, a pair of lanterns hung from the roof above another step, their dim light cast on her as she passing them by. She stepped onto the soft forest soil, and with walking staff in hand, the High Priestess trod down a worn path and through the heavy fog that brightened as dawn came up on her. 
Nearing a small covered stables, the path seemed to split just past it, accompanied by a signpost pointing in several directions. She remembered what the maid had told her, that the road splits as many travel deeper into the forest or even into the mountains. Most importantly, that the quickest route to Ijia was not even the large main one, for it made many bends to better serve outposts and cart traffic, and that a side route was shorter and better known by lone travelers. It would have fewer turns and lead directly out into the open fields, the lands before the Kingdom of Ijia. Just a little further, I must ensure His Holiness hears of my fears, once I tell him my dreams straight to his ear. She reminded herself that she was less than a days' walk away now, and was happy to know her journey was nearing an end.
The priestess took a deep breath of the forest air, the crisp scent of pine and maple trees cooled by mist filled her lungs, and felt refreshing under her thick blue robes. Content traveling down the dirt path with no one beside her and being awake before dawn, she felt as though it was any other day begun as usual, the lone walk reminding her of going to the Water Temple for morning prayers. She felt at ease, and kept her focus on walking just the little ways more, grateful for what good fortunes she had had thus far on what she set out to do. By how safely and swiftly she had traveled, Diame was heartened to believe that God was directly watching over her journey, guiding her on the path the Priestess began by correctly interpreting her sacred swevens.
Diame took in a crescendo of the birds chirping as the forest came alive by the brightness of dawn, and even the pathway became easier to see in the brisk fog. She took a deep sigh, and caught a scent of horsestalls as she continued past the covered stables, a shabby building made of weathered wood that seemed to barely stay held together. Even so, it housed a line of horses in a row, each covered head to tail with horse blankets, and they were barely astir with their eyes covered. She felt sorry for the creatures, having to sleep out in the cold barely covered, and felt content to own the warmth in her boots. 
As the signpost and many splitting paths ahead revealed themselves in the fog, Diame thought of the way she was told to get through the forest. Let's see, the kind maid said Burrows Pass would be the best route through. I do hope I do not lose my way, but I have come thus far on God's good fortunes, and I believe Her Eyes will watch over my path. She reminded herself happily. And with Ijia just at the end of a day's walk, what could possibly mar my way?
A sudden whinnying came from the last stall made Diame jump and raise her arm in defense as she passed it by, but she was relieved that it was just a lanky mule, covered in a horse blanket that seemed to be all but holes and patches. Before she could feel bad for startling the animal, she heard a rustling just past the stable walls.
Around the corner, a tattered blanket flung up from amidst a cart full of cargo boxes and bags, and there Shul was, sitting up, bewildered, and still in the ragged riding clothes that he wore yesterday. The man seemed to have slept the night in his cart on a small pallet, and he awoke in a daze up on hearing the mewling of his mule. He then noticed Diame was standing over him, and his face split wide with surprise. "Oh, Lady Delandra! Er-, a good morro'!" He nearly leapt out onto the forest floor by how quickly he scrambled out of his cart, and as soon as he was on his feet, he dropped to a bow before her, his straw hat to his heart. 
Diame tried to greet the man who had helped her travel here the day before, but for a moment it seemed impossible to work the words. She realized her hand was shaking, and leant on her staff with all her weight to ground herself. Perhaps the mule frightened me more than I expected. Please get ahold of yourself woman, it was merely a harmless animal. She shook off her shaken nerves with the thought, and at last gave the man a polite nod. "A good morrow to you as well, kind Master Shul. Eyes watch over you this fine morn." She said, returning a smile and trying not to feel so put off guard.
"Ah was hopin' so much, uh, that ah might cross yer path, to aid yeh on yer way to the kingdom, ah was!" His gap toothed smile and demeaner were jovial and lively even though he seemed to had just awoken. "Aye, such a consid'rate soul is this man ah waited fer yer ladyship to see ye arrive safely, ah did!" He said as he began ropes from the cart and walked towards her. "M' pardons, mi'lady," He said as he passed her by with a bow of his head, and with a squeak of rusty hinges, led his mule out from the ramshackle horsestalls. "Ah jus' need to get ol' Betsy awake an' leadin' th' cart, hold just a minute, and we'll be off." He assured her as he took off the horseblanket, and hurriedly added "Aye, if ye would be so kind, Your Ladyship? Thank ye." And began girdling Betsy in a haste.
"Oh, sir, you are too kind. I do not know if that would be right." I couldn't possibly ask him to help again, yet he went out of his way to wait for me? Diame shook her head of red curls under her blue hood, "Nay sir, to ask another favor of you after all you have done already would surely be considered a sin. I do not mean to be rude, but I believe my legs will bring me to Ijia on my own, thank you." She nodded to him, "I bid you a good day, Master Shul. May Eyes watch over you." And with a smile of good cheer, went on towards the signposts. I do hope he wasn't waiting here for me long, it is quite cold in the wee hours of the morning for one not atuned to Water. A thought trailed off as she went on her way. "Now, lets see, Burrow's Pass..."
        The man made a sudden yelping sound as if he were choking on something. "Er, wait, um, please, Lady Delandra, I, uh..." Shul seemed to want to say something, but Diame had already passed him by.
        Looking back over her shoulder, Diame saw a look of worry on Shul's face, and then his mouth split with his wide gap-toothed smile and started after her. Oh, God help me. What could the man be thinking? "C-can I aid you, Master Shul?"
        The man was walking towards her reluctantly, but surely, "Well," Shul took off his straw hat, and pensively scrubbed his fingers through graying hair. "Ah was jus' figurin', uh..." He nodded to himself as he stopped just before Diame, and said calmly, "That is, if w' were both 'eaded to th' kingdom proper, uh... I would be savin' you th' trouble of walkin'. Its still ways away, mi'lady, I thought surely you'd ride with me once more." He redonned his hat and gave a sigh of mild frustration, and stammering to find convincing words.
        To have such an offer refused must have seemed illogical to the man, Diame noted Shul seemed somewhat apprehensive to the idea of her not riding along. Well, I don't mean to insult his kindness, but I'm sure I will be an inconvenience to the poor man, besides. "Beg your pardons, sir." Her fair hand pointed behind him, "It seems as though I may as well be on my way, as it seems your ass needs minding."
        Shul's eyes sprang wide with confusion, "Me arse?" He then looked around, and continued the motion with a spin when he saw that Betsy had wandered from her stables, and slowly venturing on a way off into the forest. "Saints! Me ass!" and ran back towards his mule gone astray.
        "Poor fellow, I do wish him well, and hope to abstain from bothering him anymore than I already have." And with that, Diame came up on the old signpost, intaking a carved crow adorning it that nearly looked real. She could try to make out the carvings made in the arrows pointing in the ways the path split past many steep gradings and thick vegatation. Some of the roads were wide, but the shortcut she would take was supposed to be a direct route off the beaten path. "Let's see," The carvings in the wood were faint, yet seemed to have been tended to time to time. 
        Though she hadn't the time to idle, the disguised priestess couldn't help but look over her shoulder, and Shul was indeed bridling the mule to the cart in a visible haste. He leapt into the cart, scrambled into his drivers seat, then even waved to her assuredly with a grin! He tapped at the mule's reins to motion a trot, but the creature did not budge, then after a couple more tries, the man leapt out of the cart once again, produced a pole that once affixed, protruded from the front of the cart. He hurriedly began tying a red apple to hang before the mule, and the animal started walking even without him in the cart, nearly trampling him with it if he hadn't already jumped back in his seat in time.
        "Burrow's Pass," Reminding herself, Diame returned her attentions to the signpost, and scanned the names that pointed in many directions out of the Crow's Forest. "Forestglenn Road seems to be the name for the main road, and many small paths seem to branch off in many ways... Ah! Burrows pass is just a small walk down the main road from here. God's good fortunes smile up on me indeed." The sounds of hooves trotting and wheels winding turned the priestess's attentions, and Shul was nearly up on her as he sat in his cart gesturing towards her assuredly, in tow by Betsy, in tow by the apple. "Yet, why does this man pursue me so, even after I have said I wish to go my own way?" She couldn't help but return the wave back at him, then brought her hand to her face and wondered. But, what if God had sent this kind soul to guide me, and certainly I may lose my way. Maybe that is why he feels the need to help me so? Yet, if this man is not of God... She paused as he approached her, taking in the good cheer of his gap toothed grin. Mayhaps I should go on my own after all?
        "Ah, the virtue o' patience shines in ye, Lady Delandra," He gently pulled at the reins of the cart, and the doleful eyed donkey slowed to a halt. "Thank ye for waitin' for me t'get me ass bridled." Shul's grin widened and kindness squinted his eyes. "Aye, then, let us b' off. I promise we'll be in Ijia b'fore sundown." He assured her, and began pulling at the rope that opened the hatch in the back for her. 
        "But," Diame muttered mostly to herself. I was looking forward to taking the helpful advice the maid gave me, she is a local after all. There the familiar crated seat was, the same against the somewhat comfortable sack of lumps she had dozed on for so long yesterday. However, he said he would take me straight there, obviously that would be safest and least tiresome, so why do I hesitate to go with him? Am I acting like a foolish girl? 
        "Erm, wha' 'tis the matter, Lady Delandra?" Perhaps he noticed a pique of worry coming from her, for he tried to assure her by motioning to the mule. "'Tis jus' me and ol' Betsy as b'fore." He turned to pat her on the rump, to which the animal replied with a sound release of air to the man's face. 
        The priestess blinked.
        "Erm," He chuckled, surprised. "Ol' girl." He pat the animal again once more, and continued on. "Anyroad, let us be off now and we shall be at the kingdom fairly quickly, erm, by your as'ent, Mi'Lady."
        Diame thought on it once more, she was fully rested and had looked forward to the walk alone with her own thoughts. She was a High Priestess carrying around a message of importance to the Church to protect them as well as her village, even that meant the duplicity of not even telling anyone where she had ran off to, and even swore little Sindha to secracy. 
        However, one advantage she could think of is that when she was in solitude, she no longer had to keep up this 'noblewoman Delandra on a pilgrimage' charade for anyone. But for the life of her, could not make up her mind which way she would go, and yet she knew she stood there losing time, which was worse than going any route. Diame grew severely impatient with herself, and looked skyward through the thatches of leaves. Mist hung brightly on the boughs of the trees as the sun began to rise higher above the surrounding mountains. It was a new day and she felt she was where she was supposed to be. I suppose if God wills me to be where needed, a bevy of opportunities would present themselves. I suppose good company is better than without, so I could pretend to be Delandra a little longer, I suppose. I do believe I should trust Master Shul as he is wise traveler, and certainly knows his way through the woods better than I. Though I yet feel like I'm taking advantage of his kindness, I know it is a long journey ahead. Indeed, I had just climbed down a mountain yesterday and got a full nights rest, but what if I must need my strength to climb a mountain? "But, of course, good sir. I do not know these woods at all, I certainly wouldn't want to lose my way. You certainly would save me another long walk." Although she could recall the simple instructions to take Burrows Pass, and could clearly see it written on the sign before her, and was not even sure how arduous the road alone would have been, she tossed in her satchel and driftwood staff and jumped in over the hatchback herself.
        The gap toothed man nearly stumbled over his words with breathless exasperation, he seemed to have politely had a whole nother list of reasons why Diame should ride with him, but the worry melted off his face as he drew a deep breath. "Phew! I er, mean, well then!" Shul let out a nervous chuckle in good spirit and hopped himself back in the mule driver's seat. "Let us be off, w' should arrive in the kingdom proper before nightfall." He pulled the hatch closed by the rope up front and gave the lone traveler a nod from under his had. "Jus' enjoy the ride mi'lady. We'll be there b'fore you know it." His grimy lips smiled around his rotten teeth, and he turned his attentions back to Betsy.
        As the man prepared another red apple on a string to coax the animal, Diame continued to assure herself that she was on the right path. "How long until we make it to Ijia did you say again?" She idly inquired to strike up a conversation with the man she was about to chat with once more. I do hope I make it there faster by taking this cart. A shortcut couldn't have been that much shorter, right? She tried to peer through the misty road ahead as if she could see beyond the bends and surrounding trees.
        "Oh, well bee'fore sundown, aye." The mule driver stated in good morning cheer as he gave Betsy a tap with the reins, and with a light jerk, the cart was wheeling forward in motion. "You jus' not worry 'bout a thing, mi'lady. You know, did I ev'r tell you more about me wife?" Shul glanced over his shoulder with a crooked smile. "You do so remind me o' her. Err, um, but not nowadays," He turned his attentions back to steering the mule around the winding road, "years ago when w' firs' met, she was fair an' comely as y' are now, miss. I do love 'er but alas 'ow she has wizen'd and broaden'd an'-" he cut himself off and lowered his head between his shoulders, "Oh I mistake meself, please beg pardons, mi'lady. I jus' 'ave a commoners tongue, y'see."
        He spoke and Diame heard him, but her mind thought not of a response. But, what if the pass was shorter? She weighed heavily. No, fool girl. You are already on a cart going where you need to be going. Surely if I was walking around a haphazard shortcut I could get terribly lost, or what if I stumbled on the uneven road and sprain my ankle? By and by the misty cospses of pineneedle trees went by her as she was well on her way to Ijia as the cart swifty carried her down the bumpy forest path. Nay, I daresay that this is the safer route. Surely, these nagging thoughts are just part of the restlessness on my mind of knowing what I must do. She sat back stiffly against a sack of apples as Shul chatted his mind as he steadily drove the mule on. The priestess of water heaved a sigh of relief that she neared Ijia, her intents she clear in her mind. What I have seen was shown to me very clearly from the Holy Messiah herself. So big is this message, yet, I know that only I was entrusted to me to relay its importance. She reminded herself, mustering up the nerve ahead of time to speak with a bishop face to face, to explain not only her dreams but a myriad of other things. Her breaking the sacred oath to even be outside of her home being one of them. "Eljuk..." she muttered, thinking of the townguardsman and her friend. Diame nearly felt ill recalling how she snuck around him, and left her confidant in the dark of her actions. I am doing what I must. Eljuk would understand... wouldn't he...? Surely, he would and I have always given him my full trust. Her thoughts wandered once more.
        "Anyhow, me wife an' I," Shul carried on, "We nev'r 'ad any children, y'see. Jus' as well, me work keeps me mighty busy, I wouldn't see them if I was always on the road, aye? But who needs kids when I 'ave Betsy, 'ere." He chuckled and the mule seemed to whicker in response. Around another bend in the road the animal took them, through the morning fog as thick as ever. 
        Although lost in thought, Diame looked around the dense forest as it passed her by. Would Bishop Malbourne be as understanding? She wondered. He is a a man of the Faith, surely his faith will convince him to take action, just as mine has compelled me to do so. Won't it? She sighed and took in the early morning atmosphere, the sun was a bright glow above the moving trees and mist. 
        An opening in one of the cospses revealed what seemed to be an off-road, it seemed to be a straight line even though it had rough unevenness to it. Squinting her glassy blue eyes, she peered down the misty side road, a tiny sign stuck in the road reading Boroughs' Pass, plain as day. Her thoughts indeed took pause, and all she could focus on was the side path. The advice the maid servent gave to her that it was indeed the shortest path resounded in her head, but she shut the thought out, that was before she knew she would get another ride from Shul. Surely this path was the shorter one, and face less peril. Yet all the while, she still felt the need to call out to the mule driver and ask him to halt the cart. All the while she thought, she had passed the supposed shortcut by, and already the cart had made its way past another cospe of trees, and it had all but disappeared from sight while she made up her mind.
        Diame had leant all the way forward and bent her neck as she caught the last gimpse of the sign disappear into the trees and fog. "Too late now, I suppose..." she said under her breath. The thought crossed her mind that she could still refuse the man's kind offer, leap up out of the cart, and swiftly though this shortcut like she had in her mind. "Aye, far too late, now." She leant back with a sigh, as though relieved the descision was made for her. I must trust that there are many paths that lead to where God asks of me. I do hope I arrive in Ijia soon, after I have words with His Holiness, I must return to Teva with an even greater haste. She let out a sigh realizing she had been holding her breath for nearly a full minute.
        Listening to Shul talk on of his wife and occupation as Lord Igor's delivery driver, the Priestess rode along in the cart without any qualms on her descision. Her feet did ache so from her travels yesterday, and now she rode along with only her mission on her mind. Diame reminded herself the urgency of what she had seen, and would arrive fully prepared to explain to The Church why she was there. Yet she also had questions of her own. Such as, why hadn't she recieved any word at all from them? Not a single reply to her letters, even when she persisted them so? Had something happened to them? 
        Shaking off her worry, Diame took a deep breath of the forest air thick with the smell of maples and pines. Without effort, she could see all the wisps of water in the air, and sensed the vastness of the forest by feeling where every dew drop on every leaf rested. It put her at ease, and she calmly mulled over her thoughts as the shakey cart took her down the winding road to the Kingdom of Ijia.










































                IV.3 Quicken the Road


THE MORNING HOURS had marched by Diame without her noticing too closely, and she watched the forest scenery change in the early light. She felt as though she was still very much deep within the forest, and went over what she might say to the Bishop when she arrived in Ijia. She had also enjoyed the company of Shul, who had talked with barely a pause, skipping though topics on everything he could think of to make conversation about. He was now on the subject of fishing, and talked about the many different ways gutted innards could be reused. She could barely hear him with all that was going on in her mind, and the High Priestess patiently held on to her anticipation to hear from Shul when they were nearby Ijia. The thought that perhaps they were closeby and he simply forgot to tell her crossed her mind, and she continued sitting at ease in the bumpy cart.
The rising sun steadily shed light down through the canopy of the forest, and all around her, nature was alive and awake with birdsong among trees and wild game rusting among bushes in the distance. She took a sip from her water flask and uttered a silent prayer to the life which God had created.  
Diame placed the flask back in her bag and caught sight of her map. She had no idea to know where she was, and reminded of such, decided to inquire on to whereabouts she was in closeness to Ijia. 
"... Aye, 'tis true, you can fry up jus' about everythin' you gut from an animal mi'lady, but 'tis nigh impossible to compare to a real treat, me own wife's fishgut stew." 
"Master Shul?" Diame interjected.
"Perhaps, you'll come 'ave dinner with us one night an' try- uhn?" The mule driver paused his thoughts for the first time in hours. "Aye, what is it, mi'lady?" He responded without missing a beat, his cheer as strong as ever.
"Well, I was just wondering," She scanned the thick forest around her again and couldnt begin to sense where it ended. "but when would we arrive in Ijia? Surely we are almost there?" Being in the middle of nowhere, Diame indeed needed some assurance, there was just the one path, and hardly any other passers by on the road. But of course she trusted Shul knew what he was doing.
Shul grunted seemingly to give it some thought, and turned over his shoulder and smiled a gap toothed grin at her. "Lessee, I'd say another hour we may be out of Crow's Forest, perhaps even sooner." He turned his attentions back to steering his mule and leant forward to look into the distance. "Ijia is farther north still, but 'tis faster traveling in the wide open roads. Ye should reach it before sundown I reckon." He gave an assuring tilt of his hat to her. "Hmm, aye I do believe that is so. Worry not, Mistress Delandra. I 'ave traveled these roads hundreds, if not thousands of times, I 'ave!" He grinned once more and tapped the reins of his mule to help keep up her step. 
 Looking at the moving scenery around her, the surrounding trees stretched on in every direction, and as far as she could see, disappearing into the thick mist. Trying to sense where the forest might end with her attunement with water, Diame couldnt see where the fog might end. She could feel the chill of the forest stretch on and on, and pulled her hooded robe tigher around her even though the cold phased her not. "Well then, I have naught to worry about." she assured herself. I do wish we would arrive there faster. I'm sure he knows what he is doing, but that maid lass said even by foot I'd be out of the forest by late morn. Yet it seems it may be near high noon already? There was no way to know where she was, and an effort to try on foot now would surely be in vain. She knew she had to stay fast, and trust that this was another test of her faith. Shul had come along to help her, and she was going to allow him to do that. "Everything will be all right, I suppose." She smiled to herself and looked down the road, seeing a hooded figure jump out from a shrub. Her smile turned sour as she gasped, half the life startled out of her.
"Whoa!" Shul yelled to calm Betsy as the surprised beast whinnied and flailed in fear. "Calm down, easy girl!" He pulled on the reins and in short time the beast did calm itself and became docile. 
The brutal looking man stood tall with his arms crossed just ahead of them in filthy clothes with his face completely darked by a hood. 
Diame leant forward and hid over master Shul's shoulder and whispered to him, "What does he want? Is he a robber?!" She leant over him and before she knew it, she was shouting at the man, "We have nothing of value! Please, be blessed leave us in peace!" and hid back behind the mule driver.
"Aye! Actually, y'do!" the man shouted back. He pointed right at her, "You! Be still!"
All around her, the silence of the forest was broken by the stomps of heavy feet and snaps of branches. At least a dozen men emerged from hiding, each with a hood on their head or a piece of cloth over their faces. They grunted and snarled at her, and in moments had the cart completely surrounded. 
Diame sprang up and stood in middle the cart to make some distance away from them. "Please, nay! I must make it to Ijia, I have nothing to take! Shul, help! Do something!" Her heart pounded against her chest she felt as if she would faint. God, nay! Why is this happening?! The robbers had their hands over knives ready to brandish them, and what she could see of their eyes was cold hatred directed at her. As they stood still, she could hear footsteps coming from down the road. Diame's eyes widened in disbelief as a familiar gaunt-faced young lord, with a gilt monkey head's cane emerged from the fog. 
Walking casually by the thugs with their faces covered, he approached Shul as if they didnt exist. "Ah, you have done well bringing her all the way out here. Shul, it looks as though your usefulness will allow you to keep your livelihood after all." He said crassly with distaste for his mule driver. "Ah, here she is, this aethermancer is going to make me even wealthier beyond my dreams." He grinned at her a disgusting smile on his perfect teeth.
"L-" Diame couldn't believe anything she was seeing, "Lord Igor?!" She realized she was still hiding behind Shul's shoulders, and quickly pushed herself away from him, "You brought me here!?" She said with utter disgust for the man whom she just shared a cart with for nearly two whole days. I demand to know what in God's name is going on here!" Her shouted trembled as she stood upright.
The young lord chuckled a spiteful laugh at her, "Aye, I supposed I forgot to tell you," Lord Igor lifted up his gold cane and took his time staring into the eyes of the monkey head, "I... was planning on kidnapping you, and selling you into slavery. I was going to pay you no mind, as why would I waste my time with some lass in my mule drivers cart? I coud sense that you had a talent for using aether, I tested you to make sure. And now you will add to my wealth. Many would pay a fortune to have a witch at their beck and call." He licked his lips as he smiled at her, "And an especially comely lass such as yourself would double as some sick bastard's plaything as well. As you are the bounty, I ask that you do not struggle." He leered at his henchmen, "Well, what are you waiting for?! Secure the witch in aethereal binds!" He shouted.
"Nay! Someone, help!" Diame screamed, but that did not stop a robber from starting to pull himself up over the cart's catch.
"Shaddap!" The man snarled as he started to climb in, "Come along quietly lass or I'll wring that neck of yours faster than-"
In a swift motion, Diame swung her staff and cracked the man over the head with all her might, and gasped in shock as he fell backwards into the dirt. "I-I'm sorry!" Diame apologized as she covered her mouth in disbelief as the man lay with a bloodied brow by her hand. She wanted to ask if he was alright, but there was no time for that as the gang of other rogues all at once reached into the cart, grabbing for her and climbing over one another. 
"Hurry it up!" Lord Igor shouted, his voice strained with contempt.
A robber leapt over another and began to grab at her, "Nay!" She screamed as she swung her staff again, and he gripped it fast and threatened to pull it away with one hand as she used by all her strength with two to hold on. "Leave me be! Please!" Diame pleaded. On either side, men grabbed at Diame's robes, and pulled her in two directions, nearly pulling her over. "Nay!" She screamed again as she stuggled with the three brutes to not be over taken, yet more started to climb into the cart one after the other. "Help me! Holy Evaz'sa! Save me!"  Her staff was nearly wrested from her, and her strength dwindled. "Heeelp! Anyone!!!" She shouted with the last of her mustered might, hearing her voice echo off into the distance of the forest. In a wash, all she could hear was her voice, all she could see was the mist swirling around her glimmering bright blue, and it became hard to see and hear what was happening around her anymore. Diame felt a strong chill, and suddenly became even more aware of every droplet of water in the forest down to the tiniest puddle. What?! Nay, why now does the aether overpower me so?! I can scarce see a thing! Her thoughts resounded as she tried to see what was happening around her. God, any time but now! She thought she was hallucinating, but she felt as though she could move but was in no hold. 
All was still bright white to her, then she realized she was engulfed in mist so thick that it marred her vision so. Then in an instant, all the mist seemed to fade to a faint blue veil around her. She went pale, the entire group of robbers were standing around her within arms reach, their eyes wide open, reaching out as if they could still not see a thing.
"F-... Find her!" Lord Ignor shouted with a cracked voice, not even sure exactly where his cohorts were. "Do not let her escape using such base witchery, you fools!" His yell was near breathless with exascerbation as all his men instead gazed around them completely dumbfounded and disoriented.
In haste, Diame shouldered her bag, and kicked the back hatch open to the cart. It dropped down and bludgeoned the same rogue in the head once more, who only just regained himself to sit up. But Diame failed to notice any of that as she hopped out onto the ground and ducked around them through all the confusion. She ran off of the main road and passed behind some trees, and tried not to stumble as she maneuvered through a bumpy path of raised roots. She had no idea where in the forest she was or where she was running to with all her might. She knew she needed to be far away from here, yet she still had find a way out of the forest. There was a grueling commotion of shouts of frustration from behind her, yet all she could do was run with all the speed her legs could take her.




MINUTES PASSED and Diame was out of breath and it took all her will to not sick up from running. She kept moving. Looking behind her she took in full gulps of the misty air, she saw no one but would not allow herself to stop. What if they are right behind me? All her muscles locked up, and she slowed involuntarily. "Nay... Don't stop," she panted, "Keep running!" She breathlessly reminded herself, then slowed to a stumbling walk.
 She had to rest, and if she was going to faint she wouldn't let it be out in the open. She ducked behind a group of small bushes and was mostly hidden, she dropped her staff and bag and fell down on to her hands and knees, gulping for air. All she could hear was her breath, and in fear she clasped her hands around her mouth for a moment to hear if any footsteps were up on her. She heard nothing but the sound of her heart beating as if it were going to leap from her throat. There was naught else but the sounds of the rustles of wind and the deep birds. She breathed again a sigh of relief, nearly thinking she would feel ill if held it any longer. She sat still for a moment, trying to regain herself.
Diame brought her dirty hands up to her face, and saw they were shaking. "What have I done to myself?" she whispered sharply to her self. I cant stay here any longer, they will surely be up on me any moment. She grabbed her things and stood upright, cautiously peering out from above the bushes. There was no one and she arose and looked around her. She truly was alone in the forest full of fog, thankful to be so. However, she was also completely lost, and had no way of knowing where she was on the map. "I must get out of here as fast as I can, but in which direction?" She looked around her, trying to find the sun, but as it reached its zenith, it was hard to tell which way was East or West. "The trees?" She said to herself and inspected some of the nearby trees, "Moss always grows on the North side, right?" Indeed, it did seem to grow in a direction that was not where she had just came running from. She started in that direction as fast as she could, as Ijia would be to the North, eventually. She hoped. 
Diame kept a fervent run as she dodged branches and tried to find a path between all the overgrown greenery around her. She was full of adrenaline and had no thought of looking back, however, she felt like her stamina wouldn't last forever and have to stop again eventually. What am I going to do? She wondered as she ran, then she slowed to a sudden halt. "I need to stay focused, and not stay from a single path... Water...?" The priestess stopped and gave thought to her senses. A water source, a large one she had felt the presence of for some time now suddenly felt as though it was up on her. "What could that be?" It veered slightly in the direction she was headed anyway, and she started off once again in that direction.
She kept running, worried with every step that she was going in the wrong way and be captured. But she had to be close to this water source she felt so strongly. She knew she was. 
Around another cospe of trees she stopped to catch her breath when she found what looked like a small lake. The still water was shallow and clear, and light shone down to the bottom. The edges were all surrounded by trees and bushes, and she was cut off from sight mostly, so she sat a moment by the water's edge. The water smelled pure and clean and she washed the dirt off her hands and cooled the sweat from her brow. She felt refreshed and her mind returned to her, Diame thought up on what to do next. She had to stay on the move, but she thought she perhaps might be able to find another clue to lead her in the right direction out of the forest. 
She looked around her, and felt a relief as there was a wooden sign across the water, it read 'Echo Pond' from a worn carving. "Echo Pond?" Diame pondered. "Maybe I can find it on the map?" Hurriedly, she opened her satchel and pulled out the worn map, and the yellow flower Sindha gave her fell out to the ground. Carefully picking it up, Diame took a thoughtful moment to look up on it. "I will make it back to Teva, after I fulfil what I have set out to do in Ijia. I sweat it." She kissed the flower as she placed it back in her bag. 
"Let's see," Gazing up on the map, she clearly saw the forest between the mountains, and several of the main pathways. There were some of the large rivers mapped, but she could not find where in this vast forest this Echo Pond could possibly be. "Do not dare to tell me it isn't on the map?" The thought she said outloud rang true, it would be nearly impossible to mark a map without a landmark. "I guess I need to hurry, I don't have the time to waste if I don't even know where... I don't even know where I am...!" She stood up with the map in hand, and let out a heavy sigh, she looked around as if she would suddenly be able to match the infintismal forest up to a random place on the map.
Something bright caught her eye from nearby the waters edge, a small firefly, or light of a will-o'-wisp darted away from out of  her sight behind a tree. She blinked, it vanished. "What was that?" She started over to where she saw it, "I knew I saw something!" She would not doubt herself, and practically threw herself over a small shrub to get to where she saw the glint of light. She looked around her for the tiny light, and could see it not. "Surely, I was meant to happen across here, God is trying to guide me now, more than ever. And I do need Her help now!" She tried to sense the aether around her, and to the High Priestess of Water, all she could detect was the strong source of water aether ourpouring from the pond behind her. 
Diame took in a deep breath, and kept her thoughts clear, she was not going to let anything stop her. She felt the strong inundation of water, but amid her mind's eye, she could sense a faint elemental trace of light aether, and it was still just ahead of her. She opened her eyes where she envisioned seeing that faint energy, and just a stones throw away before her was a large, rough hewn tree. "There!" She ran over to the tree that looked to be ancient, its height was well beyond any other around it, and its bark was thick and coarse, as if it weathered the elements countless times. Diame approached the tree, carefully walked over its large, gnarled roots that outstretched in unnatural curls. She could still sense the light, and faintly see a glow through the tree. "Hello?!" Diame shouted, but made sure not too loudly so none else could hear her. "Hello! Can you hear me?!" 
There was no response or movement from the wisp, and Diame looked up close at the huge, gnarled tree. There was a small crevase between some of the winding gnashed together bark, and what seemed to be a deep knothole in its trunk. Diame leaned forward, and peered into the hole, and near instatly, the the ball of light shook, and flew down through the tree, into the ground, and halted again. 
Diame's eyes nearly leapt from her head, and she leapt forward and threw herself against the tree and spoke through the tiny hole, "Oh, small wisp of light! I'm so sorry to bother you, but I am lost!" she shouted at the great tree, not sure if she was even talking to something sentient.
There was no response, but the ball of light stayed where it was, almost quivering.
Diame stood there before the great tree, and looked up at the twisted wood. I don't even know if my words are even reaching anyones ears, and if they were, what would any hidden magickal creature have to trust mankind? She thought carefully, she wouldn't want to scare this easily startled being off. She had one chance to ask it for help, and she thought hard. I believe that it took an interest in me first. Perhaps whatever it was saw an interest in my magicks when I was searching for the water aether? 
The High Priestess of Water beseeched the glowing light within the tree once more. "Please listen to me, I-I'm on pilgrimage, you see. My name is Delan-" She stopped herself, she had no reason to lie about her identity to a magickal creature. "I mean, that is to say... I am the High Priestess Diame Serigh. I have traveled from Teva, and left my sacred cause to protect the water temple because..." She caught her breath, realizing she was just saying everything so quickly out in the open. But she had to press on to get this magick creature to trust her. "Because, I fear for the safety of my village, for all of mankind!" she said, unsure if magick creatures even cared about the fate of man in the slightest. Pausing for a breath, she realized that what she was saying wouldn't make sense to anyone and decided to simplify her words. "Oh, wisp! Whatever you are, please, hear me out! I don't know where I am, and I have no hope of getting out of this forest and," Diame heard the tremble in her voice and looked around, and saw no one in the mist around her. "There are terrible men after me, and they mean to capture and enslave me! I have done nothing wrong! Just, if you could help me, just show me the fastest way out of the forest, I swear I will tell only God and forget all about you! Please, wisp..." She uttered and stared at the gleam of light shining though the base of the tree's roots. It quivered not at all, and held still. 
A shout of rage echoed, far off in the distance and Diame's stomach began to sink to her feet. She had to run soon and it seemed this time spent was all for naught. "I beg you! Please!" She said on the verge of tears, and louder than she had intended. Hoping that someone was there, weighing her words, she decided to calmly hold the silence for a moment. 
She saw the wisp of light move back up though the trunk of the tree, and Diame's heart nearly leapt to her throat when a small creature emerged from the tiny knothole. She beheld with wonder a small person, glowing purple, flying by mothwings that were spotted with several pairs of blue owls' eyes. "You there! Lower your voice! You'll rouse everyone into a snaff!" A strange voice said quite firmly in a high pitched cadance, hovering above the small hole in the tree.
"By the Saints!" Diame's eyes bulged nearly out of her head, and she dropped her staff she knelt against the warped roots. "A-a faery?" She blinked in near disbelief, but with enough strange goins on she trusted what she saw right out. "Pray, help me find my way, and I'll be off. I won't cause any trouble and keep this place a secret, I swear it." She clasped her hands together, "Please, I beg of you." 
"So, heres the thing," the fairy said as he landed on the edge of the knothole. "I really must go and shouldn't even be talking to you. But evidently, I led you here! Oh, grummlies!" The purple glow around the small fairy disappeared, a young man about the size of a palm stood there at eye level with Diame. "I daresay I will have my wings pluck'd if anyone catches me here with you, girl." He had his arms folded, and his expression was not friendly. Yet the cautious creature seemed to await hearing her out, eyeing her carefully.
 "Please, just show me the way out. I mean to leave here as fast as possible and trouble you no further." Diame begged the faery, her voice near exasperation, yet the creature seemed to have nothing but scorn for her. He seems quite standoffish, by all his right. I must show him I mean no harm. "I know mankind has done frightening things that must have scared magickal creatures into hiding, but I have sought out on a mission to prevent a great amount of suffering up on the world. I hope you can trust me and see I am not someone with any ill intentions. Whats is your name, friend? Rest assured I mean to forget it as soon as I leave." She smiled, trying to break the faery's icy demeanor.
The faery fluttred his purple wings, making a strange, almost hypnotizing motion. He shrugged with a sigh. "Micarus. Friends call me Mica."
Diame blinked. Well that was easy. "Well then, Mica, nice to meet you."
"Nay, it is not. As we are not friends, I need your guarantee you will leave immediately, never return, and most importantly, never tell anyone of this place." His wings continued to flutter and flit in a nervous fright.
Nodding acquisingly, Diame continued on. "I am headed to Ijia, if you could just point me in the right direction, oh! Or even better," she opened her bag and produced her map. "If you could but mark where I am-"
"Mark where the great tree is? Are you persnickt?! Show it off or sell it, you would!" He snapped at her, accusingly.
        She calmly took a breath and assured him, "I will show no one your home, and I would surely find my way out, and never trouble you again."
        With a long pause followed by a heavy sigh, Micarus nodded to the human, and outstretched his hand to her held out map. As he eyed it carefully, two glints of light flickered out from his fingertips, and crossed her map as if he burned the scribble by sunlight. "There." The faery said, and then he pointed off as if to motion past the tree. "Travel North-East just beyond this area and a path should clear up soon. It should take you straight out of the forest. You werent too far off, but a forest can trap people if they get lost. Now, off with you." The faery was once again covered in a violet glow, and hovered in the air.
        "Thank you! Eyes watch over you, faery!" She said to the glow of light, still in near disbelief that she just recieved aid from a magick creature. "Truly, God must have willed me to find your help. I can't thank you enough." She folded up her map into her bag and shouldered it as she leant on her staff. "I shall make haste. Thank you again." She bowed and went to turn.
"I must say," Micarus said, "You are quite unlike other humans. You do have a powerful pull of the aether around you. Do stay safe, and as you keep this secret, you do your kind justice. Oushka-loo, oushka-lay. Farewell, Lady Diame." He seemed to bow through his glow, and with that, the ball of light flew back into the great tree and the high priestess watched as it disappeared deep into the ground.
What peculiar creatures... Diame mused to herself, and with a quick glace at her map, she hurried off in the direction she was pointed in. 


























                IV.4 Fate of a Wanderer


LEAPING OVER ROOTS in bounds across the forest floor, Diame kept a steady pace in the direction where she was told to go by a faery. Something she was still awestruck about, yet had no time to contemplate it. She was mindfully keeping her North-East bearing by paying attention to the direction of the sun, which was now past its zenith and now came from the West. She kept her pace in a ferver, the High Priestess of Water holding her faith as her only guide that she would find her way out.
Emerging through a thicket of swaying treebranches, she stumbled out in the open on a well worn road, the first she had seen since she had ran away from her would-be friend Shul and Igor's gang of kidnappers. Diame was taken aback, and her blue eyes widened as she strained to look down the fog. She got her bearings and began down the road ahead of her, and as long as she didn't see anyone, she was sure she would soon be out of the forest. She saw this road on her map and was certain that she had just stumbled out of the wild near the end of it, and she would then cross the open seaside fields to make it to Ijia at long last.
I do hope I know where I am going. Diame thought to herself, "Eyes watch over me, and see that I arrive in Ijia swiftly and safely." She uttered the small prayer as she kept steadily down the road. She thought of her duties in Teva, how foolish it would be if she was truly lost and never seen again, or was kidnapped and no one knew she was even gone. She left so secretively, no one could even begin to know where to start looking for her. She let that worry assure her resolve to make it to Ijia safely and kept steadily down the forest path. She had such an important message from God to deliver, and she thought of her promise to Sindha that she would return, and all her help from Eljuk and everyone in Teva. 
Diame continued down her path although she was unable to see it with the density of the fog and the many bends in the road. She could sense in the near distance the fog would disperse, and father still in the distance roared the ocean. Only she could hear the voice of the sea from such a far off distance, surrounded by the sounds of the forest. Just a little farther ahead, Ijia should be near. I'm certain of it! Diame hastened her steps, drawn by the excitement of having not seen the grandness of the royal castle in such a long time.
Drawn to the feel of the ocean, she knew she was headed in the ride way, nearing the boundries of the forest. Diame couldnt help herself and upped her steady pace into a run she hoped she could keep up. She was tired, but she was sure to arrive at the great cathedral with her message at the ready.
Nothing else mattered to her and the priestess ran, the bends in the road turned and then something collided with her stomach, and she was knocked to the ground. Her vision was blurred and she gasped for breath.
"Ugh!" she groaned, and looking around her, she saw a huge, hulking man, who had hit her with some sort of wooden club. He stood tall over her, laughing scornfully down at the woman he had just bludgeoned.
The brooding brute with filth ridden over his gnarled face grabbed Diame by her robes, and pulled her up off her feet. "Yeh wastin' all our valuable time!" He yelled in her face through mangled green teeth as he held her fast, and started to walk off with her back into the forest.
"Naaay!" Diame screamed, and struggled against his  pull. He grabbed his arm around her, and held hard with all his might that he would crush her if he wished.
"Stop strugglin'!" He shouted as he carried her off, then snarled at her contemptuously. "I 'ad to use all me wits, and I guessed you'd come around 'ere soon'r or later!" He then began to laugh wickedly, "Hehe, but guess who here cought the prize, eh! Lord Igor will compensate me well for bringing you back. Better stop strugglin', or I can't gurantee his goods will be undamaged. Hahah!" He chuckled with nothing but hatred.
With her heart racing, she felt herself being pulled away from the sea, and her ribs felt as though they would break from his grip. Nay, I can't let it end like this! I will fight! She pushed against his grip to no avail, and then screamed as loud as she could, and turned up to him and shrieked in his ears as loud as she could. He slapped her with his free hand, and threw her to the ground against the hard packed earth and stone. The shock threw her off balance, and she was on the ground on her hands and knees. She turned up to him as she struggled to get back on her feet, but he stood over her, and leant down to grab her. "Naay! Let. Me. Go!!!" Diame screamed louder, and again with all her might.
He kept laughing at her, "Aye, scream lass! Let them know right where I 'ave you! Gahaha!" And grabbed her by her robes.
Willing all her might, Diame kicked him in his stones as hard as she could, and slipped out from her blue robes he had his grip on. Down to her ceremonial gown, she stumbled as she made as much distance from the thug as she could, and ran as fast as she could. 
With a loud wheeze, the man fell to his knees. "You bitch!" the man yelled, and began to make his way back into his feet. "I'll get you for that! Ugh, in just a few moments! Blimey!" he grunted with pain and anger. 
She was in such shock that Diame's heart nearly beat out of her chest, but as her thoughts raced by, she lead herself only by the instinct to survive, and she ran. Headed towards Ijia with all her might, she hoped that the man was not just behind her. She did not turn her head to find out. But she could hear his grunts of rage in the distance, and he started after her with a furious roar. Eyes watch over me! Just run! Diame prayed as she ran, hoping to be saved from her abysmal predicament.
"I'm going to get you! And break yer legs before I drag you back!" The man shouted, as he ran after her. A loud whistling sound was heard in the distance. He gave a small pause and put his fingers to his mouth and whistled back. 
After a moment, it sounded as though the forest was alive with movement. Diame couldnt help herself and looked over her shounder. Behind the man chasing her, another gnarled thug emerged from the bushes down the road. He started after her as well, and let out a yell "Over here!" to other bandits moving behind flailing foiliage. 
"Just run!" Diame shuddered to herself as she hurried on. She could hear them gaining on her, and she was growing weak and at a loss of breath. There were several voices behind her, all angrily shouting and charging at her, she did not stop. "God, save me!" she prayed as she ran from the hulking man, who was just behind her, with others just behind him. 
He reached out his arm at her, "I have you now!" he kept grabbing at her, trying to grip onto her robes and hair. She could smell the foulness of his breath just up on her, the grunts of rage as he breathed heavily to catch her. She regretted looking back, and saw his grimy hand inches from her face. She worked up the last of her strength to scream a final time, but a whirr in the air and something shiny darted just before her eyes.
A sound as if something struck against a tree echoed and silenced other sounds momentarily, and then the man let out a trembling roar as he fell to the ground in excruciating pain. 
Turning back, Diame saw the man on his knees, holding a severely wounded hand with the other, while a white arrow stuck into a tree with bloodied arrowfeathers. She had no time to think about it and kept on moving, as the other thugs ignored their comrade and were still were in close pursuit of her. 
If she thought the forest was alive before, suddenly it seemed as though every bush and tree bough shook, and there emerged steel-clad knights, each bearing the silver and blue winged crest of Ijia on their armor. "Halt! By the authority of the Paladins of Ijia!" A knight shouted through his helmet.
Diame ran right past the company of knights, and they let her pass, and she looked back between them. The brutes chasing her could barely stop themselves in their tracks in their surprise. One fell right over on his face before the knights, and the other began to run back the way he came. An arrow struck his leg, and he fell over. Other bandits in the distance still ran towards them in the chaos, and then a mixed reaction of them still running in rage or stumbling over eachother to run away. 
"Charge! Disarm and capture!" A knight commanded with a shout that boomed throughout the forest. Instantly the road was flooded with Ijian Paladins, and their armored stomps marched steadily forward at the bandits, at the ready to draw their swords. The knights gave chase to the bandits, and gave shouts of "Halt! Answer for your crimes!" and "Stop in the name of Ijia!" as they charged. 
Coming to a full stop, Diame took a moment to catch her breath and looked back at the commotion. "Oh... my... God..." She panted as she watched the knights topple over the bandits and arrested them one by one. Many fled with the Paladins in pursuit, there was a loud cacaphony of armor rattling and the shouts of ruffian men being beat into submission. The priestess was sure that God had just helped her, but she was too awe struck to offer any praise. Truly, this journey was treacherous... but if I have made it to safety, then perhaps these knights will take me to Ijia. Perhaps thats how this must have been all God's will to end up like this from the start. Diame's breath returned to her, and she stood upright and took her gaze off the knights in pursuit of the bandits, and took in the forest around her. She wondered if there was another knight somewhere that she could talk to, and request aid to travel to Ijia proper. She saw no one but the knights arresting the bandits and chasing them down the road, even farther away from her. She was willing to wait for them to capture her kidnappers, but she felt the urgency to continue her journey.         But it was that moment she realized she was in naught but her white ceremonial dress, and she was bereft of her staff, satchel and robe in the struggle. There they were, strewn back down the road behind her. "Well, I certainly cant leave all my things behind. It should be safe enough with all these knights around. Perhaps one of them could direct me to the swiftest route to Ijia?" She started towards her belongings and felt an intensely sharp pain in her stomach and sides. She hunched and grabbed at them and the pain intensified as her adrenaline dissipated. Ugh, that brute might have cracked a rib when knocked the wind out of me. What vile men they were! I'm glad they are at the mercy of Ijian Knights. She stood upright and took a deep breath against the panges in her sides and stomach. "I'm not the greatest with Healing magicks, but what I can do should suffice." She imagined the Water Temple and the interlocking waterfalls, and there in that image in her mind was a dripping ball of light, like an over flowing spring of incandescene, it filled the waters below as it hovered above the temple. All of the Temple of Water was aglow, and lit up all of Teva. Diame saw herself standing before the temple, and wanted to reach for this power in her mind. She was extremely cautious, however, as she was brimming full of the temple's aether. To conduct such energies that are retained from within, one must take lots of care, she reminded herself a teaching from her late master. One must use a suitable amount of aether for the intent of your spell, using too much may produce an unwanted or harmful result. Especially with spells on one's self, as The Protection of Faith only protects from harm directed from others. 
With caution, Diame grabbed at the energy of the Water Temple. A glint of light protruded from the waterfall entrance, and ourpoured a hovering stream of energy, and she pulled the aether towards herself with slow and careful thoughtfulness. The Priestess trying to get the amount of energy she needed was like trying to pull a tiny trickle from crashing rapids. She felt the healing energies envelope her and she felt its warm light, her bruised ribs healed and she took a deep breath in shock, the pain ceased and she could breathe normally once again. She didn't realize how badly she had been injured up until she had been healed.
"He definitely must have hit me hard, that really hurt." Diame said, letting go of her sides and stomach, and stood upright. "There we are." She said, satisfied with the success of her healing spell. As if releasing a breath of air, Diame let go of the source of water aether within her. Things almost were as normal, yet to her eyes, every infintismal drop of mist floating in the air glowed as a speck of blue light. It somewhat marred her normal vision of the road, yet it took some getting used to, and it wore off with time. She could barely see her bag down the road, yet her staff seemed to swirl the glowing aether around it, even as it lay still on the ground. 
Making her way over to her things, Diame was careful to watch her step as her eyes adjusted to seeing the aether in her vision. It was quite strange viewing the world this way, and it even seemed that the aether was playing tricks on her, a gap in the glowing air about the size of a person was headed straight towards her, yet no one was there. Diame leant forward and blinked, bemused. The next moment she knew, the empty gap in the air was up on her, and her arms were in a firm grip. 
"What is this?!" Diame shouted, "Heeelp!" her scream rang out, then a grip wrapped around her throat, and she grabbed at it, struggling against what she throught was thin air.
Then a face reared out from the air attacking her, Lord Igor wore rage that quivered his brow and nostrils, yet his teeth were a victorious grin. "At last, you're MINE." He roared in her ear and he turned her to face him.
Diame's deep-blue eyes widened with disgust at the sight of the detestable man. As some sort of cloak fell off the young lord, he laughed as it lay to the ground, revealing him fully visible as he held her fast. 
"A cloak to bend the light, it tricks the eye rendering the wearer completely void from sight." He snarled a laugh at her. "I knew you were powerful, which will yield a high price, but I didn't know you'd be such a bloody pain in the arse! Now," he produced some sort of manacles from his pocket, "Put these on! I can't afford you to try any more tricks, witch!" 
With all her might, she struggled against him, and he readied her bindings with a merciless grin in his perfect teeth. I can't let this be the end! I won't! She wrested against his grip, but she indeed was tired from having run and fought off so many others. Her struggle grew weak, and she was flailing, out of breath, still straining to see around her through all the blue light. "Nay! Unhand me this instant!"
The young lord tightened his grip around her, "Hah! And what if I don't!" he mocked her.
A voice spoke with a commanding authority, "Unhand the lady at once, vile scoundrel!" and a lone Paladin fully clad in Ijian armor with a billowing green cape approached them from behind the trees. "I'll not ask again." His hand reached for his swordhilt at his side, he did not yet draw. He seemed to stare down Lord Igor through his helmet, and authority exuded from him as he demanded the criminal to stand down.
Lord Igor sneered at the knight, "Like hell I will! Now, stay back, or I'll snap this pretty one's neck like a twig!"
Diame stopped her struggle, but he held her fast, althought he was deftly daunted by the knight before him. Oh God, please let this knight in armor be my savior! She prayed as she remained held fast by the crazed man. The knight clad in metal was still as stone, and Diame could feel Lord Igor start to shake. The man truly was a coward, however dangerous. She upturned a lip in disgust to him and at how he planned to carry her off in binds all along.
"Let's see, attempted kidnapping would be several years in gaol, but you'd live to see the light of day. Murder, however," The Paladin took a step forward.
"Stay, BACK!" The young lord growled like a beast.
"... would be dealt with more harshly. If you break that girl's neck, I assure you," he took another step forward, and Lord Igor stepped back. "I will see to it you'll regret the day your sorry arse fell out of your mum. You will spend the rest of your days suffering a life of hard labor with severe punishments."
"I am WARNING you!" Lord Igor roared, "It would be wise to NOT test me, knight! I have killed many men as well as women, and you will not trick me!"
The knight took another step forward. "Unhand her now, and try and fight me, you filthy coward!"
"Urgh! Do I have to break her neck to make my point clear to you?!" Igor tightened his grip around Diame's neck, nearly cutting off all her breath, and took several steps back with her. "YOU turn around IF you want her to LIVE. Or if you want her so much, have her as a lifeless CORPSE! Hmmm! Choices! Well I'll make it easy for you if you dont piss off right now you STUPID, SHITE EATI-AHHH" the young lord screamed as a small pidgeon-hawk swooped down from the boughs above and began pecking at his eyes and clawing at his face in a clamor of squawks. With one arm, he kept flinging the bird away from him, and Maji flew back in for another attack repeatedly. "Get off of me! GAHH!" He shrieked in high pitched tones as he still tried to hold on to Diame as he fought off the bird out for blood.
Siezing the opportunity, the knight lunged himself at full speed at them, and grabbed the man by the arm he held Diame in. He yanked his arm free from around her, and tossed the young lord over his shoulder to the ground. The helpful hawk took flight and was gone as fast as he came.
Taking some steps away from the fight, Diame hunched over, coughing and gagging as she tried to regain her breath, and was taken aback as she saw that the young lord had been thrown onto his head, knocking the man out cold.
"I had been tracking him, I thought I had lost him for the longest time. Who would have known the man had donned an invisibility cape! Completely threw me off. My apologies for not stopping the brute sooner." The knight said as he turned upright to Diame from throwing the man. "Are you unharmed?"
Diame nodded her head to him as she stayed bent over to catch her breath.
The knight stood before her and removed his helmet,  there stood a handsomely tough man with emerald green eyes, fierce with fire and determination. Sun colored hair spilled to eitherside of his face, and the rest of his hair was tied to the back in a long ponytail. He held his helmet against his hip with one hand and placed the other over his chest, performing a formal bow to her. "I am Xavier Alexander, Lord General of the Paladins of Ijia. What is your name, mi'lady? And how is it that you've come to be out here, all on your own?" He stared at her with a genuine concern for her well being in his eyes.
It took a moment for Diame to realize she was breathless yet again, but for other reasons. What she did not know was that she was blushing deeply at the dashing knight who had just rescued her. She cought herself just blankly staring into his eyes, nearly forgetting than she didn't even answer his question. "Oh, aye, my name!" Diame chuckled absently. Oh, what do I tell him? If I say I am the Water Temple Priestess Diame, he may just send me right back home. I'd better just keep being Delandra until I have safely carried my message to Ijia. "I am Lady Delandra from, uh, a secluded, wealthy family of nobles. I was on pilgrimage to the Cathedral of the Light when I was harried by those brutes. Thank God and Eyes watch over us that you were here to stop them, Lord General." Then it donned on her, that she was in the middle of nowhere, and one of the most powerful figures in Ijia had just saved her life, and she can idly converse with such a person. Obviously, Holy Evaz'sa is watching over me. Even as I am the most lost and desperate, She has sent Holy Paladins sworn to protect the commonsfolk to my side. Such is the importance of this message I carry that the divine would intervene see to my safe travels. She reminded herself the importance of delivering her message, and how close she came to nearly never seeing the light of day again.
Coming up from the road were a handful of the many Paladins, hustling a march. As they ran around Diame's things in the road, they gathered her robe, staff and satchel as they made their way towards them. Xavier took note of them, and nodded to Diame. "Well then, I shall ensure your safety to Ijia, my Lady Delandra." He smiled at her, seemingly for her sake to assure her doubts. 
"Truly, you would help me the rest of the way to Ijia? I can't thank you enough already!" Diame nearly made doe eyes back at the man, and cought herself again from acting like a lusty foolish girl. It seemed to her as if he was a man who conveyed discipline in every one of his actions. He seemed like the person who never truly was happy, the weight of his responsibilities weighed before every action or emotion allowed to be felt. He had such a presence, she could hardly focus on anything else. She realized she was making doe eyes at him, and she turned away, feeling the heat on her face. Oh my goodness, this man is very dashing. Stop it girl, you are a sister of the cloth on an important mission. And he probably has a wife already. I wonder if he does? Wait, now is not the time for such thoughts, where is your head, girl? The mission! "Oh, haha, sorry, all the excitement seems to be taking its toll on me." She nearly began fanning herself.
"Not at all mi'lady, please take your time to compose yourself. You've been through quite a lot." Xavier said to her with a nod. 
Three of his knights stopped just before them, each one holding one of Diame's things. "I believe these belongings are yours? Here you are mi'lady, once you are ready." One of the armored Paladins said.
"Keen work, men. What of the bandits?" The general asked his knights.
"Sir, we have the lot of them bound and detained. We are questioning them now, mi'lord." another knight responded.
"As I expected, good work. Very well then, prepare my horse. As soon as Lady Delandra is ready, I am personally escorting her to Ijia." Xavier said with a salute, his fist over his heart.
"Aye, sir!" his Paladins replied, and in a hurry they ran up the road in formation to carry out their orders.


















 
















                IV.5 The Road To Ijia


SETTLING HER RED HAIR underneath her blue robe, Diame stood with the Paladin Knights, happy to be reunited with her satchel and staff. In mere minutes, they had walked up the road where the forest began to to up into a wide open glen of tall green grass, swaying in the wind. It was still quite foggy, but she could hear and smell the ocean in the near distance.
 The entire gang of twenty or so men was marched before her, well guarded and in chains and bounds. They sat on the earth and awaited their fate of being locked up in the nearby fortress's prison. Lord Igor remained in a daze, and Paladin medics were seeing to his head injury using healing magicks to bring him coherent enough so he could stand trial. 
Shuddering as she perished the thought of her would have been fate, Diame turned her attentions to Xavier, who was talking to a fellow Paladin holding the reins of a humongous horse, about half the size as the surrounding tall trees. He had big black eyes, hair white as snow, and had a long mane. The horse seemed to be fitted with two saddles, and it was certainly big enough to hold two people. The general beckoned to her and she went to him. 
"Have you ever rode horseback, mi'lady?" Xavier motioned to his steed, and gestured her toward him. "Do not be afraid of this kindred beast, this here is my personal steed, Thundercloud." 
The tall horse whickered as he heard his name, and Diame was weighing her options. Well, I am not going to refuse the offer of one of the generals of Ijia, however, I have never rode on horseback before, however, Delandra has! "Of course, my lord general. All the time in our private courtyards with my sisters!" She laughed a nervously into a strange sound she wish she hadn't made. Don't embellish too much, girl. It's bad enough you must lie, but to the knight general's face after he's been so good to me does pang my conscience. "Ahem." she cleared her throat, "Well, let us not waste another moment. I thank you again for saving me. Truly, you have strengthened my faith in God by coming to my aid, and now you help me once more to take me the rest of my pilgrimage? You are truly a godsend, Lord Xavier."
        A smile cracked up on Xavier's stoney face, "Well mi'lady, if we depart now, we can cross the great fields and arrive in Ijia just before sundown. Shall we?" He motioned Diame to the giant horse, hands ready to help boost her into her saddle.
        "Aye, let us be off. I must needs arrive in Ijia as soon as I can, and being harried by those brutes I am finding myself quite delayed. I thank you for your help once again, my lord." She then stared at his hand, and apparently he wanted her to do something. There are two saddles... but how am I supposed to climb onto this behemoth of a horse? She thought it best to not test the kind knight's patience and just give it a try. How hard could riding a horse be? She took a breath and took a step onto the gauntlet guarding Xavier's hand as he lifted her up. Diame slumped atop the saddle on her stomach, and nearly fell off to the other side, but she quickly sprawled to correct herself into a seating position and her long blue robe draped to the sides of the horse. "Well, that wasn't too difficult." She said to herself as she held tightly onto her saddle's pommel.
        "Send a messenger to Fort Forestglenn, report all that has occured to Lord Rendien." Xavier said with clear command to his awaiting Paladin knights. "Inform him I have returned to Ijia and to be ever watchful for anymore of Lord Igor's lot of kidnappers." 
        His knights resounded, "Aye, sir!" and then ran off in different ways, each seeing to a different detail.
        With a foot in the stirrup, Xavier pulled himself up right onto Thundercloud like he had countless times before. "Are you ready, my Lady Delandra?" He asked as he changed his gauntlets to his riding gloves.
        "Aye, I am, and you have my eternal gratitude for being so generous to take me to Ijia, and for saving me... Just, I can't thank you enough. I desperately need to get to Ijia quickly and your help is more than what I could ask for." Diame responded, getting used to sitting on this humongous beast so far off the ground, and so close to the Lord General.
        "Then, let us be off. Oh, and if you would, wrap your arms around me, and hold on tight." Xavier said with concern in his candor.
        "Oh, of course!" She did as such hesitant at first to wrap her arms around such a dashing man, but she pressed herself against his armor and and was happy he could not see the shade of red her face was. "Ready when you are, my lord." She said in an embarrassed pitch higher than she intended.
        "Very well," Xavier said with a sense of bated patience for the adventure that lie ahead. "Thundercloud is a big beast and will carry us to Ijia swiftly, however, his gallops are strong and will toss us to and fro, so do take care to not let go of me. As you may know, a fall from a horse is not an easy one to recover from, mi'lady."
        Diame caught herslef from blushing a shade redder and reminded herself of her mission. Fool girl, you are offered a ride from one of the most powerful men in Ijia. Just accept the fortune you have and stop acting like a blushing naive lass! She cleared her voice "Aye, I am ready. Take us there as swiftly as you can." She held her hands together tightly around his body armor, and rest her head against his cape.
        "Hold ever fast, and let me know if you need rest." Xavier gripped his reins and gave a firm nudge to the horse's sides, Thundercloud understood and began his trot through the forested area until there were no longer trees lining their path. 
        They traveled into wide bounding fields, slightly marred by the thinning mid-day fog drifting down the steady incline. Xavier once again reminded Diame to hold on tight as he gave Thundercloud another nudge, signaling him to a gallop. Steadily they rose up the encline into the highlands, and Diame could see more of the landscape, and all the scattered farmlands and hamlets in the foreground. There was a hulking mass in the distance, the two great mountains of Ijia, and nestled between them was a castle that neared the height of their peaks. The Great Castle of Ijia was built into the northern mountain, with its three tall towers that stood above all else. The shadow cast from the western mountain enveloped the west tower, and half of the main castle and cities of Ijia beneath it lining the eastern coast. 
        Growing in anticipation, Diame could hardly handle her own excitement. There it is! It is even more grand than I can remember when I was here years ago. I was rushed there and back in closed carriage on official affairs with the Church, and can not say I remember taking in the sights as vividly then as I do now. "It's truly breathtaking." She said outloud in awe.
        Xavier wore a proud grin that Diame could not see. He was proud of his knightly heritage, and honored to have been able to rescue a wandering fair lass and whisk her away to her destination of his home kingdom. She lay against his emerald green cape and seemed to be exhausted from her ordeal, yet she had the strength to endure on. "'Lady Delandra' on a religious pilgrimage..." He mumbled outloud with a vague curiosity, unsure if she heard him as he pressed Thundercloud onwards up through the motes of highland mist. 
        Ijia was far in the distance, but Thundercloud had stamina yet to run laps across continents, and carried his two companions to their destination without any qualms. 








        they continue to the farmlands and then ijia


        On a ship in the seas are tavian and mirnada right now


and time passes, we return to D and X


        
        






                IV.6 Light-Touched Earth


        THE SUN HUNG LOW in the western sky as the High Priestess and General of the Paladins traveled on horseback above the glimmering mists into the highlands. Xavier assured this 'Delandra' time and time again that they would make it to Ijia safely before nightfall. Yet, she seemed nervous about arriving in Ijia, but the way she persisted on arriving hastily conveyed some sort of unwavering determination. He had never seen someone who claimed they were merely on pilgrimage show such staunch resolve. Perhaps her ordeal took a toll over her nerves? He weighed as well so he did not judge her too harshly. They had exhanged a few words, she had questions of what life was like in Ijia, it seemed she hadn't heard too much of the recent siege laid up on Ijia from the Pevalian Empire. He thought that curious, where could she possibly be from where such unsettling news would not have reached her ears? Such a terrible thing had never happened before and how could a great threat go unheard of to this girl, yet she was headed straight to Ijia. His mind grew more and more curious, yet this was not the time to stop and ask questions. The knight general pressed Thundercloud onwards through the bounding countryside, he made a promise to take her to where she needed to be and he would not go back on his word, even though he wished to exchange further words with this mysterious girl. 
        The road had just split into two, marked by blue flags bearing the symbol of Ijia, flying high above the road by tall poles. The commonfolks road had less than the usual day's amount of people traveling it, though many of them stopped to revere the sight of the Lord General as he sped by, bounding down the road with a fair lady by his side. As the mist cleared up ahead, their eyes took in all small hamlets and farmlands that stretched on all the way to the kingdom proper. His heart weighed heavy for the poorest of Ijians, fated to work in the farmlands and never see many days of respite. He believed strongly in his oathes to protect every Ijian, no matter what their social status. That was part of being a selfless Paladin, to always help those in need, and to never draw ones sword needlessly to end conflict. Every day he abided by these laurels and taught his fellow Paladins by example how to be a chivilrous knight of the peace. He felt the weight of his responsibilities, with all knights and citizens alike always looking up to him in reverence. His foremost duty while within the castle walls is to ensure the safety of Queen Senna, to protect as her personal bodyguard. She had her elite guards while he was away, and he knew she would be safe in their care for the days he would have been gone, but he still couldnt help think of her safety. As he headed back to Ijia, he worried if she was alright as he always did when they were apart, but his heart felt lightened that would be back by her side just as fast as he had left. The castle and surrounding city and mountains grew bigger in the distance with every swift gallop of Thundercloud, soon he would fulfill the wishes of Delandra to finish her pilgrimage. Perhaps I'll chance see her again and ask a few more questions. He wondered idly a they bounded across another hill slope.
        "I can see Ijia clearer than ever from here. I am in your debt forever, my lord general." Diame said with a sense of relief as well as excitement. She had held on tight the entire time, and only asked about where they were or how much longer it would be until they arrived in Ijia.
        Xavier grinned that he had helped someone who was in dire need of it, yet he still felt like something was amiss with her story. He wondered what reasons an entire gang of bandits had for chasing after a single maiden, and setting up such an elaborate trap to kidnap her. Is something special about her that does not meet the eye? Or are times of war easily changing people's habits to those of violence? Why? Because of uncertainty of their own safety, do they pack with others to feel strong and take what they want by force? He shook his head, for none should have to ever turn to crime to support themselves. But he knew how fear easily persuades the hearts and minds of people, especially those who lack certainty. He realized he was over thinking things, yet his mind was always heavy, always weighing every thought for every grain of its worth.
        "My Lord General..." Diame said with an icy direness in her voice.
        "Aye, Lady Delanda?" He responded.
         "Well, over there," Diame pointed out at some dark clouds, rising in thick black motes over some of the farmlands just ahead off the road. "Those are not motes of mist... they most certainly are clouds of..." 
        "Of fire!" Xavier exclaimed. "My Lady, please hold on tight. We must go provide aid." 
        "Aye, of course!" She said, holding on even tighter and even had eagerness to help in her voice.
        With that, Xavier gave Thundercloud a firm signal kick, the horse sped forward faster than ever, and they hurried down the road to the source of the smoke. They took the side road off to the farms that lay in flames. There were farm folk running around in a panic with their hands in the air, some standing in the streets staring in shock. People saw their Lord General charging towards them, and began yelling at those who were awe struck in the middle of the road to move out of the way. They heeded and began shouting as well to clear the road, and people saw the knight general was suddenly there to help and moved so he could do so.
        Xavier and Diame were before the source of the billowing smoke, the farmers' humble wood and straw huts were set ablaze, bright orange and red flames bursting out the sides of the humble walls. The heat was hot against their faces, Thundercloud whinneyed a low bellow, he too could sense the danger. Xavier hopped off his horse and helped Diame off, then tied his reins to a fence of a farm that was not aflame. 
        Small crowds of scattered countryfolk approached them, and they asked the Paladin General for help in panicked shouts. All different families, all with grim fear on their faces. A man of younger years whose face was bloodied and bruised rushed right up to Xavier and spoke in a panic. "My lord! Please, help us!" he said in sharp, heaving breaths. In the firelight, his clothes were torn and bloodied, clearly he had been severely beaten. "Bandits, my lord! They've barred the doors with my family inside, and set fire to our homes for not paying them a tithe!" He collapsed to his hands and knees, "We are poor and couldn't pay what they offered, we begged them for mercy, but still, they..." he trailed off as he looked at the small wood and straw house going up in flame and smoke. A  portion of the roof caved in, and a chorus of screams was heard from within. Fear struck the man's face and he hands together as he pleaded to Xavier, "Please, Lord General can you save my family?!"
        Before he finished his sentance, Xavier ran off towards the house. He could hear Delandra calling something out to him, but his sights were set on the house set aflame. People in a line at a nearby well were pulling up pails of water, "Pardon me, miss." He said to a lady as he took her bucket of water she willingly gave, and doused himself and his green cloak in water. He ran off up to the house in flames, and indeed the front door and windows were boarded up, he hoped there still was time to save the family within. He grabbed at the wooden planks barring his way, and pulled at them with all his might. The nails pulled out of the walls and the wood gave way and broke, he threw the board aside and grabbed at the next board. "Just a couple more!" he told himself. The heat of the flames above was hot against his face, but Xavier continued breaking off the wooden planks, and grabbed at the doorhandle. He could feel the heat through his gauntlets, but his hand was protected well enough as he turned it and pushed at the door. It would not budge, and he tried to slam his body against the door. His armor clashed with the wood, to no avail. The terrified screams from within resounded again amidst the crackling of the flames. "Damn it!" he grunted as frustration overtook him, and he began to punch and kick at the door, and the weakened hinges stated to beak apart. The door partially fell back against some fallen burning debris, and he started to push it aside as he worked his way inside. The thick smoke poured out and up, Xavier ducked down and covered his face with his green cloak.  
        Inside was a fiery hell, the walls of the one large room were streaked with billowing flames, and the family beds and furnature were smouldering with embers. He couldn't see anyone among the flames and fallen rubble, but he knew he heard the family screaming in distress. "Is anyone in here?!" He yelled, fearing the worst. 
        "Aye! Under here!" a voice called out. 
        Xavier followed the voice to a shaking square cut out of the floor boards, some debris had fallen on top and he moved it aside. He pulled up a handle and inside was a young woman with two small children, a boy and a girl. They all had looks of terror changed to hope at the sight of Lord Xavier himself above them at their rescue. Black smoke began to pour into their small basement space, and they began to cough and choke. "We must hurry!" He wrapped an arm and gauntlet in his damp cloak and reached out to them. "Take my arm, and you two grab hold of your mother!"
        The woman grabbed hold of Xavier's arm, and in one motion he pulled the three of them up out of the basement boards and wrapped them in his green cloak. He covered his mouth with his other hand, and turned to the column of sunlight the doorway let in as he found the way back out of the hellfire that surrounded them. The house shook as a portion of the roof caved in, the Paladin braced himself and kept the family covered. The flames grew higher and the heat more intense, the smoke thickened and red light consumed most of the house, it was as if they were inside of an ovenfire being cooked alive. The children began to cry and cough, and the mother held on to them tight. "This way!" Xavier lead them to the front door protected under his cloak, but as they approached the exit, he came to a grim realization that too much debris had fallen in the way. He grit his teeth. Damn it! He looked around for another way out, but all the windows were all boarded. The smoke and heat was building, and more of the roof collapsed behind them. 
        The children screamed and the mother began to shake and weep, "It's going to be alright!" she coughed on the swealtering heat and deadly smoke. "Lord Xavier will save us!"
        The flames circled them, and as they drew closer, the Paladin General began to glow a bright light, and a shimmering wall of light shielded them. The mother and children began to breathe with ease, and he kept them safely nearby him. What else can I do?! He looked for another way out, but indeed all the windows were boarded up, and they were sealed in with the heat of the bright red blaze. He had strength yet to keep up his protective aura of light, but he could only keep them safe only until the house collapsed down on their heads... 


        GASPING AND WIDE-EYED, Diame could only watch as the General of the Paladins ran towards the house being engulfed in roaring flames. "Lord Xavier, it's too dangerous!" She called out to him, but off he went already to save the family. She marveled at that man's bravery, at the moments notice, he selflessly went to go go help, doused himself in water and started breaking apart at the boarded front door of the flamming building. Diame grabbed at her red hair, deathly afeared for Xavier's life, as well as for those he set off to go save. "Oh my God! Eyes watch over us!" She called out as she watched him enter the home. She looked at the farmfolk all around her, some were petrified and standing still, many openly screaming in terror. Small chickens were running loose all around her feet, and large farm animals as well, cowering cows mooed and mules with still attached farm equipment adding their sounds to the cacaphony of fear as well. 
        A squall of wind caught the embers of house houses set a flame, and several more houses roofs began to flare up in random patches as well. All the farm folk began to shout orders and run away, many stayed in the line of those gathering water pails. They scattered around, frantically throwing what water they had on the newly flared up rooftops, trying to stop the spread. 
        "What else can we do!?" Diame asked a farmer nearby her. 
        The older man shook from hes petrified shock momentarily and uttered, "At this point, young lady, pray for rain!" The both of them gaped in shock as part of the house caved in and the flames rose higher. "Oh, nay! Lord Xavier!" The man shouted, and then ran away in fear with several others.
        Waching the man flee while Xavier was laying down his life while they spoke, she clenched her fist and her grip around her staff. "I can not..." Diame uttered, approaching the flamming houses. "stand around here, and just hope and pray!" She ran towards the well, and she knew she could help somehow. Some farmers had abandoned the well, but many remained close to the flames, trying to wench up bucket after bucket even if their attempts to stop the flames were in vain. She gazed down into the darkness of the well, and she reached out with her mind to feel how deep down the water filled. It ran deep, and they would have to toss the buckets deep and wench their arm off with all the effort per a single pail. Diame resolved to help, and she didn't care anymore if people knew who she was. The High Priestess of Water held a hand and her staff over the well, she took a deep breath trying to sense the source of water. She could see a bright blue swell of aether far beneath her feet, the spring of the regions' well water which ran deep within the earth, which spreads fresh water throughout the region.
        Diame knew where there was the vast source of water, and she tried to physically command it, to grab it with her mind. She reached out at it several times, it was like feeling the water trickle through her fingers, and having no control over it. "Water! Come forth and quench these flames!" She shouted. The water remained still. "But, you must obey me!" She willed forth all the aether within her, in her mind she saw the Water Temple clearly as if it were right before her. Its magnificent waterfalls were rapids of water, aglow in bright white light from a incandescent sphere up above. This power, I need all that I can use, and I need it now! She grabbed at the temples power, and she could see light shooting down deep into the temple lake, reflecting aquamarine blue light back above, giving rise to glowing white motes of mist, climbing high above the waters surface. "I need this power, I've never used so much at once, but now more than ever I must learn how!" She shouted and raised her arms as she stood before the waters surface. All the light around her grew, enveloping all of Teva as well as the mountainsides in the valley, the mist around the Water Temple thickened with all the aether. It flew towards her and englufed her, and she felt the light engulf her in an icy warmth, and she felt a lifting euphoria as her consciousness became one with the bright aether. She felt herself flying forward from the ceremonial circle, and dove deep down into the waters surface, and became one with the water as well. She was a gushing river beneath the earths surface, and coarsed down the mountains and throughout the land. She felt herself become a stream flowing through a forest, and then she was a waterfall, powering down relentlessly onto white rapids. She could sense the aether flying towards her off from somewhere, but as she was water and light being pulled onward, she could do nothing about feeling something coming at her. She traveled down underground once more, and she continued onwards towards where she could feel herself standing up above. 
        "Hey, lady! Either grab a bucket, or move out of the way!" Some man's voice railed from behind her, to which she could pay no heed.
        The ground trembled beneath Diame's feet as she stood before the well in her trance, her arms were lifted and her staff raised high. Then the earth quaked with a violent shake, and a single ray of aqua marine light flew out of the well before her, and flew into her forehead.
        She gasped for air, and aquamarine blue light shone brightly from her wide open eyes. A gigantic geyser of water burst forth from the well, bursting high into the sky in a never ending waves. 
        Witnessing the largest spell she had ever cast, Diame wondered if her abilities were always so great, yet never tapped into. "How did I do that?!" Diame asked herself as she saw the rushing waters part the smoke and reach the skies above, but she had not a moment to lose questioning her own strength. She saw the vast amounts of water she had summoned was flowing far too forcefully from the ground to be of any use, it would collapse a house if it fell on top of it, and all the water from above began to pummel the ground and houses. "Oh, God and all the Saints!" She gasped, then steeled herself. Nay, I will not panic! She raised her arms once more to the gushing water. "This is too much! Cease your flow at once! And disperse into rain!" she shouted. She gasped as the air was taken from her lungs, and once again she felt herself rejoined with the water. 
        Once again she was engulfed in euphoric light, and she ascended into the explosing geyser. The priestess felt herself lifted skyward as the water and felt herself become even warmer towards the brightness of the sun. She felt overwhelming euphoria, to the point of bliss, she could feel these sensations as water, as her soul out of her body. From high above the smoke and flames, she felt herself become one with the clouds above, and they grew dark and heavy as the sky itself drank the well water. A flash of blue lightening streaked across the sky, followed by roaring of thunder. The dark clouds burst forth a mighty storm, and Diame felt herself become a single rain drop falling among countless others, cometing downwards to the smoke and fire below.
        As soon as the first drops of rain hit her face, The High Priestess of Water drew a deep breath of cool air, and she knew she felt herself re-enter her body. She stood before well, which no longer gushed the flowing water, but she looked up and all around her, and she was in the midst of a veritable monsoon of rain. She felt slightly weak, and she leant up against her staff as one of many among the storm. People around her ran towards the houses, making gasps of awe and cheers of praise for the  'miracle of God' taking place right above them. But, it wasn't a miracle... It wasn't a direct act of God herself. It was my own hand, and miracles are not wrought from human hands. She looked around her at the houses that were up in flames, they embered and smoked a short ways into the air, but the danger of the fire had passed, it seemed.
        A bright white light shone through a home that had been lain to nearly all but crumbled, smoldering remains save part of a wall and straw roof that still stood. The farmfolk all ran over to the source of the glow emanating from the ruins of the home. Shouts of "Its Lord Xavier!" and "Hurry, help him!" came from the crowd as they began grabbing at fallen burnt beams and tossing them aside. There, unburied from the moved rubble and debris was Xavier, a sphere of white light surrounding him as he knelt to the ground with the family of three, quivering but safe beneath his cloak. The glow of light vanished and Xavier stood to his feet, the children and young woman still clutched to him as they emerged out from the destroyed house. Men and women openly wailed and wept in the rain at the sight, and helped the four out of the wreckage.         The young man fell to his knees and held his wife and rescued children in his arms as they all bawled openly. "Oh, thank you God! Thank you, Lord Xavier!" Diame could hear the man shouting through his tears of anguish turned relief.
        She wanted to run over to them as well, but she still felt weakened from conducting all that aether through her. Willing such powerful magicks had taken a toll between her body heeding the will of her soul, she figured. As Diame rested against her driftwood staff, she breathed in the damp air and felt her stamina returning to her. The High Priestess stared up above at the storming clouds in the sky, and felt the cool waters gently pelt her face. It was indeed raining harder than she had ever seen before, right when it was needed most. "People will say this was a miracle." She said to herself. But, was it a miracle if it was my doing? She asked herself. I have a duty to predict the weather, yet I just made it rain, which is supposed to be one of many of God's miracles only She can do. Diame pondered. Could this be God's divine will? Did She bring me here, just to be present at this very moment? Just to save that family? She stared at her hands holding her staff, and opened up one before her eyes, studying what power lied within her. Then it was God's water aether, which swells through me in abundance. It is me who carries the will of God, then... Then this rain is indeed a miracle, because God brought me here to do Her will. Which means, She did not wish to do it on her own, but She wished to aid me as I performed Her miracle. Perhaps, is she trying to show me that I am truly an instrument of Her benevolence? Just as she has shown me those foreboding visions I need to share with Bishop Malbourne. She blinked her wide-eyes as she reminded herself of her self-appointed mission. "Oh, His Grace!" She stood upright, and wearily took a few steps. I am relieved that Lord Xavier and that family is alright, and happy to have helped, but I yet carry these important visions. I must travel to Ijia now as swiftly as ever. She walked towards Xavier, a few steps at a time.
        She gave pause to her thoughts as she watched the farmfolk surrounding the Paladin general. They were talking with him seemingly in excitement as well as relief, and some made big flourishing movements of the arms and then gestured right towards Diame. Xavier nodded to them, and checked among the farmfolk if any were seriously injured, and seeing that they were not, gave them a nod and started to walk to Diame, and she continued on to meet him.
        As the High Priestess walked through the rain, she felt the calmness of the water, how it brought peace to chaos. It soothed her and she was overcome with emotion. Part of her wanted to laugh joyously as she bathed in such miraculous rain, another wanted to openly weep from having been through so much peril in a single day. Diame gave a heavy sigh and leant against her staff, weighing what she could possibly say to Xavier as he neared her. Well... I hardly think theres any use in hiding the obvious now... She stood upright, feeling weakness swiftly leave her as the rain continued to fall. I must tell him the truth. Especially so, because I do not think he would hold the lie against me, though. She observed the many humble homes that still stood among them thanks to their efforts. Surely, he would understand why I needed to keep my name and title a secret from everyone. She adjusted her soaked red hair and straightened herself to meet her eyes to his.
        The Paladin General's emerald green eyes looked indeed like gems hard as stone, and the expression he wore on his soot-covered face was grim as steel. Xavier's demeanor nearly startled her, but he did not seem upset with her in the slightest. "They were almost killed..." He said abruptly. "Innocent lives, almost taken over common coin." He shook his head, and turned up at the rain. "More men have turned to cruelty and violence. War is brought up on Ijia. Yet, God will still intervene and protect a small farm village in the middle of the countryside." The water pelting his face began to wash away the soot smudges, and though he wore seriousness, he seemed genuinely wistful as he pondered the mysteries of God's mercy. It was then a din of ringing bells was heard in the not too far off distance, he turned to see large towed carts bearing barrels of water and the seal of Ijia. "Ah, the town fire watch has arrived. Late is better than never, I suppose. Well, they missed the main event but they can atleast tend to the minor injuries sustained." He began towards Thundercloud who stared knowingly at the General, and whinnied at his return. A sort of kindness emerged from Xavier's intense expression as he turned to face her again. "Lady Delandra, shall we be off? Unless this miracle here has renewed your faith and is pilgrimage enough." He said in mirth of good humor as he motioned her to follow him to his horse.
        Diame stared at him in disbelief. She surely thought he knew it was she who helped summoned the rain, and that he would ask her questions of who she truly was. To her surprise, he acted as though they merely stopped off the road to rest, and now they were ready to journey on. He beckoned to her, and she acquised and went towards him and Thundercloud. I guess I do not need to explain myself at all, atleast not for now. He does still intend to take me to Ijia, that is very good. As she made her way towards them, the rain thinned its relentless pelting drops as it petered out. She gave a sigh of relief that her spell was wearing out of aether and the weather would fair out eventually.
        Xavier gave his loyal steed a pat on the neck, then helped Diame onto her saddle, and he mounted his steed as well. Grabbing at the reins, Thundercloud gave a shake of his wet mane to loosen some rain droplets in vain. With a firm signal kick from the general, the beast began a trot out and away from the farmhomes. As the road widened, he began a steady gallop through the wet earth, churning and kicking up mud with each step. Diame held on fast to Xavier as they made their way back to the flag pole lined road, and hurried towards sunlit Ijia in the distance, leaving the darkened sky and stormy clouds behind them. 








                IV.7 The Edge of the World


        BATHED IN THE BRILLIANT LIGHT of the setting sun, Diame held fast against Xavier as they traveled far above the highlands on the overlooking the lush, green fields that lay just before Ijia. Thundercloud had taken them out from under the rain clouds, and galloped onwards through the open roads now that he was freed from the viscous mud. Looking behind her, the High Priestess saw the rain she had summoned had nearly all but ceased, and the dark clouds that remained would dispurse in time. 
        Although the cold did not bother her, Diame was still soaked to the bone, and it would be quite uncomfortable riding like that for much longer. As she held fast onto the Lord General, she was sure that he too was rusting in his armor, yet would never complain a word about it. 
        She held fast onto Xavier as he brought his white stallion to the height of the largest peninsula, and trod his steed near the edge of earth overlooking the lands below them, dotted with large nobles' homes and small hamlets and farmfields. Two sky piercing mountains partially surrounded Ijia's castle and town, one of lighter stone to the north and one of rough hewn dark earth to the west, birthing a less towering mountain range that boardering the lands' western coast. The bright sphere came nigh above the earthy points, and would soon be engulfed by the land. For the last hours of its heavenly incandescense, the golden light of the setting sun painted the open ocean an abundance of color. Sky and sea were aglow in bright vermillion hues, clouds of golden effulgence were touched by streaks of violet, and stretched above the ocean, reflecting its colors in glistening waves as far as the eye could see. In the far distance, the light faded into the faintly seen darkness of the starry night sky boardering the far off eastern horizon.
        Diame had not seen the sea at all in so many years, and with a deep breath, took in the beautiful scenery of the land, sea and sky before her from so high above the land. Awe struck by the wondrous lightscape, she thought there would be no better place to take a brief repose. "May we rest here a moment?" She said, eager to take in the fleeting scenery as long as she could allow herself. 
        Bringing Thundercloud to a halt safely near the edge of the peninsula, Xavier climbed off his horse and helped Diame off onto her feet. She thanked him kindly with a craned nod, and stepped closer to the cliff's edge and felt  the warmth of the  sunlight and gentle winds that stirred her rain-soaked hair and robes. She could see Ijia Castle at last in the near distance, nestled between its two mighty mountains and three tall towers, and surrounded by its walls connecting the mountainfoots, and arched in its center was its gigantic blue gate. Late day shadows wrought from the mighty mountains cast darkness over Ijia and part of her city, yet a radiant white glow surrounded the castle, and its brightness seemed to grow as the daylight waned. 
        Out from its gates started a paved path of white and black squares which lined the royal roads just outside its boundries, leading into a plain well worn earthern trail that winded through the open lush fields of the farmlands and commonwealth. Lined by flagpoles bearing the blue-winged bird of Ijia, the road disappeared from Diame's vision near before her, just over the edge of the cliff, and she hadn't the stomach to look any closer. Just looking down so far below this cliff makes me feel like I'm already falling, being pulled to the earth below. So high above in the highlands, she couldn't decide if she felt like she was a part of the sky itself, or would be swallowed by it. Please steel yourself girl, you live in the mountains and you've never had a fear of heights before, you're not about to start now. Diame took a breath of the fresh air, and bringing herself to a calm, closed her eyes and tried to connect to the aether whirling around her. 
        She felt the coolness of the wind that caressed her skin yet could not chill her, she felt the rays of the sun that brought warmth to her face. The sources of those sensations came from all the energies of nature that flowed around her as she stood high above ground, closer the sky where the aether danced wildly and closer to the sun, the source of all the world's aether. She reached out and grasped at that energy with her mind, and pulled at the energies of light and air, and tried to form those energies into a gentle vortex of warm wind around her. Her blue robes fluttered as they filled with air, and with the aid of magic they went from drenched to dried in just moments. Her ceremonial robe underneath and her shift were still soaked, and she safely assumed Xavier and his horse were as well, so she decided she needed her staff to enhance the of spell she was casting. 
        She made her way over to Thundercloud and pulled off her dried blue robes and bundled them up into her saddle for a moment. As soon as she unfastened her staff of worn driftwood, Diame walked back to where her vortex of wind danced on the cliffside. Xavier seemed to display a sense of curiousity as to what she was doing, but she was concentrating on her spell and would rather show him than explain. She could see the aether of her spell as whirling whisps of light, she couldn't see the flows of Air, but she knew where they were and that they were working with her spell. Raising her staff, she drew the magicked air towards herself, Xavier and Thundercloud. 
        A strong wind warmed by the sunlight engulfed Diame in a breeze that tossed her damp hair and furled her white robes wildly, yet it didn't force her off her balance in the slightest. In the next moment, her clothes were at last no longer soaked to her skin, and her spell of wind carried over to Xavier and his tall steed. It was clear Xavier knew what was happening as he didn't flinch in the slightest as the wind spell enveloped him as well, tossing his gilt locks and Thundercloud's mane. In moments they were no longer soaked from the heavy rain, the enormous white steed even let out a small yet joyous whinnie as it gazed its dark, big eyes knowingly at the High Priestess.
        There, much better. Diame gave a flourish of her driftwood staff, and the spell dispursed and was done. She was unaware of her proud smirk while she straightened her red hair and white skirts, gazing at Ijia castle growing brighter as the day waned. At least I will arrive before his holiness as though I just bathed and not as wet as a fish. She joked to herself with a chuckle. 
        A terrible roar from the ocean tore through the air and pierced her ears, she turned to see a colossal dark shadow rising from the waters. Taller than any mountain and bigger than any landmass, its black horns skewered the heavens as its wings tore apart the clouds. A set of eyes wrought from candescent black fire stared at her from the colossal shadow looming over the world, it glared down right at her with a fixated gaze that exerted pure, unrelenting hatred. 
        "What is happening?!" She shouted, blinking her unbelieving eyes.
        The monster bellowing a breath of fire, and in moments the dark red flames coalesced into a gigantic glowing orb, growing by the moment as it hurled down towards her from the torn skies above. "Nay!" She screamed with all her might as the fire neared her and the lands before Ijia. "Naaaaaaay!" Her voice was deafening as Ijia castle and its city were demolished in molten flame before her eyes, then all around her was alight in bright incandescent fire, followed by pitch darkness.


        There was a tightness around her chest, and she longed to draw breath, but something held Diame and called out to her. "Delandra!" the voice said, but she didn't recognize the name and there was darkness still. "Delandra! Lady Delandra! You must wake!" The voice strained to say. Her eyes opened to her looking down and seeing naught but air beneath her feet, dangling over the side of the cliff. She gasped what air she could and saw an armored arm wrapped around her, Xavier holding her very tightly. She turned her head and saw he was leaning off the cliff with one foot still touching earth, his other arm wrapped around Thundercloud's reins, and the giant horse shrieked and whinnied as it pulled back with them in tow.
        Gasping what air she could, Diame stopped struggling and came to the grim realization of her dangling in peril. As Xavier held her tight, the mighty horse pulled back another tug and brought the two safely back on to the cliffside. Xavier still held her fast as they caught their breath, and he leant up against Thundercloud as they walked a few paces safer distance away from the cliffside. He released her and she meant to stand on her own two feet but her legs gave way like melting jelly and she leant wholly on her staff. Her heart nearly beat out of her chest which heaved as she breathed heavily. What, what just happened?! Her eyes widened at the sight of Ijia castle, majestic and perfectly fine in the distance. There was no fire, and no horror on the horizon. "What in divine Evaz'Sa's name did I just bear witness to...?" She breathed the words in confusion, and a fair amount of anger at herself. What I just saw... she gasped at the realization. "Another vision?!" It took everything in her to stand as she leant against her staff, and yet she collapsed onto her hands and knees with exhaust, her driftwood staff dropping to her side.
        "Are you alright?!" Xavier was by herside in a moment and helped her sit upright. "My lady, you are exhausted." The emphasis he put on it seemed as though he had seen many knights under his care over exert themselves to the point of falling over and collapsing. "I could fetch you my flask? Or perhaps you must needs healing?" In the next instant, his hand was aglow in an irridescent halo, and he held an orb of light above her. 
        Glimmers of the light beaded over her face and chest, and the glow entered her body. Diame found her breath returned to her in an instant, and felt refreshed as though she were freshly awoken from a nap. She put her hand ontop his with kind gratitude, but nonetheless shied his healing magic aside. "Thank you, I am fine now." Her attentions were turned once more to Ijia in the distance, and with whatever it was she just saw, The High Priestess of Water reminded herself of the importance of her mission. Her hands were still shaking at the very thought of how she nearly fell to her certain demise and she tried to put what just happened out of her mind. "I do think it would be best if we continued on our way to Ijia. I wish to complete my pilgrimage and become closer with God, but I do not intend on meeting her anytime soon." She said as she rose to her feet leant against her staff with strength of a second wind from Xavier's healing and her restored resolve. 
        "Very well, Lady Delandra." Giving her a wry smile, Xavier helped her back into the double saddle atop Thundercloud, then climbed atop the mighty steed as well. "Hold fast, we near Ijia." He said as he gave Thundercloud a signal kick, and lead him towards the descending sloped path down the mountainside.
        Holding tightly onto Xavier, Diame felt uneasy still at the ordeals she had faced. Surviving being chased by Lord Igor and his gang of thugs was one thing, nearly meeting her end from her own carelessness was another. She shuddered at the thought as she held Xavier even tighter. He had just saved her, twice, and as Thundercloud steadiy descended the uneven, rocky mountainsides as if it were smooth ground, the Lord General was still helping her on her way. She felt as if he were a true hero, sent from above just in time for her moment of need. With what violent visions she had seen in her mind and withall that had happened to her, it was clear to her that she was under some sort of divine guidance. She felt refreshed from his spell of healing, and had the strength to hold onto him ever fast as they descended into the lowlands.
        

                        x. The Arrival
        
        AT A SWIFT GALLOP, the mighty steed Thundercloud came down from the mountains, safely carrying Diame and Xavier onto the flat lowlands. Straight away, they were on the start of the Royal Road lined with flagpoles bearing the blue winged bird of Ijia. It lead down the wide open fields surrounded by the alpenglow of the easten mountains and the wide open western sea's sunset skies. They made haste down the left side of the road reserved for official use, the scattered countryfolk on their daily route on the right side stopped in awe of the gallant knight on his galloping horse as Diame held fast as they flew by. 
        Keeping a steady grip, Diame held her arms tightly around Xavier. He seemed to know he had restored her strength enough that she could even hold onto him, as he was riding his steed nearly as fast as he could go. I think he must mean to keep his word and have us reach Ijia before sundown. The General must think I need rest, and he isn't wrong... She was comforted by the thought, yet she had no time for rest on her arrival. She thought of what she could possibly say to Bishop Malbourne to explain why she had broken an oath, being away from Teva in the first place, and then she had to break yet another oath by breaking secrecy and telling him what she had seen in her visions. My swevens are sacred and divine, yet what I have witnessed is anything but. I will explain that I just simply could not hold on to what I have seen without asking His Holiness if he did not agree that these horrors portend ill omens. He will understand the risks I took to convey this, and yet I hope he can forgive me. He will if I but ask for forgiveness. She held back a shudder with the assurance she would know for certain soon enough. She could nearly count the remaining poles lining the road to the castle proper as Xavier's horse bounded up the winding coastal road. 
        They passed by many small villages with people keeping the roads clear, and watchtowers lined with armed guards, yet none harried them as they sped by. The magnificent castle of Ijia with its three towers grew ever nearer in the distance, and lit up even brighter in a white glow as the sun continued to set behind the mountains. "Truly breathtaking..." Diame whispered to herself as she looked up on Ijia, now looming above her. She was in awe of the three tall towers, one bright white even in the approaching night, one pitch black that still glowed even though the light seemed not to touch it. The middle was gray, a balance of the two. It was surrounded by gigantic stone walls strewn with massive banners of the dark and light blue bird of Ijia. In its center were a pair of gigantic blue gates that also bore the symbol of Ijia with one wing on each gate, and each one shone brightly in the light of the setting sun. Before them was a grand pathway of marble black and white squares that lined the outside walls, and began a route that lead to the Royal Road. They continued past the castle, and down the flag lined road which lead to the coastal city built between the eastern walls and the sea.
        At a close distance, The Royal City of Ijia could be seen in all its splendor. It had multiple tiers of square roofed buildings and homes, the ones being the largest near the top, and then smaller ones as the large slope that swept from the castle to the sea. Every rooftop that was touched by the sun was painted golden, and glistened by the shining sea. Xavier brought Thundercloud down to a trot, and motioned towards the guards at the walls of the small city gates. They stayed open as they passed them by, and the rough dirt of the road became well laid cobblestone streets of the common markets. There was a fair amount of merchants with horse and cart moving through the streets, as well as the residents which were families on their well to do way. Probably what would have been the end of a bustling day in the Ijian markets. Many inns with signs in bright colors lined the road to welcome weary travelers, and hawkers shouted to sell their wares, from trinkets and jewelry to people selling fish on skewers cooking over open flames. 
        Xavier chose one of the wide bustling streets that ascended up through the town, and lead his horse between the crowds and tall cubic buildings. Many people recognized him with surprised gasps and exclaims of "It's the Lord General!" and "The General! He's returned!" as he passed them by, nodding and raising his hand to them in a a greeting salutation.
        The path opened up along the incline of a hill that gradually steepened. At the end of the path was a magnificent cathedral made of tall, colored glass windows dipicting fanciful scenes of God's acts of miracles. The side walls were made entirely of stained glass formed into archways separated by gigantic stone pillars into three tiers. The front had similar colored glass walls, with many cut in a circular pattern, with waves and triangles that made them look like radiant suns as they were glowing in sunlight. They bore the faces of all the saints, with Evaz'Sa glowing blue in the center, and above her was the largest of all the suns, painted golden orange to depict the sun itself, and centered in it was the Eye of Evaz'Sa, centering the radiant cross surrounded by the seven pointed star. Diame had not seen the cathedral in years, and was whisked there and away so fast she barely got to admire its beauty all that time before. She was awash in how serene and beautiful the sanctuary of God was, that her journey at last had come to its end. To think she had finally made it after all she had been through, and that the Cathedral of the Light looked more beautiful than she could have ever remembered it to be. It moved her to well up more than a few tears.
        Bringing Thundercloud to a full halt, the beast let out a breathy whicker. Xavier climbed off the white horse and then helped Diame down as well. "Is everything alright?" He asked her.
        Wiping away her tears with her robe, she nodded. "Aye, it's just..." Diame stood before the holy shrine of colored glass and light, and high atop the hill she stared out at the twilight settling in from the open sea. "I had no idea that arriving here would ever be so arduous." She turned to the truly virtuous knight who stood before her in armor that reflected the gilt light of the sunset. The leader of the Paladins, a chivilrous man who had swore to a code of honor in the name of God. "You are a truly noble man, Lord General. Thank you for everything." She inclined a steep bow, truly humbled.
        He bowed as well, only to motion her to rise. "Please, Lady Delandra. It was only my duty. I take great pride in knowing I came to your aid when you needed it the most. And since I did, we were able to save the lives of many, and we even bore witness to a miracle." The general's emerald green eyes looked up at the sky like glistening stones, as if recalling the rain. "I do hope your pilgrimage has helped reassure your Faith, I know mine is stronger than ever." He closed his eyes and clasped his hands and uttered a prayer before the cathedral. "Eyes watch over us." He said quietly.
        Diame craned her head down and said a prayer into one hand as she stood with her staff. "Eyes watch over us." As soon as she opened her eyes, she caught a glimpse of something bright. She looked above to see a shooting star, which sped across the twilight sky over the ocean in a candescent white stream, and then disappeared just as quickly as it appeared. She knew she was where she needed to be, and was helped along the way. It is time to see this through, I must go and speak to His Holiness at once. Knowing the strength of her resolve, she turned to the leader of the Paladins, and searched for the words to express her thankfulness a final time. "Now that I am here at last, I can not even begin to show you all my appreciation I have welled inside. Just know you have my eternal gratitude, Lord General." She added a courtsey, the formality was the least she could do to show her immense respesct for the virtuous knight.
        Placing his hand to his heart in a fist, he responded with the royal salute. "Please do not hesitate to ask for help again, it was my honor, Lady Delandra." He said with an intent nod. "And if I may, just 'Xavier' will do." He flashed a smile at her, a handsome, perfect grin across the composed, stoney exterior of his face, yet the general's intense green eyes betrayed with his true emotions. 
        Gazing deeply into those two bright emeralds, Diame saw a beautiful storm of thoughts and feelings whirling within the selfless knight that made her heart beat fast. His eyes nearly glowed with the brightness of conviction, and as she stared into them, she swore she saw the light in his eyes grow brighter. A flash of green light blanketed her vision, and she saw him engulfed in light, a spinning ring of light and fire emblazened him with a brighter than white halo. She blinked at what she was seeing, and in the next moment the intense light around Xavier was gone, and he stood in the sunlight, it seemed he was patiently awaiting her leave. She was so awestruck after witnessing that light he had within him that it took her a moment to realized her mouth was half gaped. She took a deep breath and composed herself as she put the unexpected vision aside from her thoughts with an effort. She returned the nod. "Thank you, Xavier. I only wish I had more to give you but my sincerest appreciation." 
        "Your thanks is but all I need, my Lady Delandra." He said with she same assuring smile. "Should you ever require my assistance in the future, do seek me out. I would be honored to have the opportunity to help someone so pious yet again."
        "Truly?" Her eyes widened, nearly in disbelief of his kindness.
        "I give you my word, Lady Delandra." He said with an assuring deepness to his voice.
        As they stood before the cathedral in the waning sun, Diame was reluctant to leave the company of such a dashing man of the Faith, but she was where she needed to be, and hadn't a moment more to lose. "Eyes watch over you, Lord Xavier." She said as she and took her eyes off him, hefted her satchel, and donned the hood of her blue robe over her volumes of red curls. She turned to the sacred house of glass aglow in the dying fire of the sunsetlight, and marched herself down its garden lined pathway.
                x. The Confessional
        
        TWO GILDED DOORS shone in the sunlight, and seemed to grow taller as she approached them. They were two halves to an ornate divine dipiction of the gates of Heaven, finely crafted in goldwork. Above them was a beautifully carved scene of merciful angels soaring in the sky, some sounding heralding horns, and the rest beckoning to any who approached the sacred golden gates to enter. As she approached them, Diame took a final glance up above at the mural of sky-colored Evaz'Sa, surrouned by all the saints, emboldened in their blazing sun-spheres of glowing glass. 
        The High Priestess of Water couldn't help but stop in her path in the middle of the sacred garden to start praying with the merciful house of God just before her. She knew indeed how anxious she felt, for she was just about to explain everything,  and apologize for why she had broken an oath to even be there for starters. As she clasped her hands together over her staff, she realized she was shaking, and her own nervousness frustrated her. "I have traveled too far to be dissuaded by a mere case of shaken nerves..." She took a deep breath as she stood in the cathedral gardens. The floral scent of roses, lavender and peony filled the air around her. She was reminded of her own garden at home, how its charm always kept her at ease, and she felt her resolve return. "I am home." She told herself. "And for the importantce of the message I bring, I shall be welcomed and forgiven for any sin or transgression by His Holiness." She took a breath of relief as she reassured herself. "I have nothing to fear while within the house of God. I am a High Priestess. The good bishop will heed me." Gathering her thoughts and prayers, she approached the two massive doors of wrought gold, and she reached out to the fine details of Heaven shimmered in the suns light. She placed her hand on one of the gilt handles, they were curved and resembed an elongated pair of angel wings. With a deep breath, she pulled open one of the massive doors, and out poured the sonorous melody of a mighty pipe organ serenely playing within the inner sanctuary. 
        Colorful stained glass dipictions cascaded solid beams of light in consecutive rows, shining down onto the many people within. Most of the pews seemed to be occupied, although there did not seem to be a sermon happening at the moment. The hallways were full of Sisters of the Faith, nuns with their hands held in prayer and solemn faces peeking out of their heads wrapped in white cloth, topped with blue domed hats. Some passed eachother in a fervent haste, with barely enough time for them to give each one a nod and a blessing as they nearly ran by, shaking their heads in disturbance. 
        Diame wondered what could be the matter, but remembered hearing of the recent attacks on Ijia from the folk at the inn and from Lord Xavier. She did recall the massive hole in the wall around Ijia castle as well, and a sense of unease hung in the air. I can only imagine what they have seen and survived through. She emphasised as she gathered her thoughts. However, I must ensure that they do not suffer any further calamities. Now, where is His Holiness? I do not know how much time I even have to pass on the warnings I have seen. Looking past the many sisters of the Faith the aisle, she saw him, standing up on the dais just before a large statue of Evaz'Sa. "His Holiness, the bishop is just before me." She could at last take a breath of relief, having gone through such a perilous journey just to ask an audience with him. She tightened her robes around her head to keep her face covered, unwanting to be recognized by a Sister. The High Priestess of Water did not want to answer any questions of why she was out of her village and violating her oathes. She had come this far with this feeling so deep in her heart that she had to warn the Church of the many violent visions she had seen. 
        Keeping her face covered, Diame shuddered as she walked by the Sisters, noticing the people laying in the pews, many bandaged and bloodied. Only as she grew closer could she hear their groans of pain, the pipe organ playing gently to soothe the sounds of the wounded. The Sisters tended dutifully to them, some applying medicinal salves and others held the irridescent light of healing magic in their hands over them. She felt the heavyness in the air and wished she could do something to help them, but she had to press on to prevent further calamity. 
        Just before her was the dais was a few steps to a circular pedestal of white marble, with a golden seven pointed star and the Eye of Evaz'sa in its center. At the center point was a small ceremonial table with a golden Eye of Evaz'sa on a cross, surrounded by the smoke of burning incense and candles lit on sticks and in glowing glass jars of many colors. Diame gazed upwards in awe at the grand mural made of stained glass that covered nearly the entire wall. It dipicted the glowing golden sun shedding its light down from high above, dipicting the Seven Saints as angelic warriors, all with grand wings and shown in varius robes and armors in a myriad of colors against a blue sky. Climbing to the ceiling just before the shimmering glass was a large statue of Evaz'sa made of finely polished dark violet-blue marble, reflecting the colors of the many lights radiated by the glass. The Sun Goddess stood on one foot, with wings outstretched, engulfed in a flowing robe as if she were flying through the air. Her left arm reached up to hold the sun above her, and her other reached down with an open palm to welcome all. Diame knew the meaning behind this depiction, symbolic of how the sun itself is the light of mercy She blesses up on everyone on Caelutera. 
        Diame visited this cathedral very briefly years ago, but she never forgot how this sight made her feel the connection to God and her people. Just the thought of the artisans who had made this, taken the time to create such a testimony to the blessing of life that Evaz'sa has given everyone. She took in the moment of safety she felt within the walls of glowing glass in this sacred sanctuary. I am within the house of God. She reminded herself. I am near the end of my journey, at long last. She breathed deep of the soothing incense, a refreshing blend of florals and oils simular to the same scents she burned in her sacred chambers reminded her of home. 
        Approaching the dais, Diame ascended the steps of white marble, and crossed the golden sun, her blue robes sweeping behind her as she approached the altar. Motes of sweet smoke danced over the many different colored glass prayer candles. Among them was an unlit deep blue lamp, and taking flame from one candle to it with an incense stick, the blue votive lit brightly. She snuffed the flame and put the smoking stick in with the many others in a holder, and watched the motes rise upwards into the colored light. Holding her hands together, she closed her eyes and took a moment to offer a prayer in silence. I give thanks to You, for giving me the ability to see these visions, and for safely seeing me through to my journey's end. She opened her eyes to the statue of Evaz'sa, watching the incense smoke waft around her and dance in the stained glass light. Eyes watch over me. She gave the divine statue a revered nod.
        She turned from the altar, and as she stood in the center of the dais, Diame turned her gaze to the crowd of sacred sisters. "Now, where could the good bishop be?" She wondered as she searched for the holy man among them. 
        As if to answer the High Priestess' question, she heard  over to her left a small boom of a pair of doors opening and sisters and nuns uttering reverences of 'His Holiness' to themselves in the highest respect. Looking over, a pair of polished rosewood doors worked lavishly with gold shaped like angelwings has burst open, and almost ceremoniously, two nuns held the doors open for a large man in layers of white sacred vestments, worked in gold and inlaid with rubies, garnets and pearl. Wearing a crown-like miter jewel worked in the same fashion, he carried a golden sceptre, topped with a large sphere of red crystal centered inside a cross of Evaz'sa. He stode by them, his free hand he gestured at each one of them, upright with two fingers crossed and his thumb bent. A small benediction, he blessed each sister as they parted the way, and he walked straight towards the dais. 
        Watching him make his way, greeting each sister with his blessing, they felt his reassurance and crossed themselves while whispering 'Eyes watch over us' to return the blessing. As he seemed to glide towards her, the strain to hold back the tears was almost too much, but her eyes did well up nonetheless as she held them back. His Holiness is walking right towards me! Now I have the good fortune to speak with him right away about- 
        She felt as though she were suddenly falling, dizzied and out of breath. Falling to her hands and knees up, her focus on the goldworked marble blurred, and her eyes bulged. Pure darkness entered her sight, all sound was silence. Her thoughts escaped her within a sudden void, yet she felt her own consciousness, trying desperately to reach out around her. She felt something close in to her, a body of intense heat, a soul as cold as ice. Then she saw a face, made of red fire that shed no light in the dark, and two dark spheres for eyes that were neither black nor white. The flesh burnt way, and the grimly burnt skull widened to bellow a roar through flaming teeth. Diame wanted to scream but the air would not fill her lungs. She struggled her body against a cold, unforgiving force as if trapped within ice. A single thought entered her mind, Evaz'sa, save me. The grim skull shrieked as if in pain, and retreated into the darkness. Air refilled her lungs, and she found herself with trembling hands against the dais floor. "What just happened!?" Diame could barely make the words to herself as she tried to shake off the shock. 
        Looking up before her, Bishop Malbourne ascended the final step of the dais, and was staring right at her with his fiery blue eyes, shaped by deep concern. It looked as though he was about to give Diame the blessing of benediction, then realized she was unwell. He hurried over to her side, and knelt onto his crimson red theigh boots, before her, causing a stirr of whispers from among the sisters. "Sister, be you in good health?" He spoke gently yet in a volume that all could hear him, and extended his white gloved hand to her to help Diame to her feet. 
        "A-aye." Diame said barely able to work her breath, but leant on her staff and with his hand, she rose to stand on her own. She stood at nearly equal height to the man, who was about half a head taller than she. At closer view, he was a rather stout man, and the sacred vestments stretched around his body. Nonetheless, he was highly revered and had dropped to his knee to help her in front of his flock, a small wonder every sister was a chatter with concern. He smiled at her, however he looked at her as intensely as ever, with those eyes like burning ice. "Your Holiness, I offer my humble thanks, but I must speak with you..." She saw a flicker in his eyes, as if the intensity of his stare grew with every word she said. "... 'tis quite urgent." she finished, hastily cut off by the holy man's near leer.
        "But, of course." Bishop Malbourne said in his candor, loud enough to be heard by his flock. "Merciful Evaz'Sa opens her doors to all, and the Church gives its help to all who seek it." He announced to all as he spoke over the curious whispers of the sisters. "You must be tired from your travels, dear child. Are you here on pilgrimage?" he put his hand at her back with some agitated force, and then motioned toward the decorated doors with his gilt scepter. "You must have many questions, child. Let us talk over some freshly brewed rose tea and mudberry scones."  
        They walked through the crowd of parting sisters, and once again the tall gilt doors to his chambers were opened for him, respectful bows and blessings included. The large doors to his inner sanctum swung open fully, revealing a room of more metal and goldworked objects that she had seen in her entire life. Against the back of the room was a smaller statue of Evaz'sa made of gleaming gold and behind it were purple curtrains that lined the marble walls. An altar table held a marble statue of the Eye of Evaz'sa, the crossed seven pointed star glimmered against two lit gilt candles on golden sticks to its sides.
        Diame was quickly ushered into the room by the bishop and the huge doors began closing behind them. Beaming in to her right was an open window made of large panels of clear glass that let in the golden glow of the setting sun. Before it was a large, high backed chair, lined with overstuffed purple cushions, next to it was his holiness's desk made of rosewood with its corners worked with gold, topped with scrolls of parchment and little goldworked trinkets in the shapes of crosses and angels. A smaller, simpler cushioned chair faced the decorated desk, and Malbourne motioned towards it as the doors closed behind them with a loud thud.
        "Sit." The Bishop uttered coldly, the mirth of his anger spilling through the temperance in his voice. He strode past her to his seat, "Now." he added impatiently.
        "Oh, a guest seeks your guidance, your grace?" A middle aged man's kindly voice to Diame's took her attention to her left. Wearing a violet robe and a small velvet cap, he arose from a small table, and from it began setting up a cart with a teapot and opened a metal dome covering an arrangement of berry scones. 
        "Leave us, Herschel." The bishop grunted in a way it might as well have been a growl from a wild animal.
        At the word, the bishop's secretary let go of the tea cart
and nearly ran to the double doors, lifting his robes as he kicked them in a haste. He opened a gilt door and slipped out without saying a word as it closed behind him. 
        As the door thudded closed, Diame turned to the bishop who was clearly glaring at her from his desk. She made her way to the small chair and sat before him carefully. I think my unexpected arrival may have very well upset him...










 
























        




         
         
        










         






