        V. Our Silent Paradise


        The Kingdom of Ijia, the smallest of the Three Great Nations but nonetheless a powerful influence on Caelutera. For three generations under the royal rule of the Ijia family, they have prospered. Their army is composed of Paladins, holy and selfless knights who protect and aid the citizens and help their fellow comrades in battle. With the blessing of the church and boon of the gods, they also have magick to heal wounds and chastise their enemies with divine light. But as there is Light, there is always Shadow; the other half of Ijia’s army is the exact opposite: Shadow Knights. They are ferocious, ruthless warriors who know no fear. Trained in brutal battle tactics and arcane magick, they can kill any foe with ease and even bind their soul to add to their own strength. The two opposites united as one creating a truly formidable kingdom.
        The kingdom itself is built high upon the peninsula of the northern coastline of the Western continent. The raised cliffs and the ocean itself are a natural defense. A great mountain is formed up the coastline, with Ijia’s castle built alongside it. The land slants downhill, and Ijia’s castle town is built sloping down to the level flats below. Many houses and ports are built alongside the ocean, mainly to trade with Lux Grande as Pefali became an enemy country after their recent surprise attack on Ijia. 


        Up past a secret trail to a hidden alcove in Ijia’s mountainside, two paramours meet together, enjoying a perfect view overlooking the setting sun. They lay together on the cliff side, his strong arms and cape wrapped around her tightly to keep her warm in the gentle wind. They gazed into the sun setting into the calm ocean, its light painting the clouds and sky a glorious array of soft pink, orange, red and violet. They sat and watched, holding one another silently.
        The Gallant Taurus, he aged twenty-six and The Dauntless Aries, her aged thirty-one. The man had long, light golden hair tied in a ponytail and his long bangs parted in the middle, brushing down his clean shaven face. His eyes were a bright emerald green enamating a sense of duty, compassion and love. He wore casual noble’s clothing made of white cloth and fine leather. The dark green cape was made of soft velvet keeping his love warm as he held her. Lying near them was his unholstered Paladin’s sword. The handle was plated with gold and bore the crest of Ijia. Its steel blade shimmered like polished silver and etched upon it were intricate designs and words of principal. It was concealed in an oak sheath that had been lacquered black and had inscriptions carved in gold. It rested near them in the lush grass.
        The woman lay in his arms, content and relaxed. Her hair was blue and dark as the deep ocean. It was braided down the sides and back of her head, meeting in the middle, forming one large braid that swayed down her back. Her eyes were the color of a bright summer sky, glistening like sunlight reflecting off the sea and full of strength and passion but also wistfulness. She wore a dark violet and blue blouse it was decorated with small gold bangles and she looked quite regal. 
        The sky grew darker as night approached, but for them time stood still. 
        He held her tighter for a moment, then whispered in her ear, “Senna... It’s getting late...”
She shook her head “Not yet, Xavier... Just a little longer, please...” she held herself tighter against his warm body. “It’s been such a long time since we spent any time together like this... I don’t care if we’re here all night... as long as I’m just with you.”
Xavier smiled and kissed her forehead and held her tighter. They stared into the sea as the tip of the sun sank into the waters. “Every day, Senna... Every day is heaven with you. I don’t know how much longer we’ll be able to have time like this, or to even keep our love secret. War is coming...”
Senna placed her fingers over his lips “Shhh..... No such talk... It’s just us now.”
You’re right... I shouldn’t spoil it with such thoughts.” He looked down into her beautiful eyes.
She gave a loving grin back as she stared back, then Xavier leaned down and gave her a sweet kiss on the lips. They smiled back at each other, gazing into one another’s eyes.
Xavier gently caressed down her side and hips, and kissed her again. They opened their eyes and were locked once more, “Senna... I want this moment to never end.”
Senna smiled and laid her head on his chest and caressed his stomach “As I, my love.” She let out a sigh and reality seemed to reawaken. “You were right though... We should go back, it is getting late.”
Xavier nodded and he stood up, extending his hand to help up Senna. They then walked, arm in arm.


        The guards stared off into the darkness under the starry sky. The night was undisturbed at the castle until a figure was seen walking closer in the distance. “Is that them?” A knight mumbled to himself. He took a torch and went through the gates to the advancing figure. “Who goes there?” he shouted.
A woman appeared before him in the firelight “I am Priestess Diame Serigh of Teva, I’ve come to see the Queen on a most important matter.” She said, almost out of breath, putting all of her weight on her walking staff.
        The surprised guard walked towards her, “Are you alright?! Please come right in!” Diame leaned onto him and he helped her inside the gates and to a seat at the guard post. There was a cask of water nearby and he filled a wooden goblet for Diame and then handed it to her. She drank the cold water in a single gulp while it gently stung her parched throat. 
Diame gasped for air for a moment and then caught her breath “Th-thank you... But I must speak with her highness immediately.”
        The guard shook his head “Just a moment, I need to know why you must see the Queen.”
It’s a very important matter... And I think it would be best if only the Queen heard it only for herself.”
“I’m sure it is important, but we must ensure the queen’s safety” said the guard. “I don’t doubt that you are Lady Diame, but still...”
“I understand that, but still... I think that this should remain secret. The fate of Ijia depends on it.” Diame said.
The annoyed guard eyed Diame “There can be no exceptions. You’ve come a long way to have to go all the way back to Teva, so to get an audience with the queen you must first tell me what it is you must talk to her about,” he then opened a drawer in the wood desk and pulled out some parchment, almost black with almost illegible, tiny ink writing, “Then fill out this paperwork which will be submitted to the bureaucracy, then we will notify you within twenty days if they decide to allow you to have an audience with parliament,” Diame glared silently and crossed her arms as the guard continued, “and if then you get a 60/40 majority vote, then you have to fill out and submit these,” he then pulled out a stack of papers from the drawer, all similar to the first one. Diame eyed them as they were piled on top of the single piece of paper, “... and these” he then pulled out another stack and piled them on top of the first stack, “... and just this one more.” The guard got up and opened a cabinet with a large stack of papers in a single bundle.
        A voice was heard outside “Your highness, and Sir General, welcome back!”
        Diame got up out of her seat and bowed graciously to the guard “Thank you sir, but I think I have an easier way.” She then darted towards the door. 
        The guard turned around with the thick parchment stack in his arms, “Hey, wait!”


        The large gates were opened and the queen and her bodyguard walked through them. Diame burst out of the door on the side wall. “Your highness!” She shouted as she quickly walked towards her. The queen turned to face Diame, as well as the bodyguard. 
        The queen paused and recognized her, “... Priestess Diame?” 
        A guard grabbed Diame’s arm just as she reached the queen, “Come on, don’t bother her highness, come fill out your paperwork.” Diame struggled against his hold.
Unhand her immediately.” said the Queen, glaring at the guard. “This is Priestess Diame, and she is to be treated as my guest, is that understood? Also, I would appreciate it that you will do a better assessment on who is genuine and who isn’t and the types that need to be subjected to parliament’s tedious papers”
“A-aye, Queen Senna.” The guard cowed and bowed, then walked back into the guard post.
Senna looked back to Diame, “Please, walk with us.” Diame nodded and the three of them started walking down the torch lit road towards Ijia Castle, the gates closing behind them. “Tell me why you’ve arrived in such a surprise; we would have prepared a room for you if we had known.”
Trust me, I would have never had walked all the way here if it was unnecessary.”
 “You walked all the way here from Teva?!” The bodyguard interrupted. “I beg your pardon, I am Xavier Alexander, General of the Paladins and The Queen’s Knight.”
Diame nodded, “A pleasure. I don’t want to be rude but there is something I must tell you in private, mi’lady.” 
They reached the second pair of gates which opened and led to the courtyard. They entered and began to walk through the flower and fountain lined path illuminated by moon and firelight.
Senna smiled at Diame, “Please, anything you can say in front of me you can say in front of Xavier. Now, what can I help you with?”
        Diame took a deep breath, and began her story, “For a while, I’ve had this nightmare... a vivid image of a gigantic daemon of destruction was in it.”
Ah, I remember that you are well known for your impeccable accuracy in soothsaying.” Diame nodded to Senna “... And you believe this is a premonition?”
Diame nodded again, “Aye, I am quite certain... I meditated once for a vision, and saw the same image, even clearer than in my dream... and I prayed to the Water Goddess. She showed me another vision: a dilapidated tower in a blizzard... And I felt the same fear as I did with the vision of the daemon.”
Senna thought for a moment, “Hmm... what is this tower in a blizzard?”
I think it has something to do with the ruins in the Northlands... that’s all I could think of that it could be.”
“Well, Diame,” The queen said, “You know that I respect you and your abilities very much, and I do believe that your visions will come true. So, I must ask you, what do you think this daemon is? And how the Northlands are connected to it? I know you came here for help, but still, I can’t do anything if I don’t know all the facts.”
They walked through the courtyard to a pair of grand doors which led into the inner castle hallway. 
Diame sighed but held up her courage, “Well... that’s why I came... to find out what this all means. I know the Northlands are involved somehow... so I thought that I could have a ship to take me there...?”
        Senna went quiet and then thought for a moment, “Ah... I see. Well, Diame, I will definitely consider your request. It is asking a lot, but if we have the resources to help you, we will.”
Diame let out a sigh of relief, “Thank you, Your Highness. This is a very important matter and I do hope you decide to help.”
Should we discuss this with Ijia’s Bishop?” asked Senna
“I don’t know, but we could if we must.” said Diame.
“Very well. I will let you know of my decision tomorrow, for tonight please rest in the guest’s quarters. I’m sure that guard has made suitable preparations for you.”
“Thank you, mi’lady.” Diame bowed to the Queen.
Senna looked at a servant and said to her, “Could you please escort my guest to her room?”
At once, your highness.” She responded and curtseyed to her. “Right this way, mi’lady.” The servant started walking towards the guest quarters and Diame followed.
        Xavier and Senna kept walking and went through the castle hallway. They ascended the grand staircase and kept walking through the finely decorated castle. There were suits of armor polished to a shimmer on the sides of their path, priceless paintings and artifacts hung on the walls. The floors were tiled with polished black and white marble in a checkerboard fashion. Flags were hung on the wall, embroidered with the symbol of Ijia: 
A Phoenix with a black left wing burning with blood red fire, and its right wing was white and aflame light-golden. The background was dark blue on one half and light blue on the other, to symbolize it ascending to the sky, and how the sky can be both dark and light. In its right claw, it held a shield that had the Ijian family coat of arms emblazoned, and the left held a black sword.
        They reached the queen’s room. Senna took out a finely decorated gold key and unlocked the gilded doors. Inside, she locked the doors again. Xavier went up to the fireplace and put some logs into the hearth. He held out his hand and a small charge of electricity emanated from his finger tips and struck the wood, sparking a fire. The room was aglow with the orange fire’s light and the crackling firewood gave the room a relaxed, homey ambiance. 
        The firelight revealed the extravagantly and lavishly decorated room of the queen. Finely lacquered cabinets containing luxurious regal clothing and bookshelves filled with every book imaginable in immaculate condition lined the rose-pink walls. The bed was red and pink with rose petals embroidered in the fluffy down sheets. The bedding was soft as clouds and had a white canopy made of silk. The windows overlooking the mountainside and open seas were spotless; it looked as though it were only air.
So, Xavier... what do you think about Diame’s request?” asked Senna as she opened a bottle of red wine from a cabinet.
Xavier grabbed two crystal flutes and sat down at the oak wooded table, “I’m not one for fortune telling, Senna...”
Senna sat down and poured the scarlet wine into the glasses, then put the wine bottle on the table side, “It’s not staring into a crystal ball, you know. She truly does have a gift. Even the church recognizes it.”
Mayhaps... but I’m not quite sure. We need all available knights here anyway, Pefali is sure to strike once more soon.” Xavier then took a small sip of the fragrant wine.
        “True... I also think a few little dreams are not enough to expend on a trip to the Northlands, especially since she’s not even sure if that’s where the place is in her dream... Or if there’s any point going there either way.” She held the glass up to her lips and savored the wine’s bitter sweet bouquet.
“Agreed... Well, we shall tell her tomorrow then?”
“Aye. I do feel bad for her coming all this way for nothing, but we simply can’t go on a wild chase at a time like this.”
Xavier nodded and then raised his glass, “Let’s have a toast, shall we?”
Senna smiled and chuckled, then raised her glass too “Oh, what for?”
This toast is to Priestess Diame. May the gods guide her visions and show her their meaning.” They then moved their flutes closer, almost touching.


        Diame was in her guest room, a servant helped her unpack her satchel and another servant brought her freshly cooked beef stew that she rested on a nearby dresser.
Thank you very much for your help.” said Diame as she began to change her clothes into a comfortable silk robe.
“Oh, no mi’lady, thank you for such kind words.” A servant said as she was placing the sheets on the bed.
Diame went over to her, and then began to help her tuck the sheets into the bed.
Mi’lady, please, you’re exhausted. You don’t have to...” said the servant who was making the bed.
“I know... I’m just not used to this ‘royal treatment’.” said Diame.
“Why don’t you have some of that stew I brought up? The chef made it especially for you.” said the satchel unpacking servant. 
Diame nodded “Very well then. Thank you.” She walked to the stew and picked up the ceramic bowl and started walking to the table in the middle of the room. A sudden shiver ran up her spine and the bowl dropped, the opaline glass fragmented and the stew spilled all over the floor. Diame then fell to her knees helplessly.
Mi’lady! Are you alright?!” a servant rushed over to her and put her hand on Diame’s shoulder.
“A-aye...” said Diame. Then her sight fixated on the broken fragments, and all faded to black instantly. Diame found herself in a dark room with a burning light. There was red wine and glass over the studded table. Two lovers in each other’s blood lay silently on the floor, holding broken glass shards, staring at each other lifelessly, their bodies pierced in countless arrows.
A bright light broke through the bloody scene, and Diame found herself on the floor, covered in soup.
Lady Diame?! Lady Diame!!!” a servant was yelling while shaking her.
        “What was-...” Diame said as the servant helped her to her feet and sat her in a chair. Some of the ceramic bits left minor cuts on her skin and she began to bleed.
        “Sit, please... You’re hurt... Don’t worry, we’ll treat your wounds and clean up the mess.” said a servant as she began to wipe the stew chunks off Diame.
        “W-wait...” said Diame as her eyes widened.
        “What is it?”
        “The Queen... Senna is in danger!”


“This toast is to Priestess Diame. May the gods guide her visions and show her their meaning.” They then moved their flutes closer, almost touching.
        “Your highness! Your highness!!!” shouting was heard outside of the door, being banged on, and the rattle of a turning locked knob was heard.
        “What is it?!” the queen shouted and stood up towards the door.
        “Arbalesters are mounting nigh!” the voice shouted.
        “What?!” Xavier stood up and dashed to the window. Countless glints of arrow heads glistening in moonlight were seen all lined up on the mountainside. They let fly, like a sea of shooting stars, advancing closer to him. “Senna!” Xavier shouted and with lightning like celerity tackled the queen down. As they fell, the window’s glass shards cascaded, and a thousand arrows whisked through their hair and one after another darted into the rose-pink walls with relentless consecutiveness. Infinite fractals reflecting of fire’s effulgence fell felly, filling the furnished flat. The terrible torrent at last terminated, leaving legions of lesions in all but a few of the fine furniture. With the ceased shattering sounds, the sadistic sound of silence was a sort of serenade. Xavier lay over Senna, panting, bathed in glass.
        VI. The Soaring Raven


        The girl, now age seventeen continued her training. Her bare fist cut through the large stone in a single blow. The rock shattered into hot, molten fragments.
Again.” He said, then threw another large stone at her.
Mirnada threw another punch and it cleaved straight through the rock, adding to the molten pile.
Again.” Marshall hurled an even bigger rock at her.
Mirnada threw a punch and hit the rock, but it did not break. She was hit and fell backwards to the ground. Marshall instantly caught the rock just before it crushed her, and tossed it aside, then extended his hand and helped Mirnada up.
Are you alright?” he asked.
“Y-yeah...” she got up and dusted herself off, then covered her bleeding hand with the other “Damn... this bloomin’ hurts...”
“Why did you hesitate?”
Mirnada glared up at Marshall “’Coz it was a flippin’ huge rock, why do you think!?”
Marshall looked down at her for her insolence, “Twenty laps. Go.”
Fehhh....” Mirnada began running around the training area dejectedly.
“Do I hear thirty?”
“No, Master!”
Marshall watched Mirnada as she ran around the training area. “How is your hand doing?”
It hurts like a bitch, Master!”
        “God, you have such horrible eloquence. I guess I should have trained you on how to speak properly as well as unarmed combat in these years you’ve been here.”
        “Yeah, guess you should have.”
        “Another 5 laps.”
        “Grrr...” Mirnada continued her laps. 
Marshall smiled at her and then sighed nostalgically, “I have taught you almost everything I know, Mirnada. Some of these last few skills I’ve shown you are very powerful, some are extremely difficult to use. You must be disciplined and understand the full potential of these techniques before you can learn them.”
Aye, Master.” Mirnada said, nearly out of breath.
Marshall motioned towards Mirnada to come back, “Alright that’s enough laps, come on back here and take a break.”
Mirnada ran back to Marshall, and they both sat on the green grass under the shade of the nearby tree. Marshall stared at the training area; it was four trees in a perfect square, each tied to and holding up a cloth canopy which shaded a small area of the grass field. In the middle, there were four stone pillars, each with some sort of writing on it. 
Let me see your hand.” Marshall held out his own open hand.
Mirnada held out her hand, and put it on Marshall’s. He gently tapped Mirnada’s forehead with his other hand, and then clasped both hands around hers. A warm, violet light glowed from her hand and her pain melted away. The light faded and Marshall opened his hands, revealing Mirnada’s healed wound.
What... did you just do?” Mirnada said as she looked at her hand in awe.
“I used your own magickal energy and channeled it into an aura of healing. This is one of Jorgard’s secret techniques. I now pass it on to you.” 
Mirnada stared at him, confused, “Wait... wot...? How the ‘ell am I supposed to do that just by touchin’ someone’s ‘ead?”
I have shown you how to do it.” Marshall said, “And when the time comes when you absolutely must use it, meditate and concentrate, and you’ll be able to.” He then stood up from under the tree’s shade.
Mirnada sighed and stood up, “Gee, thanks.” She said sarcastically.
I had planned on ending lessons for today, but it seems like you wish to run more laps.”
Mirnada sprang up and then bowed to Marshall, “No, Master!” 
        Marshall smirked at her, “Come on, lets go back home for lunch and your school lessons.”
        They stood in the middle of the lush, green grass field that swayed in the wind and seemed to stretch on endlessly into the vibrant blue sky. Mirnada turned to Marshall and nodded. They quietly began to walk through the tall grass, the sun on their backs, towards a collection of familiar buildings in the far off distance, with the clear blue ocean behind it.


        Freed from the darkness, Tavian traveled down the ages traversed dirt road, long plains of grass on either side of him. He had been walking for hours, away from the horror he had just escaped. He was starved, parched, and exhausted, but like the beat of a drum his legs continued to walk down the road, knowing that it must lead to some sort of village. He began to grow irate at his fatigue, and a deep rage to survive burned within him. The grass surrounding him began to blacken and wither as he stormed past it. 
        He continued walking, the will from his anger keeping him in motion. He saw a town in the distance. A dark smile came upon his lips as he staggered toward the village. He drew upon his last strength and began to quickly sprint to close the distance, leaving a road lined with dead grass in his wake.
        He passed under the sign up above the road leading into town. “Welcome to Jirata” it said. The town was small, though the inhabitants didn’t seem to live poorly. The houses were all made of grey and blue stone and were arranged around in a circle. The surrounded area was all paved in stone with a large fountain in the center. Nearby were docks and the crystal clear open ocean.
Tavian scanned around at the buildings and saw a tavern. He casually walked towards it, suppressing his irritability. The townspeople were going about their business, but they all seemed to be a little on edge as they felt Tavian’s foreboding dark aura draw closer. They all turned an eye nervously as the man in black walked through the town square towards the pub.
        He pushed the creaky wood door open, and instantly the loudness from the boisterous crowd boomed out. At first glance, he could easily tell the kind of patrons this pub was having today. 
Pirates.
        They were far too inebriated and preoccupied in their laughing, drinking, smoking and cussing to pay any mind to the shadow knight. Tavian walked through the pub silently through all the sound, and sat down at the bar. The bar was lit dimly by a few lanterns hanging from the walls. The barmaid was running around panicked, serving and spilling ale to the crude crowd. He listened to the terrible profanity spewed about from the pirate’s mouths as he waited. His mouth watered at the juicy meat rotating on a spit visible in the back room. 
“Lonnie, hurry get the rest of the drinks before they kill us.” the bartender said to the barmaid, nervously.
“Aye, aye, I know!” she said in a hurry into the back room, filling up more glasses.
Finally, the bar tender walked up to Tavian.
The server was relieved to see someone besides a pirate, yet at the same time, fearful of Tavian’s dark demeanor. He was a large, fairly aged man with a bald head and a long grayed beard. “You have some bravery to walk past all these rogues, lad.”
Tavian smirked back, “I’ve dealt with worse riff-raff, they are nothing.”
        The bartender was surprised by his reckless words, “My word, lad. You must be a real brazen one to say things like that while they are right around you.”
Tavian sighed, “The only thing I am right now is hungry.” He pointed to the giant boar roasting in the back room, “I’d like a cut of that.”
“Hah...” the Bartender said, “Very well then, lad.” He dutifully went into the back room.
Tavian watched him as he cut through the pig’s roasted flesh, a stream of fat dribbled out and sizzled in the fire.  He then looked around the room, scanning his surroundings and the unsavory patrons. He disdainfully listened in on the obnoxious chatter.
“Hey, you fuckin’ tart! Where’s our drinks!?” one of the repulsive men shouted at the barmaid.
“C-coming!” Lonnie shouted, running over to them, arms filled with giant glass goblets brimming and spilling with strong spirits. They all grabbed their drinks out of her arms, a pirate reached down her blouse, and groped her breasts “Ah, I guess this endowment would explain why you’re so slow!”
She gasped, covered her face, blushed, and ran off as the pirates all burst out laughing at her in a booming clamor.
“Here’s to our fuckin’ brilliant captain Al!” one of the men shouted. They all cheered and clanked their glasses together, spilling most of their drinks, then gulped down the potent alcohol. They all coughed at the burning in their throats, and then laughed as their faces turned a bright red. 
Tavian assumed that the large, hulking man was their captain. He towered over his crew, had a long black beard and hair, and looked very serious and intimidating, even while laughing. 
        Tavian noticed a scrap of paper on the floor behind the bar counter, it seemed to have been recently torn off the wall. 
“WANTED: Dead or Alive, The head of Captain of the Black Neptune, Alvaris Nepten. Reward 500 Gold Coins, paid by the Government of Pefali.” Then there was a drawn picture in the likeness of the large pirate sitting at the long table.
        “Here you are.” The bar tender said, placing the slab of meat in front of Tavian. “Anything else?” he asked.
        “Some bread, water, and your strongest mead.” Tavian said, then he immediately grabbed the mutton and began ravenously ripping into it with his teeth.
The bartender nodded and got Tavian his other food.
Tavian sank his teeth into the bread, and took a giant bite. He then gulped down half the glass of mead, it burned his throat as it washed down the bread and then he gulped down the glass of water. He then continued consuming his meal in this fashion. 
The bartender watched in astonishment, “Have you not eaten in a moon, lad?”
        Tavian finished eating the meat and bread, then gulped down the last of the mead and water. He leaned back and caught his breath after eating so voraciously.
Quite a show, lad.” The bartender said, jokingly clapping his hands, “Well, that’ll be twelve copper.” He said.
Tavian was quickly reminded of his empty pockets. He let out a relaxed, satisfied sigh, and then looked up to face the bar tender. “ Unfortunately, I don’t have any money on me at the moment.” He said with a straight face.
The bar tender looked angrily at Tavian, “What are you sayin’ lad? That you think you just got a free meal?!”
No,” Tavian said as he shook his head. “Let me ask you something, do you really make a lot of money running a tavern? And do you think these pirates intend on paying for any of this? And if they did, would it be enough to cover the damage they’ve done to the bar anyway?”
        “What are ye getting at, lad?”
Tavian leaned forward, then pointed at the floor behind the counter, “That flyer. The wanted man is over there, correct?”
Sh-sh-shhh!” the bar tender whispered in a panic, “Hush! The instant I saw him come in I tore the flyer down because I didn’t want him to start any trouble with me.”
“Hand it to me.” said Tavian. 
The bar tender picked it up and gave the parchment to Tavian, “What are you gonna do, lad?”
I am not a thief; I shall pay you what I owe for the meal.” Tavian said, then stood up and grabbed the flyer then marched to the table where the behemoth was sitting at. He slammed the wanted flyer down on the table firmly, breaking the boisterous clamor into a deathly silence. He scornfully stared straight at the large captain at the opposite end of the table.
The bar tender’s jaw dropped as he watched the boy’s insane recklessness. “Are you out of your god damned mind?!” He yelled.
        The pirates all glared at Tavian for his interruption, and then saw the wanted poster on the table. “Captain Alvaris Nepten, I’ve come to claim the price on your head.” he said in all sincerity.
The pirates began to laugh at Tavian as he stood unfazed by their jeers.
The flyer says either dead or alive. So come with me quietly, or I will take you forcefully, and I doubt you’ll survive if I do.”
The towering pirate stared coldly at Tavian, “Boy...” the moment he spoke in his deep, frightening voice, the laughs stopped and everything was once again silent. “You’d best leave now, before I rip you limb from limb.”
Tavian drew his dagger from his holster and pointed it at the captain. He gave the pirate captain a long, sinister stare. “Last chance, Alvaris.”
        Seeing the boy had a weapon, though small, the other pirates all drew their swords. The captain stood up and drew his blade as well. “Tear him apart. Slowly.” said Alvaris. The pirates chuckled and they drew closer to the boy.
        Tavian smirked, then scowled at them with a dark, sadistic look in his hazel-red eyes. Like a strike of lightning, he threw the dagger across the table and it found home in Alvaris’s stomach. The captain fell to his knees and howled in pain and anger, the minions all flailed their blades at Tavian in a drunk, cumbersome manner.
        The barmaid screamed and ran into the back room, the bar tender watched helplessly as the violence unfolded.
Tavian ducked and evaded all of their muddled blade strikes, and then jumped up onto the table and ran across it towards Alvaris, knocking over the glasses of booze in the process.
Alvaris had pulled the dirk out of his stomach, threw it aside on the floor, and then got to his feet. He raised his blade and held it at the ready as the shadow knight drew closer. 
        Tavian was now before the behemoth, and he sprung up and kneed Alvaris in the face as the pirate swung and missed Tavian. Alvaris fell back into his seat, which then toppled over backwards. The other pirate minions all started to rush back to Tavian and Alvaris. Tavian jumped onto the floor and then grabbed his dirk, then with a wicked bloodlust he charged towards the fallen captain laying on the ground and maliciously plunged the dagger into Alvaris’s black heart. He screamed as blood plumed from the wound. As the life left his body, his eyes glazed over and his last breath escaped.
        The other pirates were in shock and rage as their leader lay slain. Tavian with his deed done stood up facing the swarm advancing towards him. His eyes were wide and aglow scarlet, his face stretched with a terrible, evil grin. Clenched in his steel hand was his bloodied dagger he pointed at the rogues, daring them to come closer, whilst Alvaris's blood trickled down his blade. 


        Marshall and Mirnada entered through the town’s gates, and saw all the people eyeing the rattling and crashing sounds coming from inside the tavern.
Marshall ran up to one of the townsfolk, “What’s going on?” he asked.
        The man shook his head at Marshall, “I dunno. Some vagrant in dark clothing went into the tavern a while ago and then all of a sudden, this ruckus started.”
        Marshall turned to Mirnada, “Ready to break up a bar fight?” 
        Mirnada sighed, “Oh boy, this’ll be fun.”
They both ran towards the pub and opened the creaky oak door. The lanterns were out, and the inside was black except for the sunlight entering through the door. 
“Why is it so dark in there...? The windows don’t have any curtains...” said Marshall. He and Mirnada stepped inside. It was very quiet, except for the sound of heavy breathing. Then the pungent stench hit them. Marshall saw the windows from the inside; they were darkened with blood. He took another step, their shoes were sticky, and blood was all over the floor. Mirnada began to feel queasy at the sight and smell of the blood, she had never seen so much in her entire life.  Then a light cut through the darkness, a pair of red, glowing eyes opened.
“A daemon!?” Mirnada exclaimed.
Marshall walked closer to the eyes, and closer up he was able to see Tavian’s face, breathing heavily. “No, it’s a boy... at least I think it is.”
Tavian stared back at them and the light in his eyes faded back to his regular red-hazel. He began to breathe more slowly and steadily.
“Boy, did you do this?” asked Marshall.
“I... think so.” replied Tavian.
The bar tender popped his head up over the counter, “Oh, thank god, Marshall! This boy is a monster! Be wary!”
Tavian stood up and sheathed his bloody dagger. He then walked around Marshall towards the door. Marshall kept his eyes on him; he wasn’t going to let him get away with this detestable violence. “Hold it, lad.” He said.
“Oh right, my tab.” Tavian said as he lifted up the severed head of Alvaris and tossed it onto the big table towards the bar tender. “Keep the change.” he said nonchalantly as he walked out the door.
Marshall turned to the people behind the counter, “Are you both alright?”
        The bar tender nodded “Aye, Lonnie ‘n me are fine. Just make sure that boy doesn’t harm anyone else!”
Marshall nodded and then head out the door, Mirnada following. Tavian was quickly walking towards the few ships docked in the harbor, followed by Marshall and Mirnada. The townspeople looked in fear as Tavian calmly walked to the water covered in blood splatter. He could feel himself being looked at, some people turned away, others watched nervously. He glanced over his shoulder to see he was being followed by the town’s guardians. Not feeling threatened, he shrugged and kept walking to the docks. There was a ship that stuck out, the name “Black Neptune” on the side. He started to walk up the ramp leading onto the deck.
So you just genocide an entire tavern then leave?” Marshall said as he and Mirnada walked up to him, but keeping some distance.
Tavian turned around, “They chose their fate, and I have no desire to stay here any longer.”
Mirnada stepped ahead of Marshall, “Wot the ‘ells your problem?! Why did you kill ‘em?!”
They were obviously pirates. There was a bounty on the leader, and after he resisted I had no choice. The rest of the crew joined him in hell soon after.” Tavian then turned towards the ship, “And here’s a ship with no owner, so I’ll be taking it.” He then cocked his head towards them, “Sound fair?”
Mirnada turned to Marshall, “Well, what’ll we do?” she said.
        Marshall thought hard for a moment, then sighed, “... We’ll let him go, that man he killed did indeed have a death-warrant bounty. He’s giving the reward to the bar owner, so they’ll be able to recover from the damage caused... And he’s leaving so he won’t disturb the village anymore. I see no reason to arrest him.” He then shrugged. “... But I must ask you...” he then looked up to Tavian, “Who are you? Why does a boy as young as you have the eyes of a daemon?”
        Tavian looked down at him, “I am Tavian Drakon of Ijia’s Shadow Knights.” his eyes flared red for a moment, “I am simply returning to Ijia.”
        Marshall felt a chill run up his spine, and looked a little worried, “Wait... you’re... General Tavian?!”
Tavian nodded.
        Mirnada looked back and forth at both of them, confused, “... Do you know him or somefin?”
Marshall turned to Mirnada, “He is the leader of half of Ijia’s army.” He then looked back at Tavian, “What are you doing here?”
        Tavian grew impatient, “I’m not wasting anymore time with you. Goodbye.” He then continued walking up the ramp and went onto the ship. He then began to prepare the ship for departure.
        Marshall, seeing that it was pointless to bother the standoffish boy further, turned away and started walking towards his house.
        Mirnada, confused, followed him, “You jus’ let him get away!?”
        Her master looked back, and gave her a stare as if to tell her to be quiet. She understood and just sighed, “Wotever...” she mumbled.
        They walked through the town and the people looked relieved that the terrifying boy was gone. Marshall opened the door to his house, and Mirnada and he went inside. They sat down at the table and Marshall got some schoolbooks and placed them in front of Mirnada. “Let’s practice your studies for today now.” He said.
        Mirnada eyed him and staggered, “After what happened, you ‘spect me to jus’ sit down and study?! Come on, I know somethin’s botherin’ you!”
        Marshall sighed and leaned back in his chair, “I saw his evil eyes, they were so empty, yet so full of hate. How he killed those pirates single handedly with just a dagger...” he then fell silent and thought deeply.
        Mirnada stared at him for a moment, then she smiled at him, then began to chuckle uncontrollably. 
Marshall looked at her angrily, “What’s so funny?”
Wot is wrong with you?!” Mirnada said while laughing, “He was just a young’un like me! Don’t tell me somefin like I scare you next!”
Marshall rolled his eyes and shook his head, “That boy... Tavian... He frightened me a little. After all that I’ve seen in the world, I very rarely had seen something like that...”
Like what else?” questioned Mirnada.
“I met the former leader of the shadow knights many years ago when I went to Ijia... General Azaria.”
“Pretty name...”
Marshall nodded, then continued, “Aye, but she was terrifying, just as Tavian... She had those exact same daemonic glowing eyes... Seeing them again really caught me off guard.”
Oh, I see why you were actin’ so weird then... what else have you seen in Ijia?”
Marshall smiled at her “Hah, you always did love to hear stories of my travels... Ages ago I met King Mardche and Queen Ayleth of Ijia, General Ozwyn of the Paladins and General Azaria of the Shadow Knights on the eve of the Night of Lights.”
Night of Lights?”
“It happens once a year at the same time, the aurora that appears over Desye every night expands all over the night sky and it’s visible from Ijia. It signifies the beginning of the New Year. The whole sky turns into a prism of many beautiful, bright colors. There’s so much celebration and feasting... I should take you some year, but all the people I just mentioned are no longer there. Ijia is currently run by Queen Senna, Xavier of the Paladins and Tavian of the Shadow Knights.” 
Mirnada listened to him, fascinated and fixated.
Marshall continued, “Mirnada, when you have the chance, you should travel around... See new things, experience the world’s wonders as I have. You’ll have the time of your life. Remember, opportunity comes but once and I’m glad I traveled around at my young age when I took the chance.”
Mirnada thought to herself, then nodded, “Hmm... You’ve never told me wrong, I will do that when I can, Master” She then smiled at him.
        Marshall smiled back, “Well, go ahead and study, I’ll bring up lunch in a minute.”
        Mirnada got up and took her books, then nodded to Marshall as if to say thanks. She went upstairs to her room.
Marshall opened up the oven and the aroma of a well seasoned fowl that had been slowly roasting all day poured out. He carefully took it out and grabbed the nearby kitchen knife then carved off some generous pieces and placed them on a plate. He filled up a glass from a nearby water cask, placed some bread on the plate and got a napkin, he knew how much of a messy eater Mirnada was.
        Marshall felt strangely content. This girl he’s been caring for like a father all these years... she had become more than just a daughter to him. Closer than a sister or friend, she had become a part of his life. He had learned so much just by teaching her the ways of the world. He was happy to see her learning and having so much, becoming more than she could ever be as a thief in the streets of Pefali. 
The instant he first saw her, there was a connection, someone else from Jorgard. How she even got to Pefali was still a mystery to him, and he still wondered about it. Maybe it was a strange twist of fate how she came into his life, he pondered. Or perhaps it was just a strange coincidence? Regardless, he was happy he had such an influence in someone else’s life, especially a fellow Jorgard. 
Marshall walked up the stairs with these thoughts dancing through his mind, holding food for her. He smiled as he reminisced, then opened the door to Mirnada’s room.
        The window was open, and her books were still closed, but a single sheet of paper lay on her desk. Mirnada was nowhere to be seen. He put the plate down and quickly went over to the desk and saw the parchment.
Thank you for everything! We’ll meet again, promise!” and a doodle of Mirnada standing next to Marshall was scribbled on it.
He was caught completely by surprise. He went over to the window and looked out, searching desperately for her among people. He saw Mirnada running towards the ocean in the far off distance, and then she faded into a blur into the crowd near the docks and vanished.
        Marshall felt a pit in his stomach and a lump in his throat. He couldn’t stand... he sat down on her bed and silently stared at the floor. He sighed and tears ran down his face. He then leaned back and stared at the ceiling. Such an important piece of his life was gone... but he was comforted by the fact she took his advice and she was going to travel around the world. Then he froze for a moment... realizing who she was going to be traveling with. He felt physically sick, and he feared for her... then silently prayed for her safety.


        Mirnada dodged and weaved through the townspeople, as she was so used to doing. She arrived to the docks and the Black Neptune was barely a stones throw away in motion. She strained her legs and ran across the creaky wooden planks and reached the very edge. Mirnada kicked as hard as she could off the end of the pier and leapt through the air. She reached her arms out and caught one hand onto the ledge of the ship. She hung off, high above the water as the ship left the harbor completely. Mirnada put her other hand on and struggled to pull herself up. A big wave hit the ship and water plumed up onto her. Her grip slipped and she was hanging by one hand again on the slick wooden surface. She pulled herself up as hard as she could, then her hand slipped off and she began to fall, she helplessly looked down and closed her eyes. Suddenly a steel hand reached out and grabbed her firmly by the wrist. She slowly opened her eyes and in fear she looked up, and saw Tavian staring down at her with his wide, glowing scarlet eyes.
        Mirnada saw the terror Marshall was talking about, in those evil eyes of Tavian’s. She wanted so badly for him to let her go just to escape that disturbing gaze. But she was lifted up by the steel hand. She climbed up onto the deck and was on her hands and knees, then looked up at Tavian, and cowered before him. Tavian looked down at her, and she stared up at him into his daemonic eyes. His gaze seemed to become less angry and actually, somewhat gentle. The light faded and his eyes were back to his red-hazel.
        Tavian smirked at her, “Hmmph...” he mumbled, then walked back to the front of the ship and took control of the wheel. 
        Mirnada stood up and walked towards Tavian, cautiously. Then she remembered that for an instant, his evil eyes showed an inkling of compassion. In an odd way, that made her feel safe. She approached Tavian,  “Um... So... Hi, my names Mirnada!”
        Tavian looked at her for a moment, then nodded, and westward-bound looked straight ahead at the open sea, wheel in hand.
        Mirnada walked away and looked around the ship at all the intricate pulleys, ropes, levers and rolled up sails.
She turned towards Tavian and he was looking at her in his red-hazel eyes.
“Pull that lever, would you?” He said.
She saw a lever close to her and pulled it, unknowing of what it did. All of a sudden the pulleys turned, the ropes whisked through the air and all the sails opened. The ship was at full mast, and the wind propelled them and jerked the ship forward, almost knocking Mirnada over by the force. She was shocked, this was her first time on a ship and she had never traveled this fast before. She ran to the edge of the back of the ship and watched as Jirata, the only real home she ever had, shrank smaller and smaller in the distance. 
        She was scared to leave but thought of the future, and she turned around and saw Tavian at the wheel steering them to the unknown. She relaxed and closed her eyes... the cold sea breeze blowing her short black hair, and the bright sunlight warming her back. She sighed and smiled to herself. Then with excitement, opened her eyes and wistfully stared at the open ocean in front of her.
        VII. Prelude of War


        The morning sun rose, shedding light on Ijia Castle. The cloudscape was a soft array of gentle colors divinely cast from above. The mountains alongside the kingdom were shrouded in thin mist. Marching up and down the forested trails were groups of Paladins and Dark Knights scouring for any remnants of the despicable arbalester attack on the queen. Their search had taken them all night, and very few clues were found as to who was behind it, though everyone was sure it was their nemesis, Pefali. 
        The Chivalrous Libra; a man aged thirty-five. A man in medal adorned, shining white armor approaches a small group of Paladins. He was fairly tall and his hair was short and light brown. His eyes were sky blue and had a look of years of experience and a soul forged in fortitude. “Well? What have you found?” he asked impatiently. 
        They all immediately faced him and stood up straight and stout, and all took their right hands and balled them into a fist and quickly put it above their heart; this was the Ijian salute. “Sir!” they all said in unison. One of them stepped forward, “Lieutenant General Mason! We haven’t found any ballistics weapons or objects, only footprints, sir!”
Mason sighed, “At ease.” the group all relaxed a little, “You do know this is of the utmost importance we know exactly who was trying to take the queen’s life last night.”
“Aye, sir!” they replied, unanimously. 
“Find something... anything. That’s all that’s required.” Mason then saluted them, “Back to work.”
The Paladins saluted him and then turned back and continued scrutinizing every inch of the trail and trees for even the smallest object. Mason looked up the pathway and saw a figure in dark armor, blurred by the mist, walking down the winding dirt road. “Lo, who goes there?” inquired Mason. The figure didn’t answer but advanced closer, and Mason recognized the familiar man as the fog thinned. 
        The Adamant Capricorn, a man aged thirty-eight. He was tall and clad in black armor, with medals similar to Mason’s. His hair was long and black with. It was parted in the middle and draped down his back. His eyes were a vibrant, electric violet color and void of emotion. Staring at them would fill your very soul with fear.
“...General Magnus.” A few other figures in dark armor were following behind him, with barely even half of the medals that he had.
“Show proper respect, where’s your salute?” said Magnus, the man clad in black armor.
Mason reluctantly saluted him, “... My apologies, sir.” Magnus nodded, then Mason continued, “So, have you found anything, sir?”
Of course.” He turned to a nearby Shadow Knight with his black leather gloved hand open. He was handed a rolled up, muddy and damp piece of parchment, “We found this.” He turned back and faced Mason, “We haven’t looked at its contents yet; we don’t want to accidentally damage it. We’re sure it was dropped here last night.” He then tilted his head and said cockily, “And, what have the Paladins found?”
Mason was getting annoyed by his attitude, “Nothing yet, sir....”
        Magnus smirked at him, “Heh, well what can you expect of Paladins?” he shrugged and shook his head, “Well, as you were, then. Good luck, Lieutenant General.” He then pushed past him, knocking Mason off balance for a moment, and then continued walking down the trail, his Shadow Knights following him. They continued down and disappeared into the morning mist.
        Mason mumbled angrily to himself, then noticed the nearby Paladins had stopped to watch the trifling conflict, “Hey, keep searching!” they all went back to as they were. Mason continued to mumble to himself, “Magnus... Ever since General Tavian vanished, he’s let getting bumped up in rank swell his head far too much.”
        One of the Paladins turned and said, “If I may, sir?” Mason looked at him and nodded, the paladin then approached him, “I completely agree. I didn’t care for General Tavian but Magnus is just intolerable.”
“Aye,” replied Mason, “They may ring true, but such words drive Ijia further apart. Magnus has properly earned his rank and deserves respect, so even I must kiss his boots even though he was my equal until Tavian went missing. Now, keep searching.”


        Queen Senna sat in the royal guest suite, as her room had been destroyed. Xavier was by her side. Knights constantly left and entered the room; they were reporting to Xavier and receiving new orders from him. Diame was quietly sitting on a chair blankly staring out an open window. The whole kingdom was abuzz with the news of the attack on the queen’s life. A medic was examining the Senna’s body for any more cuts or glass shards. The queen had only a few bandaged wounds, and was not seriously injured thanks to Xavier’s quick actions. 
And... that ought to do it.” said the medic as she finished bandaging a final cut on the queen’s arm. “We’re all very relieved to see that you’re not seriously harmed. Just take it easy for the next few days, your highness.” Senna nodded to her as she gathered her medical supplies into her big leather bag and left the room.
Nearly pushing the medic over, a Shadow Knight and an alchemist rushed into the room, “Your highness! Sir Xavier!” the knight said, frantically.
What is it?” said the queen.
“We’ve concluded without a doubt who was behind this diabolical attack!” said the Shadow Knight.
Senna stood up from her seat and shared their urgency, “Who?!”
The alchemist stepped forward and said in a serious tone, “Pefali.” 
How are you sure it was Pefali.” said Xavier.
The alchemist lifted up his satchel, “Two reasons...” he opened it up and handed Xavier one of the arrows that had been inside of the queen’s wall. “The arrow feather is from the Red Pheasant, which is a bird native only to Pefali. And, the wood used in the arrow is black oak, which is also from Pefali.”
Xavier and Senna said nothing and stared at him incriminatingly. The alchemist stared at them confused, “... What? Do my findings not satisfy you?”
        Xavier stepped forward to the alchemist, “Before we declare war on a nation,” he held out his hand holding the arrow, “We need something more conclusive than feathers you can buy anywhere and a type of wood,” he clenched his fist and snapped the arrow in half, “Now, don’t come back until you find something solid, understood!?”
The alchemist nervously nodded “A-Aye sir.” and he left the room, bumping into the man clad in dark armor. 
Watch yourself, bumbling moron!” said general Magnus.
The alchemist bowed to apologize and ran away.
Magnus entered the queen’s room followed by his two subordinates, “Your majesty,” 
General Magnus?” said Xavier. “What are you doing back so early?”
Magnus stared hard at Xavier for a moment, “Unlike your Paladins...” he said as he raised his hand containing the muddied parchment, “The Shadow Knights found this and we bring it directly to her majesty.” he turned to Queen Senna and handed it to her.
        Senna took it and unrolled the muddy paper. The inside was legible, surprisingly. She began to read it aloud. 
Dear citizens of Ijia and its distinguished Generals, 
I do hope the loss of your queen hasn’t been too devastating.’ ... what?!” Senna looked up to Magnus, “Where did you find this?!”
        Magnus grinned as he knew he was the one who found a paramount piece of evidence, “It was where the arbalesters attacked from. It was placed conspicuously on a tree stump. We hadn’t read it yet, but it seemed that it was important enough to bring directly to you. Please, finish reading it, your highness.”
Senna looked back down at the muddy parchment and continued. 
I do hope the loss of your queen hasn’t been too devastating. If so, I send my condolences for our brash actions. Though, I feel it was justified since it’s necessary to demonstrate our prowess and intelligence. Now that Ijia has no ruler and no heir to the throne, I wonder what sort of chaos shall ensue in your pathetic little nation. Soon, your castle shall fall under the crushing fist of Pefali, and you will belong to us. So to save your lives and the lives of the innocent, I strongly suggest you surrender immediately. 
Signed, Sir O-’” she cut herself off and stopped reading it. She stared at the paper in disbelief, then crumpled it up in her fist.
Who was it from?” said Xavier to her, puzzled.
“... It was from... him...” replied Senna.
Xavier stared at Senna for a moment, then he thought about it, and suddenly he shuddered, “You don’t mean...”
Magnus shrugged, “I guess now you know what’s best course of action.”
        The queen stood tall and said in a clear, strong voice, “The unprovoked attack on us by Pefali four months ago was irreprehensible. We have just been mustering our defenses and have not retaliated for it, because we were nearly devastated and did that have the means to retaliate,” she paused and scanned all the eyes on her in the room, “And now... once more, they attack us without any provocation,” she closed her eyes and took a deep breath, “I never wanted this to happen under my rule... But so be it...”
“Senna?” Xavier said.
“From this point on...” she continued, “Let it be known to every citizen in Ijia, we have officially declared war against Pefali.”
There was a silence in the room, the kind of awkward silence that no one had the audacity to break. Then suddenly, everyone in the room began to cheer and talk amongst themselves, shattering the silence. “Yeah! We’ll get those bastards!” said some of the soldiers in the room. Some people left and began to tell others, it was yelled out in the hallway “War is declared on Pefali!” then it seemed to echo out throughout the castle, another voice was heard to shout “We declared war on Pefali!” one, right after another.
        Diame stood up and looked out the window and saw people running around and shouting and chanting. Soon, the words traveled beyond the castle walls to the town of Ijia. The whole nation seemed to be united under the fires of the vendetta and all people of Ijia’s hearts were instantly filled with burning pride.


        The dawn’s sunlight shone through the window of the ship. The brightness awoke Mirnada, and she lazily crawled out of bed. She tried to stand but the rocking of the ship knocked her off balance in her state of grogginess. She managed to find her sea legs, and managed not to stumble over. Mirnada hadn’t been on a ship before the previous day when she left Jirata and Marshall’s care to go to unknown lands with Tavian. She had slept in the former pirate captain’s luxurious quarters, and opened the door to the deck. Mirnada saw Tavian at the wheel and the colors of the morning sky’s clouds gently cast down above them. In the not so far off distance, she could see land: A castle along the side of a mountain, and a large town around its base.
Ah, awake are you?” Tavian said without looking at her.
Mirnada rubbed her eyes and stumbled over to Tavian, “Yeah, somewhat... where are we?”
Tavian pointed straight ahead, “That’s Ijia.”
We got here over night?” Mirnada asked, “Wait... so how could you have slept?”
Tavian sighed, “I didn’t... Well, more accurately, I don’t.”
Huh?”
“Only nightmares of the past reveal their faces to me when I sleep, so I have no use for it.” said Tavian coldly.
“Wait, how can you not sleep?!”
Tavian grunted then said nothing.
Mirnada shrugged and gave up, “Tch... fine.”
If you want to be useful,” said Tavian as he turned towards Mirnada, “We need to lose speed if we are to dock in Ijia,” he pointed at another lever on the ship, “Pull that to close the main sail.”
Mirnada nodded, “Fine...” she pulled one of the levers and once more the pulleys turned and the ropes twisted and moved. The sails all rolled up and the ship was moving just by momentum and Ijia and the docks drew close.
Tavian nodded to Mirnada to give her some acknowledgement, then he carefully steered the ship, and it glided into the harbor. He then ran to the ships sides and threw off the ropes to tether the ship to the docks. The Black Neptune stopped, and then it was surrounded by a large group of Paladins and Shadow Knights, ready to attack.
Is this ‘upposed to be some sorta welcome back?” asked Mirnada.
“I think this is more of a welcome for the ship itself than it is for us.” replied Tavian as he lowered the ramp onto the dock. “Follow me.” he said as he walked down the ramp.
The knights all saw Tavian, ragged from his long ordeal, and they all were in shock as the ghost from the past vivified before them. “S-Sir Tavian?!” they said among themselves. 
Tavian walked down the ramp and along the dock, Mirnada following close by. The soldiers all parted to form a path for him as he returned to his home. Some of his loyal Shadow Knights walked alongside him, “What happened to you, sir?!”
Tavian kept walking through the docks and into the town towards the castle, “I was captured by Pefali during the last attack, but I managed to escape.”
Everyone thought you had been slain on the battlefield!”
The people in the busy bazaars all saw Tavian and they all paused and stared at Tavian. They were fearful of him but at the same time, relieved that such a powerful asset to Ijia’s army had returned. They parted ways, forming a path for him.
What has happened in my absence?” Tavian asked as he continued marching on.
One of the shadow knights responded, “There was an attack on the queen’s life last night, but she’s unharmed. Now, she has just publicly declared war on Pefali only a few moments ago.”
Tavian threw his hands up and sighed, “The things that happen while I’m away, honestly...”
And... um... Lieutenant General Magnus is now... General Magnus.” said a knight.
Tavian burst out laughing, almost sarcastically, “Ah, boy is he in for a surprise...”
The knights chuckled nervously. 
Mirnada followed Tavian, listening closely nearby. The knights didn’t seem to notice her; they were too preoccupied talking with Tavian.
        They walked past the bazaar and up the stone steps lined up the hillside leading to the castle’s gates. The guards nearly didn’t recognize Tavian. They thought their eyes deceived them, and then they realized he truly did stand before them. Too surprised to say anything, they just simply opened the large wooden gates leading into the castle’s courtyard. Tavian, Mirnada and the knights followed him. He began walking through the courtyard and through the caste halls. The people all around were gasping in sheer surprise along the way.


“Lady Diame,” said the queen. 
The priestess faced her, “Your Highness?”
The fact that I doubted you... about your visions...” she sighed sadly and closed her eyes, “I truly apologize... If it weren’t for you, I’d be-“
Diame interrupted and walked over to her, “Your highness... You realize that what I see is indeed the near future... So I must press the issue on the Northlands... “
Magnus stepped forward, confused, “What about the Northlands?”
I definitely want to aid you, Diame...” said Senna, “However... given that we just declared war, I can’t spare a whole squad of soldiers; I can’t even spare a single one...”
“Queen Senna,” said Tavian as he entered the room.
Senna’s jaw dropped, and she stood up, staring astounded with wide eyes, “Tavian?!” she said, surprised. Xavier and Magnus had similar reactions. 
Tavian stepped inside, approaching them, “I hope I’m not interrupting anything.” he said sarcastically.
What happened to you?!” Xavier said, stunned.
“Long story short, captured by Pefali, interrogated and escaped, killed the pirate captain Alvaris Nepten and his crew, took his ship and sailed back here...” Tavian then turned his head towards Mirnada standing in the doorway, “And this girl tagged along with me...” he turned back towards Senna, “Now, what’s this business about the Northlands and Pefali I overheard?”
Diame walked up to Tavian and bowed, “I am Priestess Diame Serigh. You must be General Tavian?”
Former general, I’m afraid.” Magnus stepped forward.
Tavian faced Magnus and jeered, “Hah, you think that just because I took a little ‘vacation’, you’re to continue keeping my seat warm for me?”
        Magnus sighed disdainfully and shook his head, “Tavian, Tavian, Tavian ... You really don’t understand, do you?” he looked at Tavian and eyed him smugly, “You are no longer in command of the Shadow Knights, Her Majesty officially gave me the title of General herself.”
“Only because everyone thought I had been slain, which is a very foolish thing to even imagine,” Tavian retorted, “And as you can see, I am very much alive, Lieutenant General.” he then slyly smirked. “I knew how badly you coveted the title of General, Magnus, however now you can go back to your petty games with the dogs you call your ‘Elite Force.’”
Magnus placed his hand on the hilt of his blade, ready to draw it, “You’d best mind thy tongue, lest I remove it.”
Tavian chuckled and unholstered his dagger to accept his challenge, “Hah! I with a dirk am a thousand times more skilled than you with a blade. If you wish to resolve whom should lead the Shadow Knights, make the first move.” “Gentlemen, enough.” said the Queen. “Such behavior is akin to stray dogs than to decorated officers of Ijia’s army.”
Tavian nodded then eyed Magnus. He put his dagger away and faced back to Diame, “As you were saying?”
“Ehm...” Diame said, perturbed. She paused for a moment, and continued, “... I’ve been having nightmares about a terrible daemon... and visions about a tower in the Northlands...”
Magnus rolled his eyes, “So, a few bad dreams warrants us having you take you to the Northlands?”
        Senna eyed Magnus, “Sir Magnus, you know full well that it was Diame’s vision of the attack that saved my life. It’s very possible that her powers of clairvoyance could be seeing the future again, and if it is a daemon like the one in her visions, I don’t want it released unto the world.”
        Tavian felt the need to antagonize Magnus further, “Perhaps following your words and watching your own tongue would be wise, Lieutenant Gener-“
“Your highness! I must know,” Magnus angrily interrupted, “Do you plan on reinstating Tavian as General?!”
Senna nodded to Magnus. “He isn’t dead and is able to perform his duties; I see no reason why not.” 
Magnus grunted, obviously displeased. “Your Highness, I must protest. I really don’t think-“
I have an idea.” interrupted Tavian. Everyone stared at him, “What if I accompanied Lady Diame to the Northlands? Magnus would then end his whining and can be a general until I return, then we’ll take his bottle away.”
“Tavian you little-...” Replied Magnus, then he paused and thought for a moment, “...Fine. I have no problem with that.”
“Very well,” said Queen Senna. 
Tavian looked back to Diame, “As you were saying?”
“... So I would like to go to the Northlands and find out what this tower is and what it has to do with the daemon from my nightmare as soon as possible.” Diame finally finished.
 “So Tavian,” said Senna, “you want to take Diame to the Northlands?”
Tavian nodded, “Aye, I have the Black Neptune so you don’t have to spare any ships. But I’ll need some food supplies and warm clothing for the Northlands.”
“Of course, consider it done.” replied Senna.
Xavier felt a bit uneasy and spoke up, “Wait a moment, will just the two of you be able to travel through the Northlands? And you’re in search of a daemon, to what end?”
Tavian smirked at Xavier, “Heh, well are you offering to join us?”
“Aye.” replied Xavier.
Senna gave Xavier a surprised look, “Xavier? What say you?”
        Xavier turned to the queen, and in his jade eyes was a look begging for understanding from a lover. He sighed and said, “My Queen, my fealty does fall upon protecting Ijia, but to ensure the safety of the world from this daemon far outweighs it... I only wish to keep Lady Diame safe.”
        Senna realized she’d be apart from her love and accepted it, “Alright, just be safe and come back soon. Lieutenant General Mason will be in charge until you return.” 
Xavier nodded, “Yes, my Queen.” he then regretfully left the room.
Begin preparing the Black Neptune,” Tavian said to a knight, “Take all of the pirate’s loot on the ship and put it in the treasury.” the knight nodded and they both left the room and saw Mirnada who was patiently standing in the hallway, “Oh, and take care of this girl too.”
The shadow knight looked at Tavian puzzled, “Who’s the runt?”
Who you callin’ a runt?!” Mirnada replied angrily, “I don’t wanna stay here, I’d rather see wots in the Northlands.”
“Heh, fine.” said Tavian, then he faced the knight, “Give the order to have the ship prepared before noon.”
“Aye, sir.”


        Xavier gave his command to Mason and instructed him of his orders. He knew not how long he would be gone, so he said his loving goodbyes to Senna in private. He wore his battle armor made of polished white steel chest plates, chainmail and pauldrons. On his back, he wore his dark green cape and his long blonde hair in a ponytail. The Paladin was now ready to protect Diame and lend aid to Tavian and Mirnada.
        Tavian, after allowing Magnus to stay General for a bit longer, bathed off all the blood from his enemies. He kept the knife he took from Pefali as a memento after he sharpened and polished it, then holstered it to his side. Although he did properly arm himself with his dark-steel claymore he sheathed on his back and pistol he kept at his side. Fortunately, they were recovered from the battlefield after he was captured. He wore his Shadow Knight battle armor made of dark steel plates on his torso and legs. He went through his belongings and found some shaded spectacles he took with him. Also, he had enough time for the gauntlet on his right hand to be repaired. Now, the Shadow Knight was ready to demolish any obstacle in their path.
 Diame packed her necessities and finished preparing herself for what awaited her in the Northlands. She spent the rest of the morning meditating, but no more visions would come to her. She prayed that she was not wasting their time, and hoped that the gods have shown her the true path. She wore her ceremonial white robe still, and armed with her staff. The Priestess was now ready to search for the truth.
Mirnada, the young child with a burning heart of wonder wished to tag along with them. She knew they were doing something important and simply longed to understand the ways of the world. She wore her orange cloth tunic and armed herself with cesti. The disciplined girl trained in the fighting arts of Jorgard was ready to explore the distant lands.


        The four of them, after making their preparations, boarded the Black Neptune. The clouds had parted, and it was a beautiful sunny day. The sky and the ocean matched the same blue hues and stretched on endlessly. The sea was calm and the wind was blowing to the north, perfect conditions for their journey. Diame thought to herself that the gods truly did will this. Mason, Magnus, and Senna along with other soldiers and townspeople bid their farewells as the ship departed to the Northlands.
        VIII. Memories and Scars


        It was still early in the evening and the sun had just begun to set. The ocean was bright orange in the dying sunlight, and the ship still sailed northbound, nearing their destination. The heavy treasure had been removed so the ship was traveling much faster. The four of them did not know much about each other, so they finally decided to all sit down at a table on the top deck to converse. They had explored the ship beforehand and had found a bottle of wine that was hidden away, so they decided to have some. The light was dim from the setting sun and nearby lamps lit the decks with a pale orange light.


So, wot I’m tryin’ to understan’ is,” said Mirnada, “why are we goin’ to this place? I did overhear some talkin’ about daemons and visions, so I’m really confused...” 
Tavian shrugged, “I’m a little unsure about everything also, as well as who you are Diame, and you too Mirnada... please enlighten us.” he said as he sipped some of his wine.
I’m one of the Seven High Priests,” said Diame, “they are people who are chosen by Lux Grande for exceptional spiritual powers. Ever since I was young, I’ve had premonitions of the future.” she paused and took a sip from the wine, “So, I started spiritual training, and eventually I was able to master soothsaying and even had visions of the future that always came true. Soon after I had become a Priestess, the previous Divine Ambassador had died, bless his soul. The Pontiff was aware of my abilities and made me the next Divine Ambassador to Keylla, the Goddess of Water. Her shrine is in Teva Village which is where I have lived and protected for eight years. I’ve never had any visions of daemons before, and I have had a recurring one almost every night. Keylla then showed me the Northlands in a vision, so I thought to ask Queen Senna for aid to go there and see what the goddess was trying to show me... so here we are.”
Mirnada nodded with interest, and she began to add about herself, “I used t’be a thief when I was younger... stealin’ to survive cuz I never ‘ad a family...”
Diame felt sympathetic, “I’m so sorry, no child should ever suffer that.”
        Mirnada shrugged, “It’s fine, I don’t really think about it too much of it anyway. When my mentor found me, he took me under ‘is care... He taught me how to defend m’self and treated me like I was his own kid... he’s always talked ‘bout how he’s seen the whole world and I should go explore it, so I saw my chance when Tavian was leavin’ Jirata.”
        Tavian took a big gulp of the wine, and reluctantly began to talk, “... I put the past behind me. I’m really not that interesting of a person...” There was a long pause, and they all expected him to continue, but he said nothing.
        Xavier stared at him anxiously, “... That’s it?” 
        Tavian took another gulp of wine and mumbled “Mm-hmm.”
“I thought I’d learn at least one thing about you tonight, Tavian. You’ve always kept to yourself.” said Xavier.
“What is there to tell?” retorted Tavian, “I truly don’t remember anything from my childhood... My first memories are of being trained as a Shadow Knight by Lady Azaria.”
Mirnada interrupted, “Oh yeah! My master told me about her... he said he met Azaria once... and he said you both have the same red glow in your eyes.”
“The eyes... are a curse.” muttered Tavian, “Azaria had the same eyes because she wields the Brevynard, a sword imbued with powerful arcane magicks. If a Shadow Knight arms himself with it, their strength increases drastically... She allowed me to use it once when she had finished training me... the sword’s malice overcame me, and...” Tavian fell silent, “Never mind. It’s a boring tale.” he finished off the rest of his wine in a single slug, “Your turn, Paladin.”
Xavier shrugged, “Fine, if you don’t want to continue... When I was young, I joined the Ijian Army... I became a Paladin and worked my way up in ranks and eventually became the general... That’s about it.”
        Tavian shrugged, “Way to go, you said even less than I did, yet you left nothing out.”
“Heh... touché” retorted Xavier.
Tavian chuckled a little at his own wit, and the other three joined in. They talked a while longer, and then Xavier, Mirnada and Diame grew tired and they slept in the beds below. 
        Tavian navigated the ship, forsaking sleep as he always did. The talk they had tonight did perturb him. He truly did not remember anything from his past, but it never bothered him up until now. He tried to put it out of his mind, but the questions that remained unanswered plagued his thoughts as he piloted the ship through the darkness.


        The night passed, and the morning dawn broke in the horizon. They tethered their ship to an old abandoned port and disembarked. With the snowy path lay before them, they began their trek.


        The four walked through the tranquil landscape, breaking the silence only with the sound of their footsteps crushing through the snow. To protect from the biting chills, they wore warm coats made of thick fur and kept moving ever forward. The clouds were illuminated by the morning sun and gently cast down their light. Diame strained her sight through the veil of snow for any sign of the tower, but the tundra seemed to stretch on endlessly.  She saw nothing but the frozen mountainsides in the distance. Surrounded by the empty cold, they felt alone and lost in this land of pure white. 
        Diame began to worry and doubt herself... There was nothing here, no tower, no daemon... were her visions false? Did she make these generals waste so much time in their nation’s most desperate hour? She stopped in her tracks and fell to her knees. She stared at the snowflakes falling to the ground before her.
The three stopped and turned back, confused. Xavier approached her, “ Lady Diame? Are you alright?”
She stared downcast blankly; tears streamed from her eyes and froze as they fell through the air. She could hear the cruel sound of them landing in the snow.
He knelt down in front of her, “Diame!?” he looked into her eyes as they gazed down, “What’s wrong?”
“I-I’m...” stuttered the priestess, “I’m so sorry...”
“Lady Diame... Why are you apologizing?”
She closed her eyes and shook her head, “It’s... It’s that I’ve dragged you out here for nothing... I must have misinterpreted something in the vision... I took it too literally... I never thought about it until now... I was so wrong...”
Tavian grew impatient “What are you two doing? We still have a long way to go!”
“Go on ahead, we’ll catch up in a moment.” said Xavier.
Tavian shrugged and tossed up his hands, confused. He then continued walking with Mirnada following.
Xavier sat down before Diame, “I want you to know something... I have faith in you.” Diame stayed silent and wiped a frozen tear off her face. Xavier continued, “Why do you not have faith in yourself?” She tried to speak, but her words escaped her. She just wept quietly. Xavier stared at her with gentle, compassionate eyes. “Diame... I have faith in you because my life is evident of your powers... If it weren’t for your vision of the tower, you would not have come to Ijia... And if you hadn’t seen the queen and I under attack...”
“Stop... please...” she forced herself the strength to say.
“You know it to be the truth... the tower must exist... We haven’t even begun to search for it yet... don’t give up hope before you’ve even tried for God's sake...” he smirked at her.
Diame sighed and cleared her mind, “It’s just so hard... I feel like the gods have entrusted me with a burden sometimes with these visions...”
“I see...” said Xavier, “Well, running away from your problems won’t solve them... Trying to believe that your visions are false just to avoid your duties... That’s not very becoming of such a high priestess.” he put his hand on her shoulder, “We all get scared... but you’re not alone... we’re here to help you.”
Diame nodded, and took a deep breath, “Thank you... Xavier.” He smiled at her and then stood up and extended his hand. She grabbed it to help herself stand back up.


“Wot do ya think they’re doin’?” asked Mirnada.
“Hell if I know.” answered Tavian, frustrated, “I want to get this mission done as fast as we can so we can make the war preparations. The more we delay, the more vulnerable Ijia will be.” He continued walking steadfast through the snow.
“Yeah, well she looked really upset, it could’ve been somethin’ important bothering her...” responded Mirnada.
        “So?” retorted Tavian, “She asks for Her Highness's help and it is graciously given it to her, and then in repayment she cries like a child? This is how a Priestess acts...? It’s simply unbelievable!”
        “Oh please, knock it off already.” Mirnada scoffed, disgusted. “It wouldn’t kill ya to think about someone but yourself.”
Tavian eyed her, “Say what you will, I still think this is a waste of time. I’m only helping because Ijia can’t afford to lose Sir Xavier.”
        Mirnada turned back and saw Xavier help up Diame, and they continued walking. “There, see? They only needed a bloody moment.” Tavian ignored her and pressed onward. “Yer truly heartless, Tavian.” muttered Mirnada.
        He ignored her once more. Tavian saw a frost covered sign nearby, “Hm?” he approached it and wiped the ice and snow from it. Carved in it was an arrow pointing west saying “Desye Village” and an arrow pointing north saying “Valice Glacier.” As he read the sign, it sparked a familiar memory. He traced his metal hand against the carved out letters in Desye Village and scrutinized it very closely, without even knowing what he was doing.
“Tavian, now what’s wrong with you?” said Xavier with Diame by his side.
... Oh... Huh?” Tavian said as he looked away from the sign. “Err... Nothing... Oh! There’s a village to the west.”
Xavier raised an eyebrow at him, “You are acting strange, indeed.” 
Tavian regained himself, “... We should go to that village, they might know a thing or two about the tower...”
Xavier nodded, “Alright. Sounds like a plan... but are you sure you’re fine?”
“Aye...” responded Tavian, “Just random déjà vu.”
“Ok then...” He took a glance at the sign, and then the four of them continued onwards.


        The day past and the sun was beginning to set. After traveling through the cold, the fatigued four saw plumes of black smoke rising steadily into the wintry sky, contrasting the pure white.
“Is that... that village?” said Mirnada, relieved.
Xavier smirked, “I sure hope so.”
Tavian squint his eyes and stepped a little farther ahead than everyone else, trying to make out the image of the village. He shook his head in disbelief and then ran as fast as he could towards the village gates.
“What the hell...? Tavian!?” exclaimed Xavier. He then began to give chase.
Diame and Mirnada looked at each other and ran after them.
        There was a collection of ten or so log cabin type houses lined up along the base of a steep hillside, each with a chimney pouring out the black smoke. Dividing the village was a river that flowed from a waterfall cascading off the sheer hill’s edge. An old bridge spanned over the frozen river's surface. The frozen waters were thick and frozen but water flowed swiftly underneath the ice. Built into the hillside seemed to be an entrance to some sort of temple. There were pine trees scattered around as well as a few crudely built snowmen. A sign hung overhead saying simply “Desye.” 
        Tavian ran into the village and stared at all the homes. “Nay... Nay...!” he kept saying to himself. “What the... why...?”
Xavier rushed in followed by Diame and Mirnada. He stood behind him, “Tavian?! What’s gotten into you?!”
        Tavian kept walking around Desye, looking at all the houses. They seemed so familiar and he did not know why. He lost control of himself and fell into a panic. “What... what the hell is going on...!?” he could feel his heart racing, every vein in his body throbbing as if they would burst.
Diame approached Tavian and reached out to touch him, “Tavian, calm down... You can tell us-“
        Tavian spun around, eyes wide and violently glowing red, “Get the hell away from me!” he screamed angrily as he backed away from her.
        Diame, terrified, fell backwards and began to shake in fear.
Xavier grabbed the hilt of his blade and stood between Tavian and Diame, protecting her, “Grab a hold of yourself or I shall subdue you!”
        Tavian jumped back and grabbed his head, pulling at his hair, and let out a piercing shriek. He then panicked and ran through the village out the other end. Xavier watched him fade into the distance’s shroud of snow. Xavier was in shock, he never saw Tavian unable to control himself like this. Mirnada knelt down beside Diame trying to calm her shaken nerves. The curtains on the houses were pulled back one by one and many pairs of eyes gazed nervously through the windows to see what all the commotion was about. A door swung open and a perturbed old woman stepped out of her house, she looked very concerned.
        The Ardent Sagittarius; a sagacious lady with over a century of wisdom. She stood very short holding a long wooden walking staff. A necklace was worn on her neck, a small stone with a strange symbol carved on it hanging from the thin chain. Her silver hair was tied back behind her head in a ponytail. She wore a bright vermillion robe which seemed to match her temperamental personality. One of her eyes was the color of earth, but as radiant as a tiger’s-eye gem, the other was completely milky white and cataract. Both her eyes had a demeanor of wisdom, sternness and kindness. She approached them calmly but she looked very serious, she wanted no harm to come to the village. She saw Diame shaking on the ground with Mirnada comforting her and Xavier with his hand on his sword hilt. “What reason have you to disturb our humble village?” she said earnestly.
“I’m sorry...” said Xavier, releasing his grip on his hilt, “A man in our group went mad. We meant no disturbance.”
The old lady nodded her head, “Hmm... Well, what are you doing here?” she asked. People still stared out of the windows listening in.
“We’re looking for a tower. Do you know anything about it?”
The old lady gave him an angry glare, but also a look of confusion. She nodded her head once more, “Come inside.” she said as she turned around and walked back into her house.
Xavier was puzzled, Diame had regained herself but was still a bit shaken up. Mirnada helped her up and the three entered the old lady’s house.
        There was a large fire in the fireplace, giving warmth, light and a homey ambience. “Make yourselves at home,” she said as she sat down in a rocking chair on the right side of the fireplace, “Please have a seat.” she motioned towards the couch on the other side of the fireplace, facing her.
The three removed their fur coats and sat down on the couch, facing he old lady. There was a silence as they stared at her, and as she stared back with her deathly white eye.
“So...” Mirnada broke the silence, “Who are you?” she asked innocently.
“Ah, you wish to know who I am? I also wish to know who you are, and I think after the disturbance you caused, you’re obligated to introduce yourselves first.” she quipped.
Xavier leaned forward in his seat slightly, as if to bow, “I am Xavier Alexander, General of Ijia’s Paladins.”
Mirnada shrugged, “I’m Mirnada Harts, a student und’r my mentor Marshall Harts.”
“I’m Diame Serigh... Divine Priestess of Water.” she shook off the last of her shaken nerves, “Wait a moment, you’re Lady Birchie, aren’t you?”
The old lady nodded, “Aye, Birchie, Oakh, Madame Oakh... I’ve been called many things, take your pick.” she said as she smirked, “Heh, I thought I sensed something spiritual about you, Diame.”
        Mirnada tilted her head, “You know her, Diame?”
Diame nodded, “Aye, this is the Divine Priestess of Wind, Lady Birchie Oakh.”
        Oakh chuckled slightly, “Heheheh, I haven’t been called a ‘Lady’ in nearly a century, everyone just calls me ‘Madame Oakh.’”
“Ah, I see... Madame Oakh then.” said Diame.
“Wait, jus’ how old are you?” Mirnada blurted out.
“That’s... incredibly rude!” Diame stared daggers at the child for her disrespect.
Madame Oakh simply let out a hearty yet hoarse chuckle, “Wah-hah-hah-hah! Child, do you wish to know my age?” Mirnada nodded with curiosity, Oakh continued, “This year, I am one-hundred, thirty-six years aged, my young friend.” she smiled at Mirnada kindly, “And how old are you?”
“Seventeen...” Mirnada responded shyly, off put by the old lady’s cackling.
        “Um... Madame Oakh...” said Xavier.
        “Quiet! Don’t interrupt, boy!” she snapped back.
Xavier was speechless to be talked down to like that, and he muttered to himself, “But I must ask about something important...”
“So! Young lass,” said Oakh, “You’re student of Marshall Harts, I met him a long time ago! How is he? Oh! Tell me, what are you and your friends doing here?”
“Uh... He’s fine... We’re lookin’ for a tower somewhere around here.” said Mirnada. 
Oakh paused a moment, “... A tower?” she said, with a more serious cadence.
        Xavier spoke up, “Diame had visions-“
“Hush!” interrupted Oakh glaring at Xavier as he sighed and shrugged, “Tell me about this tower, lass.”
        “Diame had visions about daemons and a tower, I think.” said Mirnada.
Oakh looked over to Diame, with a deeply disturbed look in her eyes, “You had them too?”
        Diame stared back at Oakh, unbelieving of what she heard, “...’Too’?!”
        Oakh nodded, “Aye, aye! You’ve seen that monstrosity as well, nay?!”
        Diame nodded, “I have. That’s why we came-“
“You must leave and forget what you saw!” yelled Oakh.
The three stared back at her in complete silence.
“W-...why?” asked Diame, confused.
Oakh shook her head, “I apologize... But you have no idea what these daemons are or what they are capable of... When I was young... I saw it... with my own eyes.”
Xavier spoke up, “What are they? That’s what we’ve been meaning to know...”
        Oakh stared at the floor... then began to speak, “A long time ago... The world was vivisected by avarice, as God saw it. Evaz’Sa saw fit to punish mankind for their sins and force them to obey under her divine rule. But before it came to that point in the Divine Era, God was very generous; the crops of the famished began to overgrow, the ill were healed, and the accused righteous were vindicated. However, after an aeon, the exacerbated God grew weary after performing miracle after miracle... So, she simply began to only observe the people she had taken care of for so long. Quickly, God noticed our world was full of so much greed and bloodlust, unworthy of her benevolence. ”
“I've heard part of this story before...” said Diame, “What did they do to the people?”
Oakh continued, “Evaz’Sa decided to abandon the wretched world and recover her lost strength by merely observing while she rested. However, she knew if she let the unbridled chaos continue, the world known as Caelutera would surely destroy itself. So, she decided to leave traces of her divinity behind. God sacrificed part of her own dwindling strength to create entities of punishment, so they could take over her task and monitor the world’s inhabitants. Now, Evaz’Sa would be able to repose.” 
Oakh took a deep breath and forced herself to speak the next part, her eyes showing the obvious fear in them. “The Watchers, a looming name dubbed thus by the people, were the new overseers of Caelutera. They ensured that the people would stay faithful to God until she decided to return. The people were terrified of The Watchers, and dared not even speak their name. They dared not sin and anger their new masters for they were retribution incarnate.” 
        “These daemons... They’re called The Watchers?” said Xavier. “I’ve never heard anything about them...”
Oakh nodded, knowingly “Aye, even the revered and feared Watchers couldn’t endure the vicissitudes of time, and their lore fell victim to its silence. Thus, another lost chapter had been written. Who is to say why The Watchers were forgotten. Maybe because people simply didn’t talk about them, the tale just faded out of memory. Or, did people force themselves to forget so they could live without fear? No one truly knows, but whatever the reason, people continued their lives, staying faithful to their loving God and shunning the very thought of The Watchers.” 
“Wait, wait, wait,” said Mirnada, “How did people jus’ forget about them? They’re ‘upposed to be the new rulers of the world?!”
        “Who is to say why The Watchers were forgotten.” continued Oakh, “Maybe because people simply didn’t talk about them, the tale just faded out of memory. Or, did people force themselves to forget so they could live without fear? No one truly knows, but whatever the reason, people continued their lives, staying faithful to loving Evaz'sa and shunning the very thought of The Watchers.” she leaned back in her rocking chair and crossed her fingers in her lap, and stared at them, “Now... What will you do with this knowledge?” 
Xavier stood up, “We will do what we must, we can’t allow them to pose a threat to the world.”
        Oakh stood up as well, “Will you upstart against them, against their Dogma? Who are you to decide your fate?! 
        Xavier grabbed his coat and went for the door, Diame and Mirnada stood up as well and headed for their coats.
        Oakh helplessly watched them leave, “We are children of the Gods; without our parents we are lost forevermore!” she said in anger.
        Xavier looked back at her, “Indeed, but an abandoned child must know when to move on...” he turned away and grabbed the door handle, “And that’s what we must do.”
Stop... It’s nearly nightfall, what do you hope to do?” asked Oakh as she stepped towards them.
Xavier turned back to her, “We have to find Tavian, who ran off into the tundra.”
        Oakh paused, completely caught off guard, “... Did you say... Tavian?!”
... Do you know him?!” Xavier stepped towards her, “Please tell me!”
        “No... that man who ran away, he couldn’t possibly have been that boy...” Oakh mumbled to herself.
        “You know something about him...” Diame said, approaching Oakh, “We just want to help him...”
Oakh cast her eyes down and shook her head, “Tavian was a boy who lived in this village... But he died... and that other kid...” she sighed and looked back up at them, “You wish to help him, but you know nothing about his past...”
Who cares!?” interrupted Mirnada, “’e’s prolly out in the middle of nowhere freezin’ to death!”


        The sun had finally set and the land of white faded to black. Tavian staggered through the snow and darkness, ignoring the cruel wintry winds stinging his skin. He strained his eyes to see through the void, but he saw nothing. His body was frozen numb, his mind astir and muddled. Crestfallen and empty, lost in the cold relentless darkness, he stumbled his frozen limbs through the snow, unknowing where he was going, only hopelessly moving forward. 
“Oh god...” Tavian said, fighting back tears, “What daemon possesses me to do such insanity...” he was shivering and desperately hugged the thick fur coat he wore. The night’s cold was truly unbearable and it began to take its toll. “You Gods... pity me not. I shan’t beg for mercy for this cruel fate...” Tavian’s last ounce of strength faded, he grunted and fell to his knees and sat on his feet, no longer able to stand. He groaned and looked up into the cold, pitch black sky. Gathering the words from his last breath, he muttered through his frozen lips, “But... If I do die here, my only regret is... not knowing who I am... Show me... anything... That is all I ask.”
He tried to breathe again, but could not as if his throat was frozen shut. He fell to his hands and desperately tried to gasp, but could not. His eyes began to glow that same accursed red, lighting the snow scarlet before him. Tears swelled up in the back of his eyes but began to freeze before they even fell. He fell over onto his side and curled up and shivered. He gazed into the blackness beyond of what he could see from the snow illuminated by his eyes. He remembered this darkness as if it were a familiar friend, and somehow felt comforted. Some last thoughts flared in his mind, “You gods... This is the extent of your kindness...? You are worthless...” The red glow in his eyes faded, and all faded to nothing.


        Diame, Mirnada, Xavier and Oakh all sat together once more in front of the warm fire.
It’s not right of me to talk about Tavian’s past...” said Oakh, “But if you truly do care about him, you must wait to look for him. The cold in the Northlands at night is deadly if you have no shelter... But, if he is the same Tavian who grew up here... he’ll be alright.”
        “How can you be so sure?” said Xavier.
        “That boy...” muttered Oakh, as if it was a memory she wished to be forgotten. She averted her eyes and gazed into the fire, “Well, a man now, I suppose... But still...” her mind seemed to have wondered off. She just nodded to the fire, listening to the ambience of its roar, as if she understood a hidden emotion behind it.
Xavier stared patiently at her, but his confusion overcame him, “... What?” 
Ah... sorry...” she looked back at them, “Tavian, there always was something special about him... I knew him ever since the day he was born,” her eyes wandered again, as if she was trying to avoid bringing up the very thought of him, “Well, to be more specific the very instant, I was his mother’s midwife you know...” she sighed and refocused back onto the three, “Though, I must say, today when I saw those red eyes glow as I peered through the window... I thought for sure Hell was missing a daemon. Oh, and that scream...!” her eyes widened, “That scream...” she closed her eyes and put her hand up to her forehead.
        “You alright?” said Mirnada, concerned.
        “Aye...” she lowered her hand back into her lap, and continued, “Just, what happened in the past... trying to remember what we all desperately want to never think of again...” Oakh sighed again and swallowed a lump in her throat.
        “Madame Oakh,” said Xavier, “What in the world happened here?”
        “I still remember...” said Oakh, her eyes once again fixated on the fire, “The smell of the smoke... the sight of that blood... and... that scream...” she began to shake and tears streamed from her eyes, she grabbed a handkerchief and wiped them away, and sobbed into it.
Diame went over to her and kneeled on the floor and put her hand on Oakh’s back to comfort her, “It’s alright, we don’t have to talk about this now.”
I’m fine...” said Oakh, removing the cloth from her face, “I just need to clear my thoughts on these scars of the past... We will talk about it tomorrow. You may stay the night here.”
“Madame Oakh,” said Xavier, “Thank you.... But I have one final question.”


        Tavian raised his head and stared into the black sky.


How are you sure that Tavian will be fine?” continued Xavier.


        Up above, a long outstretched, gentle blue beam of light began to glow.


My dear,” said Oakh, “He grew up here and him still being alive is evident enough he can survive anything.” she paused for a moment, “Oh... and,”


        Other colored lights appeared. Soft pink and green, vibrant orange and red lights, they lit up the night sky and cast down a glorious array of colors upon the land. The clouds were illuminated and glowed in ever changing iridescence. Tavian watched in awe, childhood memories began to flood his mind of him sitting beneath the stars, watching these very same lights every night.


        Oakh looked out the window, “Ah, it’s midnight already?”
The three looked to the window and saw the lights begin to brighten the whole land in a sea of beauty. Mirnada jumped out of the couch and ran up to the window. “This must be...!” she said in excitement.
The Aurora.” said Oakh. “Tavian always snuck out late to watch it. He got in trouble with his parents since he was supposed to be sleeping. But really,” she too stood by Mirnada and gazed at the prismatic sky, “who could blame him?” she smiled and felt comforted by these lights, “One thing he always did...” she let out a nostalgic giggle, “When he was little, he would always say, ‘Those are MY lights!’ Oh, he would get so angry when I’d tease him and say ‘Nay, child, nay! They are mine!’ in response.” 


        Tavian looked up at the flowing river of effulgent hues and smiled contently. He lay frozen in the snow, watching the lights and clouds go by. He felt exactly the same as he did as a child, watching in curious wonder. Somehow, the cold didn’t seem so bad after all.
“So...” Tavian uttered, his cadence quieter than a whisper, “I guess you heard me.” a smirk stretched onto his frozen face, “You gods... truly do have me bound by some twisted chains of fate.” He forced his icy eyelids to close and blinked, his numb fingers twitched, and his lungs drew in the cold air. He clenched his fist in the snow and strained his frozen muscles to push himself to sit upright. He stared up at the aurora and felt a tingling sensation in his frozen limbs as the numbness faded away, “Alright... I’ll be a pawn in your game a bit longer, then.” Tavian felt rejuvenated and found new strength, he was unsure if it was his curse’s power, pure resolve, or a direct blessing from the gods. Either way, he managed to stand to his feet. 
He beseeched the sky itself, “Wondrous gift of the gods... guide me!” he said clearly. The river of light ebbed and flowed continuously in a single direction, as if to answer his plea. He followed the light’s flow with his eyes, and he saw small wisps of black smoke in the distance standing out in the light. “... Desye...”  he muttered to himself as he slowly walked towards it, following the guiding light. The air still as cold as ever, he continued onward with a fire burning within him. “It’s funny,” Tavian said, staring at the snow reflecting the colors in the sky, “how the most bleak and cold hell in this world,” he looked back up at the dancing rays of light, “can be as equally divine as the most blissful heaven.”


        Time passed, Tavian marched through the snow, his spirit uplifted by the magnificent sea of light. The smoke he saw nigh above him, the log houses’ windows’ aglow from the fireplaces beside his path. He felt calm and curious; he had returned.


I’d have to go back through many pages in my diary first...” said Oakh, “Then I’d be able to remember every detail about Tavian and what happened here.”
“That’s understandable... do not worry about it.” said Xavier.
“But please tell me... What do you know about him? How did he get to Ijia? How is he now a general?” said Oakh.
Yeah, I wanna know too,” said Mirnada.
Xavier concentrated and thought clearly, “I remember the day he arrived in Ijia... I believe that was... six years ago... I remember because that was about the time of Senna’s... I mean, the Queen’s birthday. She had just turned Twenty-five... He had washed asho-... What...?” his eyes averted to the colored lights pouring in from the window. A figure was drawing closer in the distance, “Wait a second...” he stood up and walked closer to the window, “Is that...?”
        The others all turned and looked out the window and saw Tavian walking towards the house. The door creaked open and he stepped in. They all stared at him with looks of relief. For the first time in a very long while, he felt like he had been welcomed home in a way. 
Heh... Hello there.” Tavian said to respond to their stares.
Xavier walked cautiously over to Tavian, eyeing him with a serious demeanor. He stopped just before him, his green eyes’ gaze burning at the Shadow Knight’s own red-hazel. 
What’s the matter, Xavier?” said Tavian as he looked around the room and the familiar faces by the warm fire, “I see you’ve made yourselves... comfortable.”
Xavier grunted and punched Tavian in the side of his jaw, “How dare you, after what you did!” 
Diame, Mirnada and Oakh jumped up. Startled, Tavian turned his head away from Xavier and covered where he was struck with his steel hand. Oakh quickly stood up from her seat and began to walk towards them; she wanted to end their fighting. Diame saw her get close to Tavian and she was reminded of his unbridled rage earlier. She bolted up and stood in front of Oakh, “Please, you might get hurt...!”
Do you have...” muttered Xavier as he looked down onto Tavian, “...any idea...” he took his left hand and placed it on top of his right hand, throbbing from the strike he dealt, “... what you could have done...!?”
Tavian rubbed his jaw with his steel hand and looked at Xavier to the side, “I guess not. I don’t even remember much of what happened.” he turned his head back and faced Xavier, “Why don’t you enlighten me?”
You ran off into the tundra on your own, you could have been killed by doing something so dangerous... Wasted so much time, we’re no closer to finding the tower because of that...” Xavier looked over to Diame, “and you threatened Diame, I really thought you would harm her, the one we must protect at all costs...!” he looked back to Tavian and met with his red-hazel eyes, “What the hell happened to you? I’ve seen you when you’re uncontrollable like that only in war times during the heat of the battle, but never in such a sudden, unprovoked burst.”
Tavian cast his eyes downward and stepped past Xavier, who was still staring at him. He gently pushed Oakh and Diame out of the way as he walked over to the fire and sat down on his knees close to the flames. The near unbearable heat melted his frozen body. The others looked at him, as if waiting for an answer or explanation. He simply closed his eyes and felt the heat caress his skin.
Well,” Oakh said, breaking the silence. She looking at everyone else, “Tavian is alive and well, that’s all that matters, right?” there was another silence, Diame nodded to Oakh, Mirnada stared at Tavian and Xavier turned away. Oakh continued, “There’s a guest room up stairs with three beds,”
“I’ll stay down here.” mumbled Tavian as he basked in the firelight.
Xavier walked firmly up the stairs, controlling his anger towards Tavian yet making it blatant he was doing so. The other three followed him, leaving Tavian in front of the fire.


Oakh slept in her room while Xavier, Mirnada and Diame went to the guest room. Mirnada, Diame and Xavier, tired from the trek through the tundra, they fell asleep quickly. However, Mirnada was restless tonight and tossed around in her sleep. She woke up and the first image was the dancing lights outside her window. She stayed in bed, trying to relax. Thoughts drifted through her mind, maybe she was too excited about exploring new places to sleep soundly. A part of her missed her home in Jirata, and thoughts of Marshall reminisced. 
She heard footsteps from downstairs, and realized it was probably Tavian. Mirnada was thinking about what he could possibly be doing still awake, and then she heard the front door creak open and close.
The ‘ell is he doin’?” Mirnada mumbled to herself. She pulled the covers off her and put on her thick fur snow coat. Down the stairs into the living room she went. It was dimly lit by the few remaining flickering embers, and Tavian was not in sight. She opened up the front door and went outside. She saw fresh footprints from the doorway leading to around the house, she followed them. “Tavian...?” she said in a loud whisper. The footprints ended at the base of a tall tree growing right next to the house. The tree was thick with snow except for one part that looked like the snow had just been rattled off. “Up there...?” she muttered. While looking up, she grabbed onto the tree and began to climb it. Up at the top she saw Tavian laying on the roof in a thick jacket and a thick blanket staring up at the aurora. “What are you doing, eh?” said Mirnada as she dropped off the branches of the tree on top of the roof beside him.
Tavian looked over to her and smirked, “Heh, can’t take your eyes off the aurora either, huh?”
Mirnada walked over to him and sat down beside him, “I couldn’t sleep... I heard you leave...” she looked up at the night sky at the calming, flowing colors, “did you come out here to try to sleep?”
You forget...” Tavian looked over to Mirnada, “I told you before, I don’t sleep.”
She paused and remembered, “Ah... right... But, you never told me why you don't sleep.”
I did tell you, Mirnada,” he said, “I have terrible nightmares... I’d opt to never see them again.”
“Come on, a few nightmares couldn’t be that bad.” Mirnada said to try to uplift him, instead he felt slightly offended.
Tavian stared coldly at Mirnada for a moment, but she didn’t feel threatened. He leaned back and gazed up at the aurora under the starry sky. “It’s just... I’ve had the same nightmare every night... for as long as I could remember... In it, I’m in a burning house and there’re no doors or windows... I’m trapped inside... I feel the heat of the flames burning my skin... I take a deep breath to scream, but I choke on the smoke...” He raised his hand in the air, fingertips outreached as if to touch the stars, “Then I wake up to my own horrible screaming... for the sake of not alarming anyone, I usually just read or play my piano instead of sleep.”
Mirnada looked at Tavian, puzzled. “So... you don’t sleep? Ever?”
Tavian sighed shook his head as he continued to observe the skylights. Wintry clouds flew by, illuminated into a million soft colors by the aurora’s brilliant light. “I nodded off in front of the fireplace for a short while...” he paused and continued to observe the beautiful sky, “and... I had a different dream tonight.” 
He slowly waved his hand in the air, following the clouds. “I had a dream that I could fly. I was diving down over this same tundra, falling through the aurora... I could feel the cold air biting my face and freezing my hair... But then I realized I wasn’t flying... just falling... falling freely, but I could never reach the ground.” He sighed and put his arm back down. “For some reason, I felt so sad... but at the same time, in a way, liberated. I woke up with tears in my eyes. I cried, Mirnada... I have not had any emotion besides rage in as long as I can remember.”
Mirnada turned toward him “Is it because you’re here? In Desye?” she asked.
Maybe... Ever since we came here, I felt so uneasy... and at the same time, nostalgic. Old memories forced themselves to the surface at a mere glance of the village... memories that I had completely forgotten.”
        “How could you ‘ave forgott’n everything about yerself?” Mirnada questioned.
        “I-I don’t know... I never could remember anything about myself before I came to Ijia...” Tavian fell silent for a moment. “... Wait, how did I even get to Ijia in the first place? ... If this is where I came from, why did I lose control over myself like that...? Why does everything here make me feel nostalgic and happy yet at the same time, I feel so terrified?!” He sat up and looked around him. “What am I doing here?!”
Mirnada sat up as well and faced him, then shook his shoulder “Hey! Snap the hell out of it!”
“I’m sorry... But I’ve never thought about WHY I couldn’t remember anything...” He stared at his hands... then his gaze became fixated on his artificial one. “This... How did I even get this? I’ve always had this cursed hand... I never knew why I needed it,” his gaze wondered around the village and something fixated his glance. He then widened his eyes with a horrified look in them, “...The river...”
“The river?”
Tavian stared at his hand and glared in sheer fear “I was in the river because of...” cogs of logic clicked in his mind, “Wait... no...”
“What?”
“The fire... from my nightmare...”
Mirnada looked at him and raised an eyebrow.
Tavian looked back at her, a look of epiphany in his eyes, “Think about it... what if the nightmare is really a memory? What if that really happened to me?”
You said something about a river too...”
“If I managed to escape a house full of fire...”
Mirnada began to follow his logic, “... If you were aflame, the first place you’d go to is a river... I see..”
Tavian paused and realized he might be jumping to conclusions, “I guess it makes sense... but... why can’t I remember any of this...?” Tavian sighed and continued staring into the sky.
“Well y’figured out something about your past...” Mirnada then smirked at him, “who woulda knew that taking a small step in the past woulda been such a big step forward too, eh?”
        “Heh... guess you’re right.” said Tavian, starting to feel a bit optimistic about his realization.
“What d’you remember about yourself? Nothing at all?”
Tavian searched his mind, “... The very first memories I have begin in Ijia... I cannot remember anything before that no matter how hard I try.”
“Well then... what do ya remember? What’s the earliest thing ya can remember clearly?” asked Mirnada curiously.
Tavian laid flat down on the roof and closed his eyes, thinking hard, “The very first thing I can remember... is waking up in Ijia’s infirmary.”


        And then, Tavian’s story began to unfold. He had not said word about himself to anyone, yet he felt like he could trust this red-eyed girl with his dark past.




        IX. An Execrated Existence


        He finally woke up.
        The boy, aged sixteen, opened his eyes slowly to a blurry white world. His sight began to focus and the scanned the small room slowly. He lay in a clean, soft bed in white sheets. The walls were made of white marble and curtains hung over a doorway, glowing in sunlight. Silhouettes of people were seen walking by on the other side. They were talking calmly, but he couldn’t understand what they were saying. He stared at the curtains and watched the shadows move. He tried to move his arms or legs, but they were stiff and sore. He moved his lips but could not speak. The boy lay still, and could only feel the caress of his own breath. He felt a longing for anything, for someone to be by his side. He tried to think about where he was, but nothing came to mind. 
        He listened to the sounds of people walking, and he heard a familiar tune being whistled in the distance. The sound grew louder, as did a pair of footsteps. A shadow came to the curtain and pulled them to the side. A beautiful young girl stepped through the threshold and closed the curtains behind her. She was fairly tall with long, blonde hair. She had full, red lips and a busty bosom wearing a low cut white uniform of some kind. She was carrying a parchment on a thin piece of wood with an inked quill, writing something. The boy heard the squeaking sounds of the feather rubbing against the paper. She placed them both down on a nearby table and then turned towards the boy, he was staring at her attentively with his red-hazel eyes. She was startled, but then composed herself and approached him cautiously, “Oh, you’re awake?” she said in a soft, angelic voice.
The boy tried to speak, but only the sound of air escaping rolled from his lips. 
“Don’t try to strain yourself, just rest. You’ve been through a lot. My name is Verna and you’re in the infirmary in Ijia castle.” she said in a warm voice.
The boy’s mind wandered. He could not think of anything about himself. A final memory flared in his mind, then faded into nothing.
“Tav...ian...” he whispered quietly.
“Hmm?” Verna said, “Tavian?”
A single tear swelled up in his eye, and streamed down the side of his face, as if he just departed from life itself.
Verna took a cloth and wiped his tear away, “There, there, Tavian... You’ll be alright... just rest.”
“Where...” Tavian whispered.
“You’re in Ijia... you washed ashore today and a paladin found you and brought you here. If a town person had found you, you’d be in a less nice hospital somewhere in Ijia’s castle town, so you’re very fortunate.”
Tavian began to feel some feeling in his arms and legs, he tried to sit up in bed, but he felt searing pain in all his muscles, he gasped at the pang and lay down again, giving up.
Whoa, easy, easy there.” Verna put her arms behind his back and helped him sit up. She put some extra pillows behind him and propped him up, “There you go... You seem to be able to eat something and you must be famished. I’ll be right back, don’t try to move, alright?” she went back through the cloth curtain and closed it behind her. 
Tavian looked down at his side and saw his right hand with a large bandage tightly spun around it. He stared at it, not knowing why it was there. He strained to move his left hand over and felt his bandage. It was thick and wrapped many times making his hand look like a bee hive. He was so curious and confused, so he found the loose end and began to tug on it, unraveling his hand. He didn’t even know what he was doing, only one thing was in his mind, to know why he was here. He kept pulling at it, the loose bandages piling to his side, but then something scared him. The ‘hive’ around his hand was very small and at this point, he should have found his hand, but where the hive was, there was nothing. He compared his forearms, and he saw that where his left hand was, his right hand was not.
        He panicked, he didn’t know what to do, he kept pulling at the white bandage, which suddenly stained red. He pulled off the last of the bandages, and saw a stump, hemorrhaging blood all over himself and the white marble walls.
        Verna reentered the room with a glass of water, she saw the white room being stained scarlet with cruor. She shrieked and dropped the glass which shattered on the stone floor.


        Tavian awoke once more, the same room, with his right hand bandaged even tighter and his left hand restrained. The curtain that once danced with silhouettes now only glowed with dim firelight. He remembered the sight of his own blood and felt empty inside.
Verna came into the room, “Awake again?” she asked.
Tavian stared at her blankly.
You gave me quite a scare, so sorry we had to restrain you, but we can’t allow you to injure yourself anymore.” she said, as she approached him. She took out a metal syringe, “I have to give you an injection so your hand doesn’t get infected, alright?”
“... What hand.” Tavian snapped coldly.
Verna felt off put by him, but she continued her duty. She took his right arm and put the thick needle at the edge of his hive bandage, “I’m really sorry, but this is going to hurt... just try to relax until its over, alright?” Tavian stared forward, fearless, emotionless. Verna pushed the needle into his wrist, and slowly injected the fluid. Tavian stared at her, and was unphased by the pain. Verna was quite surprised that he didn’t even flinch at all, “All done.” she said as she wrapped a small bandage on the small puncture. “... I didn’t hurt you, did I?”
        He stared at her, saying nothing.
        Verna gathered the syringe and got up, “Get some rest for the night, alright?”
        Tavian watched as she left and closed the curtains behind her. He felt numbing feeling tingling up from where he had his injection. He laid back and felt himself fading out of consciousness.


        Some time past, he heard voices and his eyes opened once more. He had been awoken, it was all he could do to listen to the conversation.
That boy... The one with the red eyes... Tell me about him.” he heard a woman’s voice say.
        He recognized Verna’s voice responding, “His name’s Tavian. He washed ashore yesterday. He doesn’t talk too much, and apparently he doesn’t react to pain.”
Doesn’t react to pain; what do you mean?”
“His hand had to be removed when he first arrived; half of it was missing already. He doesn’t seem to be in any pain. I also gave him an injection, he didn’t even whimper.”
“Heh, even the most stalwart soldiers fear a syringe rather than a sword. That intrigues me...”
        “... What do you mean?”
        “Which room is he in?”
        “Um... it’s this one right here.”
Tavian heard footsteps approaching him, and he saw a foreboding black shadow cast upon the curtain. It was pulled back and an ominous woman walked in.
        The Virtuous Virgo; a mysterious lady who appeared to be in her late twenties. She walked in an elegant form which betrayed her fearsome strength.  She wore her casual dark cloth tunic and skin tight black leather breeches. Her clothing wasn’t anything fancy, however her beauty, grace and scornful demeanor blatantly made it obvious she was of official stature. Her flowing, long hair was like the darkest scarlet waves from a sea of flowing rubies. It was parted in the middle and falling freely behind her back contrasting her pale, lily white skin bearing scattered battle scars. Her eyes shimmered with silver and gold and had a look of power, ruthlessness, and determination. 
        She closed the curtain behind her and saw Tavian lying in the infirmary bed, staring up at her. She approached him and let out a “Hmm...” 
Tavian’s mind drew a blank. He stayed still in the bed. 
You are Tavian, the one who washed ashore?” she asked.
He was still in a traumatized state; he didn’t know how to react to the question.
She game him a dark look, almost a glare with her silvery eyes, “I know you’re able to speak, answer me. Now.”
... Aye. As far as I’ve been told.” muttered Tavian.
“Hmph...” the woman scoffed. She grabbed Tavian’s right forearm and scrutinized the large bandage, “Hrr... This won’t do...”
“What are you doing?” asked Tavian, confused by her strange words.
The woman firmly poked Tavian’s bandage, “Does that hurt?” Tavian simply shook his head. “I’ve seen countless severed limbs... The men who have lost them howl in pain at the slightest touch, especially if it could still bleed without the tight bandage.”
... So?”
“You felt it though, correct? You felt the pain but did not react to it?”
“I guess...”
The woman glared at Tavian, “Answer my question, boy. Did you feel the sharp pain, but just did not react to it?”
... Aye.” he muttered.
“... Hmm... Interesting.” the woman said as she released Tavian’s arm from her grip.
Tavian had no idea what was going on. Why was this strange woman who seems to lack an inkling of empathy so concerned with this boy who washed ashore out of nowhere was in pain or not, he thought. “... Are you a nurse?” he innocently asked.
        The woman, almost insulted, smirked at Tavian, “Lad, I am someone much more important than a simple nurse.” She stared straight into Tavian’s hazel-red eyes, examining his empty and emotionless gaze, yet he seemed so full of hate and pain deep within, “... I see it in you...” she said, “I see a trembling fire within you... Tavian.”
Who are you?” he asked.
A dark smile was cast on her blood red lips, “General of the Shadow Knights, Azaria Thorne.” she said with a prideful undertone. “Does ‘Tavian’ have a last name?”
He carefully searched his memories, trying to remember anything, “... Tavian...” he thought hard about the significance of this name, what it meant exactly, who ‘Tavian’ was, “... Drakon...”
Tavian Drakon. I see.” Azaria said.
“Why... are you so interested in me? Do you know me?”
“People have been whispering about you all day, ‘the one handed, red eyed boy who washed ashore.’ It sounded peculiar, but what I’m interested in now is how you don’t react to pain.”
Tavian raised an eyebrow, “... What? Why?”
Azaria smirked, “And these eyes of yours... These red eyes...” she stared deep into them, as if to peer into his very soul, “I’ve seen only a few shadow knights who have eyes like these, and they’ve been through countless battles and sacrificed so much. I wonder why you have them... Where are you from, lad?”
Tavian searched his mind once more, and all he saw was blank nothingness; Pure white. “... I don’t know...”
        Azaria was impatient yet intrigued, “You feel nothing... you remember nothing...” she smirked at him, “Heh... and something inside of you... some sort of terrible rage... perfectly controlled...”
        Tavian grew impatient that this strange woman wouldn’t answer his questions, “Why are you so fascinated with me?”
        Azaria knelt to Tavian’s bedside, “You are a blank slate... I want to chisel you into a perfect shadow knight.” a wicked grin befell her face, her eyes widened and flared red.
        A chill of fear ran up Tavian’s spine. This terrifying woman... “What is she going to do to me?” he wondered.


Several weeks later...


And... that’s the last one...” Verna said as she cut out the last suture from the stump of Tavian’s right wrist. “It healed up nicely, I’d say. Finally get to take those bandages and stitches off.
Tavian looked at his stump and sighed. He was no longed in pain, however he was permanently deformed. 
There, there... A new life is just around the corner. You’re completely healed now.” she began to gather the remaining medical instruments and bandages together.
“Ahh, Tavian,” Azaria said as she pushed the cloth curtains aside. She stepped into the room carrying a black box, “fully recovered, are you?”
        “The amputation has healed entirely, and the other injuries he sustained have been treated as well.” said Verna as she stood up holding the tray of old bandages and stitches.
Azaria smiled darkly, “Finally...” Tavian had grown accustomed to Azaria’s wicked smiles. He knew she had always had some sort of ulterior motive out of everything she did, her smiling not excluded. “Nurse, you may leave now.”
Verna nodded to Azaria and stepped out through the curtains. She looked back and locked eyes with Tavian once more before she left; a silent goodbye.
Well, Tavian, congratulations on your recovery...”
Tavian stared at Azaria, “...Thanks...” he felt forced to say.
        Azaria approached him closer and sat down on a nearby chair, “From now on, you have an entirely new life ahead of you; a blank slate.”
What do you mean?” Tavian said, knowing she wasn’t going to be direct with whatever she was after.
        “You remember nothing from where you came from, you barely could speak your name, you were at death’s door, ready to leave this world.” Azaria said, as she held the black box out before her, “However,” Tavian reached forward and took the box from her. It was heavy, yet she held it so effortlessly, “you managed to survive whatever happened to you... and it was so terrible, not even you can remember...” Azaria watched Tavian’s eyes curiously gazed at the box, wondering what was within, “But... the gods chose to give you a second life... and I am your god now.” she grinned grimly at him.
Tavian looked down at the box and opened the top. He stared down into it, examining, fixated, “What... is this?”
“Your new life.”
Tavian looked down inside the black box and viewed its contents: a single black, right hand gauntlet laid out on top of some black clothing. Tavian took out the gauntlet then looked over at Azaria discontented and scoffed, “And what kind of god forgets which hand I had remaining?”
Azaria smirked and snickered, “The kind that works miracles.” she reached out and grabbed Tavian’s right forearm. 
“What are you doing?” he asked, still not certain of what was going on.
Azaria took the black gauntlet and placed it snugly around the stump, the long dark-steel cuff covering about half his forearm. She tightened the black leather straps and firmly secured the gauntlet to him.
“... A prosthetic?”
        “More than a mere prosthetic. Remember, I. Am. God.” She emphasized every word.
Tavian gave her another puzzled look.
Azaria took a dark-steel dagger out from a hilt at her side, “And now, a part of your soul shall forever remain in this gauntlet, Tavian.” she put the tip of the blade on the exposed skin between the gauntlet’s black leather straps. Tavian quickly realized what she was about to do, but before he could protest, Azaria sunk the blade a good inch into his wrist. Tavian felt the sharp blade pierce his flesh. All his limbs flinched and tightened in a reaction to the pain, including the black gauntlet.
What the-!?” Tavian exclaimed. Azaria removed the dagger from his wrist and wiped the blood off on the bed sheets, then reholstered it. Tavian grabbed his wrist with his other hand to try and stop the cruor from flowing. His gauntlet tightened into a fist and relaxed, him getting used to controlling this new hand.
        “The metal is now your flesh, bending to your will until your blood corses no more... and as for this wound...” Azaria tightly grabbed Tavian’s wrist where he was cut, she went silent but looked as though she was concentrating. Suddenly, blood began to trickle from her own wrist like stigmata. She let go of Tavian’s wrist, revealing that his wound was gone. She then lay back in a trance, eyes wide open aglow red. Her arm went limp and fell down to her side, her blood began to flow back into her wound and disappeared, leaving a small scar. The glow in her eyes faded and she seemed to snap back to her senses. Azaria then stood up as if nothing had happened, “... Your training begins at dawn tomorrow.” she then stood from her seat and left the room leaving Tavian in shock and awe.


        This woman... Azaria, the General of the Shadow Knights... how could she have such power? Was she going to train Tavian to be able to work this magick as well? Many thoughts raced through his mind, all of them filled with uncertainty. He had no idea what would unfold and further change his life forever.


“It’s so strange,” Tavian said, looking back over to Mirnada, “I haven’t thought of any of that in such a long time, yet I can remember that to the very last detail...”  He looked up at the aurora had fading away with dawn’s light. The rising morning sun shimmered the clouds like polished silver. Once again, it was the land of pure white.
        “What else happened? What was your training like?” Mirnada asked in her insatiable curiosity.
        “That,” Tavian said as he stood up and tossed his blanked at Mirnada, “Is a story for another time.” he ran to the edge of the roof and jumped off into the soft snow below.
Heh, just as well...” she took the blanket and recklessly jumped off the roof as well, landing gracefully and unharmed. Tavian pushed open he creaky door and left it open as Mirnada walked in after him. 
Oakh was in the kitchen and a lovely aroma wafted through the air. She walked into the living room to see what the sounds were and was most surprised to see Tavian and Mirnada walking in, “And here I thought you both were sound asleep upstairs!” she said while snickering.
“Heh, we gazed at the Aurora until its last breath,” Tavian said, smirking.
        “You never could take your curious eyes off of it, Tavian.” she walked back into the kitchen, “Breakfast will be ready soon, why don’t you both go wake up Diame and Xavier?”
        X. Advent of Awakening


        The five of them sat down at Oakh’s large dining table eating smoked salmon, red tea and strange, hard, red colored bread. They ate the fish alright, but as for the strange bread, only Tavian and Oakh were eating it.
I apologize, but we don’t have that much variety of food here in Desye.” a smiling Oakh broke the sounds of food consumption with her simple words.
“Oh, not at all, everything is delicious!” said Diame. She tried to rip off a piece of the red bread but it was so tough she couldn’t manage it. It slipped out of her hands and into her lap napkin, she quietly placed it back on her plate.
Oakh chuckled and passed Diame a serrated and very sharp knife, “Heh, we can’t raise much livestock because it’s so cold and the only crop we can grow is konjode flowers. We can use it to bake bread, spice and preserve our fish, and weave the hemp into cloth, rope, ...” she continued on.
        Mustering all her strength, Diame was able to carve a piece of the hard bread off the loaf. Xavier and Mirnada stared at her, admiring her courage for trying the konjode bread. Tavian watched while sipping his konjode tea, anticipating something entertaining.
        Diame felt all the eyes on her and lifted up the piece of hard bread. She bit into it and it made a dull yet LOUD crunching sound. She let out a whimper as she felt like she had bitten into a rock. The piece in her mouth moistened and broke off, but the bread was unbearably spicy. Not wanting to be rude, she swallowed it. Her face began to turn the same shade of red as the bread she just ate, “some... water please,” she said in a hoarse voice.
        Everyone was holding back their chuckles, and Tavian nudged his glass of tea closer to Diame who grabbed it and drank it quickly. It had a spicy taste like the bread but not nearly as potent. Her face faded back to her regular fair complexion, except now red with blushing. She sat back relieved.
Oakh jokingly applauded her, “You really didn’t need to eat that to be polite, heh. But konjode grass is a very strong spice that keeps a fire burning within you so you don’t succumb to the cold. The villagers all consume as much of it as they can before they set out to travel.” 
Heh...” Xavier snickered, “Well speaking about traveling, we should head out to search for the tower soon. But before we go, I do think we should know what to expect.... What do you know of the tower?”
Oakh nodded, “Alright then,” she lay back in her seat and began to remember her childhood, “About a hundred or so years ago, Desye was nothing like as it was now. Our kingdom was comparable to Pefali’s magnificence.” she averted her eyes as if she were ashamed, “... And like them, we were wealthy, greedy and arrogant. We felt as though we could be placed on the same pedestal as the gods. I was about twelve years old I believe, that’s when King Desye commanded the tower to be built. When asked why, he said he wanted to offer it to the gods to thank them for their blessings to his kingdom.” 
        She shook her head, remembering terrible things, “So, the tower had begun to be built. Extravagant murals were painted on the walls, finely carved ivory and marble statues, there were eight large ones, one on each floor and one for each god. The tower was truly a sight to behold, and it continued to be built upon. King Desye was very old and the tower would take generations to complete, so unfortunately, the great king passed away and left the project to the naïve prince, King Desye II. The young king was even more arrogant than his father, and he longed to see the tower completed. He forced people to continually work on it, all day and all night. More of the kingdom’s riches were poured into the construction of the tower, more labor was provided, and not a moment went by without construction being done. The kings zeal grew as did the tower, and the laborers were paid a ridiculous amount of money. He figured, the sooner the tower was built the sooner we could all receive a huge reward from the gods.” she looked down at the floor in disgust, “How stupid he was...” she said, shaking her head.
Many people worked much harder and faster in pursuit of the riches they were promised. There were more accidents made in their haste and many, many people died from working to sheer exhaustion. But when someone died, another was hired to replace him. One after another, people died from working on the tower. Those who weren’t involved in the construction were waiting near the tower for someone to die and they could take their place. They neglected their other duties so they could be paid so much more, farmers stopped farming and people were starving, doctors stopped healing the ones injured from building the tower. Everyone wanted to work on the tower to make money, it was insane!” she closed her eyes and remembered the last chapter in her story,
        “... Finally, the tower was finished. Nearly half the population died as a result of either working or starving to death. The king arose to the top, proud of the tower and sure the gods would be pleased. Walking on top of the clouds, he knelt before the huge idol of Evaz'Sa, our Goddess of the Sun. ‘Behold, your reward ye gods!’ he said proudly. Evaz’Sa herself then descended from the sky and parted the clouds, and she stood before him, enraged. She cared not for all the statues or how lavishly decorated the tower was, all she said to King Desye II was, ‘How dare ye offer a tower overfloweth with thine own blood!’ Evaz’Sa then flew back to her place in the clouds and took a deep breath. When she exhaled, her breath froze the king solid as he stood. The winds then stirred throughout the whole northern continent, this turned Desye into the infamous wintry world it is now. It's as though Evaz'Sa was sick of the rivers of blood that flowed from the tower and the piling dead. I wonder if it was the dead's stench that got her attention in her first place. Anyway, a great eternal blizzard was cast upon the whole land, blanketing in white our blood stained land. It was thought that Desye would ne'er not see the end of the horror and gore until this day. Though the snow covered and helped the land regain some purity, it's toll was the freezing of what little crops we had left and killing many people. This was our punishment and we justly deserved it. We desperately tried to survive, but many more of our population died out. Eventually, we figured out how to live simple lives here in Desye with the few people who survived or didn’t flee. But then... the gods created a daemon. Evaz’Sa descended to the world once again and I watched in horror as she formed it out of the bones and rotting flesh of the people who had died. It was surreal; I saw a nightmare unfold right before my very eyes. The animated bones and flesh hulked together into terrible behemoth. It was put to sleep inside the tower, and Evaz'Sa declared that it was always watching our every move... If we ever went back to our wicked ways or committed any sins, the daemon would awaken and destroy us all...”
        Oakh looked up at them with terrible fear in her dead eye, “The Daemon of the Tower of the Gods... Fa’Mes the Watcher.”
Fa’Mes...?” Diame whispered to herself, “I swear, I’ve heard that name before... hm...”
Oakh continued, “The daemon is sealed within the tower... I could feel him gradually gaining strength the last several years. Each day I felt its presence looming over me greater. It’s only a short matter of time before it will break its own seal...”
Well then,” Xavier said, “we have to purge the world of this daemon immediately.”
        “Don’t be a fool. It may not be fully awake, but its strength is still quite formidable.” Oakh said, staring at Xavier.
“But, Xavier’s right.” added Tavian, “Fa’Mes may be a challenge now if we four fought it, however at the rate it’s gaining strength, it may become unstoppable even by an army.”
Oakh sighed and stared downwards, “... I’m just concerned for your safety... But I guess you’ve made up your mind.” she put her hands behind her head and unlatched her necklace. She stared at the symbol carven on the stone and then looked up, “This is Fa’Mes’s emblem. If it touches the seal, you’ll free Fa’Mes, but there’s no other way to battle the daemon unless it breaks the seal itself.” she stood up, as did the others, and she approached Tavian, “Guard this carefully...” Tavian held out his steel hand and Oakh placed the emblem inside it.
“Aye,” Tavian said with a nod. 


The four armed themselves and prepared for whatever awaited them. Westward bound, clad in thick coats, they bravely marched through the snow and against the wintry winds to search for the ancient Tower of the Gods. Oakh stood outside her house, watching them fade into the white flurry.


        Several hours had passed, the four saw something dark and foreboding through the thick veil of snow. It reached the heavens and cast down a black shadow, tainting the land of pure white. 
That must be it...!” Diame said, though she couldn’t believe her eyes.
They continued to cautiously approach it, in awe of its sheer size. Towering high above them, it reached beyond the sky and heavens. Xavier drew closer to the black shadow’s edge carefully. Reaching out his hand, he placed it within the darkness. His hand remained aglow as if in the direct sunlight; no shadow cast upon him. 
What in the world...?” he took a step forward into the shadow, remaining untouched by the dark tendrils. “The shade is black as death, yet harmless.” he continued walking towards the tower’s crumbling entrance.
Mirnada and Tavian stepped into the black shadow, and also remained unfazed. They followed Xavier towards the towering tower.
        Diame remembered her vision; freezing to death in front of this very tower. She shuddered at the thought and gathered her wits and took a step forward on to the blackened earth. The moment she entered, her body began to glow a bright white, contrasting the dark shadow surrounding her. She gasped in surprise, her companions turning around sharing her reaction. The light emanated and spread around her, cutting through the darkness with an aura of white.
Diame?!” Xavier said as he hurried back to her, “Diame, are you alright?!”
The priestess stared at herself, observing the shadow melting away; the snow purified by her light. 
How did’ja do that?!” Mirnada asked, watching the snowy white ground being restored under her feet.
“I- I didn’t do anything...!” Diame said, flustered.
Suddenly, the earth began to quake. A low, deep grumble shattered the silence.
The growl was loud and long, shaking snow from the trees and knocking the four off their balance onto their hands and knees. Finally, the tremors subsided, and again only the sound of falling snow was heard.
It seems our presence is known.” Tavian said, cautiously standing back up.
“Really, ya think?!” Mirnada snapped at him, “Wot the ‘ell is in here? An’ can we really stand a chance against it?!”
Xavier’s emerald eyes scanned around and saw no foe, and peered into the depths of darkness within the tower’s stone threshold. “Whatever awaits within...” he drew his silver blade from the oak holster, “we must slay it. I’m convinced Diame’s visions are indeed premonitions, and if the daemon truly is of this magnitude...”
Right,” Tavian interrupted, drawing his dark-steel blade as well, “We must destroy it. Its power grows ever strong, we have our one chance here and now.”
The four stepped into the darkness, Diame’s glowing aura shone brightly, revealing the faded, detailed murals and long-weathered intricate statues. At the base of the largest statue was gold plating, the etching nearly all worn away. Mirnada approached with her child-like curiosity, “Midnight Seductress, Vak’Syla...?”
The statues in the tower were offerings to the gods.” Tavian said, approaching the deity’s marble likeness, “Vak’Syla, the Goddess of Darkness. There’s one each floor for each god.” he shook his head in shame, “The ancient Desyens... truly were fools... wasting the entire kingdom’s wealth like this.”
Along the walls were a stone staircase spiraling along side it. The stairs were crumbling and unable to be climbed. The stairs leading to the basement, however, were intact. 
Hmm... Over here...” said Xavier as he walked towards the staircase, the others followed. The light surrounding Diame illuminated the dark basement, all that was below were two giant doors made of dark-steel blocked with a large metal bar. As they approached the doors, a terrible stench crept out of the wall cracks. “In here perhaps?” Xavier placed his hand against the door; it was cold as death and sent shivers up his spine. He quickly removed his hand and stepped back. He reached up to the thick metal beam barring the door. He pushed up with all his might to no avail; it was rusted to the door. Tavian stood by him and tried to lift it as well, but failed to make a single budge and they both gave up simultaneously. Xavier sighed disdainfully; Tavian kicked the door out of frustration.
        “I’ll have to focus my arcane magick into my strength,” said Tavian, “I should be able to break the bar off then.” he closed his eyes and began to concentrate and boil up his anger to fuel his might.
        “Hm...” Mirnada pushed herself past Tavian and stared at the metal bar.
        “What are you doing Mirnada?” Xavier inquired while Tavian glared at her.
She extended her hand and felt the cold bar. 
Girl, you’ve been a burden ever since you started tagging along.” Tavian said, scornfully, “You’re inept yet you dare cast me aside?”
        “Master... you put your faith in me...” she muttered, “I’ll put mine in you.” she took a deep breath and raised her open hand over the middle of the bar. With a quick yell, she struck downwards, her hand instantly engulfed in a red flame. The metal bar’s center became red hot and split in half as her hand swiftly moved through it. 
Mirnada knelt down to catch her breath. She stared at the door in disbelief, then she snickered to herself. “... Heh...” she stared at her hand, the flames surrounding it faded away. 
The others were surprised as well, Xavier looked over to Tavian, “Where did you find this girl?”
        Tavian felt silent, then moved towards the door. He pulled on one of the bars attached to the door. The door was heavy, Xavier came beside him and pulled as well. With a loud, rusty creak, the door opened and the pungent odor of death filled the air.
The glow from Diame’s aura lit past the door, revealing a stone staircase leading deeper underground into the dark depths. Xavier peered inside, covering his nose with the thick fur coat. 
Wot is that awful smell?” Mirnada said, standing to her feet and peering in as well.
“Rotten flesh...” Tavian said with disgust. It was a stench he was well familiar with from his time spent on the battlefield. “This is where the bodies of the workers were stored.”
Diame approached the staircase, “It’s down here... I can feel the daemon’s presence.” a sudden chill ran up her spine, she gasped and fell to her knees. Her eyes wide open, she looked around. Her three companion’s bodies lay around her, covered in blood and limbs ripped apart. She stared at her own body, wounds began to open and cruor flowed out, she let out a piercing scream.
Diame!” Xavier shouted, shaking her, “What’s the matter? What happened?!”
Diame’s hands were shaking, her speech stuttered, “W-what was...” she stood to her feet with Xavier’s aid, “I saw something... It didn’t feel like a premonition, it felt more like an image forced into my mind... the three of you were dead and gore was strewn about...”
It’s toying with us.” Tavian muttered, “Fa’Mes is trying to deter you from your path. Don’t let fear grip you; it’s only an illusion.”
Diame nodded, “Aye...” she stopped leaning onto Xavier, “I’m alright.”
Xavier nodded to Diame, then cautiously began descending the stairs, sword drawn and ready in a battle stance.
        Tavian followed him, his dark-steel blade brandished as well.
Diame and Mirnada descended behind them. The four crept down the stairs carefully. They finally reached the bottom, the staircase led into a wide open room. Countless bones and fleshy, decomposing bodies piled high lined the walls. The sight and odor was unbearable. A pathway was cleared leading straight ahead, the four traveled down the path, disturbed by their sickening surroundings. They saw a large crevasse up ahead, covered by a layer of what appeared to be glowing, blue glass. It was etched in intricate designs and the glass’s effulgence ebbed making a low humming sound with every pulse. 
“What in the world...?” Diame said as she approached the chasm. She peered into it, seeing only darkness.
        “Hm?” Tavian saw a light coming from his coat pocket. He reached inside and took out the Emblem that Oakh gave him, holding it by its chain. It was aglow with a blue light and it moved like something was tugging it towards the glass over the chasm. “The emblem... its reacting. This must be the seal!” Suddenly the chain was pulled taut, and the emblem pointed directly to the glass. A ray of sapphire light shot out of the emblem and absorbed into the glass. 
        “Whoa, wot was tha’?” Exclaimed Mirnada.
The necklace, with its power now gone, dangled down from its chain. Tavian grabbed the emblem with his steel hand, and it crumbled into sand. “Ah! It’s gone?”
        The ebbing light from the glass glowed brighter than ever, and then a thin crack started to form across it. The crack started to branch out until the glass looked like a spider web. Then, the barrier slowly melted and bulged into the hole, suddenly shattering into countless fragments. The four peered over the edge, watching the shards drift down into the endless abyss. There was a dead silence except for the sounds of chiming glass. The four looked around them; it appeared that the room was shrinking. 
Those piles of bodies... are they moving closer?!” Diame said as they panicked.
A terrible sound echoed out of the chasm; the emanation of countless voices screaming in a haunting cadence. The ground began to quake with a violent fury. Large chunks of the stone ceiling began to crumble and fall around them. The countless bones and bodies writhed and squirmed towards the pit. The flesh began to melt and then congealed around bones... a silhouette of a terrifying beast took form.
What in gods’ name?!” Xavier exclaimed, dodging past a pile of rotten flesh flowing by him. The tower began to shake with an even greater intensity, nearly knocking them off balance. 
“We must flee! Now!” Tavian shouted, “The tower will collapse at any moment!” 
Xavier and Tavian sheathed their weapons, then the four turned away from the pit and ran with fervent urgency. Jumping over the bodies blocking the way and dodging the falling debris, they hurried to the staircase. Another terrible howl was heard from the pit. 
        Diame turned her head back and gazed in horror. The body of a daemon wrought of decaying flesh and twisted bones hovered over the pit, ever growing in mass. She screamed in horror and averted her eyes from the grotesque monster. Up the stairs they ran, avoiding the falling rubble. 
        They made it through the open double metal doors. Xavier stopped and looked back to ensure the others’ safety up the stairs. He motioned towards the second flight of stairs back to the first floor and the exit, “This way! Hurry!” He yelled. The four raced up the stairs. Mirnada was first up them, followed by Tavian. Xavier waited for Diame to safely begin ascending the stairs before he followed. A sudden shockwave unbalanced the four once again. A large stone loosed from above and fell towards the stairs below, directly above Diame. She looked up, daunted, and froze in fear.
“Diame! Move!” Xavier shouted, charging towards her. He tackled her just as the giant stone fell, narrowly avoiding being crushed as well. The rock crumbled as it landed and collapsed the staircase below them. The two escaped death with nary of a breadth of a single moment.
        “Xavier! Diame!” Tavian shouted as he and Mirnada ran back to them through the billows of dust.
Xavier quickly composed himself and got to his feet, crouching and about to help up Diame. “Are you harmed?” 
Diame tried to stand then screamed in pain, “Ah...! M-my leg...” the dust began to clear and Xavier saw Diame’s leg crushed under large chunks of rock and bloody rubble. 
“Oh god!” Mirnada exclaimed, nearly in tears by the sight of her fallen friend.
Tears streamed down Diame’s pale face; the pain was unbearable. Xavier frantically began lifting up the pieces of rubble off her leg and chucked them aside. The large slab of stone he tried to lift, but it was too heavy to budge. Tavian quickly came to his aid and they began to push it up with all the strength they could muster. It was so massive, they could only lift it barely a width of a hair. “AH! Stop! Please!” Diame yelled, then let out another scream of pain. Their muscles continued to strain with fierce determination, they had to save her.
        Mirnada began to shake. The sight of blood always unnerved her, and now to see it bleeding from a friend was nearly unbearable. The urgency of all this, if they all didn’t leave immediately, they would all die. She watched Xavier and Tavian trying as hard as they can to save her, risking their own lives. She stood there, her skin pale white, helpless. She remembered the comforting voice of her master. “You can do it, Mirnada. Trust me. Trust yourself.” She found new resolve and shook off her fear. Mirnada marched to the rock slab between Xavier and Tavian. She pulled back her fist, took a deep breath, and let out a yell. Her fist engulfed in red flames once more, she sent the rock flying, shattering it to mere molten pebbles. 
        The others had no time for awe. Diame’s leg was now uncovered, revealing her half protruding tibia. Any treatment was impossible here, especially with imminent death looming seconds away. Tavian interlocked his arms with Diame’s, carrying her with their backs together. A terrible, booming collapsing sound from high above was heard, followed by another, and another. The floors were collapsing, one by one on top of each other in a chain reaction.
“We must leave! Now! Not another moment to spare!” Tavian shouted as he leapt up the stairs carrying Diame. Xavier and Mirnada quickly followed. They made it back to the first floor. They ran to the bright sunlight pouring in from the exit. The ceiling from the second floor collapsed onto the ceiling which began to cave in just above them. Tavian and Diame made it out into the fresh, cold air in the clouded sunlight. Xavier made it out safely, Mirnada was a few feet away from the door with thousands of tons of stone inches above her head. She ducked and kicked off the ground, leaping out from the entrance into the daylight. A loud crash of stone echoed throughout the mountains, followed by a final couple more crashes as the basement and sub basement caved in. All that was left of the tower was the outer walls about to crumble themselves.
The four had no time to catch their breath. The tower could easily fall over and crush them still. They raced through the snow, the wind at their backs. The earth trembled, the four kept running but looked back. A gigantic set of claws shot up out of the ground and side of the tower, sending a flurry of earth, rock and snow into the air. The claw was black and green, oozing with dark blood and nails made of fused, sharpened bone. The claw sank into the ground and the daemon began to dig itself out of the earth. The side of the tower gone, it began to lean over and crumble apart in mid air, stirring the clouds.
        A chasm ripped apart in the earth, another arm reached up and they lifted the whole body out of the earth. The daemon Fa’Mes arose from the ground, standing in front of the tower as it collapsed behind him. The grotesque creature was made of the rotting flesh and decaying bones of the countless bodies fused together into a single living, breathing monstrosity. 
        It had two long, thin arms made of the dark-green, rotting flesh with oversized claws as hands made of bone. Its abdomen was a spine and bare ribs. The ribs were connected together with a thin lair of blood red flesh, pulsating underneath it in the center of the chest was a black, fleshy heart. The spine had bits of flesh hanging off of it. The legs were thin like the arms and had flat, claw-like feet. The head of the beast had three mouths, one in the bottom center, and the other two just above it, one on the left and one on the right. They all were lined with rows of razor sharp, curved, white, pointed teeth. It had one very wide, oval eye in the center. It was white and blood shot with blue veins with no iris, only a single, diamond shaped, black pupil. It stood about three stories tall of the tower, if the tower were still standing. Its three mouths opened and the flesh on its neck began the writhe. It unleashed three simultaneous low bellows. The sound carried on throughout the land. Fa’Mes let it be known that he lives. Its eye scoured the world before him. It saw the four fleeing from and an uncontrollable rage filled it. It began to run towards them, walking along the path of Diame’s blood.
“It’s coming!” Diame shouted watching it follow them.
Xavier stopped and faced it, drew his blade and moved into his fighting stance, “Get Diame out of here!” He shouted, “I will stay Fa’Mes as long I can!”
        Tavian and Mirnada stopped and faced him.
“Not alone you won’t.” Tavian motioned his head to Mirnada, “Take Diame and get out of here.” Mirnada nodded. 
Tavian stood upright and Diame rested on her uninjured leg while Mirnada went under her arm and helped her walk. Mirnada helped Diame hop away. Tavian and Xavier stood side by side, blades drawn, the terrible daemon charging towards them with bloodlust in its eye.
“How the hell are we supposed to defeat this thing, let alone hold it off?!” Tavian yelled.
        “I’ve no idea, but we’d best figure it out quickly!” Xavier retorted.
They both charged towards Fa’Mes, closing the distance. Xavier held out his blade and focused into his magick. Tendrils of white and blue lightning wrapped around his blade. Tavian concentrated his mind into a rage, His eyes quickly became aglow the accursed blood red from the urgency of the moment. Xavier swung his blade, bolts of lightning shot out from the blade, striking the beast at a distance. 
        Fa’Mes continued his approach, unassailed by the attack. It was close enough and it swung at Xavier with its gigantic claw. Xavier jumped back and dodged the blow. The claw landed in the snow, sending plumes of powder up into the air. Tavian was filled with the vehement rage and arcane magick, adding to his strength. He lunged his dark-steel claymore at Fa’Mes’s claw in the ground. The blade embedded into the daemon’s flesh and he pulled it through to split its clawed hand in half, spilling black blood all over the white, snowy earth. Fa’Mes lifted its wounded hand up and slung blood about. It let out another scornful, hideous roar. It darted its head forth towards Tavian, its mouths wide open. Tavian held up his blade and faced the broadside to his foe. He Held the hilt with his hand and grabbed near the end with his steel hand. The daemon’s head drew closer, mouth gaped wide to shred Tavian apart. Tavian held his blade with all his might against Fa’Mes’s sharp teeth to stay its deadly bite. 


        Diame hobbled away from the battle with the aid of Mirnada. They put a fair amount of safe distance between them and the daemon, but for only as long as Xavier and Tavian could stay the beast. 
        Limping along, Diame could bear the excruciating pain no longer, “Oh, stop! ... I cannot go... any further...!” she said while gasping. Diame let out a yelp of pain. 
        Mirnada laid Diame down in the snow, looking back at the trail of blood behind them. She looked at Diame, her face was even paler than the snow. Diame began to shake uncontrollably, losing so much blood. The broken bone still protruded from her leg, the red still flowing ever contrasting the surrounding white.         “Diame?! Can you speak?!” Mirnada said in a panic.
Diame lay with her copper hair laid out in the snow, her crimson blood flowing endlessly. She began to gasp for air, her eyes wide open, glazed, the life in them fast fading. 
“... Please... say somethin’!” Mirnada screamed, hopelessly. “I can’t... I can’t let yeh die... please... hold on...” she was met with only silence. She looked into the distance and saw Xavier and Tavian, exhausted, yet fighting the monstrosity with steadfast resolve to protect herself and Diame. Her mind felt like it was on fire, tears streamed down her face, freezing as they met her cheeks. “I... wot can I do...?” she muttered, then hung her head covering her face with her hands, “Master... 'elp me.” she took a deep breath, and cleared her mind, “If I 'ave Jorgard magick... please will this to work.” she moved her hands and pushed down on the bone, forcing it back into place. As her hands met the bone, they were aflame in violet light. As she pushed, the bone mended and the blood stopped its flow. The torn flesh healed and the skin reformed. The violet light flowed from her leg and began to encompass her whole body. The color in her already fair skin was restored and her shivering quelled. 
Mirnada remembered the familiar violet light as it once healed her. She still didn’t understand this gift she had, or even how she used it. She looked at her hands in disbelief as the violet flames faded away.
        Diame began to breathe normally, and their eyes met, “... Mirnada?”
        Mirnada, relieved, collapsed onto Diame and began to sob, “Yer alright... yer alright...”
        Diame began to sit up, “My wound...? What happened?”
Mirnada sat up as well, then helped Diame to her feet, “I’ll tell ya later, can ya stand?”
        Diame stood on both feet, barely, “Aye... my leg still hurts, but I can walk.” they looked back at Tavian and Xavier fighting the daemon, “Oh god... How are they keeping Fa’Mes at bay?”
They’re doin’ it to protect ya...” Mirnada said, turning towards her, “An’ me too.”
Diame watched the battle in the distance, “We must aid them...”
        Mirnada shook her head, “No, Diame, not when yer still hurt. Get back t’ Desye, warn Oakh... I’ll help ‘em.”
“But I-“
        “Go! You c’n walk, I’ll help ‘em! Jus’ do it!”
        “Aye...” Diame said reluctantly. She began to limp through the snow, eastward bound.
Mirnada quickly ran back to join the battle. 


        Xavier charged magick into his sword again and swung it fervently several times, firing bolts of lightning at Fa’Mes that exploded in a small plume of white fire with every strike. The daemon turned toward him and bellowed, Tavian ran up to the distracted Fa’Mes and stood under its ribcage. He looked up and saw the black heart, beating and writhing unnaturally. He leapt up into the air, sword arched, and cleaved his blade through the dark flesh mass. It cut open, spilling out its vile blood. Tavian landed behind the daemon as it let out another ear splitting scream.
        Fa’Mes stepped to the side and took a moment to recover its balance from the devastating attack. It turned to face both Tavian and Xavier, and glowered scornfully at them. It raised its head and looked through the snow for an easier prey, it saw Diame in the distance and Mirnada approaching closer. Xavier looked back, and saw Diame walking uninjured. He paused in confusion for a moment, and Fa’Mes raised his arm and swiped at Xavier. He looked back only to see the claw strike him, flinging him aside. He landed on his back and slid though the snow a distance away, his sword landing in the ground nearby.
        Tavian wasn’t daunted seeing the daemon incapacitate his comrade. It only increased his hatred for this detestable creature, ergo increasing his strength. He reached out his hand as if to grab something. The blood pouring from Fa’Mes’s heart began to flow toward Tavian. He held out his claymore, and the daemon’s blood surrounded his blade. It began to form serrated spikes along the edges and then froze in place. Fa’Mes let out another terrible roar from its three mouths. It gazed at Tavian with its one eye with nothing but scorn. 
        Fa’Mes suddenly leapt forward with an arm outstretched, claws poised at Tavian. Tavian stood readily and grinned with bloodlust. He jumped into the air just as the claw dug into the ground. He landed on top of its hand and deeply embedded his sword into Fa’Mes’s arm. He twisted the blade and some of the frozen spikes of blood broke off into the wound. Fa’Mes tried lifting his arm but it was immobilized. Tavian pulled his blade out and sliced through the undead flesh. The daemon reached his other claw to Tavian to pull him off, but Tavian evaded and landed back on the snowy ground. Fa'Mes’s arm was hanging halfway by a thin mass of flesh. It’s claw grabbed the useless limb and tore it off, tossing it at Tavian. He swung his sword and deflected the claw. 


        Mirnada ran up to Xavier as he lay dazed in the snow. She lifted him up and tried to snap him out of it, “Xavier? Are ya alright?”
        Xavier looked around him and grunted, “Aye...” He stood to his feet with Mirnada’s help, “Where’s Diame? Was she walking or have I gone mad?”
        Mirnada shook her head, “Nah, she’s fine, trust me. We gotta ‘elp Tavian though.”
        Xavier nodded and picked up his sword in the snow and they ran to Tavian’s side.
        Fa’Mes took a step back and took a moment to scrutinize the three unfamiliar creatures before it. The daemon had underestimated them. The strength they had to protect Diame truly was formidable, and finally, the daemon recognized it.
“What ails you, daemon?!” Tavian taunted.
Fa’Mes opened its three mouths and out poured a dark blue flame that flowed like plumes of mist across the snow. The three tried to jump out of the way, but it quickly engulfed Tavian and Xavier. Mirnada was able to escape the blue flames and watched in horror. Tavian and Xavier fell to their knees and writhed in excruciating pain. They weren’t burned by this cold fire, but they felt the paralyzing pain of countless deaths.
        Mirnada could only watch helplessly as they screamed in agony. The flames dissipated and they lay on the ground, silently, unable to move. Fa’Mes approached Mirnada as she cowered in the snow. She could only shake in fear as Fa’Mes loomed over her and let out another bellow. Its one eye gazed over her then it saw Diame limping in the distance. 


        Diame looked back and saw her fallen comrades and Fa’Mes’s one eye seething her in the distance. She began to breathe heavily in fear, and limped her injured body as fast as she could away from the daemon. Fa’Mes began to run crouched like a beast using its one arm like a third leg. Each kick off it made as it ran sent tremors throughout the ground. Diame desperately strained herself to hold the distance between them, but Fa’Mes quickly closed the gap. A tremor from the colossus knocked Diame over onto her back. She tried to stand up again but the quaking was too intense. Fa'Mes stood over her, its mouths open, ready to devour her. She could only raise a quivering arm in her defense.
“Oh god...” Diame could only utter. Tears steamed down her face. She was helpless. Her body suddenly began to glow the same pure white aura as before. Fa’Mes raised its head and then lunged it forward, its mouths wide open. The white wisps of her aura floated above her and concentrated into a bright sphere of candescent white. Time seemed to stand still as Diame looked above her and merely stared up on it. Though moments before her certain death, all seemed to be forgotten. She gazed with innocent curiosity at the immaculate light. It suddenly shot forth into a pillar of illumination straight through Fa’Mes’s chest, burning a large hole and reducing his heart to burnt cinders. The beam of light then bent upwards and vanished into the sky.
Fa'Mes fell backwards and bellowed a terrible howl. He collapsed onto its back with such force the earth shook as if being torn asunder. Diame was disoriented yet cautiously got to her feet. Fa’Mes repeatedly let out pitiful roars as it flailed its limbs. Diame stared at the daemon as it desperately clung to life. She dared not approach it. A low, rumbling sound boomed from the heavens. Diame raised her head and gasped in shock. She ran away from Fa’Mes as fast as she could as countless beams of light rained from above. Each beam was poised towards the daemon and all crashed to the ground making a devastating explosion, incinerating Fa’Mes body into obliteration. The barrage of light continued to fall behind Diame as she ran following the trail of blood back to the others. 
        
        Mirnada was watching the light raining and trembling with every explosion that shook the ground. Xavier and Tavian seemed to have shaken off the flames’ curse that was torturing them and watched in awe of the surreal sight. At last, the final beam of light crashed into the ground where only a flurry of snow and ashes remained.
“What in the world?!” Xavier said, as he stood to his feet. He scoured the snow around him, and his charge was nowhere. “Diame!?” he saw the plumes of ash and snow and thought the worst had befallen her. He ran towards it in a panic, scanning through the haze for Diame. Suddenly the ash and snow shone with blindingly bright, vibrant blue effulgence. He took a step back in caution and bewilderment. Then, the shadow of Diame’s silhouette approached him through the haze. “Diame!” Xavier shouted, running over to her as she became visible outside of the fog. With her last strength she mustered to let out a whimper, and then collapsed into Xavier’s arms. He held her tightly; safely. 
The light grew brighter and a sudden squall rushed through the snowy field. Xavier held Diame as he tried to hold his footing against the snowy torrent. The blue light concentrated into a single glowing orb. The light floated up into the sky as if carried by the strong winds. The clouds parted in the sky above them; blown apart by the gale. 
The clouds dissipated and the force of the wind stopped. They gazed upwards in disbelief at the clear blue sky, swathed in the sun’s warm rays. The silence was tranquil yet terrifying. Mirnada and Tavian couldn’t take their eyes off the blue, glowing mass of light ascending to the heavens. Xavier watched the light as he held a shaking Diame fast in his arms. It rose beyond the sky until it became no more than a speck of light. A new blue star now in its sky throne; a mere glint in the daylight.
        XI. The Arcane Axiom


        Diame lay unconscious on the couch in Oakh’s living room. Covered in blankets and basking in the warm firelight, yet her skin was pale and cold as ice. She breathed very deeply and she sweat as though she had a deathly fever. She let out whimpers in her sleep and mumbled nonsense. Oakh dutifully sat on a chair by her side with a damp cloth and wiped off the cascading sweat.
“Poor dear...” Oakh said as she dipped the cloth into a nearby bowl of warm water. She rang it out and put it back on Diame’s forehead. Oakh then clasped Diame’s corpselike hand with her own. With her other hand she hovered it over Diame’s face, and took a deep breath. Oakh moved her lips but made barely a whisper. A silent prayer she made earnestly.
“Ya need any more ‘elp?” Mirnada said as she brought out a hot kettle of freshly brewed konjode tea and set it down on the nearby table.
Oakh stayed silent as she continued her prayer. She opened her earth and snow eyes and turned to Mirnada. “Nay, dear child. But, pray stay nigh.”
“Aye, alright.” Mirnada said with a nod. She sat down on the wooden floor next to Oakh. She could only watch Diame as Oakh nursed her. She noticed the eerie ambience in the room. The only sounds were of the low growls of the flames and Diame’s slow, heavy breathing. The whispers of the prayer Oakh was making... the words she uttered were almost unworldly, and only added to the heavy mood. The occasional crackling of the logs broke the macabre atmosphere. 
Oakh finished her prayer and took a deep breath, once again opening her odd eyes. She watched Diame laying there at the brink of death and felt her heart in a vice. “A lass so young... forced such a cruel fate...” Oakh muttered to herself. “I entreat you...” she said in a very serious voice.
        Mirnada looked up, losing her fixation on the awkward environment, “Hm?” she turned to Oakh who quietly stared at Diame.
        Oakh took a deep breath, “... What wickedness fell up on her...” she said as she turned towards Mirnada. Oakh had a calm and solemn expression, but the reflection of fire in her white eye chilled Mirnada. “What happened...”
        Mirnada saw the deep concern Oakh expressed. She composed herself, “’er leg was crushed...” Mirnada remembered the horror of that sight, “an' all that white snow was stained red with 'er blood...”
Oakh looked down at Diame with a confused look, “What say you...?” she knew her leg bore no sign of injury. 
My master... he taught me magick.” She said gazing down at her hands. “’er leg’s wound’s closed... ‘n the bone’s nearly ‘ealed.”
“I see...” Oakh poured herself a cup of the hot, deep red tea and paused as she tried to articulate all at once, “... Hm... Marshall was your master, was he?”
        “Aye.” Mirnada nodded. “I’m still becomin’ akin t’ this new strength, bu’ I got ‘er back from bein’ whiter ‘an a ghost.” Mirnada paused, remembering the moment Diame’s life dwindled, “She... she almos’ died... an’ I don’ even know ‘ow I saved ‘er...”
“Child, have you ever heard the word aethermancy?” Oakh said, sipping her spicy hot tea.
        “Aye, Marshall did a few times durin' my trainin'. Didn't really explain wot it was b'sides it means I could use magick.” Mirnada said, staring over at Diame's healed leg, “An' iuno 'ow to use it really, or even wot I can do with it.” She paused and thought about her physical strength and celerity prowess, then continued, “'e was trainin' me how t' fight. 'e even said I could already use magick... and through 'is trainin'...” she remembered her long years of training, the boulders she could break with her bare fist, and that fire within her she now burned with. That power of healing she had and never knew. The jump and how she flew through the air to escape from being crushed in the tower. “'e said this was all Jorgard magick.”
        “The Forbidden Lands?” both Oakh's eyes widened. Her brown, earth colored eye cast a look of fear, while her cataract eye gazed emotionless and reflected naught but the light of the fire in it's dead pupil. “I knew... I knew it. Your eyes, and you're Marshall's apprentice...” she leaned back and closed her own eyes, “To think I would ever meet not one but two people in this lifetime from there.”
Mirnada was taken aback. Marshall never did tell her about Jorgard, but she knew that just from being there made her stand out in many ways, from her appearance to her magick.
“Unh...” Diame muttered, and her breathing seemed less labored. 
Oakh and Mirnada both turned their attention back to Diame as her eyes opened slowly. They leaned in over her and Diame saw the two's faces looking over her with cautious relief.
“Thank God...” Oakh said as she sat back and exhaled her bated breath.
Diame looked around, dazed. “Oh...” her mind began regaining consciousness. Memories of what just transpired flooded into her mind. The tower collapsing on her, the grotesque daemon chastised in brilliant light. She felt the warmth of the fire and the nursing care of Mirnada and Oakh and knew she was safe. “Madame Oakh... Mirnada...” she slowly strained to sit up with all her strength.
“C-careful, dear...” Oakh helped Diame sit upright on the couch. 
Diame was dizzy still, but she sat and looked down at her once broken leg in disbelief. She remembered the sensation of that excruciation, now nothing more than phantom pain. “My leg...” she leaned down and clasped hands on her limb where her bone once protruded. She felt her smooth healed skin, the firmness of her shin... it was sore, but the bone had been completely mended. The only conclusion she muttered, “Was it all a dream?” she said staring up at Mirnada.
        Mirnada shook her head and said nothing. She helped Diame sit back up.
“It may not be the right time... but I must know...” Oakh leaned forward on the edge of her seat, “What befell all ye once Fa’Mes awoke?”
Mirnada had the vivid memories, freshly burned into her mind. “Th’ pendant ya gave Tavian... The daemon’s Emblem broke th’ seal. All th’ corpses in the basement melded as one, that’s ‘ow he appeared.” Oakh blinked in disbelief for a moment, then shuddered for she knew Mirnada spoke the truth. Diame slowly remembered as Mirnada continued. “Th' tower collapsed... Fa'Mes arose from th' ground... Tavian 'n Xavier stayed it...” Oakh listened, overwhelmed by what she was hearing, “Th'n, Diame fell... an'...” Mirnada began to shake and looked at her hands, “I... I 'ealed 'er wound... an' iuno how... but, Diame came back... an' she...” Mirnada looked over to Diame, “an'... she made beams o' light rain fr'm th' sky... an' poof... there lay Fa'Mes slain.”
Diame gasped and her eyes widened, she looked up at Oakh whose mouth was wide agape in awe.
“I-I saw that light!” Oakh said, “T-truly, Diame? Ye summoned that holy cascade and that is what vanquished Fa'Mes?”
Diame remembered that moment. Gazing up at that monstrosity with it's hideous maws and heinous claws. A tear welled in her eye, she remembered the feeling of certainty she was going to die. “... Aye... There was a stilled moment... whence the daemon loomed up on me... it was as though time ceased its flow.” Diame raised her arm over her head, remembering her last desperate moment, “I didn't want to die, but that was all I could do... and I uttered one last prayer to God...” her arm lowered and she covered her face with it, wiping away her tears. 
“... and She listened.” Oakh continued.
Diame knew this to be true. She sat quietly, unable to move with the weight of gratitude on her shoulders. 
“Dear, dear child...” Oakh comforted Diame, and smiled at her, “God herself... She heard your prayer and in Her infinite mercy, Her light became your shield.” Oakh was met with blank stares by both Mirnada and Diame, “This was an act of God, who answered your prayer when you called out, Priestess Diame.”
Diame sat still, saying nothing.
        Oakh knew she was overwhelming her with these great new truths. She tried to think of words of comfort, but none came to her. Before she could say anything else, footsteps descending from upstairs were heard. Down came Xavier and Tavian, their first sight is seeing Diame sitting upright and well again. 
Xavier rushed over to her, relieved, “Diame, you're well!” he said as he stood by her. She simply nodded.
        Tavian stayed standing at the base of the stairs and quietly watched. He folded his arms and then leaned against the wall, seeming to be lost in his own thoughts.
        Mirnada's attention diverted as she looked up at the lone shadow knight, “Obviously, Tavian is jus' as overjoyed.”
Tavian scoffed with a smirk, “Deftly, I am athrill with glee...” he said with an almost sarcastic tone, “... for our mission is completed.” he paused and eyed the Paladin, “Right, Xavier?”
Xavier remembered himself and his duty. He scanned the eyes of Diame, Mirnada and Oakh, then stood and looked back over to Tavian. “Aye, indeed it is.”  
It is near dusk now... we depart to Ijia tomorrow morning.” Tavian said, uncrossing his arms, then turning to go back upstairs.
        “Hold... I have words for your ears only.” Oakh said, standing up with all her might against her stiff bones.
        Tavian looked back at the old lady over his shoulder, “Is that so?” he asked with calm curiosity as he turned back around.
Oakh grabbed her staff leaning against her chair and stood to her feet. She then nodded to Xavier and Mirnada, “We shall return shortly, keep an eye on Diame, will you?” They nodded back.


        As the daylight waned whilst the sun set, the clear skies of Desye revealed the fast approaching dusk.  The once overcast land of eternal snow now bereft of all clouds, and the long forgotten sunset at last could once again paint the sky canvas. The western horizon was awash with gold and red which faded into violet. It contrasted the night's starlit eastern sky, illuminated by the light of a rising amber crescent moon. Directly above in the heavens, there was the single blue glint of light of the newly born star, casting down its indigo candescence.
        The door of Oakh's log cottage opens over the snowy earth. Out she steps her frail body holding onto her walking staff. Tavian exits as well, following her and shuts the door behind him. Without saying a word, Oakh begins walking off on her own through the snow. Tavian catches up and begins walking alongside with her, waiting for her to say something. Her eyes were focused forward, passing by the other few cabins of Desye, treading through the white snow towards the setting sun.
        “If you merely wanted to take a stroll, you could have just easily said so.” Tavian broke the silence with.
        Oakh scoffed, “Hmph... if only...” she paused and took a deep breath, her mind heavy with deep memories at last resurfaced. “Tavian...” she paused and shook her head in frustration, “Is that your name?”
        Tavian was almost offended, but knew she had deeper meaning to her words. Still, his patience dwindled, “Did you mean to discuss something? Or are you wont of a failing memory?”
        “Oh, fuck you.” Oakh snapped back, frustrated, “I mean to convey something of great importance...” her anger escaped her, and she was once again wistful, “... But...”
        Tavian stood still in the snow, “Then you tell me now.”
Oakh slowed her steps to a halt as well, the two of them standing just outside the village. She stood holding her staff, and her staff began to shake as she mustered the strength to speak.
        Tavian stood unwavering, watching her. He knew he was intimidating her, but that was not his will. He knew that this old hag knew something about his past. “Out with it. My ears hunger for the sound of these silent words.”
        Oakh stared off into the crimson sunset in distance, then over her shoulder to Tavian standing with the moon rising over his shoulders. “There was a boy in this village... named Tavian.” she paused then beckoned to him, then kept walking, Tavian following once more. Oakh continued as they trod through the snow, “There was another boy in this village, named Faris.” they kept walking, the village a distance away from them now, “These children... perished... six years ago.”
        Tavian listened carefully, not sure how to take her words, “... And you say this as I stand before you?”
        Oakh shook her head as she recalled the painful details of the event, “I... remember that terrible day. It was what the village wanted to forget about, but I kept it written down... I never wanted to forget... though I don't think I could even if I tried.” she paused her speech, but kept walking with Tavian by her side, eager to hear her story, “I found an old entry in my diary... I wrote every detail...” she looked over and gazed at Tavian, this dark man with the daemon's eyes, “When I first saw you... when I first heard your name... I surely thought I had gone mad.” she looked onward once more, closing in on a lone, large snow frosted pine tree in the middle of the white field. 
        “Gone mad, because you had thought I was dead all along?” Tavian asked.
        Oakh fell silent as they approached the tree. Underneath the snowy boughs of this old pine tree lay a few mounds of snow. They stood before them, Oakh motioned Tavian towards the small snow piles. “Nay... not because I thought you were dead. What I felt was something that I knew could not be true.” 
        Tavian was even more unsure what Oakh was talking about, or why he was even brought here. But, obviously this tree was more than what met the eye. The mounds of snow beneath it, he leaned in and reached out with his hand into the snow. There he felt a cold slab of stone underneath. He wiped his hands across it, pushing off the years of fallen snow. There before his eyes lay a grave with the name Tavian Drakon carved near illegibly onto it. His year of death was dated six years past.
“I thought I had gone mad because... you are dead.” Oakh said as she stood there, motionless.
Tavian gazed down upon the gravestone bearing his own name. There was naught but silence as his thoughts raced through his mind. There was no explanation, he stood before where his body lay dead and buried. He said nothing.
        Oakh stood over Tavian as he knelt before the headstone. She leaned against her staff more as she mustered the strength to begin her tale, “There was a fire.” she said in a hoarse voice.
Tavian's eyes widened... his dream... the fire, the smoke, the pain, he remembered the accursed nightmare he had whenever he slept. Oakh extended her hand before the second mound of snow and flicked her wrist. A gust of wind kicked the snow off into a plume and cast aside, revealing a second headstone. Tavian read the name Faris Bellemoore, his death the same day as Tavian's.
Oakh saw the truth beginning to unravel in this man's mind as she continued, “A house caught flame six years ago. It was the Drakon house... At the time of the fire, only the two boys were inside.” she gazed down at the ground, remembering when the teen's casket was lowered six feet under, “A charred body was found inside the remnants of the home... this is where he was buried.” she shuddered remembering that dreadful sight, “The face was burnt off and twisted, unrecognizable by anyone in the village... however... Faris wore a metal lace necklace with a tiny bone pendant. That was the only way to recognize the body as his.”
        Tavian stood to his feet and crossed his arms pensively. So many years of his life had laid shrouded in darkness, now for his first glimpse of these long forgotten truths. What was soon to be known of his past chilled his heart, but not even this could cower his resolve. “How did the fire start? What else do you hide?”
“You tell me first, what do you remember of this day?” she had longed for answers as well. “Surely... you know something... anything.”
        “The fire...” Tavian now found a meaning for these painful memories, “A nightmare that pervades any restful slumber with it's vile torments. I relive the horror vividly as if I can feel my flesh smolder once more.”
        “Envision it in your mind's eye, what do you see?” Oakh asked, eagerly.
Tavian felt the heat, he could smell the smoke and charred flesh. He could see flames in his outstretched former right hand. A burning corpse lie at his feet, the mouth wide open as if in agony. He gasped as this image froze inside his mind. Fire aethermancy, the burning flames from his hand. “I caused the fire...” Tavian uttered without thinking.
        Oakh took a deep breath and steeled her nerves, “At last... the smallest scrap of what in God's name happened.” her staff began to shake as she leant her weight on it. Her long forgotten suspicions once again resurfacing, she then knew the dark truth she must convey. “To what end the truth takes you, I care not. For I can see only but one possibility that pierces the darkness shrouding Faris's death...”
        The Shadow Knight, bearer of lost arcane magicks and a blood darkened sword. He towered before the old hag and listened to her every word. His red-hazel gaze at last locked with her earth and snow stare.
        The matriarch eyed him scornfully with all the might her good eye could see, though her haunting blind eye peered even deeper into his soul. Oakh stared unblinking, the rage in her eyes pierced his mind. “You... And you alone Tavian,” she mustered all of her strength in her shaking voice, “You started the fire! That which murdered Faris was your own hand!”
“Enough of this!” Tavian shouted uncrossing his arms and staring down at Oakh's chilling gaze. He pointed a finger of his steel hand in her face, “I followed you to hear of what you know of my past, not to hear the mad speculations of a senile old hag!”
        “Oh? The truth escapes even you.” she took her staff and tilted it to push aside Tavian's hand, “You tell me something, Tavian, do you remember anything before the fire? Your life in Desye, mayhaps? How did you travel an ocean to get to Ijia?” she locked eyes with him with her convictions on her face and ever shaking in her voice, “Imagine the village seeing that house burst into inferno, the body of Faris in there, and you in fiendish might vanished into the flames of the hellfire.” she looked him up and down, “Now I see you returned, like this. Tell me, do you know of those who make bloodpacts with daemons for power?”
Tavian scoffed, “Of course, my master Azaria harnesses  powers that belonged to a daemon, which she endowed me with. I myself have not, nor would I ever sell my soul to what end a daemon do what wilt with it. I would sooner die.” he scowled at her.
“Can you be so sure?” she squinted her eyes back at him, as if calling a bluff, “You say you serve no daemon, but perhap wont of a failing memory are you yourself!”
        “Old wench!” His anger thundering in his voice, his patience had run dry, “A thousand times I say, I serve no daemon!” Tavian shouted.
        “Mayhap... you serve no daemon... now.” Oakh turned from him and took a few steps away, “What saved you from the fire? I can only wonder if you opened the fiery maw of hell and leapt inside the underworld from that house.” she turned back towards the village with the rising amber crescent moon casting its pale light up on the dark blue sky and snowy earth. The few wispy clouds in the dark veiled the moon as she began to take over her night sky. Oakh paused, marveling at the lunar scene, “Or could I be wrong,” she turned back to him, “Dare I say, it all could have been the protection of a dark angel?”
         Tavian stood with the sun set at his back and the sky still arouge with the dying sun's red light let bled behind the mountains. She speaks of daemon pacts and divine protections... changing her frail mind from accusations furthering to nonsenses. Though what transpired here this eve vanquishes questions, they yet multiply as I learn more. But, I forget myself... I am a knight and my duties here have ended. I will ponder these mysteries on my own time. Tavian kicked his feet through the snow treading back to Desye to Oakh's home. He walked up alongside her and spoke not a word. He looked in the distance and saw a shadowed figure alongside Desye's entrance path.
        Oakh broke the silence, “That daft woman... she left her house again?” she said in surprise.
        Tavian peered ahead at the figure. It was a petite woman wearing a black veil over her face, wearing a very thick dark fur coat. The very few patches of her exposed white skin gave an eerie reflection of pale moon light. She stood there facing them as they continued closer to her and the village. Though Tavian couldn't see her face, he could feel her stare through the dark veil. He could feel a cold, eyeless gaze on his skin, chilling his nerves. “Who is that?”
        Oakh gave a dismissive grunt, “Nobody of concern.” she shook her head at the woman, “She is a troubled soul who resides here.” 
        They walked until a stones throw from the entrance when the veiled woman suddenly marched into the direct path of Tavian. She stood there blocking their path, saying nothing but peering at Tavian with her unyielding gaze.
        Tavian watched her move before him, this woman fixated on him. She stood before him, staring past her veil. He looked down at her, barely seeing her face past the veil in this darkness. “Do you have words for me as well? If not, move.” He could barely see her lips move underneath her veil.
        The woman's voice was very quiet, as if she were a spirit speaking in whispered wisps of bated breath. “Nay, walking dead. Unreal... untrue. Tavian has long past, I see not his living spirit. Nay, I feel only the embrace... of cold emptiness. Long have I laid him to rest, eternally under death's caress.”
        “Your words are wasted, can you not see you speak to Tavian alive before you?” Tavian said, crossing his arms.
        The veiled woman shuddered and turned away, “Six years past, a home turned to naught but ash. The daemons plot began, a cherub slaughtered.” she muttered under her breath. “You... will break... and lose. You damn us all.”
        “Hmph, another speaks in naught but riddles and all words without value. I take my leave.” Tavian walked around the woman to advance further to Oakh's house.
        The veiled woman reached out from under her black fur coat and grabbed Tavian's wrist with her corpse cold hands. He turned back to her and she spoke again in barely more than a whisper, “You live on, and are cursed to never know. Go then, man with hands baptized in blood.”
        Tavian jerked his hand out of her boney grip and continued back through the snow to Oakh's home. He entered, Oakh and the veiled woman stayed at the village's entrance. Oakh stood gazing with her cataract eye and the veiled woman with her unseen stare.


        Back inside, it was still warm, though firelight was dying down. Xavier alone sat in the couch idly by the fireplace. Tavian came inside away from the cold gazes and was welcomed by the home's warmth. He sat down in the seat across from Xavier. He took a log of wood and fed it to the hungry fire to warm himself from the bitter chills of the night. “Xavier, my friend.”
        Xavier scoffed, coming out of his deep thoughts, “Yes, Tavian?”
        “What do you believe is wrong with this insane world?” Tavian asked while watching the flames grow and gradually lit the room brighter and warmer.
        Xavier cleared his throat, and stared into the fireplace, “Well, these last few days I have seen and experienced some very strange things. A girl who can mend flesh and bones like a master healer, as well as channel the destructive powers of fire. I have seen a fell daemon slain by a priestess by the mere wave of her hand, and her clairvoyant visions made true.” He glanced back to Tavian, “and you calling me friend.” he finished with a slight retort.
        “Heh. Truly, strange times we live in.” Tavian said. He could hear the faint sounds of the girls talking upstairs and footsteps through the ceiling. “Diame, she has recovered?”
        “Aye... she can walk on her own as if her leg never befell harm.” Xavier said, in awe. “Not to mention how she even mustered the strength to utterly destroy that daemon is beyond me.” he looked up as if staring past the ceiling, “and that star... it casts a light that makes my skin crawl. It lingers in the heavens as if a wicked presence casts its looming eye up on the land.” he shook his head, “It's ominous. A boon for the kin of the dark.”
        “Aye, though we felled the daemon Fa'Mes, it seems our efforts aided the darkness nonetheless.” Tavian cast his eye up on the fire as it consumed the wood and grew strong and roaring. “What do we report back to Her Majesty? 'We took Lady Diame for a stroll through the snow and unleashed an ancient daemonic curse on the world. Nothing else to report.' And then what?” asked Tavian, “We have our duties. So, must we make haste and bolster our men for the ever blood drunk Pevali, and forget about everything we've seen here? I know something foul fuels the empire's intent.”
        “A larger scale...” Xavier pondered, taking in the happenings of today, “When the strings of fate are pulled, we men become naught but small marionettes. The almighty puppeteers use us as they will to shape the world.”
        Tavian nodded, “Aye, the skies of Heaven stir. I feel unbalance... unrest.” he paused, and gave Xavier a serious look, “All this, from our actions.”
        “Hmm...” Xavier crossed his arms, “It appears we have ourselves caught up in the affairs of the divine.”
        “Precisely.” Tavian sat back in his seat, the knight brooding in the firelight.
        “When Diame came to the castle, within hours she had saved the queen's life as well as my own. Her even being at the castle was because of the visions she had.” 
        “You see my point, then.” Tavian leaned forward, “Ever since we came to the Northlands, I have felt uneasy. You've seen it. Something in the past here involved me, and I happened to be brought here for this mission. In addition...” he formulated his thoughts, each accompanied with a gesture of his hand, “Pray tell me this...” he rolled his eyes around in thought as he continued, “If a High Priestess has a vision, is compelled to come seeking aid and also saves the lives of those she beseeches...”
        “Now she has the aid of two Ijian generals bring her to the place she has seen... and we break a powerful, ancient seal with no tarry. She was injured, and that girl happened to be there to heal her wounds...” Xavier added.
        “Then she smites a daemon with a single raise of the hand.” Tavian tilted his head to his Paladin comrade. “Before, I merely questioned the possibility of the divine... But now, I can have no more doubts. I know they interfere with the affairs of mankind once more. To what end is the question.”
        Xavier nodded and thought carefully, “Tavian... Madame Oakh spoke of 'The Watchers'. Could that eye-shaped star above us...”
        “... a Watcher!” Tavian shook his head, “But, if this star was supposedly created by God, then why does it defile her earth with such an ill-light?”
        Xavier arose from his seat and cast his gaze down to the roaring fire. He leaned in front of the fireplace mantle and faced Tavian, “I am but a oath-sworn knight of God. I received Her light and Her strength to uphold the laws of God as well as mankind.” His eyes once again cast downward. Xavier's emerald green eyes who have seen the atrocities of war. His eyes have looked into the grateful eyes of those he has saved. He has seen the cold stare of a merciless enemy he was forced to stay with a blade of righteousness. The flames' reflection danced in his green gaze. “I know of the evil that lurks within the hearts of men. I have protected people from this darkness and vanquished what rears itself. As a man opens his mind to avarice of power and wealth, only true darkness may enter.”
        “What say you?”
        “You trusted to call me friend, I shall trust you with these words.” Xavier turned himself to meet with the gaze of the brooding Tavian. “I have long suspected the Church's conscience is not clear of these sins of man as well.”
        “Hmph... A Paladin speaks against the Church. Your words would be your last... if anyone less clandestine than myself hears them.”
        “The Church has stated in the Manifest of Caelutera that God created the Watchers and that our victory over the underworld was already won centuries ago. That the droves of daemons that exist today are merely a few scattered remnants. This is the dogma of the Church, but what I have seen challenges their beliefs. The evil I have seen today is a daemonic presence far greater than a wondering succubus or a mischievous imp. But, would the Church deny what that can see right above them?”
        “They could... if their minds are open to this evil you speak of.” Tavian continued, “So, tell me!” he gave Xavier a hard look, “Do you believe your Church is corrupt, Paladin?”


        Upstairs inside the guest room, Diame had been chattering with Mirnada while she rest. Her strength had gradually returned from her ordeal. Diame was sitting on her bedside, just having the strength to walk up stairs. 
        “Ay, I can hear the guys a'yellin' again.” Mirnada said as she was looking around the many closet doors and drawers in the guest room.
        “They are bold men. I'd expect them to speak boldly.” Diame said as she smirked at Mirnada as she explored every drawer in the room. “Curious one, aren't you?”
        “Aye, I always know, somethin' good always hidin' nearby.” she opened a drawer and found some clean robes, “Hmm.” she looked at more drawers in the room, some contained some orange-red soaps made from Konjode grass in them. “Interesting...” 
        Diame giggled and looked around the room as well, “Madame Oakh has taken such good care of us. We'll be leaving so soon.” “After what has happened today... I know, I must go to Lux Grande with great haste. I must tell them of...” she could feel and relive the moment of death, she felt ill, “the daemons and...”
        “Ay, ay, no need t' worry yerself with that now. Take yer mind off it, yeah?” Mirnada looked over to the big closet, “Say, lets look in 'ere!” She slid the door to the side and there was a closet with something with a sheet cast on top of it. “Wot could it be!?”
        “Um, Mirnada...”
        Mirnada grabbed the dusty cloth and revealed an empty bathtub. “Ay, lookie here...” she grabbed it and immediately pulled it out into the room. 
        “What are you doing?”
        Mirnada grinned at Diame with an over excited look on her face. “You, mi'lady, are goin' t' bathe away all yer troubles!”
        Diame blinked at her.
        “You've been though a lot, n' I c'n tell, yer a dainty flower not e'er traveled past yer tiny fenced garden.” Mirnada smiled and clapped her hands at her, “So! You need t'relax, an' wot better way th'n a naice 'ot bath!”
        “I... suppose, but where will we get water from?”
        “You tell me, wat'r priest'ss.” Mirnada winked at her. 
        Diame did want to change out of her soiled clothes and bathe her own blood off her. “I think... I am feeling a bit better, Mirnada.” she stood from her bed and walked her way over to the window, gazing up on the stars and moon. She opened it and stood to the side of the window, “Would you bring the tub here, please?”
        Mirnada smiled and pushed it over closer to the window, eager to see what other magicks Diame could do.
        Diame reached with her arms out the window towards the sky, beseeching the crescent moon. She felt the presence of all the water around her. The moisture in the air, the blood inside their bodies, the moon's watery light cast up on her, the snow in the night sky gently falling to the ground. She could feel every snowflake in the palm of her hand and every cool moonbeam touched her fingertips. The snow began to gather and hover around her hands. Soon she had a snowball hovering and spinning in the air, gathering more and more moisture and growing in size. It then hovered in and landed into the tub. She closed the window, “There we are.”
        Mirnada had watched in amazement the entire time, “Naicely done!”
        “Well, it was a good idea. But now I need your help.”
        Mirnada nodded. She held out her hand and concentrated. She now having more control over her ability to control fire, her hand engulfed in flame. She immersed it into the snow and it began to melt and hiss. Her hand still remained aflame underwater, and it heated it up and began to steam. She removed her hand and the flame went out as soon as it was removed from the water. “An' there we 'ave it!” 
        Diame smiled at her, “Thank you.”
        “No pro'lem!” Mirnada then grabbed at Diame's clothes, slightly startling her. “Now jus' take these off, an'...”


        “The men of God created the Dogma, not God herself.” Xavier responded, “This is man's law made holy merely because they speak from position of power. I believe that if the men of the Church still possess their righteous virtue, they will listen to reason.”
        “And if not?” Tavian crossed his arms, longing to see where this man stood in his allegiances.
        “If the Church is truly corrupt, then Ijia herself makes an enemy of Lux Grande as well as Pevali.” Xavier began to pace around the room, “And High Priestess Diame... her allegiance is with the Church. What she has seen here she will surely divulge to the Pontiff.”
        “But, if she walks The Path...” Tavian fingered a notch of his armor with his right hand, making a metallic tapping “... surely even the corrupted Church would not... no, could not stop her if she is truly an instrument of God.”
        “We do not know how Lux Grande is going to react to this once they learned we were the ones responsible for the Watcher...” Xavier shrugged his shoulders, “We're either heroes or heretics.” 
         Tavian stared into the fire and concentrated hard on it. The fire in the fireplace grew even brighter and let out a few loud crackles. “That is yet another thing to be fearful of the Church, their dogma is indeed their power. I have come to know of many dark truths the Church would rebuke with all their might as treacherous blasphemy.” he felt a pulse of dark energy course through him, glinting his eyes red for a moment, “Though, I am not a member of that Church.”
        “But, Lady Diame is, and she possesses great power. I, too, was baptized within the hallowed walls of Lux Grande. I know of the miraculous strength of light God has gifted to her people.” Xavier continued to patter his bare feet against the wooden floor, examining every old intricate object scattered about Oakh's home. “As I am sure, Madame Oakh must hold within her some power as well. Duly so, she is the High Priestess of Air.”
        Tavian scoffed, and stood to his feet and gestured his hands out, “'High Priestess' or no, I would be surprised if those old bones could carry any power at all!”
        The front door swung open and clashed against the wall, echoing a thunderous slam rattling the log house and clinking every glass trinket. Xavier and Tavian both turned their heads towards the door. They saw a short, black figure in the dark of night begin to step into the house.
        “It's that witch again!” Tavian shouted, as he jumped up, then turned to face an enemy.
        “Huff!” a glaring, wrinkled face came forward into the firelight to reveal Oakh, “I may have startled you to your feet, but no need to call names.” 
        Tavian disarmed himself of hostility, “Apologies, I thought you were...”
        “Huff!” Oakh pushed past Tavian as he frowned at her. She took her seat at her chair closest to the fireplace. “Hah, oh that fire is quite nice. My aching back, yes.”
         Tavian retook his seat, folding his arms with a vexed sigh. Mad old hag... what do you know? He leaned back in his seat, grateful to be inside a warm home nonetheless. Still, naught but rambling nonsense. Nothing more. No time to tarry dwelling on an old hag's ravings. He nodded to himself in assurance, But then... that fear he felt when he first stepped foot into Desye, this is indeed my home village. Yet, what caused me to lose control of myself? He shook the thought from his mind, not wanting to replay it. Enough... we leave this place first light tomorrow, I leave these distractions behind as well. 
         Xavier stood still for a moment, then turned to resume pacing as he was. The pattering of his feet on the floor and the crackling of the pine logs filled the wordless living room. What I have seen today... just the existence of Fa'Mes contradicts the church. They say no daemons may dwell on the surface, save a few lesser daemonic beasts who evade the light. So then, how could a beast as huge and as powerful as he possibly have had such a hold in this world? He paced by the frosted window glass and looked out to repose up at the crescent moon, but the blue glint of the daemon's star caught his eye first. It flickered menacingly in the sky, as if the tiny glimmer was trying to outshine the moon. Now, this... this 'star', sourced from Fa'mes, pervades even the heavens. His skin began to crawl, as if staring at the blue light was draining the heat from his body even in the presence of the fireplace. He shuddered and turned away in disgust. And whats worst... aye, we lead Lady Diame straight to it, and she succeeded where we failed, with a single wave of the arm. Just then he remembered someone most important, where is she?
        Then, a door opening upstairs and footsteps were heard descending them. Mirnada walked into the living room and met with everyone's glance.
        “Oh Mirnada, come sit with us, dear.” She motioned for her to sit in the part of the sofa closest to her, “How fares Lady Diame?”
        Mirnada closed herself to the fire and sat right in front of it on the floor instead. Not to be rude, but the fire drew her towards it like a moth drawn to a warm glow, “She's jus' fine. Restin' 'n well tak'n care of.”
        “Thank you lass, we were fortunate to have you with us.” Xavier tilted his head to her, “Your aid to Lady Diame has been helpful to our mission.”
        
        Diame felt the steaming water of the bathtub with her cold fingertips. It was almost too hot to step into. She stood naked in the room staring at herself. The dried blood on her leg from her healed wounds reminded her of something that could only have been from a distant dream. She shook her head and walked up to the window, standing naked in the moonlight. She breathed deeply and gazed up on the stars, eager to doth aloft the anxiety plaguing her mind. Her hands reached back back into her auburn hair and she began to unravel her hair. Her crimson locks freed into beautiful silky strands, cascading down her back and breast. She shook her head and her hair swayed longer down her lily skin legs, down to her feet. She knelt on her knees and sat skyclad, clothed only by the robe of her own hair. Starry eyes beheld the glory of the night, Lunaheim's moonbeams rained its rays in Diame's shimmering locks, and her eyes filled up with the moon's glow. 
        Diame clasped her hands together and uttered her prayer, “Goddess Evas'za, holy is thy name and divine is thy guidance. I humble before thee, in thine infinite mercy, heed my prayer.” she took in the night sky and closed her eyes, “What you have asked of me was no easy task, my Lady Goddess, but nonetheless, I have succeeded. All I ask is please make clear to me what task you wish for me to fulfill.” She bowed her head in somber silence.
        A cold draft blew in from the night, her bare skin bearing the chill as it shook her concentration. Diame turned her head back to the steamy plumes rising from the tub beckoning to her. She stood to her feet, stepping over to the welcoming waters. She placed her bloodied leg in first, eager to wash away the memory of her day's ordeal. At last she slowly sank her beautifully pale body into the water of perfect temperature. The hot bath comforted her delicate body, her bones had felt the bitter cold of the harsh Desyen winds for too long. She lay back in the warmth, her body relaxed and her mind clear. 
        Diame closed her blue eyes and took in the night with her other senses. The sounds of wind squalls blew out in the frigid night, voices of her companions talked downstairs, and even the silence of the falling snow was heard. The spiced scents of the konjode soaps wafted through the warm mists. She reached out to the soap bar next to her side and cleansed her leg and body of her sweat and blood. The suds began to fill up the tub with the rich, sweet, peppery aromas of konjode and frankincense filling the room and she became ensorcelled in its perfume. Diame's mind sloughed all worry from her thoughts, and her weariness melted into bliss. 
        Diame drifted into her other world as her consciousness faded. Her eyes closed and body submerged in a warm paradise, she felt awash in a tropic ocean. Without seeking an image, visions of her swimming through the sea filled her mind. She was far underwater, suspended and slowly drifting through the open deep. She looked around her and her mind's eye could see the under sea scene. Sun's rays pierced the far up water surface sending arrays of light beams reaching down to her though the ocean depths. She followed the light beams and they led deeper down into the dark depths of the ocean floor. She swam though the sweven seas, not knowing what she was searching for, but the light beckoned to her like a distant voice calling her name. She swam deeper in the water, following the path of light. 
        All around Diame, the ocean began to reveal forms that took shape in the light. The Mer, the mysterious fish people who guard the sea, they were all around her. They had elongated fishtails that connected at their waist, above that was pale and pink skinned men. They were hardened defenders, warriors who have fought countless battles. Their bodies were muscular and bore many a war-scar. Most of the mermen had long hair and long braided beards. Their hair was adorned with many small bones and teeth tied to their hair, the many trophies from their battles. They held spears and tridents, though they did not threaten nor did they mean harm to their visitor in dreams. No, they seemed almost relieved to see her, yet cautious and fearful the deeper they got. 
         Diame could see the look of worry on the brave men's faces as they swam deeper into the dark depths. They looked like fierce, noble men who would gladly fight any battle and self sacrifice themselves without a second thought for the sake of protecting their sea and home. Why do they show such terror in their eyes?
        As soon as her mind asked the question, Diame discovered the end of the guiding beam of light.  She looked up and could barely see how far the beam of sunlight stretched from its source to the ocean depths. She looked deeper below, trying to see past the darkness. She swam closer to the bottomless deep, she could feel an ocean current gradually though forcefully dragging on her, pulling her deeper down. The mermen looked in horror, like they watched an ally step into an enemy's trap and were already branded for dead. Diame looked back up to them, beckoning for help. Three mermen descended and swam deeper after her, a heroic rescue to save her from the sea's abyss.
         The beam of light drifted farther and farther away above them. Diame was caught in the pressure and drag of the mighty ocean as well as her three would-be heroes. It was a false hope, they knew they couldn't save her. They simply didn't want her to know the horror of dying alone. To he who now rules the sea. Diame drifted deeper into this darkness, her vision extremely limited. Around her were the three mermen, consigned to their fate and swam by her side as she guided them deeper down.
         Diame's eyes could not see deeper no matter how hard they tried. She treaded in the deep waters, the fear beginning to take hold of her. She couldn't go further, her instincts were keening of some unseeable imminent threat. A sharp pang of danger pricked her mind, a moment of lucidity returned. Aware and awake, the vivid portrait her mind had painted for her was now a lucid dream. She became conscious she was within her own dream, and she had never been able to be lucid in a vision, usually they were beyond her control. But this is no lucid dream. It made no sense to her. A lucid vision? 
        The priestess took in the silence of the ocean's deep. She couldn't wake, but she could feel the water, she could breathe deep beneath the sea, the mermen safeguarding her stayed very close by to her, worried, on guard, searching. Diame faced one of them and her kind eyes met with the hardened warrior's. This merfolk man had long dark blonde hair, interwovern with animal teeth, seaweed and coral. He waited facing her as if awaiting command, his battle-worn coral trident arched and at the ready. She opened her mouth to speak, seawater rushed in and she took a deep breath of it. She was surprised by the sensation of waterbreathing, but needed to talk to this merman warrior. 
        As Diame spoke, whatever words she said she didn't know, but he understood with a nod, he gave a hard look straight forward and pointed his spear poised to strike. Diame looked ahead, there was a faint glow in the waters deep. The mermen saw it too and all poised their spears, their nerves were steeled and ready to face death itself. The faint glowing figure was drifting around the ocean depths, churning the waters unnaturally. A deep, low grumble reverberated throughout the ocean floor, it thundered from every direction at once and lasted until the entire sea resonated with it; the mere sound of the creature's voice. Diame's eyes widened and she shuddered at a realization; there are many daemons yet unseen, and just this one's mere voice presents itself more daunting than Fa'Mes.
        The beam of light stretched down from above, extending itself down below, a column cascading before Diame. The deep dark ocean depths became engulfed in illumination, all could be seen for a few fleeting moments. There before Diame was the colossus of an enormous serpentine sea beast. The vast void of water depths were filled by a single long serpentine tail, writhing and stretching on endlessly. Swimming upwards from beneath the sea creature emerged a swarm of foreboding fish. Hundreds of schools of Remorae, the vicious, jagged-toothed piranha-creatures that reside within the deepest, darkest regents of the sea. 
        Diame could see all these sea creatures swirling in the water, afraid to approach her with her light beaming down in front of her. The mermen still waited ready to strike, unwavering defenses. The mighty sea serpent turned and twisted its coiling body through the briny sea, slithering its way towards the priestess and her protectors. Its head was finally revealed as it lunged through the sea at them. Its mouth was long and flat, like a crocodiles, and had many long, whisker like protrusions that looked like a beard of bent pins. Its head was scaled and had several large semi transparent fin protrusions for steering. On its crown he bore two large, black horns that stretched and looped and curled into a razor sharp points. Its huge eyes were dark and colorless like black jewels, but reflected the light within them as its gaze. Its fixation was solely set on Diame's life, lunging through the twisted torrents menaced two glowing spheres ardent with hatred.
        Diame let out a long echoed scream of waterbreath that chilled all the ocean's ears with her distressed terror. Her shriek provoked the three mighty Mer to action, sudden flashes of quicksilver scales darted they to meet the fell daemon of her dream. One of the Mer warriors lunged directly to the beast in staunch resolve, the might of a whale in his trident. Another moved around the beast, his spear at the ready to flank the daemon. The third mer warrior locked eyes with Diame, his turquoise eyes wide-open. He lunged toward her, doing all he could do he wrapped his arm tightly around Diame's waist. He pulled her back floundering his fin, swimming away from the beast with desperate fervor. Diame held fast in his mighty grasp looking back and watched faint reflections of the dimming light. The Remorae swarmed on the two Mer warriors, the schools of the clawed fins and open needle teeth at the ready. 
        The sharp coral edges of the spears pierced the eyes and heads of the Remorae, the Mer have faced many of these foes before. But, not in this number. The tridents of the Mer stabbed and slew the Remorae one by one, and their blackened cruor and entrails spilt out, darkening the waters. But the masses of droves could not all be repelled. One of the two Mer continued his mighty battle through these fish creatures, intent on reaching the true foe, the behemoth sea snake staring with its dark glowing eyes. He fought his way directly to the daemon. A Remorae latched its needley maw onto his shoulder. Blue Mer blood then spilt into the ocean. He too yelled in pain, then desperately stabbed his spear backwards into the fish's face, breaking the beast's teeth, freeing himself. He ignored his pain and swam ever closer to his target. 
        The other Mer swam around the beast, fighting through the endless Remorae to reach the daemon's flank. He was strong, and his determination was within his honed skill in the coral trident he held arched. He swam with all his might directly into a school of the piranha-creatures that protected their serpentine master. The tri-pronged, sharp serrated coral tore through the blackened fishy flesh, three-by-three. The Mer warrior let out a battle cry that echoed through the waters as he slew the swarms of vicious Remorae with gruesome dispatch. Fanning his tail-fin fast though the dark blood clouds, he swam his way through, trident at the ready as he found the side of the Daemon's serpent-like head. His fin beat against the water and sent himself as fast as he could swim. He lunged and threw his trident with all his might shouting ferociously. The coral tips pierced the blackened snake-scales of the Daemon, and sank deep into its palpable neck, just below its skull. 
        The beast let out a roaring wail, its anger shook the ocean depths. Huge jets and streams of blacked daemon cruor put the seas of Remorae gore to shame. Its colossal head turned from Diame to the cheeky mortal Mer who dared make the daemon bleed. He stared the daemon down, disarmed now his trident had found home in the daemon's flank. The crocodile-like mouth opened revealing rows up on rows of long, jagged, white teeth like a shark. The maw was easily big enough to swallow a house, it engulfed in the waters surrounding the Mer. He showed no fear and faced his death. He waded motionless in the water as he entered the cavernous mouth of the serpent. 
        Diame felt a strange sense of mortality, as if she were the one who met with death. She felt a pang of tightness in her chest, met with the unmistakable high of adrenaline, her heart beat like a thunderous drum. In her head, she heard thoughts of pure emotion. They were ever fearless and prideful, growing stronger and stronger. Her mind was astir with the thoughts of the last moments of a warrior in his final battle rush.         
        The Mer closed his eyes, the mouth of the Sea Serpent snapped shut, the sound of the selfless Mer's death was the crunch of bones within infinite teeth.
        Diame shuddered and tried to close her eyes, but she was unable to. She watched the death of the Mer kin, her vision focused on the crocodile maw of the Sea Serpent. The Mer's death and a satisfied glow in the two spheres of the daemon was a sight she was forced to see.
        The remaining injured Mer slew the remaining few Remorae immediately near him, deathly aware of the fate of his friend, and how soon he would share it. He had no time to hold his wounds, many more foes closed in on him from the deep. He swam leaving a trail of blue blood, he made his path for the Sea Daemon surrounded by the schools of waiting Remorae.
         Diame was held strong and secure by the Mer carrying her, though the tight grip hurt her. I can feel this pain, I can feel the emotions of these mermen... and as a nightmare often contains sights one does not wish to see... what manner of mad dreamworld must I be in? The other Mer continued to bravely distract the Daemon and slay the Remorae as she was carried to safety. Even though he hastened to take her as quickly away from the beasts of the deep, they remained within distance. Diame tried to speak to the warrior, but he would not respond as he tried to swim to safety, straining himself with all the strength he can muster. Her rescuer was weakening, the snapping mouthed Remorae followed by the Sea Serpent were quickly drawing closer and closer. 
        The piranha-creatures' countless maws gaped to inhale water and propelled them faster as it  jet from their gills. The glints of countless teeth opened then snapped shut in a clamor that echoed louder as they enclosed up on the remaining Mer warrior. The scent of their enemy's mer-blood drove the piranha-creatures beyond madness. The rattling sounds from bites of sharp teeth mixed with snarls and grunts became more chorus like, and all their oily fish-eyes rolled in a frenzy. A huge whirl of quicksilver scales looped in the water, the school of razors poised at the lone Mer. Bravely, he swam into them, spear at the ready into the sea of mouths.
         Diame desperately reached out towards him over the rescuer Mer's shoulders, as if her hand could save him somehow. My Lady Goddess, protect him! Her eyes widened and she yearned to release the sound of her voice.
        The Mer charged forward, staring into the snapping piranha maws. He thrust and swung his spear, piercing the bodies of two or so Remorae at a time. They were quickly up on him, and surrounded him on all sides. He swiftly looped through the water as well, evading them through the darkened waters, all the while the Sea Serpent drew closer. He had complete disregard for the blood pluming from his wound, his only resolve was repaying them back in kind with their own. All his strength went into spearing their heads, and avoiding their teeth and claws.
        There were tendrils of light beams from far above extending down in thin rays that swayed with the water. Diame looked up, she could see a point above past the darkened waters where she was dragged down. In fact, she could see the very faint silhouettes of Merfolk in the watery glow. But the Remorae were closer, and the Daemon was just behind them.
         The Mer carrying Diame looked over his shoulder and saw his remaining kin's fending off the Remorae. He won't last much longer. He thought, and Diame heard. Before she knew what was happening, he forced his muscles forward once more with a final burst of energy. With speed and a strong arm, he threw Diame forward, up towards the surface's light. He looked up at her, his fierce turquoise eyes met with hers a final time, then he swam down to join the other Mer.
        She felt the currents of the sea coarse around her as she hurled through the water. She couldn't look back, only forward to the faint glimpses of light and life far above. But then, Diame began to sense her saviors thoughts even more so, and could even see through his eyes.
         She saw herself as the Mer who carried her, speeding through the torrents into the fray. He charged trident first with a loud battle cry into the largest preponderance of piranhas. The coral of his trident met with the teeth that would have met with his kin's neck. Without time to react, they fought together keeping the Remorae at bay as long as they could. Though we are vastly outnumbered, we will give our lives to fight for you. Now! You must hurry, leave this place! He continued to fight as the sea horrors enclosed on them. He stopped for a moment and looked up, Diame saw herself through his eyes, then felt herself return to her body, looking down at him from above.
         Disoriented she looked around her, the darkness of the water was closing in on her, the light above growing dimmer. Go, my queen! Swim! She heard his voice a final time. She swam up and up, kicking her legs against the currents. The pursuit to enter the light strengthened her, above was the only way escape to this darkness. Diame felt the strain on every muscle and joint in her body as she struggled to reach the surface. My God, help me... give me the strength...!
        The mermen dispatched more Remorae, the wounded one losing strength fast. His movements were slower, a Remorae sunk its teeth into his fin, the razors sunk deep into him. Another one bit and latched on his arm. He yelped and tried to push them off with his spear.
        Turquoise-eyes grabbed the Remorae with the points of his trident and pulled them off. But it was all in vain, his comrade had no strength left in him. He stayed in front of his kin, using his trident with all his strength he could muster to protect him and slow their advance to Diame. He was surrounded by a school of the Remorae, swirling around him like a chattering vortex. They all swam towards him, he braced himself, his weapon at the ready. With a sudden panicked flick of the fins, the piranhas all swam away at all directions, as if they suddenly feared for their lives. The Mer questioned not, and attended to his mortally wounded kin. He propped him up, the little life left in him accepted his fate. Turquoise-eyes understood, and accepted his fate as well. They turned to the Daemon of the Seas together, meeting with the two glowing black spheres.
        The eyes grew bigger and started to illuminate its face and body once more. The snake head was bore deep with the two huge black gems. The crocodile mouth parted slightly, baring its white teeth as if it had a twisted grin. The eyes flashed a light so black that it even made the silhouettes of the Mer brighter for a moment. Diame's skin pricked hundreds of times, she felt as if submerged in a pool full of snakes biting her one after another. Diame felt a sharp burning sensation that shivered up and down her spine, then spread to the tips of her fingers and toes. She writhed like every nerve in her body was pierced by hot needles as the psychic venom pervaded her soul. Her body felt weaker by the second, as if she could not will her body to move. Her hard kicks and arm strokes became struggled, and her limbs flailed. She went limp as she succumbed to a lucidity consuming toxin as every movement passed. Her movements slowed to a halt, she couldn't will even a conscience thought.
        She could only see the glowing spheres and the black light that grew brighter and darker. Then she heard a voice unlike any other resonate in her head. Its words were slithery and long, and it spoke in a deep boom. Thy God holdss no ssway here, priesstessss. Her pupils dilated. She no longer could draw breath. She couldn't move although the pain had subsided, she felt only numbness now. The voice took over in her mind, she was emotionless in a frozen trance. The Sea Snake's black gem eyes flickered, a sense of satisfaction came from the daemon. Many exisst who wissh to hide thysself... its head turned down and faced the two paralyzed Mer, but thou cansst hide thysself from mine eyess. Its eyes flickered yet again, then its horns on its crown began to illuminate. A bolt of twisted lightning arched between the two points of the curled black horns. The electricity was dark blue and darting bolts spread in random directions as the daemon's horns pulsated and charged with more lightning. The pricce of idioccy for thosse who defy my masster'ss will... Its mouth gaped open, every tooth pulsed with a bolt of lightning. The energy between its horns arched bigger and brighter and lit up the sea in a dark blue light.
        The long serpentine tail-like body of the daemon could be seen extending so far deep it originated from a break in the ocean floor. A surge of blue energy coiled up the beast from beneath the underworld itself. In a moment it traveled up to the head of the daemon and swirled around it. Then like a cannon, the horns and mouth discharged forth a thundering burst of blue lighting that rumbled the entire sea. It poised forward in a column of light aimed directly at the two Mer warriors. The beam widened and engulfed the Mer, webbing tendrils of lightning extended in every direction beyond the eye could see. The two Mer were instantaneously disintegrated in this clasm of lightning. The flashes of lightning from the horns and teeth ceased in an instant, and the last random bolts fired from the Sea Serpent's head. The light stopped, but the clamor of thunder had yet to cease until it had echoed and rumbled throughout the entire sea of Caelutera.
        The gem like eyes focused yet again on Diame. They drew closer to her as the daemon slithered through the sea of Remorae gore. The snake's head swayed side to side as it churned the waters, growing ever nearer. The glowing eyes darted in a hypnotic dance, as akin to how a cobra might mesmerize its pray. Thine precciouss light houssed in thy ssoul... its horns began to pulse and arched with lightning yet again, I sshall ssnuff it out. It's mouth gaped open and it drew closer with intent fervor. 
        
        “Ah heh! Nothin' to it, I guess” Mirnada said as she sat flat on the floor close to the warm flames.
        “Where is the lady now?” Xavier asked.
        Mirnada rolled her head back over her shoulders, “Why, 'avin a naice 'ot bath!”
        Everyone blinked, Mirnada gave an upside down grin.
        “A bath?” Oakh looked up as if seeing past the ceiling boards, “Oh, you did drag that out. That's alright, I would have run her one myself if you had asked...” she blinked again, “Wait, now... how did you get the water, much less heat it?” she asked although already certain of the answer.
         Mirnada closed her eyes and stared with her grin that widened with accomplishment. She giggled, then straightened her neck, facing the crackling logs. She held up a hand over the flames. She could feel the heat against her skin, and felt the fiery elemental vibrations that coursed through her blood as energy warmed her veins. She smirked privately, a small assurance of delicate self-pride. To gain just an inkling of mastery over her powers made her think of Marshall. What he saw in her, she finally began to see. The intensity of her magick, to what end of the powers she could draw upon still remains clandestine even to her. A red flame for heating, a violet flame for healing... Her mind wandered, she relaxed and contemplated on the fireplace.
         The old and wise priestess cleared her throat purposefully, but it was met with the unmistaken silence of deep thought. “Well then...” she muttered to deaf ears. Her gaze averted to Tavian and he stared at the floor, cross armed and brooding as usual. Hmph. I have many words for him, but he will never listen. Once he can find and accept the smallest part of his soul, he may yet...  Her earth and snow eyes cast to Mirnada, her hand was still hovering, feeling the flames as if her hand was inside the hearth. She was completely fixated, her attention not straying from the fire. That child... she nodded to her even if she couldn't see it, I shall talk with her before she leaves. Clearly, she stirs all the aether around her without effort. A Jorgard child with improper training is... dangerous. As is for anyone who can not control the aether they wield. Her attention turned to Xavier, pacing by the window, This man... he bears the weight of conflict. She closed her eyes, and listened to the words that spoke from his face. His strength comes from his own convictions... his faith is in God as well as it is in the Church. But, therein lies his struggle. She nodded, this time to herself as well as Xavier, I, too, have wrested with my own faith and the beliefs of the church... But never in a way such as this. I can only imagine what it's like to be a Paladin, a warrior of God bearing the true faith, to yet have that thin red string of doubt tugging in the back of one's mind. Oakh leaned back in her chair and began to rock back and forth slowly with a couple of wooden creaks escaping. What these four have seen... nay, what they have done! To have felled Fa'Mes, that... that which has terrorized Desye for all these years. To what purpose Evas'za has for these four... 
         She scanned the room once more, her eyes cast on each person once. Oakh looked up past the ceiling boards once more, Lady Diame... you were called here. Aye. You, and your three guardians. All of your purposes, separate yet the same. Her visions need to be protected. Where I can only hear the faintest words whispered by the wind, she has seen countless visions reflected into her mind. Truly, her talents are a gift from God, divinity draw her here. She carved her own path unwittingly and was joined with followers by happenstance of coincidence and luck! There were drops of water forming between the cracks in the wood. More and more water droplets hung from the ceiling, sliding across the wooden surface and combining into larger droplets. Oakh blinked, Does that girl not know how to keep a bath within the confines of a tub? She sighed.
        There was a loud splash heard upstairs followed by the dull sound of water heavily lapping against the ceiling. Then water droplets began to trickle steadily from above, the allusion of a rainstorm in Oakh's living room turned Xavier, Mirnada and Tavian's attention.
        
        Diame floated lifelessly in the water, her eyes filled with terror as the swirling blue lighting mustered to engulf her. She writhed within her own mind to will herself to move, or just to even hear her own thoughts. She wished to release a scream for help, but all was in vain. The energy pulsing through the Sea Snake crackled ferociously as the lightning currents sizzled the sea waters. The leathery lips lining the open crocodile-mouth of the beast twisted into a grinning glower. And with thiss, Diame, your life endss.        
        The quieting of the words with the immediate accompanying roar of electricity chilled her, if she could have felt it.
        There was a faint warmth in the distance behind her. Diame could sense another, yet distant, presence in her sea of thoughts. Her mind began to feel lighter, as if stones were falling out her ears. Her limbs and face began to twitch with involuntary motions as she struggled to regain self control. The numbness... it turns to a stilled pain... is the beast's toxin loosening its hold? Her eyes could move freely as if she suddenly had a full night's recovery. She slowly turned her head in the waves of water, her long hair flowing freely behind her in long flows. From far away and above, a tiny glint of light pierced the darkness like a pinprick. The light was hurling down through the sea, the glow gaining size as it drew closer.
        
        There was a shocked stillness on Madame Oakh's face as water droplets fell one by one throughout her home. As Tavian and Xavier jumped to their feet, Mirnada twisted and leapt backwards over a short table. The two could only stand and watch as she had made a bolt across the living room and began ascending the stairs.
        The girl met with their looks of surprise for a moment “Er, no need t' trouble yerselves over nothin'!” Mirnada waved them away as she disappeared up the steps, “If aught she jus' 'ah a slip! I'll 'ave a look-see.” there was a stop in her steps as Mirnada took the time to shout back “Ladies o'ly!” 
        “A lady is not you...” Tavian muttered to himself, crossing his arms and tapping his fingers impatiently. Then the men eyed each other, and stood ready with uncertainty. 
        There was a slow wrapping at the door upstairs, “Diame?” Mirnada called melodically. The cautious knocks were followed by a pause.
        Xavier eyed the two of them, “I can't just stand here!” he took a step towards the stairs. There had to be something he could do to help. 
        Madame Oakh raised a hand to assure him, “Let the girl check on her.” she said grandmotherly, “It wouldn't do any good for a man to burst into the lady's bath.” She wanted to say more, but she took pause when she met with the concern swelling in Xavier's deep-green eyes. He is truly beside himself. The poor man.
        “But, I...” Xavier knew well he couldn't just stand here, yet there must be some way he could be helping. The air was heavy with vibes of wrongness, he glanced at Tavian for a moment, he nodded a mutual acknowledgement that something was foully amiss. 
        Oakh sighed and cleared her throat, “Fine then,” she stabbed the floor with all her weight with her staff, “I'll check on her too.” she said with a much too sweet smile. She tried to stand hurriedly, then she shuddered with a sharp gasp and her eyes widened, “I feel... a presence! A malevolent spirit is in my house!” she fell back into her chair she began to shake, “It... it seeks Diame!”
        A loud, slow creak came from the upstairs door followed by Mirnada softly calling out “Diame?” then a sharp creak and a hard slam. “Yii-eee!” Mirnada screamed with all the strain in her voice.
        Xavier darted for the stairs with Tavian at his heels.
        
        What wretchednessss iss thiss? The Daemon-Serpent's voice resonated angrily as lighting poured from its mouth. It iss of no conssequencce! It aimed its ebbing cone of lightning at Diame that grew faster and with more ferocity. 
        Without time to think, Diame had regained some control over herself and swam up towards the light that was drawing closer. The small glint of light was now the size of the sun in the sky. As it drew closer, more and more light pillars cascaded from above, stretching with all their might to reach Diame. The distance was vast, but the light was closing it moment by moment.
        Foolss, you act too late. With that, the lightning coursing through the horns and teeth of the sea snake broke forth, all that was seen was a flash of dark blue silhouettes in the sea. The snake tongue flicked and slithered and a ferocious hiss was let from its mouth. The lightning beam discharged, roiling the water as it hurled towards Diame. 


        Xavier ascended to the top of the stairs to find Mirnada lying on the floor in the hall, the door wide open. She was on her back, hands and feet staring upright into the room, eyes wide peeled and mouth gaped. Xavier stepped over her and ran through the the bedroom's threshold. 
        There Diame lay, suspended in the air within a sphere of soapy bathwater. The huge snow-globe waters spun and churned wildly, soap suds forming in the water dripping off onto the floor. Bright white moonlight eerily glared in from the window, the flare pervaded the room in a flood of blinding illumination. The watery orb bent and twisted all the light like a crystal ball around the priestess. Shadows of unfriendly hands caressed around Diame in dark blue flickers at moments at a time. Diame floated with her back arched, her arms outstretched and her legs were tightly wrapped around themselves. Her arms were loosely swaying in the waters movements, and her red hair flailed with the rapid movements of her aquatic cocoon. Her eyes were closed, and her face was serene yet vacant. 
        Tavian also hopped over Mirnada and charged in beside Xavier, also standing beside him unknowing what to do. A daemonic presence possesses her indeed! It wills her to mance the waters as sure as she had surrendered herself freely. How can this be?! He clenched his steel fist and pounded it against the wall once in frustration. “What holds her grips with immense malice! Even she couldn't withstand...” he cut himself off, for he knew the complete disdain and disregard daemons have for human life. He needed not to reiterate the obvious danger she was in, so he just crossed his arms.
         Xavier stepped forward, looking up at Diame hovering, the light spinning around the room.  A way to combat this malevolence ensorcelling her... Unintentionally, Xavier began to mance the magick himself. The light in the room, the overabundance of his affinity began to draw itself within him. His bare feet stepped across the wet floor up and stood just before her. 
        Forms of hands kept flickering in and out of light and shadow. The blackened flesh of the ghostly hands flickered and faded in and out of sight by the glow of a blue light. They grabbed Diame, and the fingers would indent her skin, then sink into her and fade into contrast. Over and over, dark hands appeared and grabbed her, disappeared, keeping her locked in this hold. 
        “Can aught be done!?” Madame Oakh said as she leaned in on her staff. Mirnada was behind her, hiding yet helping her stand. She entered and stood between Xavier and Tavian. She had seen spells used in many ways, and in her time dealt with the use of black magick. But this, she hadn't felt a presence like this in many years. It cannot be...! The blue light, the black hands, the chill in her bones. “Fa'Mes was felled, was he not!? Why!?” She shuddered, sick with fear, “How can its vile magicks yet still seek her?!” 
        Tavian turned his head to her, then back to the window. Then that light is... of course! “The star!” he blurted out, uncrossing his arms. 
         Xavier held up his hand, he felt the warmth of the light he had drawn in, the sensation connected him to its source spinning around the room. Indeed the presence of a powerful daemon weighs foully on the air. But there is more than wickedness in here, this light sickens me to touch it, yet there is another force carrying it. A presence that bears a light with a different aether, one pure and holy!


        The watery depths within Diame's head were still in a chaotic struggle. Diame kept swimming away and up towards the sun within the sea. Its light was straining thin beams through the black murk. The lightning chasing Diame at last found her, close and ready to engulf, then suddenly the bolts slowed and twisted. The cone of lighting was within arms reach of her yet could not touch her. It spun in a furious vortex, crackling with the thunder of an underwater storm. 
         Diame kept kicking desperately, not taking time to look back at the lightning was slowing. As long as she fought to escape, her will could keep it at bay. Her focus centered on hopes of salvation as the dim sphere that grew in size yet was still untouchable. The light...! Why can I not reach it!? She willed herself harder. I must... I can not die here...!


        “I... I'm going to try something.” Xavier said with all caution. 
        A pleading, “P-please, anythin'!” caught Xavier to turn his head and saw Mirnada ducking out behind Madame Oakh. She was shaking and holding onto her robe white-knuckled. “You 'ave t' save her...”  she said meekly.
        He nodded confidently to assure her, and he turned back to Diame in distress. Xavier felt out with his hand as he stood next to the hovering Diame. Standing before the sphere of water she looked as if she were in a mystic womb caught between light and darkness. He felt both energies, in a combat. If I am to save her I have but one choice. To draw in the foul dark as well as this light that isn't completely tainted. He felt the tips of his fingers reach past themselves, and the energies flowed in many beams of blue, black, and yellow-white light. He felt the sickly energy first, the blue haze surrounding the black light. Rancor of Fa'Mes... I remember this wrenching in my gut, I felt as if I could never stomach food again. It emaciated every nerve in my body, I could not move. The hatred from his spirit refuses to loosen hold on her. He drew the energies in deeper, the feelings of sickness traveling up his arms. Then he felt the black waves on this fingertips. This is... a terrifying power, far beyond Fa'Mes. A daemon has a direct hold on her... but how?
        “What sense you?” Madame Oakh questioned.
        “There are two distinct malevolent presences with energies that twist and chill uniquely.” Xavier said, eyes closed and still concentrating on the magicks that flowed through him. “And still more. This light...” He pulled Fa'Mes into himself further, the disgust of thought of what he was doing was nearly as bad as the blue flames curse he once suffered. The black energy stemmed up the veins in his arms like thorns. He agonized, drawing in this much poisonous aether and the toll it began to take on him. He responded, he began to glow a faint glimmer of his own protective light to shield himself somewhat from all this deadly energy. To draw in this much of the Daemons' energy, I must be mad, but, it must be the only way to save her. I can not exert all my own aether too soon, but it is taking all I have to hold them back. If I could only reach this light, it is so close yet so far away. He could feel the presence of the light. It was warm, gentle and strong like a flame. Come to me, light. The sensation of the light grew stronger against his fingertips, but he could not draw it in. 
         He can withstand all that malice? The oath-light of the paladins must be what protects him so. Tavian watched as the magick light beams were drawn from the watery sphere. Diame seems slightly less distressed, he is bearing some of this curse. Noble, yet I hope not futile. He tapped his fingers against his crossed arms. I feel useless. I hope he knows what he is doing.
         A sharp pang stabbed in Xavier's gut, twisting and he knelt agonizing. Ah... the source of this magick fights back. I am interfering. Good. I care not how I suffer, she is in worse danger. He stood once more, his hand aglow holding the blue and black light. The yellow-white light was pulling towards him, yet still out of reach. I can feel power like a tidal wave surging in this light. It wants to reach Diame, in fact it is protecting her from completely succumbing to this black magick. His strength began to waver, the black and blue energies taking over him slowly, him fighting back with his own light. If I can not draw this light in, it is because it is meant for Diame. But if I added my light to it... Willing all his spiritual strength, he gathered all the light he could from within himself. My aether, my light is yours, Diame. He felt the last of his life force pulse through his blood, his light filling him up. It extended out his arms and pushed against the evil he had tapped into. Bright candescence spilled out of his hands, stringing up the beams of magick with strong pulses and into the yellow-white light. 
        As his light left his body, the darkness he had welcomed in began to take vengeful hold of him. The poisoned black and blue light festered deeper into him, he felt a grip on his chest as if his ribs were constraining his own lungs. He gave a sharp gasp and collapsed, Madame Oakh and Tavian rushed to his side while Mirnada shrieked in the doorway.
        The hot-white candescence of his light fed into the sickly glow of the yellow-white light. The rays of jaundice separated and dispersed from the unknown light source, and it absorbed Xavier's strength and shone a new, purified light. The light within Diame's aquatic prison began to glow bigger and brighter, the water ball turning into a sphere of swirling light.
        
        A loud, distant, slow, echoing shriek turned Diame's head as she continued to swim. It was filtered within the muffle of the sea depths, yet rang with a familiar voice. She saw nothing but the faint glow of the sun hidden within the murk of the dark. The closer and closer she got, the more frustrated and exhausted she was. Why! If this light be not my rescuer, then what will be!? The tips of the lightning bolts were fingers away from her toes, flinging daggers of sparks in violent desperation to reach her. Even these projectiles slowed in time, and the great comet of crashing blue electricity followed in Diame's wake.
