        Xavier felt every muscle in his body convulse and spasm, feeling every individual ache. His body felt as if a giant ball of ice was melting, as if consuming itself. From the tips of his toes and fingers warmth and normal muscle control was restored. He felt the sensation of coldness leave himself until he felt a cold ball of ice in his chest melt to nothing. He breathed regularly and lay on the floor.
        “You alright?” Tavian asked, letting Xavier's arm fall to the floor.
        Xavier muttered something incoherent, and stared up at the ceiling. He breathed normally and twitched occasionally.
        “He'll need a minute or two.” He stood then turned up to the sphere of rust, that no long was a smooth elegant orb, now it was a grossly misshapen gelatinous ball of filth. “Oakh, what think you?”
        Oakh observed the aether spinning in the room carefully. “The daemon means to kill Diame. We can distract and sway it, but it will be for naught. She will die soon unless we sever their connection completely, but what holds her in this grip binds with so much power.”
        Tavian reached his steel hand toward the ball of gunk, nearly touching it. I will do what I can. He reached his hand into the sphere, it squished as if reaching into a pool of mud. An ill bubbling churned in his stomach. He felt the presence of corruption resound in his head, What weak magickss you intervene with can sstaunch me not. He felt his gut twisting, he fought it as much as he could, it amplified nonetheless. He felt layers up on layers of needles prickling his skin and innards, he snarled and began channeling his Arcana to ward it off. The lassss is mine. I sshall make you ssuffer for your arrogancce. The sensation built more, it felt like a toxin searing away at his nerves. He drew harder up on his Arcana to repel the power to little avail. 


        The priestess gasped for air within the ocean of red. She struggled, drowning while hearing this wretched sea serpent pervade her mind. So there before her writhed the long coiled scales, dimly aglow in its underworld magicks that made it glow pale blue. The twisted head, the charred black serpentine skull swaying towards her with bitter ire in its fiery black jeweled eyes. Hatred boiled all to thick blood.
        My air is cut short. Diame's throat tightened. She turned to plead to the white sun shimmering up above the scarlet. An I can not free myself, the thought shuddered her, I die. She reached out, straining her arms to grab the sun. This creature sought and can attack my mind only through my soothsaying eye. This is my magick, the light of my aether; my mortal soul! It wills me to drown, I canst feel my lungs fill with this sickly blood! But this is a dream, and I must compel this daemon away! She gazed up to the white sun, it began to extend thin, dim beams of light that seemed to push back the redness of the ocean around it. A bright blue, the sapphire shade of Diame's eyes, shone giving the candescent sun a cerulean corona. The rays swayed like natural waves of the sea and slowly began reaching through the red, revealing clear oceanic waters.
         You inssolent sshite! The venom of mine magickss sshould have prevented you from calling forth on thiss light! The snake from hell opened its snarled maw of charred, twisted teeth and a single giant bolt of searing red lightning pealed as it fulminated forth. 
         Diame stared into the cannon's mouth, with an unflinching resolve. Thou fell daemon that possesses me, Her body could draw breath no more, drowning numbness creeped along her limbs. In Evaz'Sa's hallowed name, She used the last of her expended strength, pulling her exasperated arms up above her, beholding the sphere of light. Creature, begone! The blue aura of the sun grew bigger and brighter, the whiteness of the sun filled it in as it grew. More of the red ocean melted into more pure seawater as the beams outstretched.
        The column of red lightning roiled forth, all the strength of daemonic might shaking all with the breaking of thunder. The beam homed in towards Diame, unrelenting and fast.
        The white sphere of the sun continued to grow and its mass closed the seemingly endless gap between Diame. Its blue aura engulfed Diame, she took a deep breath of sea water, her air restored she panted a sigh of relief. She turned to face the Daemon-Serpent, her blue eyes shone a blazing blue that out shined the sun in radiance. 
        The column of red lightning was up on her, crashing in a fulminating whirl approaching with arching speed.
        At where the lightning would have appeared next, Diame outstretched one of her soft hands out towards the killer bolt. She pulled the lightning towards her, she would not run from this danger, but would wrangle and wrest it to submission. Her eyes burned a hue of blue that made the wispy aura of blue around the sun thicken and become reinforced with power. The cannon of red lightning continued relentlessly from the serpent-crocodile mouth, yet the column faded into a pinprick that formed into a sphere the size of a marble within Diame's hand. The daemon expelled more energy in its rage, but to no avail. Diame held all power the daemon intended to use against her in the palm of her hand, and it continued to grow. Not phased in the slightest by the presence or power of the daemon, the white sun was now encompassing the sea. The white light of the sun permeated through the clear waters, more light filled the sea than water. The redness of the daemon's presence was reduced to circular clouds of bright red at the sea bottom, the rage of the underworld.
        The Daemon-Serpent's lightning began to wane, the glows of blue and red that pulsed along the scaled coils now were dim and faint. The boom and ire of the cannon that threatened Diame's life was now weak and absorbed into her palm. In an instant, the weakened beam thinned into a single glimmering strand, and disappeared. The will of the daemon was strong, but all its strength was diminished. What flesh from face and teeth from maw that had remained attached to its skull had been near completely torn off in the wake of its own cannon. Even the two black spheres that burned with hateful flames now became dull black jewels that glimmered faintly in pathetic spiteful eye-splits. It let out a weakened roar that was nonetheless filled with the bitter hatred of defeat. Foolissh light-dweller. Its black eyes and snarled snake maw glowered with all the flesh that remained that could convey twisted emotion. The aether within you burnss with unquesstionable sstrength. Yet, however you may cling to your meaninglessss defiancce, your wretched light will falter and sshall be added to the greatnessss of the Lordss of Pandaemonium. Fear thiss, the Ssecond God portentss ssuch! Its black eyes squared and locked directly with the glow from Diame's.
        The red marble of condensed lightning spun in her hand, the white sun at her back and she completely engulfed in a solid blue corona. Diame reached forward with her other hand, holding it down towards the daemon in a halt. What you portent compares not to what I will. And my will is strong, and I will your ill presence purged and gone! The white surface of the sun enveloped her back, and absorbed her body inside of it. The light engulfed most of her, except her hands. The red marble flew forward, away from the sunlight as she was completely absorbed within the surface of hot white light. Warmth of the sun filled her, as if she were radiating it out of her own body. The red marble suddenly burst with the force of all the lighting condensed into a single moment. The pealing of thunder split the waters, all was a sphere of air and lightning. It was as if the entire ocean floor broke and crumbled, the sea waters drifting apart in the explosion as if sucked away by the vacuum of space. The white sun now engulfing Diame hurled forward, the blue Corona turning into the tail of a comet. The vastness of the ocean was now the infinite void of space. Every drop of sea water was flung far and every droplet twinkled as infinite stars. The Daemon-Serpent coiled up from some unknown cavern that glowed red with hellfire hovering in space. It alone was within this void and all its openness, the hulking sea serpent-crocodile and the sun hurled at it like a comet of light. At the very center of the sphere, Diame could faintly be seen completely enveloped in bright white light.
        The Daemon-Serpent stood still, an undaunted towering coil. The comet of light collided with the snake in the center of the coil, engulfing nearly all of its body. The force of impact let out an explosion of candescent shards of light that pierced the black scales of the underworld creature. Sounds of glass and ice cracking and crashing in a hailstorm of light shards emanated from everywhere. A final roar of defeat escaped the maw of the serpent, then the head tossed back in the force of the explosion. The comet's mass continued to increase, and the entire serpent was consumed, the maw to hell crumbled to sand and faded. The light grew until the entire void of space was one completely white sun, with Diame in the center, arms outstretched.


        Xavier and Tavian lay on the floor with the sphere of black tar hovering above them in Oakh's guest bedroom. Xavier laid with eyes open, eyes blankly staring at the ceiling. A moment of consciousness returned to him and he tries to sit up every now and again, then his eyes roll back and he once again lay incapacitated. Tavian was on his hands and knees, grabbing at his chest, trying to repel the daemon magick with his arcane defenses. Yet he still felt the countless needles that pierced his skin, nerves and gut, and could do no more but writhe and fight it off.
        Madame Oakh stood still with Mirnada wide-eyed and clinging to Oakh's cloak yet. She stared at the black sphere and felt the malicious will of the daemon spirit. She shuddered in fear and defeat, her heart sank to her feet.
        A tiny pearl of light appeared inside of the black sphere, and in a flash the blackness of the orb turned to blood red, then to blue, then to a white ball of light. The white ball of light hovered in the room, filling the room with pure white candescence. 
        Oakh felt a sudden weight fly from her shoulders, as if the air had been heavier before. She stood taller and gasped for a breath, as if she had forgotten to breathe. Mirnada did the same, feeling as if the air had become thinner suddenly, like a cloud of dark smoke had been removed rom the room. They covered their eyes from the sudden brightness of the sphere of light.
        Tavian suddenly fell head to the floor, holding his sides. His body felt like a million needles were suddenly pulled out of him like an overstocked pin cushion. For every invisible wound, a warm kiss of light filled him that comforted him. He felt as if he were in a sudden deep sleep of well deserved rest that bathed him in warm swathes of healing light.
        Xavier sat up with a gasp, suddenly hearing a distant voice in his head that echoed like a hymn of angels, As they gather strength, her life becomes more endangered. He looked around, seeing only a ball of light that glowed a dim golden yellow, and the room was dark with shadows in all corners of the room. The sphere looked like it were a lampshade with a candle and Diame's shadow within. He saw Oakh and Mirnada covering their eyes from its brightness, even with candescent white reflecting from their hands. They seemed to be moving slower too, like time was almost stilled. But for some reason he could stare directly into this sun. He saw a faint silhouette of Diame in the sphere, but hovering before him were smoky wisps of mist that carved a human form. The clouds of blue and white made a transparent human face that seemed to hover like a mask disembodied over the cloak of fog it wore. “What say you? Name thyself, spirit.”
         The white wind whirled around him, he gasped and inhaled lungs of the light mist. His mind once again echoed in a harmonious song-like voice, If her light is taken, all hope dies with it. The white mask hovered there. White, unblinking eyes pierced right at him. Only the lips and cheeks moved as it sang words. Caelutera will perish. All that live depend up on the safety of this one woman's soul. The mask split with a sharp crack, chips of shimmering glass-sand cascaded down the mask's face and eyes. Heed this with all thy will, or unspeakable calamity will befall up on the world. The mask split apart into large fragments, the broken apart lips still moved in unison like speaking into a broken mirror, The Watchers cometh, the sigils will break. The mask broke again into smaller fragments, the voices multiplied, The Watchers cometh, the sigils will break. The mask fragments split again and again, repeating with more voices and more intensity, The Watchers cometh, the sigils will break!
        Xavier exhaled all his breath, and in an instant time restored to its normal flow with a blinding flash that filled the room, a candescence that even hurt his eyes. The sphere containing Diame returned to a white candescent ball. The fog and broken mask were nowhere to be seen.
        Tavian sat up and crawled back and away from the sphere, regaining his strength. He turned his eyes as well.
        The light from the white sphere swelled, then shrunk to the size of a pearl. Everyone's eyes could one again see with this gentler light, and they looked in relieved disbelief. The sphere was returned to clear soapy bath water, with Diame floating inside. The tiny glint of light emanated from her chest, and she waded with open arms and wide eyes. Before anyone could speak a word, the pearl faded within her. The glassy sphere lost its shape and gravity sent it crashing to the floor, with all the  water splashing in every direction. Water that managed to be recontained back in the bath was shot out as Diame landed harshly in the tub. Sudsy water soaked the entire room, with waves of such sudden strong torrents it left all trinkets on shelves in disarray and the guest beds sodden. Everyone was splashed with the waters, and the scent of spiced konjode grass filled the room. Water droplets trickled from the ceiling, streams went down walls, and water rushed through the floorboards and out the bedroom door, flooding down the stairs and throughout the house. Diame lay nude and unconscious in the tub, curled in a ball. All was silent except for the sounds of water throughout the home and their own panting.
        With quick trots and careful use of her staff, Madame Oakh rushed over to Diame. Mirnada stayed close behind her, still holding onto her coatsleeves. Tavian raised himself and knelt beside the tub with Oakh. She reached forward with her bony hands and felt Diame's chest. No breath moved her lungs. No pulse beat her heart. Oakh reached under Diame's head and held her up from the tub. Oakh looked down at her hands wrapped around her red hair, but the crimson crept past her locks. Blood touched the droplets of her wet skin, dripping down her arms in ruddy chase.  “Oh, Diame!” Oakh wept over her.
        Xavier willed himself up onto his knees, and he crawled weakly to the tub. He placed his hands over the rim and in surreal horror he, Tavian and Mirnada in a circle watched the weeping Oakh cradling the lifeless priestess. “Diame!” He patted her face to rouse her, but glazed eyes still stared skyward. “Merciful God, this can not be so! Diame!” His voice strained and cracked with dry tears, “Diame! Nay, nay!” 
        Tavian shook his head, “The daemon was too much for her, my Arcana was weak, it nary did aught against that wretched being,” he snarled in disgust as he continued, “and fie if now we have not lost.” 
         All that live depend up on the safety of this one woman's soul. A strong memory of words Xavier wasn't sure how he heard refilled his mind. Unspeakable calamity will befall up on the world. It resounded in the same hymnal cadence. He scanned the eyes with everyone who gazed quietly up on Diame. “Nay, you shall not die!” they all looked at him with mixed looks of puzzlement. 
        Tears streamed from Oakh's white and brown eyes as they scorned at Xavier, “What can be done!?” she shuddered and glowered miserably. She began to speak but no words left her lips.
        What can be done? Xavier pondered himself with as well. “This... this can be undone.” he turned to meet with the teary ruby-eyed girl.
        Mirnada stared back at him. “Wot?” 
        “What did you use before?” Xavier reached for Mirnada's hand, she pulled it back with startled reflex. “You cast healing magick on her ere now, did you not?”
        “A-aye, I... I did, but... um.” She gulped, “Iuno how!” Mirnada held her hands up emptily.
        “Child, you do indeed know how!” Madame Oakh put her hands on Mirnada's shoulders and turned her, “You said yourself, you mended her leg!” She tried to meet with Mirnada's face but her head was turned to Diame. Oakh gently placed her hands on top of Mirnada's, “You have the gift of magick. Do not be afraid to use it, child. You wish to help her? You are the only one who can bring Diame back to us.” 
         All eyes were on Mirnada suddenly. Not again... her hands tightened and she gulped. What did I even do to save her before? She made her way to the edge of the bath where Diame paler than moonlight lay. Master... help me... Images of her pushing the bone of her leg back into place to have it mended instantaneously in a rush of violet flames. Breaking the barred steel door open with the fire of her hands. The rush of adrenaline she got when she used her gift. It all came to her in a flash. I can do this. I have to. If I can't, no one's here who can save her now. Oh, I wish I could speak to Diame... She reached forward and placed her right hand on Diame's damp red hair. I will try. Master, now of all times, help me make purple flames and not the bad ones. She held her hand there on her cold head, she could feel the faintest sign of life within Diame like a flickering spark of heat. But she could not feel it change, and her wounds did not heal. Work! She willed herself with all her might, yet to no effect. She saw the violet flames in her mind, but they wouldn't appear. Her hands tightened, and it was as if she were trying to shake the spell out of her by force.
        “Hold child, that is not how you conduct magicks.” Oakh sighed.
        Mirnada willed and envisioned the violet flames, but they would not conjure still. She released her grip and looked up at them, “I-I'm tryin'. I'm sorry, I can't get 'er to open 'er eyes.” Trembling tears began to swell in hers. She closed her eyes and she wept helplessly.
        This can not be, this shall not be. Xavier gazed down at Diame, then back to Mirnada. “I have been taught the basics of healing, useful many a time for a scrape or bruise in battle. Never have I seen any purple flame used in Ijia, but I'm sure the same laws of magick apply to your spells too.”
        Mirnada looked up at Xavier, red in the face “Then wot is i' I c'n do! I want to 'elp 'er just as dearly as you d'!” she shouted, then stopped as she began to choke on her tears.
        Xavier extended his hand over the tub, opened and relaxed. “Take my hand. Together, we will revive her.”
        Take his hand. Master help me, show me again, Marshall! Just once more. She stared at Xavier's hand. The violet flame. She remembered a time when Marshall touched her forehead and the light poured from there. He used her power to heal her own hand, she realized. Channel the power within yourself. That is the key to all secrets of Jorgard Aethermancy locked away in your blood. “Master Marshall!” Mirnada shouted with shut eyes, envisioning the light with all her might. She reached for Xavier's hand, she reached for the violet flames she wished for.
         The moment Xavier felt Mirnada's hand within his, he felt the warm pulses fire aether makes when one conducts it flow through his arm. She deftly contains magick and potential, how to release the spell? He reached within his own memories. An arrow on the battlefield, shot by an enemy. It pierced his steel legging, but did not fully enter. The sharp arrowhead stabbed him, he had to hobble off the field as a novice under a surprise attack. He removed his armor and the arrow with it, but the wound was bleeding severely. He had just learned the basics of Paladin arts the days before, and with his own talent, healed his own leg. Once he was mended, to his own surprise, went back to fight on the battlefield to defend the good of Ijia. That first memory of the spell's success always began his healing spells. He felt the presence of the spirit of mist within him as a powerful light force. He felt the warmth of the light fill him, and let it flow out of his hand to meet Mirnada's.
         A dull ball of candle light appeared between their hands. Mirnada's eyes were still closed, calling for the healing fire. She felt the light from Xavier's hand, it was as if it were trying to draw the spell out of her. The dim orb grew to a dim purple. Mirnada opened her eyes and to her surprise saw the first sign of the light she sought in their hands. I can do this... you did teach me something after all, Master... A circle of violet light emblazoned itself on Mirnada's forehead, she closed her eyes once more.
        The orb between their hands crackled like electricity, and with a spark of light, plumes of violet flames engulfed both Xavier and Mirnada's arms. The flowing river of liquid purple light-glow filled Diame's bath with warm fire, filling it to the brim and covering her completely in light. The room was engulfed in this light, all seemed to be made of dark polished amethyst reflecting the light of the healing bathtub bonfire.
        Mirnada and Xavier felt a wave of euphoria enveloped in the light of the powerful healing spell. It was the nature of magick for the caster to experience part of the spell they were casting. A combination of the church's light aether used with Jorgard ancient spells joined the two in feeling the healing bliss. It was as if they had a months rest instantaneously, yet the spell was not complete. The figure of Diame flickered in and out with the lapping of light.
        Tavian sat on the damp floor and watched the spectacle of the spell. Who knew the kid could heal wounds, but can she really bring back from the dead? From where does she hold this much power?
         Xavier released his hand from the girl's, the sensation felt like severing a never ending current of warming light. He fell backwards suddenly feeling numbness, then back to feeling his natural surroundings. He lay on the damp floor.
         The light swelled and ceased its flow, leaving Diame bathing in light. The violet flames arose as if the bath were oil alit on a lantern cup.
        Mirnada fell backwards as well, the symbol emblazoned on her head flickering. Her eyes and mouth agaped and violet light sprang forth from both, then ceased, and she lay unconscious.
         The light evaporated, burnt into mist by the fire. The mists coalesced into a cloud around the window, and all at once it seeped outside, disappearing into the sky. Tavian and Oakh stared at each other, then hovered over Diame wondering of her fate. 
        “Did they succeed? Is she...?” Madame Oakh brushed her hand against Diame's clammy cheek, and her eyes opened slowly. “Diame! Diame!” she kissed her on the head and put her arms around her. Oakh wept again.
        All was in a haze for her. Diame remembered little, last thing she knew she was taking a bath. As she began to sit up slowly, she began to wonder why Oakh was embracing her, and further why everyone was in the room with her still bare. “Tavian,” Diame asked in whispered, squeak of a voice, “What in the name of all the saints at once happened in here?” her blue eyes widened, locked with his red-hazel.
        He opened his mouth to speak, but wasn't sure where to start. Before he could speak a word, a loud thunderous slam of a door opening shook the house, followed by heavy footsteps. The sound ran up the sodden stairs, then a heavy slip and fall with a loud unknown curse. Carefully and urgently the footsteps made their way to the top of the stairs. 
        A tall, bald, bearded man built like twenty oxen came charging into the room, catching himself in the doorway so the large man didn't slip on the damp floor again. He gave the most abashed look on his grizzled face when he saw the four strangers doing what they were doing with Madame Oakh. With full lungs he shouted, “What in the name o' all the saints at once is happenin' in 'ere?!” he went and knelt beside Oakh at the tub, “Madame, madame!”
        “Aye,” she turned up from Diame, “Oh, Gruph!” she turned to him and even they were both kneeling, Madame Oakh's head only came up to about his chest. She began to stand, to which he helped her. “Many strange things have happened tonight. God have mercy.”
        “Then what were,” the behemoth of a man shook his head in further confusion, “What was making all the light? The whole village saw lights comin' from your window, and-”
        “That is all well,” Oakh said, staring back at Diame, who was staring back at her. Her complexion was now a shade of deep beet red, “Perhaps we should leave her some privacy to dress herself and we can discuss this over some hot tea?” She left the room and descended downstairs with Gruph's help.
        Tavian averted his eyes from Diame and helped Xavier to his feet, Mirnada was moving about and seemed to rouse herself awake on her own. “I'd advise against anymore practical magicks for the night, my lady.” he said as he carried Xavier out.
                        




























                XII.  Night's Auspice


        Not too far off the coast of Ijia, there a black island surrounded by craggy rocks pierce the waters. Entrance is difficult for anyone, so many charter around the area completely to reach the safe harbors of Ijia Castle Town. At the late hour of this night, a group of three in dark robes with donned hoods climbed up the craggy black rocks to reach the flatlands above. It took time, and the ocean of the night was foggy and the sliver of crescent moon did not offer much light. Perfect conditions for infiltrating unnoticed for the brazen trio. Just enough light to navigate among shoals, and plenty of mist to cloak beneath. Although the sea mist made the climb treacherous, they neared the top of their climb.
        A set of hands pulled up a peering cloaked head over the rocks to the flatlands. It was safe, no one else was in sight. “An easy entrance to an uneasy task.” a female voice muttered under her hood. She climbed up and with one arm pulled up the next cloaked follower, then that follower helped the final third. They stood there in the still of the dark night, able to take a breath from their harsh climb. “We find safe grounds and re-arm. None of their clan seems to be around this side of the isle, but they hide and set cruel traps. Do not forget this. We move.” She turned and walked before her followers could utter with quiet respect “As you command, Zenith.” 
        She crouched slightly and moved with graceful silence through the shadows. All the clinking of metal she carried with her was muffled under her cloak. The ground cracked dryly under her feet with occasional rustles of the few blades of dry grass that could grow on the black island. Around a thick nestle of near-leafless trees and a rocky alcove she ducked into a small concealed clearing. She sat and her followers ducked through the dry brush one after another. They sat as well and they each looked around. The pale sliver of the moon was broken through the thatch of tree branches overhead. The brush was thick and they would not be seen.
        The first to sit removed a bone-white stone from her pocket and placed it on the ground. It instantly lit and made a small bubble of light; just enough to see your hands. She waited for a moment and then pulled her cloak off over her head, and the others did the same. She lay the cloak down on the ground and on her many things were strapped to her, some cloth bundles, one was narrow but as long as a small horse. They all had ropes and some climbing gear on, which they removed and placed on their cloaks. They each removed their bundles and lay them in front of themselves, and the followers awaited the leader to speak. “We wait at your command, Zenith Azaria.”
        The dim glow of the stone grew more, and faces were at last revealed. Azaria had silver and gold eyes that pierced into any who looked into them. Her long black-ruby hair was tied together nearly and hung down her back under her armor. Her skin was lily-white, and she had high cheekbones and fierce facial features for a female. She had her light armor on, meant for stealth and maneuvering. Her neck and upper chest were exposed, but her shoulders had darksteel pauldrons. Her body armor was made of darksteel scale plates that covered her stomach and breasts. She had legging clad in layers of thin darksteel plates into tough leather and metal boots. She began undoing the laces on her bundles carefully while she eyed her followers doing the same. “Raven Icargo, Crow Delina, we made such haste here, I feel as if we were meant to be here tonight. The cultists are gathered entire out in the open at the far side of the isle, leaving the rest deserted. They are deftly up to something. And that.” Azaria pointed up to the blue star in the far north with obvious distaste twisting her face, “The new star. Have the cultists begun performing some sort of cursed rites that could violate the sky with such an ominous phenomenon?” She pulled back the dull gray cloth covering the large bundle, revealing a long, darksteel sheathe. A black hilt to a large sword lay inside. The middle of the cross guard had a large eye-shaped stone. Steel was wrought into a shape of eyelids on either side of the hilt, within a dark-red jewel. It looked near-black, but in certain glints of light the gem flared bright orange. “Whatever it may be they do, they nonetheless conspire tonight. The new star could foretell many things, and none of them benefit any but the cult. Or the underworld.” she added knowing her followers would take in the deeper meaning of what lies in the underworld.
        Her followers listened intently as they untied their bundles as well. Delina was a young-looking woman, though her age undefinable. Her dark hair was short in a fashion more suited for a boys, and in the back what short hair was there was pinned up. Her eyes were a bright daffodil yellow that reflected a once soft woman who sloughed off her femininity for the power and responsibility of Shadow Knighthood. Her idol and master were the one and same woman before her. She removed her cloth from her bundle revealing two weapons; a short sword, darksteel blade oiled over years to a mirror sheen, yet the gladius reflected hardly any light. Her other weapon, a scepter about the length of her arm. Two intertwining poles of black and white into a single, short staff, one was darksteel, the other greyish-white wood. They fastened around and bound a silver colored orb. Her sword she kept in its sheath down her side tied around belt strap that circled around her back and front body armor. Her scepter was tied tightly into a bundled holster on her back. She wore similar armor to Azaria's, but there was much less of the heavy darksteel. She wore only a few thin plates of the durable metal inlaid against a light leather bodice that ended in a short steel and leather skirt. Her leggings were stitched dark cloth into soft leather boots inlaid with sable fur. Her preference of lighter armor was to better suit her use of magick. Heavier armor hinders conducting flows of spells, but her magick wouldn't be needed if they stayed shrouded in this dark night. They weren't here to go charging into the nest of the enemy attacking needlessly. They wouldn't even need her magick for defense, she hoped. 
        Icargo was a fairly tall middle-aged man with the sides and top of his head shaved. Tied behind his head was a single shoulder-length braid of dark brown hair tucked beneath his battle armor. He wore darksteel pauldrons and a thin, maneuverable plate of dark steel across his chest, accompanied by thick and light leather armor around his torso and back. He wore leather pants with thin steel panels and metal boots completing his armor. His eyes were blue ice, a constant cold, near-white stare. He looked as though he had charged into battle countless times, seen countless things, and you began to see them if you saw his stare for too long. He, too, had a polished gladius he undid from his bundles and looped a leather strap around his belt, keeping his sword at his side. His other bundle had a crossbow and a box of bolts he held at the ready.
        Everyone put their climbing gear into their robes and they and all the bundles were rolled together and tied around their backs. 
        “We are ready.” Azaria darted a pale hand and snatched the glowing stone from the ground. It dimmed to darkness with a whirr and she pocketed it as she stood. “We walk through the near pitch black of night.” Her Shadow Knights rose as well. “Even though we possess sight in darkness, there are many hiding... surprises.” she said with distaste. “I know this island well enough to know it does not welcome anyone. Be wary with your life and trust your instincts.” her knights nodded. She turned and ducked under the brush into the open fields. She strode with haste through the flatlands, the dry earth cracking quietly beneath her and her followers' feet. 
        Up ahead was more flat earth that went on into darkness. There was some small flickers of light in the far distance, but it was blurred by the scattered thatches of dried trees reaching skyward. The sounds of the ocean crashing against the rocks roared all around them. The rolling clouds of mists pooled in random pockets in the ground. Heavy fog sent the scent of tide pool air all around them and hindered sight. But on they went, speed but with caution. The lights in the distance grew brighter and they ran closer, the fog now thick to their knees. 
        “Halt!” Azaria suddenly stopped in her tracks, dust motes added to the fog beneath her as everyone stood still at the ready. She pointed just on ahead, the fog suddenly disappeared, with the lights a long stones throw away below them. The flatland stuck out on a peninsula overlooking beneath. She crouched down, the cool, moist air enveloping all beneath her eyes. Her gaze skimmed the surface of the deep pool of fog, wisps of white coalescing back into a thick blanket of mist on her wake. Her hands felt the damp ground as she crept closer to the edge. The others followed shrouded in the same way, and the three overlooked the rocky edge to see countless moving people a steep climb beneath them.
        In the valley below many torches were lit in a circle on high metallic totem poles around its circumference. In the center of the valley was a pyramid made of black stone surrounded by a massive crowd of hooded figures. They chanted in a chorus of whispers in perfect unison speaking in words from a previous Era. Azaria knew the words yet the chant she had not heard before. 
        The pyramid was as if a small mountain had been carved down to a flat top and torch-lined stairs. At the top was a large stone slab with a small group of people in jet-black robes. There was one figure that looked like a man, but it was much taller than any other. It dwarfed other men around him, and it wore a black, white and red ceremonial robe and miter. It wielded a size befitting darksteel cudgel in its grip, big enough to be a war hammer in the hands of an ordinary man. The mace had a cruel ball of spikes protruding from it. The tall man stood still holding the cudgel in his arms as if cradling a babe. It seemed to be part of whatever rites they were performing. 
        The wave of voices began to elevate. In the circle of people closest to the pyramid base, they thew up their arms and their chant that had been a whisper elevated to shouting. The cursed hymn became louder in a buzzing of whisper clicks and yells, all words spoken in perfect unison.
        “What is it they do, Zenith?” Icargo asked, his near white eyes blending into the mist perfectly. 
        Azaria kept her eyes locked forward and down on the conspiring cult with disgust. She frowned as she realized the chant they were performing, 
        
        “Rend the souls of Caelutera to the ground,
        Faithful light snuffed out, never to be found.
            Offers the True God, Her peoples' cruor warm,
           The sigils break, the Watchers empty their womb.” 
         
         She eyed Icargo with a nod over her shoulder, “That is what they say.” Azaria swept her eyes to the base of the stairs. A figure of naked skin reflecting torchlight began ascending the steps, the crowd's whisperers throng by throng became shouters as the person ascended. As it took step by step of the black pyramid, the features of a man with his hands bound behind him and blindfolded glowed in firelight. They mean to give an offering tonight. Rites for what purpose? She kept her focus to observe the beginning of the inevitable. Her and her two knights watched and waited. What they came to do. The man ascended with careful reluctance up the pyramid, those to be sacrificed that fall are forced to reclimb. As he was nearing halfway up the ebony steps, the flatlands held an arena packed shoulder to shoulder of chanting cultists, reverberating their chant in oldtongue gutteral groans.
         The sight of what was being performed in front of Delina chilled her, but her trained nerves retained their steel. Years of hearing mere rumors of the cult plotting and conspiring, years of finding only a handful of cultists in our hunts, years of hearing Azaria's tales of their masses... Never in my dreams would I think so many existed in Caelutera, much less right in the Ijian seas! They conspire to kill, but why? To please their God? She shook her head, yet continued to watch. Nay, it must be a rite to a powerful spell. Those hollow shells of men will spill living blood to perform execrable daemonic magick. To what purpose? The new star above head must be what stirs them so, but why? She uneasily kept looking down at the dark scene unfolding before her from the dizzying height.
        The blindfolded man's cut feet ascended the final few black stone steps. On his last step he took an extra unknowing no stairs remained, then stumbled to his knees. He kneeled nude save his bindings, the firelight cast awkward shadows across the skin of his back. The tall man in the ceremonial black, white and red robe took a step forward and keeping his cudgel cradled, he raised a single hand. Utter silence. The chorus of voices halted in a moment, every hooded head crooked, bated for bloody spectacle. The tall man put his left hand over the man's head, its huge grip pulled and rest the victim's head on the marble-stone slab. He removed it, and remained still in even more silence.
        Knives of chills ran down Azaria's back, the same sensation affected Delina and Icargo as well. They crouched uneasily, watching and waiting. The black pyramid surrounded by frozen hoods, statues of men. The torch-lined circle's flames grew skyward as hellish pillars, as if yearning to set the moon alit. The tall man lowered the cudgel he swathed to his side, then paused. The ocean roared all around the island, lunatic waters ebbed and crashed into the craggy walls from every side. Azaria could only hear the booming mixed white noise crashing from all directions, the waves building louder and louder, until every wave sounded the same from everything around her. Whatever it took, she stared, waited, and listened.
        The tall man raised his cudgel high above his head with both hands, if the victim could look up, the scythe of the moon crowned the cudgel. With one swift swing, the weapon met the stone slab, and the tall man stood still in his red and black ceremonial robe. The headless body was all that remained. The marble slab lay besmeared and soaked with what looked like slick oil reflecting the crescent moon. The blue star twinkled within the blood pool dubiously as well. The tall man leaned forward and grabbed the headless body of the victim by the legs with a single hand. He hung the body upside down, dangling and shaking the corpse dry of all its blood. He discarded it over the slab, and it rolled and tumbled down the steps of the pyramid. He took his cudgel, and lay it on the side of the slab. He held his hands up high, and beseeched the moon in the sky, hovering them over the reflection in the pool. The stone slab was flat, but it looked as if it were a deep basin of glistening black-rubies. The oily slick ebbed to one side of the stone slab, and syrupy like slow tar cascaded down the black marble pyramid, step by step. The reflection of the pale moon on the bloody slab began to stretch against the surface of the pyramid. The top crescent tip remained within the basin of the slab, but the image of the lower end of the moon crept over the slab's edge. A sliver of silver slithered down the black pyramid through the reflection of the bloody steps. A serpent of moonlight grew as it dominated each step, emblazoning the mirror of the moon huge across the side of the pyramid. 
        The ocean waves continued their torrent against the island with vehement force, the ground shook slightly with each crashing boom. The torch pillars spun wild sparks from them that arched glints of raining fire. The clouds in the sky twisted in a circle, like a hole had been made in the heavens. The circle of clouds encompassed the blue star, haunting waves of blue effulgence filled them. The blue star began to twinkle wildly, a glimmering single blue spark that would burst and ignite the night sky. 
        A glower of rage twisted Azaria's face, hidden beneath the shroud of mist. Fie, if I had known they conspired to cast such a powerful spell, I could have stopped them. Why did I not know of an intent of this magnitude? Have they truly grown in power so much they can perform such rites with a single mere mortal sacrifice? As if answering her question, the accursed sapphire crowning the night sky began to open, a blanket of clouds swathed like eyelids around the blue eye-shaped star. 
         The skies menace and grow eyes!? Nay, they couldn't truly be summoning a Watcher! She shifted where she hid among the mist. If a Watcher were to be summoned, she thought even she would be unable to stop such a thing. She watched and waited, the only thing they could do.
        The blue eye was like a vortex of cloud wisps, forming a thick swirled eyelid and the glassy orb of the eye was bent blue starlight. Within it, stray plumes of mist spun in the glow of the light, it looked like a giant winking marble. The blueness of the iris was more intense than the pale light of the moon, and the night was alight by this single star's light. The ebbing of the ocean was met by squalls of air howling from above. All around her, Azaria heard the trees' leafless branches rattling like clattering rib cages.
        The man in the ceremonial robe lowered his hands, as if the ritual were complete. The besmeared pyramid reflected the crescent of the moon and the eye of the star, as if pulling the light from the sky down onto itself. The tall man stood over the basin of blood and placed a single hand over it, the black slick roiled and bubbled furiously. 
        The power to do THIS much dark magick!? On my life, I've ne'er witnessed a Lich Lord even withstand the light of the moon. So banished to the darkest regents of their caves, how could he even enter the night? He execrates and unhallows the sky as freely as a bloody street mage peddles parlor tricks! She involuntarily punched the hard packed flat earth with her gauntleted hand. We have come far too late, I could have put an end to this!
         The pool of black liquid roiled and coalesced smaller until the remains of bubbling blood was a small floating orb. It glowed faintly with a red light, then the blood began to freeze and crystalize, become transparent and shed a foul light. There hovered a red gemstone the size of a human fist, it glimmered brilliantly with wicked luster. The man in the ceremonial robes encompassed it in one of his hulking hands. A twist to the grey-leathered, older than old looking face of the tall man rendered a foul smile that scorned the very emotion of the humans that make the same facial expression. The gem it had was the fruit of all the night's efforts, the Lich dreamed of what fouler more heinous deeds he could force up on the world now. This dark satisfaction is what made it bare its full teeth in a smile of relished hatred.
        Every alarm in Azaria's mind rang true of what she could not believe before her eyes. The dark had been subdued for hundreds of years, now they are powerful enough again to create a gemstone that houses a living soul, bereft of body? She deduced the sacrificed must have not been a regular man, but one that had the gift of aethermancy, the ability to conduct the flows of aether around them.
        The substance of a soul is made up of elemental aether, the very same life-giving spirit energy that dwells within all forms of matter. From wind and warm sunlight to rocks and rivers, the abundance and diversity of Caelutera's natural sources of magick gives potential for aethermancers to shape the elements to their will. The aether born within humans resonates with natural elements of the same color, and the intent of the caster conducts the elements into a spell. Evaz'sa controls the cycle of souls, and thus aether is reborn into human bodies and lives to experience sentience, then when the body dies and decays, the soul will continue to retain memories and knowledge gained in life. Souls of the departed reunite with God within her infinite aetherlight of the sun, to continue the cycle of life. 
        However, the results of underworld magick is meant to corrupt the flow of aether, to claim the magick that creates life for their own ends. Through their wicked rites, the magick-wielding essence of a person can be condensed down into a physical gem, its aetherlight free to be fed up on by any power hungry hound. The Lich Lord held pure power, a renewable energy and sentience encased in a stone. The underworld always has sought powerful mages to harvest their soul gems, however, the underworld had not been able to use that ability on the surface of Caelutera for hundreds of years. Azaria disconcertedly stared up at the sky adorned with a blue star shaped like an eye. What venomous magick has been spread into the world as quickly as the serpent bites?!
        As if bored from lack of attention and now taken with sleep, the eye in the sky winked and the light it shed ebbed with it. The clouds shifted and moved in random directions, the eyelids opened beyond the eye of the star, and faded into winds. The blue marble flashed, shedding all its light at once, then returned to the faint blue twinkling of how stars usually twinkle. It was once again the same size as it was before, the northward star continued to loom in the sky.
        The winds that stirred above turned their fury below and the sky bellowed down a mighty gale that threatened to tear the flames out from their torches. A hurricane engulfed the island, Azaria braced herself against the cold sea air that chilled against the pale skin of her face and chest like abrasive ice. All the trees rattled viciously, and even the fog enveloping the isle evaporated into the vehement winds. As the squall held Azaria, she could only cover her eyes to battle motes of dust with one hand and the other grabbed the ground to not be lifted back. Delina and Icargo braced themselves heavily too, wholly unprepared for what they were experiencing this evening.
        The tall Lich Lord gazed at his prize, the glowing red gem. The crescent moon lurched back up the pyramid in a single motion. The torches died down, and the torrents of wind settled like a storm had passed through. The oceans at last calmed. The ritual was complete, the elements at last rested. With a sudden jerk, the Lich Lord focused its hateful smile  straight towards Azaria's hidden vantage. Her cloak of mist had been blown away, revealing the three cliffside Shadow Knights in plain sight. The gem in his hands flared, and his dead eyes glowed red. He raised his other long bulky arm and pointed one of his long pointed fingers directly at Azaria. He opened his maw of long, crooked teeth and let out a sound that could have drowned out all the previous sounds at once. A terrible howl that carried incredible distance filled the open flatlands. A red light was within the Lich's mouth, and all the hooded crowd below all moved in the same sluggish motions. They all turned and halted facing up to Azaria, Delina and Icargo above in the firelight. An uproar of angry shouts from all the hooded cultists added to the wail of the Lich. The crowd split and formed into swarming platoons marching towards unseen paths in the crags to the fields up above to hunt where the Zenith Azaria and her Shadow Knights dared enter.
        A twist of rage glowered Azaria's face further. If they charge us, I will be forced to use the sword I must not. Yet, I can't allow a Lich Lord to keep one of those. She focused her silver and gold eyes furiously on the red gem the Lich held. They can't be allowed to use that! A Lich who can withstand moonlight, much less any kind of light, and can manipulate and corrupt all light the night bears. And now, he can freely condense souls into crystals for what end the cult needs them. The Lich ceased its shout and picked up its bloody cudgel. He carried the glimmering red gem and mace in either hand and he began descending the bloodied steps of the pyramid in long strides, he wanted Azaria most of all.  Whatever the cost, I intend to undo what I must. “I have a plan.” She arose quickly and turned to her followers, “For now, we run! Back through the fields!” They both gave a start, then they all ran away from the bloody clamor.
        The blanket of mist was gone from the winds, and the ground was exposed. They ran across the hard packed dirt as fast as they could, the only light was the crescent moon, though even that seemed tainted. Back through the dark open fields that seemed to stretch onward into an infinite void. But they ran fast across the black ground and limited dry grass. They reached a point in the middle of the field, then Azaria began to see a sea of cloaked heads just a few striding paces ahead of them. The three of them stopped, Azaria backed up and stood. She looked around her, the same squirming shapes of cloaks surrounded them all around, hiding within the darkness. “We stand our ground. Here!” She drew a long sword with a thin blade. I can not slay them with the Brevynard. If I do, it won't matter how many I cut down! This sword she produced from a bundle on her back, just below the giant greatsword with the brilliant orange-red gemstone within it. It was long and narrow darksteel, made for quick slashes. The Katana will be sufficient enough for these daemon-worshippers. I'll save the Brevynard for Him. She swung the sword in a swoop and arched her blade in a battle stance. 
         Delina quickly had her scepter in her hands. She clenched the leather binding the two twisted materials together. Darksteel and White wood, carrying a silvery orb. The ability to fight those who desecrate in the dark, with their own element. Arcana magic has served me well. She envisioned a giant black sun, and began conducting darkness energy up through the metal of her scepter. The mirror-like surface of the orb darkened and reflected no light, a sphere blacker than the dim night. The skill to convert darkness aether into light magic, that is my gift. She envisioned the black sun stretching beyond what her mind could see, until all the void of space was in fact filled with the darkness of the black sun's light. When the power of darkness full enveloped her mind, she began to see pinpricks of stars appear through the mesh. Then all became light, and her mind was filled. She snapped back to reality, and the sphere of silver on her scepter now was bright and incandescent. Light spilled across the ground and the edges of dark hoods. Pale as death hands with bony fingers hung from their black robes' sleeves. The cultists surrounded them, faceless hood after faceless hood. They all stood a short stones throw away from the trio. Delina's daffodil eyes widened. She swung the scepter in different directions, shedding flares of light left and right. So many of them! What does Azaria have planned!? She stood her ground, weapon at the ready.
        Unfastening a strap holstering his crossbow, he stood ready with it at his side. A long, piercing bolt of darksteel was knocked from a wooden box that dispensed a bolt at the touch of a button. Without looking, Icargo routinely placed the bolt in his crossbow. His gladius hung at his other side, at the ready if they enclosed them too much. His mind was clear and focused, flares of light from Delina's scepter hung in the air and lit up his ice blue eyes. He could only see the shapeless ruffle of cloaks amid a dark enclosing curtain of cultist cloaks. He aimed towards a single cultist, the closest one to them as he could judge, and without second thought, shot. The trigger snapped a mechanical sinew, and with a quick whip of the wind, the steel arrow found home within the hood of a cloak. A visible protrusion of arrow feathers from the hood was sure of the target, and the creature took another step or two, then collapsed forward onto itself. Other advancing cultists trampled as they step by step enclosed up on them.
        Underneath the feet of every cultist, a circle of thick fog began to fill once again the blackened earth. Tendrils of clouds crept across the ground, blanketing motes of fog were kicked up to the sky under countless cultists. A few of Delina's flares hung in the sky a treetop's height above them, and the battlefield was lit by hovering incandescent spheres. They lit the swirling fog unnaturally.
        Azaria stood at the ready with her long blade. She took a couple steps forward, but not enough to leave her knights unprotected. She waited for the threat to dare to creep closer. They did.
        Bolt after bolt was fired, steel pierced skull at a single push of a trigger. Icargo aimed and fired, the bow gun snapped in repetition. Hood after hood was pierced and the cultists fell one after another with guttural sounds of pain inflicted to things that once were human. He shot faster, a bolt hit a robed chest, the cultist kept walking. He shot another at the same one. Hit in the chest again. Black tar poured forward down the furls of the robe, and it collapsed with a gurgling wail. He must have downed six or seven, and each of their corpses were trampled, unmourned. 
        Another flare was fired from Delina's scepter, it hung low in front of her. She could almost see under the hoods of the cultists before her. Dark maws, some toothless with older than old looking members. Some mouthes snarled and snapped with foul, twisted teeth. All their skin was deathly pale from never seeing sunlight. Most winced their eyes that glimmered like round black pearls encased in eyelids of dead flesh. One of them hated the light more then the others, it seemed, and it charged straight for her. She was almost taken aback that she was targeted by one, but she knew what must be done. Before the distance was closed, she held out her scepter. Light filled her eyes, and a flamethrower of white fire burst forth in a wide vortex. She aimed it directly towards the cultist running towards her, and he was completely engulfed in fire. He let out a hoarse yell, and the running figure was burnt to cinders in a moment. A pile of smoking charred cultist corpse donned with a robe of ash lay before her, the last few plumes of white fire left the body, with a single outstretched hand only a pace from her. She shuddered, but had no time to disgust the creatures. The cultists hated her fire and she could feel a creeping sensation against her, like their hatred of her directly caused her this malice. She stood unwavering nonetheless, her scepter clutched tight. 
        All around them the crowd of cultists enclosed the gap tighter with every moment. As they grew too dangerously close, Azaria felt her instincts telling her to strike. She leapt forward, body twisting while still retailing her battle stance. She arched her blade and landed with a sudden turn just before the throng of robes started. The single slash she made cut through the cloth robes, and three hooded heads fell before their feet. Then their bodies landed atop their tops, and Azaria arched her blade once more. Two cultists, one female and the other male, charged forward with hidden ritual knives in their hands. Their pale white skin wielding blades flashed towards Azaria, and with a single swoop of her long sword and a dodge, she severed the woman's arm, and the man straight through his torso. The cultist cut through the half fell to the ground, then dragged himself closer to her, and with another arched slice to the ground, she severed the head. The one handed cultist strained her throat with an ear piercing scream and cowered back into the crowd of huddled robes. Azaria stood eyes-wide, burnished silver and gold staring, daring any to step closer. The crowd stopped.
        The cultists stood on top of some of their fallen, and they would not walk further to trample more of their dead and face Azaria. The cultists surrounded them to just where their many fallen lay around the three shadow knights. Hanging hoods permeated hatred from faceless faces. They stood there encircling them, refusing to come closer.
        They hesitate for I refused to use the Brevynard on them. Utter madness. They fear death, which they worship, and won't sacrifice their own coward lives unless it benefits the cult. She kept her blade held, she would not move for as long as they didn't.
        There was a strange stillness in the air. The sounds of a still crowd, all breathing and snarling and growling. Unmoving. 
        Delina gave a sudden start, she felt hot sweat and light headedness like she was falling into a fiery abyss. Before she could react, she could feel the fire burning, in the distance. She turned her head and tried to peer over the swarm of hoods. Ascending from stoney crags between thick branched thatches was an uncanny red glow. She could feel the presence of a powerful hateful glee, the twisted mind of a powerful once-human. The bright red glow against dark stone grew more intense and made silhouettes of trees. As it moved closer, Delina could feel the sensation of heat more intensely, as if the Lich Lord directly emanated it from wherever it was in the glow. Hoods stood with backs turned to a misty forest with a glowing red cave.
        There was a rumble of trees, some suddenly crumbled to the earth, and treetops were tossed side by side. Leafless trees crashing against one another, the snaps of breaking mighty oaks smashed against each other as they rattled and resonated. Huge plumes of dust and mist filled the sky in a great column that dispersed in higher winds. It was a glowing mist nebula surrounding the crushed trees, a single red glint was filling the cloud with light. Holding it was a tall silhouette wielding a swinging cudgel. Its ceremonial robes were tattered and bloodied, and intense red light was aglow within the Lich's dead eyes and mouth. It was letting out a constant, low bellow that sounded like rumbling human vocals strained with all their might to announce scorn and hatred. It pointed its cudgel straight towards Azaria, and snarled leathern lips around twisted teeth into a grim grin. With a sudden lunge it started into a run out through the dust clouds, its red light conflicting the hovering white flares. 
        “We charge!” Azaria leapt forward as soon as she gave the command. She went striking forward and vertically cleaved a cultist straight down the middle. She recovered her stance, and with long swoops began wilding carving a path into hooded robes.
        Icargo and Delina charged, matching Azaria's speed just behind her. Icargo had a handful of bolts nocked, he loaded one after another with one hand and pulling the trigger with the other has he ran. Lunging cultists were met with a shot straight to the head. Their right flank he covered with his bowgun fire.
        Running along the left, Delina held out her scepter and let it emanate a steady, floating wall of white flame. Cultists backed away from the heat and light, others flung themselves into the wall of glassy flames attempting to somehow harm the shadow knights. But, all pale-skinned wretches who touched the fires were burnt to smoldering cinders in a near instant. Hovering high above her were her flares of white flame, wobbling through wind with them like balloons in tow. But the light they shed could no longer reach them. They hung over their heads, and the closer she got to the Lich, the stronger the abysmal burning sensation crept over her. The night's darkness was restored with every step, her orbs growing darker as if their light absorbed by an invisible fog. The mere presence of this once-human eats away all my light flares! The glints trailed dimly above them. She felt she entered a bubble of darkness light couldn't enter. Even the moon and the blue eye of the watcher seemed to be engulfed in the blackness of the night sky.
        The cultists continued to bar their way, they each swiped quick flashes of darksteel. Azaria could still see well in this dark, but could only cut away at so many of them at once. A trail of slain cultists lay in the shadow knights' wake, yet they still remained barred by hoods with barely seeable once-human faces and pale flashes of skin wielding small ritual weapons. 
        Behind the crowd of hoods, the Lich raised his hand and all the cultists moved strangely as if puppets on a string. The crowd of a colosseum awkwardly stumbled onto themselves and parted into a circle of dozen strides, and now a dark open field lay between the Lich and the shadow knights. The Lich held his ruby gem up high, as if trying to outshine the remaining dwindling light with his own. 
        Azaria and her knights continued their race through the battlefield. She flew through the dark flatland, the tall once-human stood in a pool of its own red-hot light. The heat emanating from it burst like the three had leap into an oven by stepping within the red light. The shadow knights held their weapons battle ready beneath the tall man, who hulked over them about an arms distance in height. With a quick swing of steel, her blade met between spikes of the Lich's cudgel. With all her might she pushed against the knock back, and dug her feet into the hard packed earth. They pushed their weapons against each other in a gritty grip.
        As the heat of the Lich's presence scorched her, Delina felt it more difficult to grasp onto her magick. She felt as if she were trying to hold onto her own magick presence of her astral sun, she could see it, but it was engulfed in all the dark magick surrounding the Lich. I can't even tap into my own magick while I'm near him! What can I even do!? She anguished helplessly as Azaria held off the strength of the Lich. 
        The Lich towered over her, his neck elongated and bent down in Azaria's face as she held the blade of her katana firmly wedged between the bloodied spikes of the darksteel cudgel. His eyes were like slimy black pearls glaring at her in red light, his long, crooked teeth were wide releasing a bellow that rang her ears and even fouler was the Lich's breath that grit her nostrils with rank death. The red light from his eyes and soul gem coursed through him and his weapon, the evil energy of the daemons. She could feel the call to use the weapon she should never use. The blaring orange-red eye of the Brevynard on her back burned through her like a pike of hot coals as if the heat from the Lich and the evil within the sword fused through her. Fie! He even can will the gem in the sword to resonate with his own power! But, what can possibly force the powerful arcana sword to bend to the will of a Lich?! That accursed gemstone! Holding her katana against the pressure of the Lich took every last ounce of strength to not be toppled over by him, quickly she reached around her back and grabbed the heavy hilt of the hulking great sword. As soon as her hand met the well worn black leather wrapped around the sword, her strength peaked. The true power of the leader of the Shadow Knights, the wielder of the Brevynard. The arcane magicks flowed through her, and her swords were drawn. In one arm she held the katana fending off the Lich, and with this strength she held the great sword in her other hand. She felt the magicks manipulating her, arcane aether moving her muscles effortlessly, and she for a time could perform feats wrought from this arcane, unhallowed strength. But there was a wrongness in her magick, she felt the Lich's presence within the soul gem, feeding off its energy, something he should not be able to do. With a swing of the large blade, she struck the Lich on his cudgel, hitting him with the force of both her weapons. The sudden clash of metals echoed a loud metallic clang that heralded the battle of these ancient magicks. The tall Lich had to take a step back himself to prevent from doubling over, but he had quickly recovered and already swung his cudgel back at her. Azaria deflected it with the Brevynard alone. She held him off once more, she tried to further tap into the magick of her sword, if she could fire up its power strong enough, she could overcome the Lich. Even though she didn't want to use this power, she had no choice.
        Coming from all around them, hooded figures began entering the circle of red light. Their faces could clearly be seen under their robes now, pale-skinned faces reflecting red and squinting black eyes from the light. Their mouths were all open glowers, snapping and growling. They swung their ritual weapons in wild motions at the shadow knights.
        A blade sliced right by his face, cutting the air and missing narrowly. Icargo turned, a cultist had thrown a knife at him, he stood with one pale arm extended, the other readying to launch another. Oh, nay, my friend. You won't be doing any more of that. Icargo raised his bow gun, and the cultist wound his arm. A quick pull of the trigger, a snapping of metal and bolt fired from his cross bow. It struck the thrown knife, it deflected and ricochet off. The bolt, however, found home with a fanfare of burst blackened blood in the cultist's throat. It reached for its neck in a final motion and then fell to be trampled as more and more cultists lunged at Icargo, luckily not all could throw knives, but they wielded them deadly enough. He fired and kept them at bay best he could.
        A female cultist approached Delina. She had long white hair parted in the middle hanging down her hood, her face was like white, oily leather. She had sunken in black pearl eyes, and a mad grin on her toothless mouth. Is there no end to them!? She held her scepter with both hands, holding the spiraled white-wood and dark-steel coils that ended in a silver orb. The black sun was dimmed by an overpowering red light. No white fire produced for her. “Damn it all!” Delina felt a twisting hopelessness as the female cultist lunged towards her, a ritually carven kris dagger in her hand. Before the cultist drew too close, her eyes closed and Delina had herself in a full spinning motion. She felt her scepter hit something, she cautiously opened her eyes, and the cultist lay on the ground, bludgeoned in the head. Black-pearl eyes stared off into nothing, a white face covered in black blood and a toothless grin still twisted with glee. The Astra mage shuddered, but before she could disgust too long, and several more cultists were before her, each with a crudely fashioned ritual dagger. “Zenith, help me!” Delina pleaded with what remained of her panting breath. But, she turned to look where metal clanging against metal rang loudest, and there Azaria deflected blow after merciless blow. The Lich, weapons-locked with the Zenith, her leader wielding the Brevynard against the Lich. I am a fool! No one is here to save us! She felt a warm, dank and rank as the grave breath on her back. She spun round, a cultist, a man with a face half rotted with maggots writhing out of white flesh grinned in the blaring red light, his bony hands reaching to touch the skin on Delina's shoulders. She shrieked and jumped back, the old cultist stumbled forward after her, he gave her a mocking giggle acknowledging her fear. She turned and ran towards Icargo, shrieking again in disgust, exhaling whatever breath she might have breathed of his. As she closed the stride, she looked back and didn't notice all the other cultists standing just outside of the red light. One by one they began to enclose up on them in the circle of the red light, exposing under every hood and each revealing a hideous face.  She felt the overwhelm, the panic. She approached Icargo and put her back against his, “We cannot possibly fell them all, especially so, I am unable to tap into my magicks as long as we remain in the presence of this Lich!” She and he were surrounded by the flanks by cultists, but the Lich stood between, “We must aid the Zenith!”
        The Lich brought back his weapon, and struck repeatedly against the wide and flat darksteel blade Azaria held against him. Each strike she met and returned, deflecting the blow with the Brevynard with one hand, her other wielding the katana. Cultists dared approach her while she fought their leader, wielding long daggers and striking at her between blows delivered from the Lich. She swung the Brevynard up and struck against the Lich's ever in motion cudgel, and then quickly swung her katana to parry the blades of the enclosing cultists. Metals clashed furiously, Azaria willed more power from her dark sword, the heat emanating from the gem within the hilt surged through her veins, her muscles twisted and tensed with agony, then with a fierce strike, landed a mighty knock back on the Lich's weapon. He stumbled back for another moment, but more white-leather-faced cultists lunged at her. With one arm, she raised the long, thin edge of the katana and using only the quick cutting of the long, light blade. She made quick dispatch of the robed once-humans with their short daggers. The blade sliced through the attacking robes, she didn't bother taking count or how many at this point, and left a pile of mangled bloodied cloth and stinking death of what remained of them. Azaria turned, The Lich had already recovered and struck again with his cudgel, she deflected it entirely, she sliced up at him with the katana, leaving a vertical slice up its belly and chest. Skin tore, sinew sliced, and bones were cut. But not a single drop of blood shed, not a single wince of pain could be found within the glower of infinite hatred the Lich wore on its once-human face. The Lich clutched the glimmering red gem in its hand, the solid red light it emitted coalesced into a thick haze of light, and in a stream, began to wrap wisps of red light around the Brevynard. The blaring vermillion gem of the cursed sword began to wane its own brilliance, and even worse, trickles of orange energy began to flow back through this spiral of mist. She felt weakness, a fatigue she normally felt after a battle using the power of the ancient sword, but never so much strength left her while she still wielded it. The sensation of hot coals pressed against her returned, all over her body this time. It felt like her strength was literally flowing out of her blade in waves of heat. She felt her power falter, the heavy Brevynard gaining weight, and still only wielding it with one arm, it fell to the ground in her hand. Azaria fell to a knee, and began to pant in desperate panic. She felt lightheaded, dizzy, unable to even will conscious thought. Beads of sweat raced down her face in persistent chase.
        The Lich kept his cudgel raised, but he held out the soul gem. A cone-like vortex appeared beneath the gem, and thin tendrils of orange waves stemmed from the eye of the Brevynard. A slow moving spiral of spiritual energy began to unravel from Azaria. All the wisps extended out from her, and regardless of their direction, once it touched the red light of the Lich's gem, all of Azaria's orange light were absorbed into it as he drank from a well of her life force.
        A glint of darksteel passed through the cascades of light, and a crossbow bolt pierced the head of the Lich. It stuck through his temple to the back of his skull, a scowl of mild irritation twisted the leathery skin around its black eyes. He turned his gaze and unyielding bellowing towards the two weapons-drawn shadow knights running towards him, then in spite, more and more tendrils of bright orange produced from Azaria. The gem in the Brevynard dimmed to black. The mist spiraling from Azaria looked like ropes entwined with orange and gold light, then the orange turned to scarlet, then flickered between darkening to the color of blood and back again. She doubled over and leaned on both her weapons, letting out agonized groans that could barely be heard over the bellowing Lich. He had a wicked satisfaction on his pale face, and he arched his his spiked mace high, the crescent moon clouded in a miasma crowned the cudgel from its dark throne in the obscured sky.
        “Nay!” Icargo stopped at the short stride he was away and readied a bolt.  “Stop, you vile abomination!” He raised his bow gun to the level of his eye, and carefully, and with true refined talent, let a bolt fly. With true aim, it struck the gem in the Lich's hand. A steel against glass clang resonated, and the bolt found home in the rotted flesh hand holding the jewel tight. The red pool of light they were within flickered, and the intense waves of heat surrounding them ceased and cooled for a moment, only to return. The spiraling ropes of light wobbled like each layer were its own top-off-balance and nearly fell apart and unraveled into mist, but the aetherial ropes floated back into place in a perfect spiral. But, it was just the distraction needed to buy time for Azaria. 
        The Lich turned to Icargo, even more enraged at the minor annoyances he never even compared to the threat of Azaria, and even she had been subdued. He held the gem tighter in his hand, trying to bleed more energy from it. Icargo fired bolt after bolt at the soul gem, the Lich moving the gem to protect it and deflecting the bolts with his arm and mace. A bolt or two hit the gem and the light at heat ceased for moments, or pierced the Lich's flesh like small protrusions of bolts along its arm. 
        As the gem was struck and shaken, the gold, orange and red strands of the spiraling rope began to unravel like threads, each one one of those three colors, then they dissolved into mists of light. Azaria leaned on her weapons, panting still, but she felt her strength gradually returning to her. The Lich was only a few steps from her, merely his attention turned, his ceaseless wrath soon to be released onto her shadow knights. How could he tap into such power? Have I lead us to defeat bringing us here!? Her burnished gold and silver eyes widened as the Lich twisted its face at Delina and Icargo, and she gasped. “Never.” she let out in a breathy mutter to herself. Her grip on the Brevynard tightened. “I will never taste defeat...” The gem within the eye-lid shape of the hilt was a dull black. She forced herself to her feet. Every one of her muscles ached and burned, the strain from being forced to used the cursed sword, like a hot coal had been pressed against each muscle in her body to will it to move. She stood with a weapon in each hand, the Breyvnard heavy and blade touching the ground, and she held the katana outward. One chance. She sheathed her katana in the hidden bundle on her back. She used the strength of both her arms to hold up the heavy and mighty greatsword, the cursed Brevynard. The long curve of the wide and flat darksteel blade was etched with intricately woven ivy leaves and thorns in the black metal, it almost didn't look like a sword at all. The gem was still black, small glints of orange in catches of light, but nothing else. Azaria took a deep breath, and concentrated on the image of a black sun. It was a large blackened ball of magma, orange-red pouring from tiny cracks in the pumice surface. It eclipsed a blaring red light, and could not shed any of its own. It looked sickly, corrupted, violated, raped, even. Oh you always were strong, and cunning, and now you're nothing more than a shell of a man but with strings tied to the hands of Archdaemons. “Damn shell of a man... unhallowed life without end!” she tightened her grip on the sword till she was white-knuckled. The orange cracks in the black sun began to shift, every plate of the pumice earth shifted and cracked apart, small continents swallowing into an orange, churning sea of fire. The glow of this sun emanated stronger and stronger, and the gold light expanded beyond the red, a burning medallion sun crowned perfectly in her mind was all she could see.
        The tall man in tattered ceremonial robes was turned with sizing up Icargo's strength, distract with devising cruel ways to use his cudgel. But, sensing a furnace of power, the Lich crooked his head around. Azaria stood there in an aura of brilliant vermillion, eyes aglow with scarlet light.
         “I'll end you.” she uttered, and the black gem of the Brevynard flared brighter than her own light with bursts of gold and orange. As the Lich turned with an arch in his cudgel wielding arm ready to strike, Azaria leapt through the night air, eyes focused on the gleam he held. With a fast dodge and swing of the cursed blade, black fire burst forth in a blink from where she cleaved through the hand the Lich coveted the gem in. The dark flames dissipated into ashen embers at the severed arm and wrist of the ancient flesh. Its leathery grip tightened around the gemstone as the hand heavily fell to the ground. The gem and undead hand tumbled across the ground, spilling light in every direction in a roll into the crowd of cultists. In a stretched moment, the thick, dark gloom overhead, the menacing heat and red light from the Lich, it all condensed and swelled into the gem, concentrating into a single ball of light encased within the glassy red walls of the fist-sized gemstone. 
        The pale white glow of looming light was restored to the battlefield in an instant, hiding hooded faces. The fingers of the hand writhed and gripped, desperate to still draw magicks from it, the vain efforts of the still animated flesh. 
        The sound of the Lich's bellow continued, but without the force of power it once had. It was weaker now, within a more human vocal range. The sounds it made mourned the loss of the soul gem, he could care less about the rent undead flesh. With vengeance, he turned, swinging his cudgel at Azaria, she parried it with the Brevynard and they were once more weapons-locked. But once his strength was sapped, the Lich was no more as strong as a tall man. Against the weight of her weapon, he faltered to a knee, his face at eye level with Azaria now. He continued to bellow a weaker, yet ear splitting yell with perhaps a touch of genuine fear. 
        “Oh, would you to be silent!” shoving the Brevynard forward, she clashed the weapons together, forcing the spiked cudgel swinging backwards to pummel into the Lich's leathery face. A hard blow was dealt straight to its nose and mouth, it made a short, whimpering howl from receiving the unexpected blow, then Azaria was met with bated silence, while liberating a few of his gnarled teeth in the process. The Lich fell back onto itself, the tall man crouched in a huddle of tattered ceremonial robes. Azaria turned and scoured the ground among the middle of the crowd, white light beams were spilling up through shadows of robed legs. The gem! She charged towards the light beams, the Brevynard in hand. The cultists in her way had their attention turned to the gem, they coveted its power as much as any Lich Lord, but they still barred her way. She swung the blade broad sided, she dared not land a cut of the cursed blade to their flesh, merely the force of flat metal was enough to fell them over. A few hoods were struck from behind and collapsed to the side. Others standing she shoved as well, having to actually grab their dank and rank robes made her stomach turn, but the power of the Brevynard flowed through her, and she pushed them aside, she tossed a cultist colliding with another to fell them both. One by one she dealt with the backs of the crowd, all of the mass of cultists were reaching over shoulders and trampling over one another. Countless pale arms extended to the gem, the center of the light pool spun and tossed as cultists closest to it fought over it.
        Amid the crowd, Delina stayed close by Icargo as he defended her as they slowly inched their way through the crowd closer to the gem. Cultists all around them seemed to ignore them entirely, yet they tried to push and shove past them like they were any other person. 
        Icargo had his bowgun in one hand with a bolt held between his teeth, his other hand wielded his gladius sword. He swung his blade indiscriminately at cultist arms reaching in every direction around him, the crowd pulling at one another, all fighting to get the glowing red stone. Blackened blood splattered from pale flesh as Icargo wounded weaves of once-human limbs. Wails of pain resonated from cuts dealt, and hateful faces turned to him. Three cultists nearby, all reached out with their leathery bloody hands, ready to grab him under the surrounding throngs of trampling feet. He fired his bowgun, at the close range his aim had small room to err, and quickly it pierced the once-human's head, and he was trampled under others before the body could even hit the ground. The second cultist had a knife's blade pointed right at Icargo, arm held back, shaking, working up the nerve to throw it. Icargo froze in thought for exactly one moment, then wound his arm back, and threw his sword at the cultist, the blade pierced straight through his chest, and he fell to the ground. Before he could take a breath, he grabbed the knocked bolt from between his teeth, and loaded it in the shaft of his crossbow while cocking it back. As soon as he looked back up, the arm of the cultist grabbed his face with a tackle, and down to the ground they tumbled.
        Delina crouched close to the ground, her back to Icargo, she turned with a start as soon as he suddenly toppled over next to her. 
        The cultist wrung his arm tighter around Icargo's neck, the choking stench of the robes turned his stomach. The pale-skinned face twisted with gleeful vengeance as he strangled his arm tighter, then his eyes suddenly went wide and mouth gaped with a silent scream. Icargo pushed the heavy robed man off of him, the cultist had a bolt protruding from his groin. Tossed into trampling feet, the man's corpse rolled.
         Delina grabbed at Icargo, helping him up. As soon as they were back up on their feet, they saw the motions of light shift suddenly. Looking toward the center of the crowd, a single cultist held the gemstone with the Lich's hand tightened around it. It seemed like the crowd had stopped fighting over control of the gem as soon as there was pause enough for one of them to tap into its power. Rippled waves of light pooled from the man in robes as he beheld the gem in his hands. He grabbed at the bolt that stuck out from Lich's hand, and pulled until he freed the gem from the severed hand's grip. Dropping the dead hand, the cultist held the gem up to his beady black pearl eyes, as if figuring out how to fully work its magick.
        A snarl visited Icargo's lips, "Protect yourself and help the Zenith," He turned to Delina with a desperate look on his face, "I will do what I can, just get out of the crowd!" Before Delina could react, Icargo knocked another bolt and let it fly forward. With a few snaps of leather, he reholstered his bowgun and darted off. He ran to where his sword was thrown and pulled the bloody blade from a cultist's corpse, then hacked and slashed deeper into the crowd fervently. A throng about seven people thick stood between him and the soul gem. He had to get it from them, now. Who knows what other magick the cultists could use, and a mere gem can let them become more threatening than before. 
        Before she could protest, Icargo had left her, sword swinging. Around her were cultists, she only stood up to shoulder height of most of them. Few paid any mind to her, they were completely absorbed in the glow of light. She moved through gaps in the crowd, moving in quick darts in the direction she hoped Azaria was in. But it was impossible to see over the hooded robes, for now at least. All she could do is run between and weave in the crowd, catching sights over shoulders of Azaria and Icargo. There was a clear space behind  another cultist, and peering behind him was a big flat rock. She climbed up on its rough surface and was about a leg taller than the crowd. In the center was the pool of light, oscillating and making strange glass chime whirring sounds. Icargo was only a person or two from coming up on the cultist holding the soul gem. She peered around the crowd more, and a faint orange glow brought her eyes to Azaria making her way through the once-human throng. Delina tightened her fist over her scepter, I can help them, I have to! She closed her eyes and held up her scepter. The presence of the Lich was no longer overshadowing her own ability to conduct her aether. She envisioned the full dark void of space in her mind, and gradually small pinpricks of light pierced the black blanket with quick succession. Her mind began to fill with Astra starlight, and the world around her melted for a moment.
        With a hard shove, Icargo at last pushed aside the cultist between him and the gem. In the middle of the swirling pool of light, a man with white hair stood with his hood cast down his back. He held the soul gem in his hand, drawing up on its power with triumph in his grin. His eyes were big black spheres that reflected the soulgem's light with a mad lust for its power. Then the eyes rolled and he turned to Icargo, and a snarling grin twisted his face. He drew a large ritual carved kris  from a furl in his robes, and with one hand he held his dagger and the other the gem. He pointed the blade at Icargo and flinched the edge towards him to show he means a threat. 
        I'll teach you a bloody thing or two. Icargo swung his gladius to meet with the cultist's large dagger. Then the cultist's blade quickly darted, and Icargo had to readjust his swing to parry. The cultist swung again and took steps closer, then began swinging the knife with unnatural speed. It was all Icargo could to but to deflect the knife with his sword with counter parries that had to match the cultist's speed. Kept at bay, Icargo couldn't get close to the gemstone, the cultist drawing up on it in a blade frenzy. More white light flowed up the cultist's arm as he consumed more of the red gem's power. Each strike gained in ferocity, and Icargo struggled to meet the dagger with his sword. Clangs of metal rang with each deflected blow, and cultists stood staring in a circle around them.
        The Brevynard's broad sided blows felled robe after dark robe down. Azaria stood atop a mass of incapacitated cultists making her way through the crowd closer to Icargo at the flashing pool of light. She was up on her knight engaged with the gem-wielding cultist, a few more heads stood in her way. She shoved them aside in a fervor.
        Behind her a few strides away was the Lich Lord, silent with gnashed and bloodied teeth. He took a step at a time with quiet patience, cudgel tight in remaining hand. His hateful black eyes bore a hole into the back of Azaria, unbeknownst to her he approached.
        Atop the rough hewn rock stood Delina enwrapped in an auric glow. In desperation she channeled more power than she needed, and the flow of Astra filled her with intense emotions. She felt a sort of universal bliss, as if just by sight could feel the light and warmth of every star in the night sky. In contrast, she could feel the infinite void of space, a gap of cold darkness stretching beyond imagination. The further she filled herself with Astra, the further she could see through her mind. She felt could almost grasp an understanding of the infinite of space filled with countless stars, yet the pinpricks of stars seemed to be a single ball of light. The only thing keeping it from being a single ball of light was the continual expanse of the darkness in her mind. She forced herself to concentrate on the battlefield, stopping the conduct of her own aether. The building sensation of Astra held in place, light flowing through the veins of her arms and up to her mind. Delina opened her eyes and scanned the battlefield. Using her mind's eye to sense where the pool of shimmering light was was easier than actually looking for it. She could feel the strong gravity of someone else conducting the soulgem's aether pulling towards her. 
        Icargo felt his stamina leave him, and his limbs became sluggish sponges after deflecting so many brutal blows. The cultist wielding the gem relentlessly struck at Icargo's blade, a further grimace of glee snarled on the cultist's pale leathery face. Black spheres widened aware of the Shadow Knight's diminishing strength. After metal met his weak perry, the cultist spun and robes swooped, then Icargo felt the ritual knife pierce through the leather and cloth covering his left side. The blade sought deeper to pierce his heart, but he tossed himself back and within arms distance swung his blade. He managed to land a strike on the knife pulled out of him, deflecting the blade as he bled and fell backwards. A sharp pain in his side felt like warm ice trickling down his ribs. He felt cold hands at his back, cultists shoved him forward forcing him stumbling back onto his feet. He barely had the strength to stand and hold his sword, and the cultist struck again with his knife. Icargo's blade failed to move fast enough, and he felt the cut of the cultists knife against the armor protecting his chest. Only fast enough to swung his sword again just to repel the attack of the already struck knife, Icargo desperately fought to defend himself. The cultist sought the kill and further lust for his blood. 
        To Delina, it looked like two shadows fighting in front of a blur of brightness. Limbs and weapons moved too fast to fully see, but the sight of one of the shadowy figures she was sure was Icargo, and he fell. She still held fast onto the overflowing black and white flickers of Astra, even her own vision was slightly blurred in glowing contrast. She had to help her comrade, but at this distance, to cast a spell in the already in place flows of aether surrounding the cultist's pool of light would be very difficult. What can I do, I can't very well run over there while carrying this much power. It was true, she could barely stand while holding this much Astra aether within her. Her attention was drawn to an orange glow that seemed even more brighter than anything in the glow of her vision. She sensed the power of the soulgem that inhabits the Brevynard and how much of its strength Azaria was calling up on. While she flung aside cultists, behind her enwrapped in an unseeable, lightless void was the aura of the Lich. Shivers of panic raised the hairs up Delina's spine, she had to help the Zenith as well. The Lich was mere arms reach away from behind Azaria, and he began to raise his cudgel high. In a desperate moment, Delina reached out to feel all the magick whirling around the battlefield. The powerful pool of light emanating from the soul gem threatened Icargo, Azaria's orange glow and presence of the Brevynard was familiar. But, another energy hovered overhead, even more familiar to her. Her hovering flares of Astra light still hung overhead like low hanging stars among the leafless treetops. But to her, connected through her unique Astra affinity, they were within reach of her mind's eye. As she raised one hand and grabbed for them, she raised her scepter in the other. She felt their incandescent heat in her hand, and then the pulses of light and dark traveled up the coiled darksteel and white wood. When her Astra flows reached the silver ball wrought between the two coils, she felt a sensation of warm, electric light leaving her body, and an arc of white lightning cracked like a whip as it beamed skyward. It split into tendrils that danced from flare to flare in sparks of light, connected by aetherial ropes that snapped as quickly as they appeared leaving streaks of orange across the night sky. Then the white flares all burst forth in size in a cluster of explosive booms. The heavens were suddenly mid-day illuminated by tens of suns. 
        Icargo parried another one of the cultist's forceful swipes, then he fell onto his back. Against the hard packed earth he was tossed to, he raised his blade in defense to anticipate another expected strike. He covered his wound with his free hand, the warm ice sensation had spread across his side and he began to feel dizzy. He gazed skyward, weapon raised with the last of his strength. But behind the threat of his foe, the sky began to glow.
        The cultist grinned and licked gnashed teeth at the Shadow Knight like a vulture salivating over carrion. The grip of veiny death-white hands tightened on the glimmering gem, and the light surrounding them swelled. He raised his ritual knife and a twisted glee seethed in his black pearl eyes. Then leathery brows squinted from intense sunlight bright all around him, and the pale faced once-human crooked his neck and looked up.
        "The underworld take you, filth!" Icargo crawled on his back against the rock-packed earth as fast as he could. Before him, the cultist gaped his gnarled maw and above him he beheld a roaring torrent of incandescent flame. 
        The flesh and robes ignited in the unrelenting cascades of fire, and the once-human cultist shook violently to remain alive, pulling desperately from the power of the gem. The man lit entire, his yell was hoarse and airless through the cloak of flame. As he ran forward in flames, he collapsed as life left him. Cast from his ashen hand, the pool of light coalescing into the small red fist sized gem and it tossed to the ground. In the chaos, the gem was unsought and rolled across the earth. 
        All around Icargo, spheres of incandescence hailed and burst in a volley, quickly turning the battlefield into a fiery crucible. He stayed as close to the ground as he could, crawling face and belly across the earth to avoid the waves of searing heat just over his head. After the rolling gem of light he willed his way as it was swallowed into the glow of raining fire.
        Great glassy walls of fulminating flame ignited hooded figures as they ran and wailed. Smoke and grey ash plumed  aglow in ember's effulgence. The panicked crowd scattered like a buzzing, burning swarm of locusts in glowing orange clouds. The light ceased thundering down, rumbling and wailing were the only sounds in its wake. A fiery wall streaked across the ground, consuming all cultists within the path of the inferno, leaving scorched earth.
        The crowd broken apart by the flames bursting before her, Azaria thought her chance to get to Icargo and extricate the gem was open. Then the torrent of fire changed its path with a sudden bend, and consumed the earth as it turned towards her. The wall of white flame targeting her made her feel like she were suddenly staring down the sun. Then behind her a roar of bloodlust. She turned, and the howling face of the Lich was there to greet her, cudgel swinging. She gasped and before she thought to swing her blade, she had leapt to one side. The hulking and rank with death Lich Lord swung the cudgel at where she was, and cracked a large break in the flat earth. Then as Azaria landed, less gracefully than she would have wanted, she turned back to face the unhallowed abomination. The torrent of incandescence swallowed him whole, consumed into the roaring blaze.
        The Lich dropped its cudgel and flailed his long remaining arm and hacked limb. What was left of the burnt drapes of his tattered ceremonial robes whirled through the air and corrupted once-human flesh melted and sloughed to charred bone. The tall walking pillar of fire was bellowing through thick wisps of black smoke towering out from it, then it collapsed to the ground in a pile of wailing, burning robes and rot.
        Conducting the fiery flows of aether, Delina danced her scepter in a trance. The white and black Astra flickered in her eyes as she conducted the aethereal walls across the flatlands. Through the blaze, a faint orange glow and a pinprick of incandescent light could be seen through her Astra eyes. Azaria and Icargo are somewhere around there! She swung her scepter and did a spin in her leather boots atop the craggy rock. The fire dispersed above her comrades, and a dome of air appeared. She made it large enough to ensure she would safely encompass both of them. She carved paths of fiery walls, the dome of air swirling making a safe eye amid the storm of fire.
        A mere step away from Azaria, the Lich's wailed through the wall of fire weakly as he melted down like a living candle into the ashen pile. I won't allow myself to savor any foul satisfaction out of this thing's demise. She turned away from the defeated, abhorrent creation of a human. Perish and meet a true end. The battlefield was bright with branching walls of glass, layers of Astra fire made everything strongly aglow. Across the flatland, the cultists ran in every direction before Azaria. All this, has to come to an end. Her fist tightened around the drawn Brevynard as she turned about, searching. Where is it!? She scoured among the light trying to find the one glimmer of light among walls of white. Among the great furnace of bright, she saw Icargo lying on the ground in a huddle. Silver and gold eyes wide with worry, she hurried through the gauntlet of flames over to him. If they have taken down one of my knights, I swear I'll destroy every last one of them! I'll ensure they'll perish in countless ways the most befitting and... She came up on Icargo, she had never seen a tall and well built man curled in a ball on the ground, lest they were a corpse. She sheathed her blade as she crouched nearby and reached over to him. Uncovering his face from his arms, she slapped against his cheek to wake him, to see if he was alive. "Icargo? Raven Icargo! Are you all right?" 
        Regaining consciousness slowly in hazey moments, Icargo opened his icy blue eyes, and coughed in the hanging smoke clouds. He met with Azaria's overhead gaze, a faint smirk appeared on his lips. "Zenith..." he said weakly, "I have ta'en a hurt." She looked down at his side and he released the clamp of his hand to show her his wound. Shiny streaks reflected off the slicks of red wetness escaping down the black leather of his armor. He let out a single exasperated laugh, then a dry cough, and he recovered his wound tightly with his hand.
        She put her arms around him and propped his head up and laid him against her bosom. "You have indeed..." Azaria's knight was injured, and she had no idea where Delina was in the field on fire. Curses! If I had known the fiends wielded a soul gem, I would have brought down up on them an army of Ravens! She looked down at the reflections of a red pool on the ground by Icargo. I will not let the Shadow Knights fail here. Not here, not ever. "... You are badly wounded. I need to stop your bleeding, and we need to find Crow Delina, and..." She raised her head and scoured hopelessly among the sea of white flames and running, flaming hoods for a tiny glimmer of light. Damn it! If another cultist finds it and uses the magick sealed within the gem...
        "Zenith," Icargo moved his other hand, tucked away beneath his arm and breast, and he began to straighten up.
        Her gaze fell down to him, "Don't try to stand yet, you fool! You'll tear your wounds more than I can-" and Azaria cut off at the sight of the carnelian red soul gem nestled in Icargo's hand. Between his fingers, a faint, dim marble of light was calmly aglow. Its magick looked exhausted, as well as the life force of her knight. 
        She reached to his hand and Icargo let go of his grip, which began to quiver from holding the fist-sized thing for so long. 
        Azaria beheld the gem in her hand, she sensed the energy that had been abused to exhaustion. The gem the Lich Lord made in his lust for the magick within the human soul. 
        "Where is our Crow? Where's Delina?!" Icargo asked weakly, and struggled to stand.
        "Hold still!" She shoved him back down. I've no time to gawk at gems! Azaria quickly wrapped the gem into a cloth bundle and tied it in with the rest strapped to her. She grabbed Icargo's hand tightly against his side. She put pressure against the blood ever trickling out from between his fingers. I'll do what I can for now. She envisioned her orange sun, a blaring sphere in her mind, radiant and golden with her aether. She released mists of energy from it, and all her senses heightened. Her hand felt past Icargo's, and she felt the icy warmth and sting from her knight's wound. She concentrated on the feeling harder, almost pulling at the cold sensation of cruor leaving a wound. She felt the sting in her side, she winced and grimaced as the sharpness grew, and her flesh beneath her armor began to tear.
        In long, breathy gasps Icargo tried to say something or make a sound. He felt his wound feel a sudden heat like a smithy's hot iron pressed against his side. He  tried to toss side to side, but Azaria held him still and tight, and pushed harder on his wound. He looked up at her eyes and the spheres of silver and gold were bloodshot and housed a crimson light. Hundreds of pinpricks were felt in his flesh, as if hot pins were stitching his wound back together with magickal, cauterizing heat.
        The new wound open in Azaria's side was deeply cut and the pain was constant as if she were receiving the blade deeper with every passing moment. The piercing sensation neared her heart, and blood rushed out the wound and she could bear no more. She imagined the sun in her mind's strength diminishing, the roaring fire dying down  and magma cooling. The golden light faded like an extinguished flame. She released her hand from Icargo's side and pulled her arms around him, sitting up upright. "To your feet Raven, we must immediately find our Crow and take flight." They stood, but as soon as she lifted him, she hunched to one side. The tear in her flesh was nearly unbearable, she didn't know how Icargo as a mortal could have been still alive with the full wound. 
        In a daze, Icargo sat up and was already standing, although it was with a limp. He removed his hand from his side in disbelief at the closed wound. Through the slit in his leather armor where the blade entered, there was closed skin. He pressed down, and the sharp pang from his innards nearly made him double over. Beneath, his flesh was still not fully healed. He felt dizzy from the loss of blood and the brightness and roar of flames and cultists running all around him. Beside him, Azaria leaned on herself, her hand against her own side. She noticed his gaze and she stood straight up, gritting her teeth in a growl. Her eyes winced for a moment, then they gave a solid stare. As if in a moment of arrogant pride, she relished receiving the life threatening wound. A strange badge of honor for the Shadow Knights is to have a wound found worthy to be Healed by the Zenith herself. But, he saw how she must be fighting off whatever she must be feeling. The true leader of the Shadow Knights until every last moment. The Zenith, she... she took this rent flesh from me, and now is hindered to even stand!? Yet she desires not to willingly show it, I can see how she steels her nerves against the same pain. I am but a reckless fool! Curse the dark and all this! He could stand, he unholstered his bowgun. The magickal flames shielding around him were slowly dying down, burning up the rest of the aetherial energy the spell was wrought with. He searched among the dimming flames seeing if among any of the figures  running through the walls of fire he could find Delina. But they were all formless, moving around in a blur, scattered and unseeable. He turned back to Azaria, she was still nearly doubled over. "Zenith, I await your command." 
        "A... moment." Azaria envisioned her sun once more, it was darkened with a faint glow around it. She willed it to grow but the flames grew only slightly. She could feel heat pulsing on her back from Brevynard. The magick within the gem inside of the sword beckoned to her. Her wound wouldn't kill her, but she was still slowed. I'll do what I must. She merely reached her hand to the hilt of the broad darksteel sword stowed like a burden on her back. The power of the blade was called up on, and she felt the flows of aether enter her through the sword. With her other hand she felt the sharp pain of her wound at her side. She focused the will of the Brevynard into herself, and she saw the sun in her mind once more. The dim surface of the sphere swelled in orange golden light then burst forth in a sudden surge flows of her aether. With a gasp, she felt intense heat coursing through her and pressed at her wound from the inside. The flesh closed beneath her armor, healing as if it were never there. Releasing her hand from the sword, she severed the flows of aether once again. Her pain and the heat were replaced by hot invisible stitches that made the surrounding flesh feel dull and numb. Sweat beaded off her face and she panted to catch her breath among the acrid smoke. Her side was still tender, but she and her knight could now move, at least. With Icargo staved from death temporarily with her Arcana magicks she had rather not have to awaken. She had the gem, the Lich was felled, But where is Delina? The walls of flame that were once the height to fence off throngs of humans had lowered to patches of fire pits. The blinding glow of light was now ground level dissipating into scorching white embers. The battlefield was still thick with the vile stench of burnt once-human flesh, and there were still faint wails in unison all around them. The cultists would be back soon, and in greater numbers. Through the clearing smoke and fire, Azaria and Icargo trod through the dying flames of the battlefield. We must find her and leave this damnable isle at once. Lest we lose the stone as well as our lives. She pushed through plumes of smoke and marched around and over burnt bodies. Icargo was closely following behind her.
        Up on a large black boulder, Delina awoke in a daze, head and heart pounding. She was thick within a haze of smoke arising from charred, stinking robes polluted throughout the flat field. In short breaths, her lungs were met with the harsh air, and she coughed and gagged in the rank, putrid aroma. Unable to breathe or see through the thick clouds, she hastily slid her scepter into the bundle on her back and scrambled down the jagged rock with barely enough time to feel for footholds through her soft leather boots. As she descended, she had time to question what had happened with racing thoughts. She remembered being swelled full with the overwhelming Astra, the sensation that her mind could expand endlessly intaking the light of stars and even more darkness to hold them. Usually there are intense sensations when one conducts flows of aether, but what stuck out to her as out of the ordinary is how she closed the Astral Flare spell. She merely reached out towards her floating flares, then the rest was lost with the smoke. She could barely remember releasing the spell, though she did distinctly recall dancing while twirling her scepter and conducting the flows of fire spell to form it into a moat of flame. But what of Zenith Azaria and Icargo? The fire couldn't have... When she tried to recall any more detail it was faint, like trying to remember a distant dream. When she put another foot down through the haze, she was so surprised to meet ground she let her hand slip entire and fell back with a sharp gasp. After a short distance of weightlessness, to the hard packed earth she fell flat on her bottom. After recovering from the momentary shock, she let out an exclaimed "Ouch!" as she picked herself up, back leaning against the black stone and her hand tending to her sore rump. I didn't know I conducted so much Astra that I can't even stand as though I still have sea legs. The intense Astra aether had left her and it was as if she were able to see the field with new eyes. 
        The intense glow of the battlefield fires had died down severely, the ground was peppered with only a few remaining ember patches. Dark of night had reclaimed the island with pale moonlight that reflected eerily off catches of smoke blanketing the field of charred robes. 
        Before her was a sea of dead, felled by her flames and her comrades' blades. The sight of so much shed blood of these things that resembled human perturbed her beyond nightmares. The fact most of them were burnt by her own spell was no comfort either. Better they than I, yet I do pity them though. They were human with lives of their own once. A loud series of wails from far off chilled her, accumulating and unseen. Delina cautiously moved away from the boulder, daring to venture back through the battlefield. 
        It was difficult to see more than a few strides ahead of her through the moonlight obscured by a screen of ashes and dust. Where could they be? All that were lain across the stone packed ground were countless dead cultists. She took steps through the miasma, stepping around stinking mounds of charred robes. Her stomach nearly turned at every step, and she tried to keep her eyes focused on finding a clearing out of the haze. Some moonlight poured in through a hole in the smoke, a fresh breeze of misty sea air. She ran towards the opening, heels clopping quickly against the flat ground. A breath of cold succor filled her lungs, and before she could gasp for another breath, she felt a tug around her soft leather boots. She fell  sharply to a kneel, and looked back to meet the one-eyed glare of a cultist nearly all charred on the ground. Half of the face was burnt exposing black bones and teeth, the remaining flesh was half twisted in a grin. Delina let out an ear piercing shriek that carried beyond the cloud she was just within the edge of. She kicked wildly and pushed away with her other leg, but she dragged the cultist with her. It made a gurgling cackle and grabbed another hand on her leg as it was dragged in tow with her. To the Crow's horror, she realized only half a body was clung onto her. She shrieked again, and held out a hand. Instantly, a single star in space filled her mind, and a fist-sized sphere of white fire shot from her hand, completely immolating the face and let the robes catch flame. She crawled on her back still fighting the cultist's grip off her boot, her scepter digging into her shoulders. Finally into the dim moonlight, out of the cloud and still dragging the half-once-human aglow in candescent fire. 
        She was inhaling to shriek again, but then she heard a pair of footsteps come up behind her. Icargo had his sword drawn, and with a quick cleave he lobbed off the flaming arm. Delina continued to kick her leg around until the charred undead hand flew off into field. She was picked up by Icargo and faced to see Azaria, standing arms across her breastplate with a frown of pure rage on her full lips. "Zenith!" Delina gasped.
        Azaria saw she was uninjured. At least one of us is. "We fly. Now." She turned, her long dark hair tossed with a sheen of moonlight. "To the cliffs, we are nearly home free my Shadow Knights!" she took a step, a sharp pang pricked her side. Her wound was tearing, the numbness of the hot stitches dulling with each movement. She almost couldn't stand, but another resounding wail nearby reminded her there wasn't any time. "Make haste!" she grit her teeth and she started into a sprint, her knights in close chase.
        The three whisked through the flat fields, headed towards the thick brush and alcove near the coast. They charged through thick wisps of smoke and leapt over fallen corpses. If there were any more cultists, they were hidden, yet not unheard. The grotesque chant of screams drew louder and closer, yet still remained unseen. 
        The skin on Delina's back crawled, and not just from the sounds. The sights she had witnessed made her wish she was anywhere else but here. She ran harder.
        They came up on the thick brush guarding the hidden alcove, Azaria pulled the thick thatch of leafless branches back and her knights ducked in. Azaria dropped a pale stone on the ground that gave just enough light to see their equipment. 
        The three crouched in the small clearing, backs to the stone wall. They each unholstered their weapons and unwrapping their bundles, and each unfolded a cloth robe containing their climbing gear. 
        Azaria took a bundle around her side off, adding to her concerns, the dark cloth was wet with blood escaping the wound she took from her knight. Her vision blurred for a moment, and her movements were sluggish. Damn it! We are so close yet so far, I cannot climb like this. I would tear myself apart before I met the rocks below.
        After Icargo finished donning his robe he secured his bow and blade, then he felt a pull at his side like a string unraveling. He felt a thin hot needle pierce his skin, the sensation took the breath out of him momentary. He turned to Azaria, and she was shaking her head in confusion and worry. The hot string pulled faster, and the tear in his flesh agonizingly reformed. "Zenith, can we take flight?" he groaned through his teeth. 
        Her gold and silver eyes met with his ice blue and gave a hard stare, "Do not say such coward things." She pulled her robe over her head, "To the cliffs, I have a plan." and ignoring her wound, put the heavy bundle of the Brevynard on her back.
        Delina had only just noticed the deep injuries both Azaria and Icargo bore. Her daffodil eyes went wide, but she said nothing and kept to securing her bundles and donning her robe.
        The three had only just secured their climbing gear when a cultist wielding a dagger in each hand leaped out from behind the rattling brush. He flailed both his arms, swinging his knives wildly at Delina as if she were a stalked prey. Before she could flinch, a glimmer of darksteel flashed before her face and Azaria stood before her, arched with the blade that she called her katana. Delina jumped up sharply inhaling a gasp, and stood back against the stone wall, the Zenith parrying both daggers with the long blade. 
        Azaria shoved the cultist back with another clash of weapons, "Fly!" she commanded without turing her head.
        Icargo blanked the wound from his side, letting out a roar as he grabbed Delina by the arm. They ducked out of the thatches of the alcove, hastily rustling through a forest of dead tree branches. The sounds of the ocean crashed all around them, and at last they made it into the clearing overlooking the water. 
        They were safe on the cliffside, Delina looked over the edge and was relieved to see their boat still tied to the rocks below. But, what of Azaria? And her and Icargo's wounds! 
        Icargo stood with his hand on his side, adrenaline kept him from feeling the pain but that wouldn't close his wound. His eyes gazed back into the darkness of the forest, "Where are you, Zenith?" The response was silence sans the sounds of the sea. He felt Delina lean against him, he looked down and she stared back into the forest with him. Her pale face was drawn with worry for the Zenith. Tears from yellow eyes caught glimmers of light as they rolled down her cheeks. "She will be fine. Steel your patience." he assured her, assured himself. They stood in the crescent moon's glow, staring with anticipation into the shadows of forest. Then there was a yell that was cut short that carried from the trees. Delina covered her hands around her mouth and hid behind Icargo's back, peering out. There was rustling moving quickly towards them. He unholstered his crossbow and knocked a bolt. He loaded the steel shaft and raised the weapon to his ice blue eyes, cooly he gazed over the aim groove into the forest. He would not fire until he could clearly see.
        The clamor of the branches grew more violent, as if in struggle. Then the pale face of a cultist reared into the spilt moonlight, black pearl eyes stretched open to the point they looked as if they would burst.
        Icargo's finger touched the trigger, but then he stopped before he pulled. Behind the cultist was Azaria, one hand wielded the katana, in her other grip she had wrung the robes around the cultist's own neck. She carries the flailing fiend as if it were a wild boar safely in a silk sack! Is she mad!? He kept his weapon raised, then he noticed that when the once-human struggled his arms, there were no hands to be seen. He then uncocked his bow and lowered it. 
        Azaria walked through the sea mists, closer to the flat stone edge to her knights, and threw the cultist to the ground. The streaks in her gleaming gold and silver eyes burned a furious red. Wet streams of ruby reflected off the armor at her side, and it was clear she could not feel it.
        The cultist crawled on his back and handless limbs, black-pearl eyes wincing up at the dim glow of the moon above. 
        Azaria stood over the pitiful, disgusting creature, and she sheathed her katana. Before the action could be confused with mercy, she drew the Brevynard from her back. The heavy, curved blade swung in a long swoop and stopped at the cultist's neck. The face that belonged to a man shivered in fear, but Azaria knew the thing was incapable of knowing human emotions. Even so, she had planned on reminding him. Swinging the sword back, she rest it downward in one hand, then knelt and grabbed the cultist by the throat and held it down against the stone ground. The dark gem inside the Brevynard pulsed brightly with brilliant orange light, and Azaria's hand produced a dark colored flame. The cultist's crooked mouth opened releasing a hoarse yell as its black eyes rolled. She could feel herself feeding on the thing's life force, dark violet energy flowed warmly up through the veins in her arm. Soon, her whole body was glowing in dark purple energy. The wound in her side closed in an instant, she felt the stitches mending her immortal flesh whole. That should do.
        Gushing out of the cultist's robes was a fountain of black cruor. The wounds she returned to him would more than match the ones she had, and he would keep them. The once-human man made more strained airless sounds, and laid on the ground, paralyzed by the wrath of Azaria.
        She pierced her red gaze into his black pearl eyes, "Now then, I have something I want to ask you." The cultist's face turned away, she bumped it back with the steel hilt of the Brevynard."Nay, friend. I know you can hear me."
        The cultist met Azaria's red gaze guiltily, eyes locked but head still wary and edging back.
        "That's right, now..." she bumped his face with the hilt again to point it skywards making sure the glint of the blue star reflected in his vacant eyes. "What is that? How was your Lich able to withstand the moon's glow?"
        The cultist rolled its black eyes away from the sky, crooked its head to cliffs, seeking escape.
        "Raven Icargo,"
        He blinked, "Aye? ... Zenith?"
        "Place your hand on me."
        Taking a step towards the cliff, the sharp pain reminded him of his wound. Icargo knelt and reached through her hair, putting his hand on her shoulder, the skin near her neck was wet with sweat and mist. The violet energy flowed up through his fingertips and warmness filled the blood in his hand. Up his arms and down to his wound, the warm life aether mended his flesh. He let go and stood with pain completely ceased, and fighting energy restored to him as if he breathed a second wind.
          Thick black fluid burst forth from the furls of the cultist's robes. It made more gasping sounds, then turned its head back fearfully to Azaria. It made an unsettling huge grin on its pale face, chanted in a mutter the clicks and harsh guttural sounds of the ancient tongue. “Rend the souls of Caelutera to the ground," it heaved another breath, "Faithful light snuffed out, never to be found." 
        The chanting echoed from the forest, Azaria and her knights turned to see shadowy figures rustling in the thick branches.
        "Offers the True God, Her peoples' cruor warm," the cultist on the ground continued the words of the ancient tongue, and the words resonated in unison from the trees.
        "Delina! Torch the forest!" Azaria shouted.
        The sudden surprise was apparent on her face "W-what?!"
        Azaria let out a grunt of frustration, "Do this now and without hesitation, my Crow!"
        The chanting of hundreds of voices came closer, and hoods stepped one by one out of the branches. "The sigils break, the Watchers empty their womb!”
        Drawing her scepter, Delina envisioned the night sky in her mind.
        There was a tug on the blade of the Brevynard, and as Azaria turned back to the ground, the once-human's pale hand had wrapped around the blade and had pulled it through his own neck. The head burst into black fire, quickly spreading to consume the rest of the body as well.
        Nay! "Damn you, foul creature!" Azaria pulled the cursed blade away, but the black flames continued to consume the cultist. The robes remained, but the body had all but been burnt to ash. What was left was a thumb-sized pebble, it had the luster of a piece of jet-stone. "There is not a moment to waste for this!" she grabbed the small gemstone and placed it within a bundle, then the Brevynard put back in her holster on her back.
        Coming out of the forest were cultists with ritual knives and thin weapons long enough to be swords. They were moving in quick darts like an angry hive of fire hornets. Delina swung the heavy silver ball of her scepter and a series of bright flares spread forth. The dry brush of the dead forest all inhaled a deep gust of air, then ignited the darkness in the burst of Astral Flare. Within the forest, all was lit up and countless cultists' faces were seen opening to scream, but all that was heard was the roaring of fire.
        Icargo had been fumbling with the hooks still in place at the side of the sheer cliff. He and Azaria looped rope through climbing hooks and thick metal rings attached to their belts. The sudden explosion provided them some well needed light. Azaria looked back to the fulminating mass of white light that was now a wildfire spreading across the whole island. 
        "Take another lot o' you back." Icargo snarled, and he had just secured the last of his climbing gear when Delina came trotting back so fast he thought she would collide with him. 
        "I have..." she took a deep breath, "eliminated... the..." Delina was about to go on, then Icargo began tying her into her climbing gear.
        Azaria waited by the cliffside while Delina lowered herself down, followed by Icargo. None else emerged from the inferno, and she watched as thick, black smoke billowed endlessly towards the sky. Haunted images as ancient as her earliest memories crept into her mind, she shuddered even more at the blue star in the sky. Whatever the cost, we shall attain victory. She rest her hand over the bundle containing the soul gems she carried. Their weight seemed even heavier now.         Her Shadow Knights had descended down far below, she repelled down in the same manor. The brightness above was a stark contrast to the dark, misty crags of the black rocks far below at the shore of the black isle. Her soldiers had safely descended and boarded, Icargo stood over the edge of the boat, grabbing at the knots tying the boat down as Delina sat afloat preparing to raise the small sail. Azaria untied her gear hastily and ran across the black-gravel beach. The coolness of the misty air greeted her as her steps crunched across the rough hewn sand.
        "Zenith, do make haste!" Icargo motioned for her to hurry, then went back to working the huge knot holding the rocking boat ashore.
        She ran faster, I'd like to be off this isle a lot sooner than you think. Azaria hopped on the boat and gave it a sharp heave. Icargo nearly toppled over, yet he regained his balance and continued to fumble with the thick knots keeping the boat docked.
        "Aside, man. I'll take it from here." Azaria pushed him back with only a little force, then she drew the Brevynard. In a hack of the cursed blade against rope and rock, both were hewn apart. The pebbles scattered across the beach, and the waves of the sea carried the small boat off. They both sat back and breathed a bated sigh of relief. 
        With the pull of a rope, Delina let rise the black sail, and it quickly caught the strong gale of night air. The boat set away from the craggy shoals, the Crow set her yellow eyes up high on the burning island. She turned towards the unseen darkness of the horizon, putting away thoughts of how many lives she had ended. She was grateful to be gone.
        The island was an ignited torch in the middle of the sea, Azaria watched it burn. It unnerved her that she had no idea how much the dark had grown, and she and her knights barely escaped with their lives. An army of Ravens. If I had an army. She chuckled at herself, letting thoughts of what they could be fighting get ahead of her. What could possibly allow an unhallowed, damnable Lich Lord to touch moonlight? And create soulgems from living mages as free as in the Dark Era?         Her gold and silver eyes turned upwards, the blue star adorned high above the brightness of the island. They were a considerable distance away into the open sea, but she could see figures moving around in the water in the brightness around the Island. Tall ships bearing huge sails emblazoned with the Ijian black and white bird wielding a sword and shield on a blue crest. The Ijian royal fleet can handle things out from here... If their Shadow Knights have any mettle left. She faced the wide sea, the strong winds billowing them eastward back to their hidden home. Clutched tightly in her pouch, a fist sized red gemstone.




